// ============================================================

// ── CIVILIZATION RECORDS ────────────────────────────────────────────────
const CIVS = [
  {"id":1,"n":"Lemuria / Mu","s":-50000,"e":-25000,"r":"Pacific (Theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"pacific","d":"Hypothetical lost continent proposed to explain cultural parallels between widely separated ancient peoples. Originated in 19th-century geology and later absorbed into Theosophist and occult traditions by Helena Blavatsky. No geological evidence supports a sunken landmass in the Pacific, though the cultural diffusion puzzle it sought to explain remains genuinely interesting.","up":312,"dn":891},
  {"id":2,"n":"Pre-Flood Advanced Culture","s":-13000,"e":-10800,"r":"Global","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"Proposed lost civilization destroyed by the Younger Dryas cosmic impact event (~12,800 BCE). Championed by Graham Hancock (Fingerprints of the Gods; America Before) and geologist Randall Carlson. Argues anomalous megalithic sites worldwide, advanced astronomical knowledge, and flood myths in 200+ cultures point to a sophisticated predecessor civilization. Mainstream archaeology disputes the interpretation of the evidence.","up":2103,"dn":1240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-13000,"e":-10800,"label":"Hancock / Carlson — Younger Dryas Impact Destruction","source":"Fingerprints of the Gods (1995); Magicians of the Gods (2015); Carlson, Kosmographia ep.72","researcher":"Graham Hancock / Randall Carlson","up":1820,"dn":934},{"s":-35000,"e":-13000,"label":"Extended Pre-Flood Civilisation — LaCroix","source":"Matthew LaCroix, The Stage of Time (2019)","researcher":"Matthew LaCroix","up":621,"dn":1203}]},
  {"id":3,"n":"Atlantis","s":-11600,"e":-9600,"r":"Atlantic (Theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"atlantic","d":"Advanced island civilization described by Plato c.360 BCE, said to have been destroyed 9,000 years before his time in a single catastrophic day and night. Plato's only sources — his dialogues Timaeus and Critias. Allegorical philosophical fiction, or encoded cultural memory of a real Bronze Age collapse? The debate has never been resolved.","up":4821,"dn":2103,"dateTheories":[{"s":-11600,"e":-9600,"label":"Plato's Account — 9,000 years before Solon (~9,600 BCE)","source":"Plato, Timaeus & Critias (~360 BCE)","researcher":null,"up":3102,"dn":1891},{"s":-1600,"e":-1450,"label":"Minoan / Thera Eruption — Galanopoulos","source":"Galanopoulos & Bacon, Atlantis: The Truth Behind the Legend (1969)","researcher":"A.G. Galanopoulos","up":2841,"dn":1203},{"s":-3100,"e":-1100,"label":"Bronze Age Egypt — Anachronistic Mistranslation hypothesis","source":"John Luce, The End of Atlantis (1969)","researcher":"John Luce","up":891,"dn":2103}]},
  {"id":4,"n":"Yonaguni Monument Culture","s":-10000,"e":-8000,"r":"Pacific / Japan","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"Submerged stone formations discovered in 1986 off Japan's Yonaguni island, 25m below sea level. Geologist Masaaki Kimura argues they are man-made ruins of a pre-flood city. Most mainstream geologists contend they are natural sandstone formations shaped by tectonic activity and sea-level rise. The debate hinges on specific carved features that appear tool-made.","up":2821,"dn":1903,"dateTheories":[{"s":-10000,"e":-8000,"label":"Kimura — Pre-Flood Man-Made City","source":"Prof. Masaaki Kimura, University of the Ryukyus; Graham Hancock, Underworld (2002)","researcher":"Masaaki Kimura","up":2103,"dn":1201},{"s":-2000,"e":-500,"label":"Natural Formation — Tectonic Jointing","source":"Robert Schoch, Yonaguni survey report (1998); Boston University","researcher":"Robert Schoch","up":1891,"dn":982}]},
  {"id":5,"n":"Göbekli Tepe Culture","s":-9500,"e":-7500,"r":"Anatolia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Builders of the world's oldest known megalithic temple complex in southeastern Turkey. Pre-dates agriculture by 1,000+ years — fundamentally overturning the assumption that organized religion followed settled farming. Who built it, and why it was deliberately buried, remain open questions. Excavation continues under the direction of the German Archaeological Institute.","up":8241,"dn":203,"dateTheories":[{"s":-12000,"e":-9500,"label":"Sweatman / Cygnus Alignment — Pre-YD Construction Phase","source":"Sweatman & Tsikritsis, Mediterranean Archaeology & Archaeometry (2017)","researcher":"Martin Sweatman","up":1203,"dn":891},{"s":-9500,"e":-7500,"label":"Schmidt Consensus — Hunter-Gatherer Ritual Centre","source":"Klaus Schmidt, Sie bauten die ersten Tempel (2006); DAI excavation reports","researcher":"Klaus Schmidt","up":7821,"dn":312},{"s":-11600,"e":-9500,"label":"Hancock — Survivors of Pre-Flood Culture Built First Temples","source":"Graham Hancock, Magicians of the Gods (2015); America Before (2019)","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":3891,"dn":2103}]},
  {"id":6,"n":"Çatalhöyük","s":-7500,"e":-5700,"r":"Anatolia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"One of the world's oldest and largest Neolithic settlements, home to up to 8,000 people. No streets — residents entered rooftop doors and climbed down ladders. Wall murals, figurines and burial practices reveal a rich symbolic life. UNESCO World Heritage Site.","up":4102,"dn":189},
  {"id":7,"n":"Ancient Sumer / Mesopotamia","s":-4500,"e":-539,"r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Cradle of civilization. First writing system (cuneiform, ~3400 BCE), first law codes (Ur-Nammu, Hammurabi), first cities, first organized religion. The Epic of Gilgamesh is humanity's oldest surviving literary work. The Annunaki — Sumerian gods of sky and earth — have been reinterpreted by Zecharia Sitchin as extraterrestrial beings, a theory widely rejected by scholars.","up":12932,"dn":312},
  {"id":8,"n":"Ancient Egypt","s":-3100,"e":641,"r":"North Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of history's longest-lasting civilizations, spanning 3,700+ years. The alignment of the Great Pyramid to true north (within 0.05°) and the Orion Correlation Theory (Bauval, 1994) connecting the Giza pyramids to Orion's Belt have fuelled enduring debates about lost astronomical knowledge. Graham Hancock argues the Sphinx dates to 10,500 BCE — contested by Egyptologists but supported by geologist Robert Schoch's water erosion analysis.","up":19450,"dn":421,"dateTheories":[{"s":-3100,"e":641,"label":"Mainstream Egyptology — Dynastic Egypt from ~3100 BCE","source":"Encyclopædia Britannica; Oxford History of Ancient Egypt (2000)","researcher":null,"up":18200,"dn":412},{"s":-10500,"e":-8000,"label":"Schoch / Hancock — Sphinx Water Erosion Pre-Dates Dynasties","source":"Robert Schoch, Voices of the Rocks (1999); Graham Hancock, Fingerprints of the Gods (1995)","researcher":"Robert Schoch / Graham Hancock","up":5821,"dn":3201},{"s":-36000,"e":-10000,"label":"Schwaller de Lubicz — Esoteric Ancient Egypt","source":"R.A. Schwaller de Lubicz, Sacred Science (1961)","researcher":"Schwaller de Lubicz","up":1203,"dn":4891}]},
  {"id":9,"n":"Indus Valley (Harappan)","s":-3300,"e":-1300,"r":"South Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Advanced urban civilization with planned cities, running water, standardized weights and sophisticated drainage — contemporaneous with Egypt and Sumer. Mohenjodaro and Harappa housed up to 40,000 people. Its script remains completely undeciphered. The civilization's sudden collapse around 1900 BCE may relate to climate shift and Saraswati river desiccation.","up":7621,"dn":341},
  {"id":10,"n":"Minoan Civilization","s":-2700,"e":-1100,"r":"Crete / Aegean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Europe's first advanced civilization. Palatial complexes at Knossos, spectacular fresco art, maritime trade dominance and the still-undeciphered Linear A script. Collapsed ~1450 BCE — possibly from the Thera (Santorini) volcanic eruption, one of the largest in the Holocene. Often cited as a candidate for the real Atlantis.","up":5102,"dn":231},
  {"id":11,"n":"Mycenaean Greece","s":-1650,"e":-1100,"r":"Aegean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Bronze Age Greek civilization and the inspiration for Homer's Iliad and Odyssey. Collapsed abruptly ~1200 BCE as part of the wider Bronze Age Collapse — a still-debated catastrophe involving climate change, drought, migration and systems failure that brought down nearly every civilization of the eastern Mediterranean simultaneously.","up":4421,"dn":312},
  {"id":12,"n":"Assyrian Empire","s":-2500,"e":-609,"r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The ancient world's most formidable military power, pioneering iron weapons, siege warfare and psychological terror as instruments of state power. The Library of Ashurbanipal at Nineveh preserved thousands of cuneiform tablets, including the flood narrative that predates the Biblical account.","up":4103,"dn":312},
  {"id":13,"n":"Shang Dynasty China","s":-1600,"e":-1046,"r":"East Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"First historically-verified Chinese dynasty, confirmed by oracle bone inscriptions — the earliest form of Chinese writing. Bronze ceremonial vessels, ancestor worship and a theocratic monarchy defined this formative era. Their astronomers recorded solar eclipses with precision.","up":4891,"dn":289},
  {"id":14,"n":"Vedic India","s":-1500,"e":-600,"r":"South Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Produced the Vedas — humanity's oldest surviving religious texts. Foundation of Hinduism, Sanskrit literature, Ayurvedic medicine and Indian philosophy. The astronomical references within the Rigveda have led some researchers to propose composition dates as early as 4000 BCE — contested but not definitively disproven.","up":7432,"dn":318},
  {"id":15,"n":"Olmec","s":-1500,"e":-400,"r":"Mesoamerica","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Mesoamerica's 'mother culture.' Creators of colossal stone heads — up to 3.4m tall, carved from single basalt boulders transported 150km. Some heads display distinctly African facial features, fuelling persistent but unproven debates about pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact with West Africa.","up":5230,"dn":412},
  {"id":16,"n":"Phoenicia","s":-1500,"e":-300,"r":"Levant","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Master seafarers who gave the world its alphabet — the ancestor of Greek, Latin, Arabic and Hebrew scripts. Founded Carthage and may have circumnavigated Africa under Egyptian commission around 600 BCE, as recorded by Herodotus — 2,100 years before Vasco da Gama.","up":5712,"dn":289},
  {"id":17,"n":"Ancient Greece","s":-800,"e":-146,"r":"Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Birthplace of democracy, Socratic philosophy, Euclidean geometry, theatre, the Olympics and the scientific method. Plato, Aristotle, Archimedes and Hippocrates defined intellectual frameworks still in use today. The intellectual foundation of Western civilization.","up":14821,"dn":502},
  {"id":18,"n":"Achaemenid Persia","s":-550,"e":-330,"r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"World's first superpower — ruling 44% of the world's population at its peak, from Egypt to India. Cyrus the Great's Cylinder (539 BCE) is arguably the first declaration of human rights in recorded history. Its administrative, postal and road systems influenced every subsequent empire.","up":8432,"dn":421},
  {"id":19,"n":"Carthage","s":-814,"e":-146,"r":"North Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Rome's great rival and the pre-eminent power of the western Mediterranean. Hannibal Barca's crossing of the Alps with war elephants in 218 BCE remains one of history's most audacious military campaigns. Completely destroyed by Rome in 146 BCE — its libraries burned, its site salted.","up":5821,"dn":312},
  {"id":20,"n":"Roman Republic & Empire","s":-753,"e":476,"r":"Mediterranean / Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The civilization that most profoundly shaped Western law, language, architecture, religion and political thought. From a city-state to a Mediterranean superpower spanning 5 million km². Its fall in 476 CE marks the conventional end of the ancient world and the beginning of the Middle Ages.","up":21230,"dn":612},
  {"id":21,"n":"Han Dynasty China","s":-206,"e":220,"r":"East Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Golden age of Chinese civilization. The Silk Road opened global trade; paper was invented; Confucian bureaucracy established a model of governance lasting two millennia. The Han defined Chinese cultural identity so thoroughly that the majority ethnic group is still called 'Han' today.","up":8823,"dn":401},
  {"id":22,"n":"Maurya Empire","s":-322,"e":-185,"r":"South Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"India's first great empire, unifying the subcontinent under Chandragupta Maurya. Under Emperor Ashoka (c.268–232 BCE), it embraced Buddhism and non-violence, distributing edicts of compassion carved into rock across the empire — some of history's earliest expressions of universal human ethics.","up":6102,"dn":289},
  {"id":23,"n":"Maya Civilization","s":-2000,"e":1500,"r":"Mesoamerica","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Advanced astronomers whose Long Count calendar tracked celestial cycles with extraordinary precision. The only fully-developed writing system of pre-Columbian Americas. Their 'Classic Collapse' around 900 CE — in which dozens of cities were simultaneously abandoned — remains one of history's great unsolved mysteries.","up":9821,"dn":401,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2000,"e":1500,"label":"Mainstream — Maya Long Count Origin ~2000 BCE","source":"Coe, The Maya (2011, 8th ed.); Sharer & Traxler, The Ancient Maya (2006)","researcher":null,"up":8201,"dn":391},{"s":-3114,"e":2012,"label":"Long Count Correlation — Creation Date 11 Aug 3114 BCE","source":"GMT Correlation; Thompson, Maya Hieroglyphic Writing (1950)","researcher":"Thompson / GMT","up":4103,"dn":812}]},
  {"id":24,"n":"Byzantine Empire","s":330,"e":1453,"r":"Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Eastern Rome, lasting 1,100 years after the Western Empire's fall. Preserved Greco-Roman knowledge through Europe's Dark Ages. Its fall to Ottoman forces in 1453 drove Greek scholars and their manuscript libraries to Italy — directly triggering the Renaissance.","up":9102,"dn":501},
  {"id":25,"n":"Islamic Golden Age","s":622,"e":1258,"r":"Middle East / Global","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Unparalleled advances in algebra (al-Khwarizmi), astronomy, optics (Ibn al-Haytham), medicine (Ibn Sina) and philosophy while Europe languished in its Dark Ages. The House of Wisdom in Baghdad was the world's greatest intellectual centre. Ended by the Mongol sack of Baghdad in 1258.","up":8432,"dn":612},
  {"id":26,"n":"Viking / Norse","s":793,"e":1100,"r":"Northern Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Master navigators who settled Iceland (874 CE), Greenland (986 CE) and established a settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows, Newfoundland (~1000 CE) — 500 years before Columbus. Also founded Kyiv and traded as far as Constantinople and Baghdad via the Volga trade route.","up":10321,"dn":521},
  {"id":27,"n":"Mongol Empire","s":1206,"e":1368,"r":"Central Asia / Eurasia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Largest contiguous land empire in history, covering 24 million km² under Genghis Khan and his successors. While catastrophically destructive in conquest, the Pax Mongolica enabled unprecedented Silk Road trade, cultural exchange and the transmission of technologies between East and West.","up":11923,"dn":701},
  {"id":28,"n":"Aztec Empire","s":1300,"e":1521,"r":"Mesoamerica","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Dominant Mesoamerican power centered at Tenochtitlan — a city of 200,000 built on an artificial island in Lake Texcoco, larger than any contemporary European city. Destroyed by Hernán Cortés and, more decisively, by smallpox in just two years (1519–1521).","up":7821,"dn":412},
  {"id":29,"n":"Inca Empire","s":1438,"e":1533,"r":"South America","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Largest pre-Columbian empire in the Americas, stretching 4,300km along the Andes. 40,000km of roads, extraordinary dry-stone masonry (stones fitted without mortar to within 0.5mm), and the quipu information system — yet no writing. Conquered by Pizarro and 168 men.","up":7102,"dn":389},
  {"id":30,"n":"Ottoman Empire","s":1299,"e":1922,"r":"Mediterranean/Mid East","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"One of history's longest-lasting and most powerful empires, straddling three continents for over 600 years. At its peak controlled southeastern Europe, western Asia and North Africa. Its dissolution after WWI directly created most of the modern Middle East's borders — and its conflicts.","up":11230,"dn":621},
  {"id":31,"n":"Pre-Columbian Contact","s":-500,"e":1400,"r":"Trans-oceanic","t":"debated","cont":"global","d":"Evidence for contact between Old and New World civilizations before Columbus. Hard genetic/botanical evidence: sweet potato reached Polynesia from South America ~1000 CE; Polynesian chickens found at El Arenal, Chile dated to pre-1492. Contested claims include the Olmec heads (African contact), cocaine in Egyptian mummies, and the Newport Tower (Norse). The sweet potato data is now mainstream; the rest remains debated.","up":3103,"dn":1821},
  {"id":32,"n":"Anunnaki / Sumerian Gods","s":-450000,"e":-10000,"r":"Global (Theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"Zecharia Sitchin's interpretation (The 12th Planet, 1976) of Sumerian cuneiform tablets as literal history: the Anunnaki were extraterrestrial beings from planet Nibiru who genetically engineered Homo sapiens as a slave species to mine gold. Mainstream Assyriologists unanimously reject Sitchin's translations. However, the Anunnaki as sky-gods are genuine and central figures in Sumerian/Akkadian mythology.","up":6231,"dn":8921},
  {"id":33,"n":"Ancient Alien Intervention","s":-300000,"e":-3000,"r":"Global (Theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"The hypothesis — popularized by Erich von Däniken (Chariots of the Gods, 1968) and the Ancient Aliens TV series — that extraterrestrial beings visited Earth in pre-history and influenced or directly created human civilization. Mainstream science finds no credible evidence, but the theory raises genuinely interesting questions about the rapid emergence of complex civilization after ~300,000 years of anatomically modern humans.","up":8103,"dn":14230},
  {"id":34,"n":"Ubaid Culture","s":-6500,"e":-3800,"r":"Mesopotamia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Pre-literate agricultural culture spread across Mesopotamia, named for the type-site Tell al-Ubaid near Ur. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — distinctive painted pottery, mudbrick architecture and early temple platforms excavated across dozens of sites. Established the settlement foundations at Eridu, Ur, Nippur and Uruk that would become Sumerian civilization. Ubaid-style pottery recovered along the entire Arabian Gulf coastline suggests maritime trade networks of surprising range predating written history.","up":3201,"dn":189},
  {"id":35,"n":"Eridu — First City","s":-5400,"e":-2000,"r":"Mesopotamia / Iraq","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The oldest confirmed city in Mesopotamia. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — identified with Tell Abu Shahrain in southern Iraq, excavated revealing 19 superimposed temple levels. Named in the Sumerian King List as the first city 'where kingship descended from heaven.' Its patron deity was Enki — Anunnaki god of wisdom, freshwater and creation. UNESCO World Heritage candidate.","up":4102,"dn":241},
  {"id":36,"n":"Uruk — World's First City","s":-4000,"e":-3100,"r":"Mesopotamia / Iraq","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The world's first true urban centre, home to an estimated 50,000–80,000 people at its peak. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) cuneiform. Birthplace of writing — cuneiform script emerged here ~3400 BCE. The Epic of Gilgamesh is set here. Patron deity: Inanna/Ishtar. The Uruk cultural period's influence spread across the entire Near East.","up":5812,"dn":312},
  {"id":37,"n":"Nippur — Sacred City","s":-5000,"e":-800,"r":"Mesopotamia / Iraq","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The spiritual capital of ancient Mesopotamia — site of the Ekur, great temple of Enlil, chief of the Anunnaki pantheon. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) cuneiform. More tablets have been recovered from Nippur than any other site — tens of thousands covering mythology, law, medicine, mathematics and astronomy. A city whose religious importance survived every change of political power over 4,000 years.","up":3891,"dn":198},
  {"id":38,"n":"Anunnaki — Cuneiform Record","s":-3500,"e":-500,"r":"Mesopotamia","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Anunnaki are documented in thousands of Sumerian, Akkadian and Babylonian tablets as the principal pantheon. Evidence type: (B) cuneiform exclusively. Key figures: Anu (sky), Enlil (authority), Enki/Ea (wisdom), Inanna/Ishtar (love/war), Ninhursag (earth). Their flood narrative (Atrahasis Epic) predates the Biblical account. This entry covers the documented mythological tradition — Sitchin's ET reinterpretation is catalogued separately.","up":5203,"dn":1891},
  {"id":39,"n":"Pre-Flood Kingdoms (King List)","s":-30000,"e":-10800,"r":"Mesopotamia (Theorized)","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Sumerian King List records 9 rulers across 5 cities who reigned before 'the flood swept over the earth' with individual reigns of 18,600 to 43,200 years — totalling 241,200 years. Evidence type: (B) cuneiform — the Weld-Blundell Prism (Oxford). The five antediluvian cities have archaeological confirmation of post-flood occupation. Mainstream scholarship interprets the reigns as mythological. Alternative researchers argue they encode compressed records of a pre-Younger Dryas civilisation.","up":4103,"dn":2891,"dateTheories":[{"s":-30000,"e":-10800,"label":"Literal Reading — Encoded Historical Record","source":"Zecharia Sitchin, The 12th Planet (1976); Matthew LaCroix, The Stage of Time (2019)","researcher":"Sitchin / LaCroix","up":2103,"dn":3892},{"s":-5000,"e":-3000,"label":"Mythological Hyperbole — Reign lengths are formulaic","source":"Thorkild Jacobsen, The Sumerian King List (1939); Britannica","researcher":"Thorkild Jacobsen","up":4891,"dn":912}]},
  {"id":40,"n":"Bad-tibira, Larak, Sippar & Shuruppak","s":-28000,"e":-10800,"r":"Mesopotamia (Theorized)","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The four remaining antediluvian cities of the Sumerian King List. Each carries a deity: Bad-tibira (Dumuzi), Larak (Pabilsag — no confirmed tell located), Sippar (Shamash, confirmed at Tell Abu Habbah), Shuruppak (Ubara-Tutu, last antediluvian king — his son Ziusudra is the Sumerian Noah). Evidence type: (B) cuneiform for pre-flood phase; (A) archaeological for post-flood layers at three of four sites. All pre-Younger Dryas dates classified debated.","up":2103,"dn":1891},
  {"id":41,"n":"Upano Valley Civilization","s":-500,"e":600,"r":"Ecuadorian Amazon","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"A sprawling pre-Columbian urban network discovered via LiDAR in Ecuador's Upano Valley — results published in Science (January 2024, Rostain et al.). Evidence type: (A) LiDAR + ground excavation. Reveals interconnected settlements with monumental platform mounds, massive ceremonial plazas and straight sunken roads stretching tens of kilometres. Individual settlements housed up to 10,000 residents. Graham Hancock cites Upano in Ancient Apocalypse as evidence Amazonian civilization was far more sophisticated than acknowledged.","up":6821,"dn":412},
  {"id":42,"n":"Amazonian Geoglyphs (Acre)","s":-200,"e":1200,"r":"Acre, Western Brazil","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Hundreds of large geometric earthworks discovered across Acre state, Brazil, after deforestation exposed them to aerial observation and LiDAR. Evidence type: (A) aerial survey, LiDAR and limited excavation. Constructed beneath what was previously considered undisturbed primary rainforest. Purpose remains debated: ceremonial, calendrical, or territorial. Graham Hancock and José Iriarte (University of Exeter) argue they indicate a far larger pre-Columbian Amazonian population than previously acknowledged.","up":4103,"dn":1203},
  {"id":43,"n":"Kingdom of Mapungubwe","s":1075,"e":1220,"r":"Limpopo Valley, S.Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Africa's first stratified class society — elite lived atop the sandstone hill, commoners below. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — excavated since 1930s; UNESCO World Heritage Site 2003. Its Golden Rhinoceros, Golden Sceptre and Golden Bowl show extraordinary craftsmanship. Chinese Song Dynasty porcelain and Indian glass beads confirm Indian Ocean trade. Declined ~1220 CE from climate cooling; its people and traditions migrated north, likely contributing to Great Zimbabwe.","up":4201,"dn":189},
  {"id":44,"n":"Great Zimbabwe","s":1100,"e":1450,"r":"Zimbabwe Plateau","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The largest pre-colonial stone structure in sub-Saharan Africa — 11m walls, 250m circumference, 900,000 fitted granite blocks with no mortar. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Capital of a gold-trading kingdom controlling commerce between the interior and the Swahili Coast. Chinese porcelain and Persian ceramics confirm Indian Ocean trade. Colonial-era denial of its African origins (attributing it to Phoenicians, Queen of Sheba) is one of archaeology's most documented episodes of racially motivated misinterpretation — comprehensively refuted.","up":5812,"dn":312},
  {"id":45,"n":"Kingdom of Kush / Meroe","s":-2500,"e":350,"r":"Nubia / Sudan","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of Africa's great civilizations, flourishing along the Nile south of Egypt for nearly 3,000 years. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. At its peak Kushite pharaohs conquered all of Egypt as the 25th Dynasty (~744–656 BCE). The pyramids of Meroe number over 200 — more than all of Egypt's. The Meroitic script (developed ~300 BCE) remains only partially deciphered. Kush controlled gold and trade routes connecting sub-Saharan Africa to the Mediterranean world.","up":4801,"dn":201},
  {"id":46,"n":"Aksumite Empire","s":100,"e":940,"r":"Ethiopia / Horn of Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of the great powers of late antiquity alongside Rome, Persia and China. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) inscriptions + coins. Controlled the Red Sea trade route. Adopted Christianity under King Ezana ~330 CE — before most of Europe. The towering granite obelisks of Aksum reach 33 metres. Ethiopian Christian tradition holds Aksum is home to the Ark of the Covenant, kept at the Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion.","up":5201,"dn":312},
  {"id":47,"n":"Mali Empire","s":1235,"e":1600,"r":"West Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The wealthiest empire in medieval history. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) manuscripts from Timbuktu. Mansa Musa I controlled over half the world's gold and salt supply. His 1324 pilgrimage to Mecca with 60,000 attendants and 12,000 gold-carrying slaves flooded Mediterranean markets, causing inflation for a decade. Timbuktu's University of Sankore housed 25,000 students. Hundreds of thousands of medieval manuscripts survive.","up":6102,"dn":289},
  {"id":48,"n":"Swahili Coast City-States","s":800,"e":1500,"r":"Kenya / Tanzania Coast","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Sophisticated Islamic trading city-states stretching 3,000km along East Africa's coast. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — extensive excavation at Kilwa Kisiwani, Mombasa, Malindi, Lamu. Ibn Battuta (~1331) called Kilwa one of the world's most beautiful cities. Song and Ming Dynasty porcelain recovered at every major site. Kilwa struck its own coins from the 11th century. The Swahili language, spoken by 200 million people, emerged from this Bantu-Arabic fusion culture.","up":5401,"dn":241},
  {"id":49,"n":"Green Sahara / Humid Period","s":-9000,"e":-3000,"r":"North Africa / Sahara","t":"debated","cont":"africa","d":"From ~9,000 to 3,000 BCE the Sahara was a verdant savannah supporting large human populations. Evidence type: (A) geological + archaeological: fossilized lake beds, ancient river channels, cattle bones, fish remains. The Tassili n'Ajjer plateau (Algeria) contains thousands of Neolithic cave paintings depicting hippos, crocodiles and swimmers in regions now receiving under 20mm rain annually. Climate transition back to desert ~5,500–3,000 BCE may have driven migration into the Nile Valley, catalysing Egyptian civilization. Mainstream climatology; civilizational implications remain debated.","up":4103,"dn":1203},
  {"id":50,"n":"Khmer Empire / Angkor","s":802,"e":1431,"r":"Cambodia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The greatest empire of Southeast Asia. LiDAR survey (Evans et al., 2016) revealed Angkor as the largest pre-industrial city on Earth — over 1,000 km², up to one million people. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + LiDAR. Angkor Wat (~1122 CE) is the world's largest religious structure, aligned to the spring equinox sunrise. Its elaborate hydraulic system managed monsoon water across the entire metropolitan region. Collapse linked to climate disruption of this system during prolonged drought in the 15th century.","up":8921,"dn":421},
  {"id":51,"n":"Jōmon Culture","s":-14000,"e":-300,"r":"Japan","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The world's oldest known pottery-producing culture — predating agriculture, challenging assumptions about craft complexity requiring farming. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Pottery dated to ~14,000 BCE. Hunter-gatherers maintaining settlements for over 14,000 years, producing cord-marked ceramics, clay figurines (dogū) and lacquerware. Their genetic legacy lives in modern Japanese and Ainu populations. One of the most compelling examples of complex sedentary society without agriculture.","up":3812,"dn":198},
  {"id":52,"n":"Caral / Norte Chico","s":-3000,"e":-1800,"r":"Coastal Peru","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The oldest confirmed civilization in the Americas — contemporaneous with Egypt's Old Kingdom and Sumerian Ur, yet virtually unknown in popular history. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — excavation by Ruth Shady Solís; UNESCO World Heritage Site 2009. Massive platform mounds, sunken plazas and planned urban complexes across 30 sites — without pottery and without a writing system. Among the earliest known quipu (knotted string records). No weapons, fortifications or conflict imagery found anywhere.","up":5102,"dn":231},
  {"id":53,"n":"Teotihuacan","s":-100,"e":550,"r":"Central Mexico","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The largest city in pre-Columbian Americas — at its peak (~450 CE) housing 125,000–200,000 people, sixth largest city on Earth. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Pyramid of the Sun (third largest pyramid by volume), Pyramid of the Moon and the Avenue of the Dead align astronomically. Who built it remains unknown — the city predates the Aztecs by nearly 1,000 years. A 2017 tunnel discovery beneath the Temple of the Feathered Serpent, filled with mercury and pyrite mirrors, suggests cosmological ritual of extraordinary sophistication.","up":7821,"dn":412},
  {"id":54,"n":"Tiwanaku / Puma Punku","s":-500,"e":1000,"r":"Bolivia / Andes","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"A pre-Inca ceremonial centre at 3,850 metres altitude near Lake Titicaca. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Tiwanaku itself is confirmed as a major Andean centre. Puma Punku's H-shaped andesite and sandstone blocks — fitted with sub-millimetre precision, featuring straight channels and drill holes — are the debated element. Alternative researchers including Hancock cite the stonework as evidence of lost high technology. Mainstream archaeology attributes it to Tiwanaku craftsmen using stone and bronze tools. The technique remains genuinely unresolved.","up":6203,"dn":2891,"dateTheories":[{"s":-500,"e":1000,"label":"Mainstream — Tiwanaku Culture 500 BCE–1000 CE","source":"Kolata, The Tiwanaku (1993); Janusek, Ancient Tiwanaku (2008)","researcher":null,"up":4821,"dn":891},{"s":-15000,"e":-10000,"label":"Posnansky — Pre-Flood Astronomical Dating","source":"Arthur Posnansky, Tiahuanacu: The Cradle of American Man (1945)","researcher":"Arthur Posnansky","up":2103,"dn":2891},{"s":-10000,"e":-5000,"label":"Hancock — Pre-YD Lost Civilisation Construction","source":"Graham Hancock, Fingerprints of the Gods (1995)","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":1891,"dn":2103}]},
  {"id":56,"n":"Cahokia / Mississippian","s":600,"e":1400,"r":"North America (Illinois)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The largest pre-Columbian city north of Mexico — almost entirely absent from mainstream American history education. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. At its peak (~1050–1150 CE), Cahokia housed 10,000–20,000 people near modern St Louis — larger than contemporary London. Monks Mound contains more earth by volume than the Great Pyramid of Giza. A wooden Woodhenge tracked solstices and equinoxes. Collapsed around 1300 CE from flooding, disease or political fragmentation.","up":4201,"dn":312},
  {"id":57,"n":"Rapa Nui / Easter Island","s":300,"e":1722,"r":"Pacific Ocean","t":"debated","cont":"pacific","d":"One of Earth's most isolated inhabited islands, home to a civilization that carved and erected 900 basalt moai weighing up to 80 tonnes. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. How statues were transported remains debated — experimental archaeology by Carl Lipo demonstrated rocking locomotion was viable. The civilization's apparent collapse before European contact (1722) was long attributed to self-inflicted ecocide; this is now contested, with introduced rats, European disease and slave raids proposed as primary drivers.","up":5812,"dn":1203},
  {"id":58,"n":"Akkadian Empire","s":-2334,"e":-2154,"r":"Mesopotamia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The world's first empire — the first polity to unite multiple city-states under centralized rule. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) cuneiform. Founded by Sargon of Akkad (~2334 BCE). Akkadian language became the Near East lingua franca for 2,000 years. Its sudden collapse ~2154 BCE was likely triggered by a century-long drought — one of the earliest documented cases of climate-induced civilizational collapse, confirmed by dust records from the Gulf of Oman.","up":5201,"dn":289},
  {"id":59,"n":"Hittite Empire","s":-1650,"e":-1178,"r":"Anatolia / Turkey","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Dominant power of Bronze Age Anatolia, rival to Egypt. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) cuneiform — thousands of tablets at Hattusa in eight languages. Among the first to master iron smelting. The Battle of Kadesh (~1274 BCE) produced the world's oldest surviving peace treaty — a copy hangs in the UN today. Collapsed abruptly ~1178 BCE in the Bronze Age Collapse; its capital burned, its language lost for 3,000 years until deciphered in 1915.","up":4891,"dn":241},
  {"id":60,"n":"Nabataean Kingdom / Petra","s":-400,"e":106,"r":"Jordan / Arabia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Masters of water in the desert — the Nabataeans built the ancient world's most sophisticated water harvesting system, enabling cities in extreme aridity. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Their capital Petra, carved into rose-red sandstone cliffs, was the hub of the incense and spice trade. The Treasury (Al-Khazneh) is among the ancient world's most dramatic achievements. Nabataean script is the direct ancestor of the Arabic alphabet. Annexed by Rome in 106 CE.","up":5102,"dn":198},
  {"id":61,"n":"Babylonian Empire","s":-1894,"e":-539,"r":"Mesopotamia / Iraq","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Home to the Hanging Gardens, the Tower of Babel (almost certainly the Etemenanki ziggurat) and the Code of Hammurabi. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) cuneiform. Babylon dominated the Near East twice — under Hammurabi (~1792 BCE) and Nebuchadnezzar II (~605 BCE), who destroyed Solomon's Temple and exiled the Jews (the Babylonian Captivity). The Ishtar Gate — reconstructed in Berlin's Pergamon Museum — gives a sense of its legendary scale. Conquered by Cyrus the Great in 539 BCE.","up":9201,"dn":421},
  {"id":62,"n":"Sassanid Persian Empire","s":224,"e":651,"r":"Iran / Middle East","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The last great Persian empire before the Islamic conquest, and Rome's most formidable rival for four centuries. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) inscriptions. Consciously revived Achaemenid Persian culture and Zoroastrian religion as state identity. Capital Ctesiphon contained the world's largest single-span brick arch. The exhausting Sassanid-Byzantine Wars (602–628 CE) left both empires unable to resist the Arab Muslim armies that defeated both within a decade.","up":4201,"dn":289},
  {"id":63,"n":"Elamite Civilization","s":-3200,"e":-539,"r":"Iran / Khuzestan","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"One of the earliest civilizations in the world, contemporary with Sumer and its persistent rival for 2,500 years. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + Proto-Elamite script (undeciphered) + cuneiform. Centred on Susa (modern Shush, Iran). The Elamites sacked Ur and carried off Hammurabi's law stele (now in the Louvre). Proto-Elamite (~3200–2900 BCE) is one of the world's oldest writing systems — and remains entirely undeciphered, one of archaeology's great outstanding puzzles.","up":3102,"dn":198},
  {"id":64,"n":"Parthian Empire","s":-247,"e":224,"r":"Iran / Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The empire that checked Roman expansion eastward for nearly five centuries. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) coins. Defeated and killed Crassus at Carrhae (53 BCE) — one of Rome's worst defeats — capturing the legionary eagles. Their cataphract cavalry (fully armoured horse and rider) revolutionized warfare. Remarkably little is known internally as they left few records in their own language; most accounts come from Roman and Chinese sources.","up":3201,"dn":212},
  {"id":65,"n":"Songhai Empire","s":1464,"e":1591,"r":"West Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"West Africa's largest empire — stretching 2,000km along the Niger River. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) Arabic manuscripts from Timbuktu. Under Askia Muhammad (~1493–1528), Timbuktu's scholars produced hundreds of thousands of manuscripts on theology, astronomy, mathematics and history. Ended at the Battle of Tondibi (1591) when a Moroccan army equipped with firearms crossed the Sahara — demonstrating how rapidly firearms technology could overturn established military power.","up":4102,"dn":231},
  {"id":66,"n":"Kingdom of Benin","s":1180,"e":1897,"r":"Nigeria / West Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of pre-colonial Africa's most sophisticated kingdoms, renowned for extraordinary bronze and ivory artworks. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + oral tradition. The Benin Bronzes — hundreds of plaques and sculptures — depict history, rulers and ceremonies with remarkable precision. Portuguese traders (1485) described Benin City as comparable to Lisbon. Destroyed by a British punitive expedition in 1897; the looted bronze collection is the subject of ongoing repatriation disputes.","up":5201,"dn":312},
  {"id":67,"n":"Nok Culture","s":-1500,"e":500,"r":"Nigeria / West Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Sub-Saharan Africa's earliest known iron-smelting culture and producer of the continent's oldest figurative terracotta sculptures. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Mastered iron-smelting by at least 500 BCE, possibly independently of Mediterranean Iron Age development. Hollow terracotta figures — some life-sized, with distinctive perforated eyes — suggest complex religious and social life. Possibly ancestral to later Nigerian kingdoms including Benin. Language, political organisation and ultimate fate are all unrecorded.","up":3102,"dn":189},
  {"id":68,"n":"Garamantian Civilization","s":-500,"e":700,"r":"Libya / Sahara","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"A sophisticated desert civilization that mastered water engineering in one of Earth's most hostile environments. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — extensive excavation in the Fezzan region of Libya. The Garamantes constructed over 3,500km of foggara (underground aqueducts) tapping fossil water aquifers to irrigate fields and sustain cities. Controlled trans-Saharan trade routes. Declined as fossil water supplies were exhausted — an ancient warning about unsustainable resource use.","up":2891,"dn":201},
  {"id":69,"n":"Etruscan Civilization","s":-800,"e":-90,"r":"Italy / Tuscany","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The civilization that preceded Rome and shaped it profoundly — yet remains one of antiquity's most enigmatic peoples. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) Etruscan script (partially deciphered). The Etruscans gave Rome its first monumental architecture, gladiatorial games, the toga, the fasces and possibly its name. Their language is a complete isolate — related to no other known language. Elaborate painted tombs at Tarquinia depict feasting, music and sport. Gradually absorbed by Rome between 300 and 90 BCE.","up":4891,"dn":231},
  {"id":70,"n":"Celtic / La Tène Culture","s":-800,"e":50,"r":"Europe (widespread)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Not a single empire but related cultures sharing language, art and religion across Europe from Britain to Anatolia. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) Greek and Roman accounts. Celtic knotwork and zoomorphic art is one of antiquity's most distinctive traditions. The Druids were oral scholars memorizing vast amounts of law, astronomy and history — leaving deliberately no written record. Celtic languages survive today in Welsh, Irish, Scottish Gaelic, Breton and Cornish.","up":6102,"dn":312},
  {"id":71,"n":"Srivijaya Empire","s":650,"e":1377,"r":"Sumatra / Maritime SE Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The dominant maritime empire of Southeast Asia for seven centuries — a Buddhist thalassocracy controlling the Strait of Malacca and trade between India and China. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) Chinese Tang Dynasty records + Sanskrit inscriptions. Its capital Palembang was a centre of Mahayana Buddhist scholarship — the monk Yijing reported 1,000 Buddhist monks in residence. No major temples found, suggesting wooden architecture consumed by jungle. Declined after Chola Indian raids (1025 CE).","up":3201,"dn":198},
  {"id":72,"n":"Champa Kingdom","s":192,"e":1832,"r":"Vietnam (Central/South)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"A Hindu-Buddhist maritime kingdom flourishing along central and southern Vietnam for over 1,600 years. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — the My Son sanctuary (UNESCO World Heritage) preserves 70+ temple towers. Master sailors whose ports connected China, India and island Southeast Asia. Their distinctive red-brick tower architecture influenced temple-building across the region. Gradually absorbed by the expanding Vietnamese Đại Việt kingdom from the north, finally completed in 1832. The Cham people survive as an ethnic minority in Vietnam and Cambodia.","up":2891,"dn":189},
  {"id":73,"n":"Ancestral Puebloans","s":100,"e":1300,"r":"American Southwest","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Builders of the most sophisticated architecture in pre-Columbian North America — cliff dwellings, multi-storey complexes and astronomical observatories without metal tools, wheels or pack animals. Evidence type: (A) archaeological. Chaco Canyon (New Mexico) was a ceremonial centre connected by arrow-straight roads up to 9 metres wide across a 650km regional network. Pueblo Bonito has 800 rooms aligned to solstice and equinox sunrises. Mesa Verde cliff dwellings are among the Americas' most dramatic achievements. Abandoned ~1300 CE — prolonged drought is the primary proposed cause.","up":4891,"dn":289},
  {"id":74,"n":"Moche Culture","s":100,"e":800,"r":"Coastal Peru","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"One of the most artistically sophisticated pre-Columbian cultures — known for portrait ceramics of such individual specificity they are believed to be true likenesses of real people. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — excavation at the Huaca del Sol/Luna pyramids, and the Lord of Sipán royal tomb (1987), one of the richest intact ancient burials in the Americas. Their iconography depicts ritual combat, sacrifice and ceremony with unusual detail. Decline ~600–800 CE coincides with catastrophic El Niño flooding followed by drought.","up":3891,"dn":198},
  {"id":75,"n":"Chavín de Huántar","s":-900,"e":-200,"r":"Peruvian Andes","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The foundation upon which all later Andean civilizations were built — the earliest major ceremonial complex of the Andes. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — UNESCO World Heritage Site. Built at 3,177 metres altitude, featuring stone galleries, plazas and temples. The Lanzón — a 4.5-metre fanged granite monolith — stands at the complex's heart. Acoustic archaeology reveals the galleries were designed to disorient — likely for ritual initiation possibly involving San Pedro cactus.","up":3102,"dn":212},
  {"id":76,"n":"Poverty Point Culture","s":-1730,"e":-700,"r":"Louisiana, North America","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"A pre-Columbian civilization that constructed one of North America's largest earthwork complexes nearly a thousand years before Cahokia. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — UNESCO World Heritage Site 2014. Six concentric C-shaped earthen ridges and five mounds constructed ~1700 BCE — contemporaneous with Egypt's New Kingdom. Traded obsidian from the Rockies, copper from the Great Lakes and galena from Missouri — a continent-wide exchange network of astonishing range. Language, ethnicity and reason for abandonment are all unknown.","up":2891,"dn":189},
  {"id":77,"n":"Lapita Culture","s":-1600,"e":-500,"r":"Pacific — Melanesia to Polynesia","t":"confirmed","cont":"pacific","d":"The ancestral culture of all Polynesian peoples — origin of the greatest ocean navigators in human history. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — distinctive dentate-stamped pottery across a 5,500km Pacific arc. Originating in the Bismarck Archipelago (~1600 BCE), the Lapita people colonised virtually every habitable Pacific island navigating by stars, swells, wind, birds and clouds without instruments, in double-hulled canoes. Their descendants include the Māori, Hawaiian, Samoan, Tongan and Tahitian peoples.","up":4102,"dn":198},
  {"id":78,"n":"Scythian / Saka Culture","s":-900,"e":200,"r":"Eurasian Steppe","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The dominant culture of the Eurasian steppe for a thousand years — nomadic horse warriors whose territory stretched from Ukraine to China. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — spectacular kurgan (burial mound) excavations across Russia, Ukraine and Kazakhstan. Masters of a distinctive animal-style gold art. Herodotus describes their burial practices in detail — confirmed by excavation. Scythian women sometimes fought as warriors, possibly inspiring the Greek Amazons legend. Cannabis ritual steam bathing is also archaeologically confirmed.","up":4201,"dn":231},
  {"id":79,"n":"Land of Punt","s":-2500,"e":-1000,"r":"East Africa / Arabia (Debated)","t":"debated","cont":"africa","stub":true,"d":"Ancient Egypt's 'Land of Punt' — source of gold, ebony, myrrh and exotic animals — is referenced from the 5th Dynasty onward, including in Queen Hatshepsut's temple reliefs. Its precise location is one of Egyptology's greatest unresolved questions: Somalia, Eritrea, Yemen and Zimbabwe have all been proposed. Evidence: (B) Egyptian texts and temple imagery only. No confirmed Punt site has ever been excavated.","up":1891,"dn":812},
  {"id":80,"n":"Hopewell Tradition","s":-200,"e":500,"r":"Eastern North America","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","stub":true,"d":"A widespread cultural and trade network across eastern North America exchanging obsidian from Yellowstone, copper from the Great Lakes, mica from the Appalachians and shark teeth from Florida. Centred on monumental Ohio earthwork complexes. Not a single empire but a shared set of burial practices, artistic styles and exchange networks spanning thousands of kilometres. Why the network collapsed around 500 CE is not understood. Detailed entry needed — community contribution invited.","up":2103,"dn":198},
  {"id":81,"n":"Pre-Clovis Americans","s":-20000,"e":-13000,"r":"Americas (Debated)","t":"debated","cont":"americas","stub":true,"d":"Evidence accumulating that humans reached the Americas thousands of years before the Clovis culture (~13,000 BCE). Sites including Monte Verde (Chile, ~14,500 BCE), Chiquihuite Cave (Mexico, ~26,000 BCE, contested) and White Sands (New Mexico, ~21,000–23,000 BCE) suggest earlier arrivals. How they came — coastal route, trans-Pacific contact, or multiple waves — is actively debated. This is a stub entry awaiting fuller community analysis.","up":3102,"dn":1891},
  {"id":82,"n":"Cucuteni-Trypillia Culture","s":-5500,"e":-2750,"r":"Ukraine / Romania / Moldova","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","stub":true,"d":"One of the largest Neolithic cultures in Europe — some settlements reached 15,000 people, among the largest communities on Earth at that time. Known for distinctive painted pottery and the mysterious practice of deliberately burning their own villages every 60–80 years. Their relationship to later Indo-European migrations is debated. Language, social structure and reasons for village burning are all unresolved. Community contribution invited.","up":1891,"dn":189},
  {"id":83,"n":"Sanxingdui Culture","s":-2000,"e":-1000,"r":"Sichuan, China","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","stub":true,"d":"A Bronze Age culture in Sichuan producing extraordinary bronze masks, trees and standing figures unlike anything in the ancient world — including figures nearly 3 metres tall and enigmatic protruding-eye masks. Completely unknown until discovered by chance in 1986. Has no known connection to contemporaneous Yellow River civilizations. Ongoing excavation (new pit opened 2021) continues to reveal extraordinary objects. Full entry needed — experts in Chinese archaeology invited to contribute.","up":4201,"dn":312},
  {"id":84,"n":"Göbekli Tepe Builders","s":-9500,"e":-7500,"r":"Anatolia / Turkey","t":"debated","cont":"asia","stub":true,"d":"Who built Göbekli Tepe — the world's oldest megalithic complex — remains unknown. The site predates agriculture by 1,000+ years. Mainstream archaeology attributes construction to organised hunter-gatherers. Graham Hancock and Matthew LaCroix argue the sophistication implies either more advanced social organisation than assumed, or survivors of an earlier civilization. One of archaeology's most important open questions. Expert contribution from archaeologists and alternative researchers is actively invited.","up":5102,"dn":1203},
  {"id":85,"n":"Minoan Linear A","s":-2500,"e":-1450,"r":"Crete / Aegean","t":"debated","cont":"europe","stub":true,"d":"The undeciphered writing system of Minoan Crete — one of archaeology's great outstanding puzzles. Linear A was the Minoan primary script and ancestor of Linear B (deciphered in 1952 as early Greek). Despite Linear B's decipherment informing the script's structure, Linear A has not been decoded. The underlying Minoan language appears unrelated to any known language family. If deciphered it would open a direct window into Europe's first civilization. Epigraphers and linguists invited to contribute.","up":3891,"dn":312},
  {"id":86,"n":"Yamnaya / Proto-Indo-European Horizon","s":-3500,"e":-2000,"r":"Eurasian Steppe (Pontic-Caspian)","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The proposed ancestral culture behind the most widespread language family on Earth — spoken today by over 3 billion people across Europe, Iran, India and the Americas. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — kurgan (burial mound) culture of the Pontic-Caspian steppe; ancient DNA studies confirming massive population movements ~3000–2500 BCE; (C) comparative linguistic reconstruction of Proto-Indo-European vocabulary. The Yamnaya people, semi-nomadic pastoralists with wheeled wagons and domesticated horses, expanded explosively in all directions. Their descendants include Greeks, Romans, Celts, Persians, Vikings, Slavs, Sanskrit speakers and most of modern Europe and South Asia. Two competing hypotheses exist for the original homeland: the steppe (Kurgan hypothesis, Gimbutas) and Anatolia (Renfrew). Ancient DNA evidence now strongly favours the steppe origin. What drove the expansion — disease, technology, or social organisation — is debated. Matthew LaCroix and others argue the Proto-Indo-European mythological corpus (the 'Myth of the Storm God slaying the Dragon') encodes astronomical and cosmological knowledge from a much earlier period.","up":6102,"dn":891},
  {"id":87,"n":"Dravidian Civilization / Tamil Sangam","s":-300,"e":300,"r":"South India / Sri Lanka","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The oldest surviving literary tradition of South Asia and the cultural expression of the Dravidian language family — spoken by 250 million people today and almost certainly the linguistic tradition of the pre-Aryan Indus Valley civilization. Evidence type: (A) archaeological + (B) Tamil Sangam texts (~300 BCE–300 CE), among the oldest surviving secular literature in any language. The three Tamil Sangam academies produced over 2,000 poems covering love, war, ethics and nature with a sophistication comparable to classical Greek literature. Dravidian languages (Tamil, Telugu, Kannada, Malayalam) show no relation to Indo-European or any other language family — they are either a linguistic isolate family or, controversially, related to the undeciphered Indus Valley script. If the Indus script is ever deciphered as Proto-Dravidian, it would push the written Dravidian tradition back to 3300 BCE. The survival of Tamil as a living classical language for 2,000+ years is itself a civilizational achievement.","up":4891,"dn":312},
  {"id":88,"n":"Epi-Olmec / Isthmian Script","s":-300,"e":500,"r":"Gulf Coast Mexico / Mesoamerica","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Possibly the oldest indigenous writing system of the Americas — predating the deciphered Maya script — yet remaining almost entirely undeciphered. Evidence type: (A) archaeological — the Cascajal Block (~900 BCE, if confirmed as writing) and the La Mojarra Stele (~156 CE) contain the most substantial Epi-Olmec texts. The Cascajal Block, if genuine, would make Olmec the oldest writing tradition in the Americas. The Isthmian/Epi-Olmec script contains ~150 distinct signs, suggesting a logosyllabic system similar to Mayan — but the underlying language and most readings remain unknown. John Justeson and Terrence Kaufman proposed a partial decipherment in 1993, reading some passages as a Proto-Zoquean language, but consensus has not been reached. Its relationship to the Olmec civilization (the 'mother culture' of Mesoamerica) and to Maya writing is unresolved. If deciphered, it would transform understanding of early Mesoamerican intellectual history.","up":2891,"dn":1203},
  {"id":89,"n":"Ancient Israel / Levant","s":-1200,"e":-586,"r":"Levant / Middle East","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Iron Age kingdoms of Israel and Judah, emerging from the Late Bronze Age collapse. Source of the Hebrew Bible — one of the most influential literary and religious texts in human history. The destruction of the First Temple by Nebuchadnezzar II in 586 BCE and the Babylonian exile transformed a territorial religion into a portable, text-centred one — the model for all subsequent Abrahamic traditions. The Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered 1947–1956, preserve texts 1,000 years older than any previously known Hebrew manuscripts.","up":8201,"dn":512},
  {"id":90,"n":"Aramaic Civilization","s":-1200,"e":700,"r":"Levant / Syria / Mesopotamia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Arameans gave the ancient world its most durable lingua franca. Aramaic became the administrative language of the Achaemenid Persian Empire and the everyday spoken language of Jesus of Nazareth. It spread across the Near East for over a thousand years. Modern Aramaic dialects survive among small communities in Syria, Iraq, and diaspora communities. The Nabataean branch of Aramaic directly evolved into the Arabic alphabet. One of the most consequential languages in human history.","up":3201,"dn":198},
  {"id":91,"n":"Hawaiian Chiefdom Confederacy","s":300,"e":1810,"r":"Hawaiian Islands, Pacific","t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"The Hawaiian archipelago was colonised by Polynesian navigators around 300–600 CE, developing one of the Pacific's most stratified and elaborate chiefdom societies. The kapu system regulated every social interaction. Monumental heiau temples, massive fishponds, and intensive irrigation networks demonstrate extraordinary organisational capacity. Unified under Kamehameha I by 1810, the Kingdom of Hawaii persisted until American annexation in 1898.","up":740,"dn":27},
  {"id":92,"n":"Tongan Empire","s":950,"e":1865,"r":"Tonga, Western Polynesia","t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"The Tu'i Tonga Empire was the most extensive maritime polity in Polynesian history, exercising tribute and influence across 40+ island groups from Hawaii to Tikopia. The Tu'i Tonga lineage claimed divine ancestry and maintained a sacred hierarchy unlike any other Polynesian society. The great stone trilithon Ha'amonga 'a Maui — three massive coral limestone blocks — may encode astronomical alignments. Tongan trade and cultural influence shaped the entire western Pacific.","up":520,"dn":31},
  {"id":93,"n":"Nan Madol — Saudeleur Dynasty","s":1100,"e":1628,"r":"Pohnpei, Micronesia","t":"debated","cont":"oceania","d":"Nan Madol is one of the most extraordinary and least-known architectural achievements on Earth — a city built entirely on artificial islets in a lagoon, constructed from interlocking basalt columns weighing up to 50 tonnes each, transported by unknown means. The Saudeleur dynasty ruled Pohnpei from this ceremonial capital. How the basalt logs were transported across open ocean without metal tools remains unexplained. Graham Hancock covers Nan Madol in Ancient Apocalypse. UNESCO World Heritage Site 2016.","up":2840,"dn":380,"dateTheories":[{"s":1100,"e":1628,"label":"Mainstream — Saudeleur Dynasty construction 1100–1628 CE","source":"Rainbird, The Archaeology of Micronesia (2004)","researcher":null,"up":1240,"dn":180},{"s":-1000,"e":500,"label":"Alternative — earlier construction phases indicated by oral tradition","source":"Hancock, Ancient Apocalypse (2022)","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":980,"dn":640}]},
  {"id":94,"n":"Kushan Empire","s":-30,"e":375,"r":"Central Asia / South Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kushan Empire bridged four great civilisations — China, India, Persia, and Rome — on the Silk Road. At its peak under Kanishka I (c.127 CE), it stretched from the Aral Sea to central India. A major patron of Mahayana Buddhism, the Kushans spread Buddhist art and philosophy eastward into China. The Gandharan artistic tradition — which depicts the Buddha in Hellenistic style — is one of the most remarkable cultural fusions in history.","up":2891,"dn":189},
  {"id":95,"n":"Sogdian Civilization","s":-600,"e":1000,"r":"Transoxiana (Uzbekistan/Tajikistan)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Sogdians were the dominant merchants of the ancient Silk Road for over a millennium. From city-states around Samarkand and Bukhara, they maintained trading colonies across Central Asia and China. The Sogdian letters — found in a Chinese watchtower, dated ~313 CE — are the oldest private correspondence from Central Asia. Sogdian script became the ancestor of Uyghur, Mongolian, and Manchu writing. Dissolved by the Arab conquest of the 8th century.","up":860,"dn":42},
  {"id":96,"n":"Khazar Khaganate","s":650,"e":1048,"r":"Pontic-Caspian Steppe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Khazar Khaganate dominated the steppe corridor north of the Caucasus for four centuries, serving as a crucial buffer between the expanding Islamic Caliphate and Christian Byzantium. Remarkably, the Khazar ruling elite converted to Judaism in the 8th or 9th century — the only major medieval state conversion to Judaism. Their capital Atil on the Volga Delta was a cosmopolitan trading hub destroyed by Sviatoslav of Kiev in 968 CE.","up":780,"dn":140,"dateTheories":[{"s":740,"e":840,"label":"Koestler — argues Khazar conversion seeded Ashkenazi Jewish ancestry","source":"The Thirteenth Tribe (1976)","researcher":"Arthur Koestler","up":1240,"dn":2180}]},
  {"id":97,"n":"Timurid Empire","s":1370,"e":1507,"r":"Central Asia / Persia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Founded by Timur (Tamerlane), the Timurid Empire was a paradox — built through catastrophic military conquest yet transformed into one of history's great centres of art, science and architecture. Samarkand's Registan complex, the Bibi-Khanym mosque, and the Gur-e-Amir mausoleum represent a pinnacle of Islamic architecture. Timur's descendant Babur founded the Mughal Empire. Timurid scholars produced advances in astronomy, mathematics and medicine that influenced the European Renaissance.","up":3102,"dn":198},
  {"id":98,"n":"Cycladic Civilization","s":-3200,"e":-2000,"r":"Cyclades Islands, Aegean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"A remarkably sophisticated Early Bronze Age island culture producing the most enigmatic art of the ancient Aegean — stark white marble figurines with folded arms, simplified to near-abstraction, found across the Cyclades. Their meaning remains unknown: idols, grave goods, or ritual objects? The figurines influenced Picasso and modern sculpture. The Cycladic people were skilled navigators and traders, connecting Crete, mainland Greece, and Anatolia in the formative period before the Minoan rise.","up":2891,"dn":189},
  {"id":99,"n":"Carolingian Empire","s":768,"e":888,"r":"Western Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Charlemagne's unification of most of Western Europe was the first serious attempt to reconstruct Roman imperial authority in the West. The Carolingian Renaissance — systematic copying of Latin manuscripts, standardised script (Carolingian minuscule), cathedral schools — preserved classical knowledge through the early medieval period. The political division of the empire among Charlemagne's grandsons in 843 CE directly created the ancestral territories of modern France, Germany, and the Low Countries.","up":4201,"dn":231},
  {"id":100,"n":"Republic of Venice","s":697,"e":1797,"r":"Italy / Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"La Serenissima — the Most Serene Republic — endured for over 1,100 years, the longest-lived republic in history. Venice was the pre-eminent commercial power of the medieval Mediterranean, controlling the spice trade and producing extraordinary art (Titian, Tintoretto, Bellini). Its constitution and system of checks and balances influenced the framers of the American republic. Napoleon ended it without a battle in 1797.","up":5891,"dn":289},
  {"id":101,"n":"Kievan Rus","s":882,"e":1240,"r":"Ukraine / Eastern Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The founding state of Russian, Ukrainian, and Belarusian civilisation, centred on Kyiv. Founded by Varangian (Viking) Rurik dynasty. The conversion of Vladimir the Great to Orthodox Christianity in 988 CE defined Eastern European cultural identity for a millennium. The Primary Chronicle (Nestor, ~1113 CE) is the foundational historical text of the Eastern Slavs. Destroyed by the Mongol invasion of 1237–1242.","up":3891,"dn":231},
  {"id":102,"n":"Zapotec Civilization","s":-700,"e":700,"r":"Oaxaca, Mexico","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Zapotecs of Monte Albán built the first city in Mesoamerica and developed one of the region's earliest writing systems. Monte Albán was constructed on a levelled mountaintop, commanding views in all directions — a colossal engineering project. The Zapotec calendar and astronomical observatory influenced subsequent Mesoamerican cultures. They were the first Mesoamericans to use a true writing system with phonetic elements, predating Maya writing.","up":2891,"dn":189,"dateTheories":[{"s":-700,"e":700,"label":"Mainstream — Monte Albán occupation 700 BCE–700 CE","source":"Marcus & Flannery, Zapotec Civilization (1996)","researcher":null,"up":2100,"dn":120}]},
  {"id":103,"n":"Toltec Empire","s":900,"e":1150,"r":"Central Mexico (Tula)","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"The Toltec were the legendary predecessors of the Aztecs, who regarded them with almost mythological reverence. Their capital Tula (Tollan) in Hidalgo, Mexico, was a major centre of 60,000+ people. The warrior-columns and chacmool sculptures at Tula have near-identical counterparts at Chichen Itza in the Yucatan — evidence of direct contact, conquest, or cultural diffusion across 1,500km remains debated. Quetzalcoatl — the Feathered Serpent — is a Toltec deity absorbed by the Aztecs.","up":2103,"dn":891,"dateTheories":[{"s":900,"e":1150,"label":"Mainstream — Toltec flourishing at Tula 900–1150 CE","source":"Davies, The Toltecs (1977)","researcher":null,"up":1800,"dn":200}]},
  {"id":104,"n":"Taíno Civilization","s":250,"e":1600,"r":"Caribbean (Hispaniola/Cuba/PR)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Taíno were the first people Columbus encountered in 1492 — a sophisticated Arawakan-speaking culture with chiefdom organisation, zemí (spirit) religion, ball courts, and complex agriculture. Their population, estimated at 250,000–1 million on Hispaniola alone, was virtually annihilated within 50 years through disease, slavery, and war — one of the most catastrophic demographic collapses in history. Taíno words including hammock, canoe, barbecue, hurricane, and tobacco passed directly into English.","up":3201,"dn":198},
  {"id":105,"n":"Mississippian Culture","s":800,"e":1600,"r":"Eastern North America","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The most complex pre-Columbian society north of Mexico, building flat-topped platform mounds across the eastern half of North America. Cahokia near modern St Louis was its largest centre — at its peak around 1100 CE it may have housed 20,000 people, larger than contemporary London. Maize agriculture, long-distance trade networks, elaborate burial practices, and theocratic leadership characterised the culture. It had largely declined before European contact, possibly due to climate deterioration.","up":1050,"dn":48,"dateTheories":[{"s":600,"e":800,"label":"Pauketat — Emergent Mississippian phase extends origins by two centuries","source":"Cahokia: Ancient America's Great City (2009)","researcher":"Timothy Pauketat","up":420,"dn":130}]},
  {"id":106,"n":"Kingdom of Kongo","s":1390,"e":1914,"r":"Central Africa (Congo/Angola)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of the largest and most sophisticated kingdoms in pre-colonial Africa, the Kingdom of Kongo at its peak controlled territory across modern DRC, Angola, Republic of Congo, and Gabon. A centralised monarchy with a complex provincial administration. The Kongo nobility adopted Christianity voluntarily after Portuguese contact in 1483 — King Afonso I wrote letters to the King of Portugal protesting the slave trade as early as 1526. Its administrative sophistication influenced later Central African political structures.","up":3201,"dn":189},
  {"id":107,"n":"Ethiopian Empire (Solomonic)","s":1270,"e":1974,"r":"Horn of Africa / Ethiopia","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Solomonic Dynasty claimed descent from King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba — a lineage affirmed in the Kebra Nagast ('Glory of Kings'). The dynasty endured for 700 years, making it one of the world's longest-ruling royal houses. Ethiopian Orthodox Christianity — with its unique canon including books not found in other Bibles — preserved a remarkable literary and artistic tradition. Emperor Haile Selassie I, last of the dynasty, became a messianic figure in the Rastafari movement.","up":4201,"dn":231},
  {"id":108,"n":"Kingdom of Dahomey","s":1600,"e":1904,"r":"West Africa (modern Benin)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Dahomey was one of the most powerful West African kingdoms of the 17th–19th centuries, known for its highly disciplined military — including the Agojie, an all-female warrior corps of 6,000 who served as the king's elite guard. The kingdom was deeply involved in the Atlantic slave trade, raiding neighbouring peoples and selling captives to European traders. The Agojie (inspiration for the film The Woman King) were among the most feared fighters in West Africa.","up":3891,"dn":241},
  {"id":109,"n":"Nubian Christian Kingdoms","s":350,"e":1504,"r":"Nubia / Sudan","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Following the decline of Meroe, the Nile Valley between Egypt and Ethiopia was divided into three Christian kingdoms — Nobatia, Makuria, and Alodia — which collectively resisted Islamic expansion for over seven centuries, longer than any other region. Their art, preserved in remarkable painted church murals, shows a unique fusion of Byzantine, Coptic, and indigenous Nubian traditions. The kingdoms' disappearance remains poorly documented — likely a combination of Mamluk pressure and internal transformation.","up":2201,"dn":189},
  {"id":110,"n":"Vijayanagara Empire","s":1336,"e":1646,"r":"South India (Karnataka)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The last great Hindu empire of South India, a bulwark against the Deccan Sultanates for over two centuries. At its peak under Krishnadevaraya (1509–1529), Vijayanagara was one of the world's largest cities with 500,000 inhabitants. The ruins at Hampi — 26 square kilometres of temples, palaces, and markets — are a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The empire's defeat at Talikota (1565) and the subsequent sack of Hampi ended South India's medieval Hindu political independence.","up":4201,"dn":198},
  {"id":111,"n":"Pagan Kingdom of Burma","s":849,"e":1297,"r":"Myanmar (Bagan region)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Pagan Kingdom unified the Irrawaddy Valley and adopted Theravada Buddhism as the state religion, triggering a remarkable temple-building programme. Over 10,000 Buddhist temples, stupas, and monasteries were constructed in the Bagan plain between the 11th and 13th centuries — over 2,000 survive today in various states of preservation. The kingdom's fall to Kublai Khan's Mongol forces in 1287 ended Burma's first great empire.","up":3201,"dn":198},
  {"id":112,"n":"Goryeo Dynasty","s":918,"e":1392,"r":"Korean Peninsula","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Goryeo Dynasty gave Korea its name and produced some of the finest achievements of East Asian civilisation. The Tripitaka Koreana — 81,258 wooden printing blocks of the entire Buddhist canon, carved with extraordinary precision — is the world's most complete and accurate collection of Buddhist texts, still preserved at Haeinsa Temple. Goryeo celadon ceramics are regarded as the pinnacle of East Asian pottery. The dynasty survived Mongol invasion through strategic vassalage.","up":3891,"dn":198},
  {"id":113,"n":"Chola Empire","s":-300,"e":1279,"r":"South India / Tamil Nadu","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"One of the longest-ruling dynasties in world history and the greatest naval empire of the medieval Indian Ocean. The Cholas launched a devastating naval raid on Srivijaya (1025 CE), the only recorded naval attack by an Indian empire on Southeast Asia. The Brihadeeswarar Temple at Thanjavur — built under Rajaraja I (~1010 CE) — remains structurally and architecturally extraordinary: its 66-metre tower and 80-tonne granite capstone were raised without modern machinery.","up":4891,"dn":231},
  {"id":114,"n":"Safavid Empire","s":1501,"e":1736,"r":"Iran / Persia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Safavids transformed Persia into a Shia Muslim state — the defining act of Iranian national identity. The conversion of a predominantly Sunni population to Shia Islam, accomplished in a single generation through a combination of persuasion and coercion, permanently shaped the Middle East's sectarian map. Isfahan under Shah Abbas I was one of the world's most beautiful cities. The Safavid court produced extraordinary carpet weaving, miniature painting, and architectural achievement.","up":4201,"dn":231},
  {"id":115,"n":"Mughal Empire","s":1526,"e":1857,"r":"South Asia / India","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Mughal Empire at its peak ruled 150 million people — a quarter of the world's population — and produced 25% of global GDP. The Taj Mahal, Red Fort, and Fatehpur Sikri represent a fusion of Persian, Central Asian, and Indian architectural traditions of extraordinary refinement. Under Akbar the Great, the empire practised remarkable religious pluralism. Its decline and British colonisation transformed the history of the modern world.","up":9201,"dn":421},
  {"id":116,"n":"Younger Dryas Boundary Culture","s":-12900,"e":-11500,"r":"Global (theorized — multiple sites)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"A theorized global culture destroyed or severely disrupted by the Younger Dryas cosmic impact event approximately 12,800 years ago. The physical evidence for the impact — platinum spikes, nanodiamonds, magnetic spherules, and the Carolina Bays — has been documented across four continents by Firestone et al. (PNAS, 2007) and substantially expanded since. Graham Hancock and Randall Carlson argue this event destroyed a predecessor civilisation, explaining global flood myths and anomalous pre-Holocene archaeological sites.","up":2840,"dn":1640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-12900,"e":-11500,"label":"Firestone et al. — YDB impact event, physical evidence across 4 continents","source":"Firestone et al., PNAS (2007); Journal of Geology (2018)","researcher":"Richard Firestone","up":1840,"dn":980},{"s":-13000,"e":-10800,"label":"Hancock / Carlson — Lost civilisation destroyed by YDB event","source":"Magicians of the Gods (2015); Kosmographia podcast (2019–2022)","researcher":"Graham Hancock / Randall Carlson","up":2140,"dn":1240}]},
  {"id":117,"n":"Pre-Flood Global Maritime Culture","s":-20000,"e":-10800,"r":"Global coastlines (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"A theorized network of maritime cultures occupying coastal zones now submerged under 120+ metres of post-glacial sea level rise. Graham Hancock's central thesis across Fingerprints of the Gods (1995), Underworld (2002), and America Before (2019) is that sophisticated coastal civilisations were destroyed and their evidence drowned. The 27 million square kilometres of land inundated between 20,000–7,000 BCE are almost entirely unexcavated. Mainstream archaeology acknowledges pre-Holocene coastal occupation but disputes civilisational complexity.","up":2640,"dn":1540},
  {"id":118,"n":"Younger Dryas Impact Sites","s":-12900,"e":-12800,"r":"North America / Northern hemisphere","t":"debated","cont":"global","d":"The physical impact sites of the proposed Younger Dryas cosmic event — most likely an airburst or impact swarm from a fragmenting comet. The Carolina Bays: 500,000+ elliptical depressions across the eastern seaboard, all oriented NW–SE, which Randall Carlson interprets as ballistic ejecta from a low-angle impact. The Channeled Scablands of Washington State: catastrophically carved by Missoula megafloods Carlson links to glacial ice sheet destabilisation. Platinum and iridium anomalies confirmed at the Younger Dryas Boundary across four continents.","up":1840,"dn":980},
  {"id":119,"n":"Richat Structure Culture","s":-12000,"e":-9000,"r":"Mauritania, West Africa","t":"theorized","cont":"africa","d":"The Richat Structure (Eye of the Sahara) — a 50km-wide circular geological formation in Mauritania — has been proposed by Jimmy Corsetti (Bright Insight YouTube channel) and others as the physical remains of Plato's Atlantis. The concentric ring structure matches Plato's description of alternating land and water rings. When the Green Sahara was at its peak (9,000–5,000 BCE), the region was fertile. The mainstream geological explanation is a symmetrical dome eroded over millions of years.","up":2140,"dn":2480,"dateTheories":[{"s":-9600,"e":-9000,"label":"Corsetti — Richat as Atlantis, occupied during Green Sahara humid period","source":"Bright Insight, YouTube (2018–present)","researcher":"Jimmy Corsetti","up":1840,"dn":2140}]},
  {"id":120,"n":"Anunnaki Gold Mining Culture","s":-450000,"e":-10000,"r":"Southern Africa (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"africa","d":"Michael Tellinger's synthesis of Zecharia Sitchin's Anunnaki hypothesis with the archaeological record of southern Africa: thousands of ancient stone circle ruins across Mpumalanga are interpreted as the remains of a vast gold-mining operation run by or for Anunnaki extraterrestrial beings. Sitchin argued in The 12th Planet (1976) that Homo sapiens was genetically engineered as a slave species to mine gold. Professional Assyriologists reject Sitchin's translations; professional archaeologists attribute the stone circles to indigenous Iron Age pastoralists.","up":1840,"dn":3240},
  {"id":121,"n":"Denisovan Civilisation","s":-300000,"e":-30000,"r":"Asia / Siberia (debated)","t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"The Denisovans — identified from DNA recovered from a finger bone in Siberia's Denisova Cave in 2010 — were a distinct archaic human species that interbred with both Neanderthals and modern humans. Andrew Collins argues in Göbekli Tepe: Genesis of the Gods (2014) and Denisovan Origins (2019) that Denisovans or Denisovan-modern human hybrids were the builders of early megalithic sites including Göbekli Tepe. Ancient DNA shows Denisovan ancestry peaks in Melanesia and Aboriginal Australians. Their full cognitive and cultural capacity is unknown.","up":1640,"dn":1240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-300000,"e":-30000,"label":"Collins — Denisovans as megalith builders, contributing to pre-agricultural complexity","source":"Denisovan Origins (2019); Göbekli Tepe: Genesis of the Gods (2014)","researcher":"Andrew Collins","up":980,"dn":840}]},
  {"id":122,"n":"Harappan Script Culture","s":-3300,"e":-1900,"r":"Indus Valley / South Asia","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Indus Valley Civilisation produced one of the ancient world's most widespread and most completely undeciphered writing systems. Over 4,000 inscribed objects carry the Indus script — yet not a single text has been definitively read. Proposed decipherments range from Proto-Dravidian to Proto-Indo-European to a purely logographic administrative system. If deciphered, it would open a direct window into the most populous Bronze Age civilisation. The script's disappearance around 1900 BCE with the civilisation's collapse adds to its mystery.","up":3891,"dn":312},
  {"id":123,"n":"Dogon Astronomical Tradition","s":-3000,"e":2000,"r":"Mali, West Africa","t":"debated","cont":"africa","d":"The Dogon people of Mali possess astronomical knowledge that Robert Temple argued in The Sirius Mystery (1976) could only have come from contact with an advanced civilisation or extraterrestrial beings: detailed knowledge of Sirius B (a white dwarf invisible to the naked eye) including its 50-year orbit and density. Temple proposed transmission from ancient Egypt or direct ET contact. Sceptics argue the specific Sirius B knowledge was transmitted by visiting Western astronomers in the 1930s. The debate remains unresolved.","up":2640,"dn":1840,"dateTheories":[{"s":-3000,"e":2000,"label":"Temple — ancient astronomical knowledge transmitted from unknown advanced source","source":"The Sirius Mystery (1976)","researcher":"Robert Temple","up":1540,"dn":1640}]},
  {"id":124,"n":"Indus-Saraswati River Culture","s":-7000,"e":-1500,"r":"Pakistan / NW India","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Saraswati River — described in over 50 hymns of the Rigveda as a great river flowing from the mountains to the sea — dried up around 1900 BCE due to tectonic shifts and monsoon weakening. Satellite imagery has revealed a vast dried river system corresponding to the Vedic description. Some scholars argue this river system, not the Indus, was the core of Harappan civilisation — and that its drying caused the civilisation's collapse and the population's migration to the Ganges. This reframes the Harappan civilisation as a Vedic rather than pre-Vedic culture.","up":2840,"dn":1640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-7000,"e":-1500,"label":"Frawley — Vedic civilisation along Saraswati predates mainstream dating","source":"Gods, Sages and Kings (1991)","researcher":"David Frawley","up":1540,"dn":1240}]},
  {"id":125,"n":"Easter Island Extended Contact","s":300,"e":1722,"r":"Pacific / South America","t":"debated","cont":"pacific","d":"Beyond the moai, Easter Island's civilisation raises persistent questions about trans-Pacific contact with South America. The sweet potato — a South American domesticate — reached Polynesia by 1000 CE. Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki expedition (1947) demonstrated the possibility of eastward Pacific voyaging from Peru. Recent genetic studies confirm pre-Columbian genetic admixture between Rapa Nui Polynesians and South Americans around 1200 CE. The direction and nature of this contact — Polynesian reaching South America, or South Americans reaching Polynesia — is still debated.","up":2840,"dn":980,"dateTheories":[{"s":300,"e":1722,"label":"Heyerdahl — South American contact via westward rafting","source":"Kon-Tiki (1948); Aku-Aku (1958)","researcher":"Thor Heyerdahl","up":1540,"dn":1240}]},
  {"id":126,"n":"Etruscan Origins Debate","s":-900,"e":-90,"r":"Italy / Tuscany","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"The Etruscans' origin remains one of antiquity's great puzzles. Ancient sources proposed three theories: indigenous Italian origin (Dionysius of Halicarnassus), migration from Lydia in Anatolia (Herodotus), and migration from the Alps (Livy). Modern ancient DNA studies (2023) support a largely indigenous Italian origin with some Anatolian admixture — but the language remains an absolute isolate, unrelated to any other known tongue. The genetic evidence and the linguistic evidence point in different directions, making the Etruscans a continuing mystery.","up":2891,"dn":189},
  {"id":127,"n":"Poverty Point Astronomical Culture","s":-1730,"e":-700,"r":"Louisiana, North America","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Beyond its role as a trading hub, Poverty Point displays sophisticated astronomical knowledge. The six concentric C-shaped earthen ridges are precisely spaced and oriented. The Mound A effigy (possibly a bird or human figure) and Mound B are aligned to the summer solstice sunset. LiDAR survey (2013) revealed the earthworks were constructed rapidly — possibly in as little as 90 days — implying extraordinary social organisation for a supposed hunter-gatherer society. The rapid construction challenges standard models of how complex societies develop.","up":2103,"dn":580},
  {"id":128,"n":"Orkney Neolithic Complex","s":-3800,"e":-2200,"r":"Orkney Islands, Scotland","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"The Orkney archipelago contains a concentration of Neolithic monuments — Skara Brae, the Ring of Brodgar, the Stones of Stenness, and Maeshowe — that together constitute a ritual landscape of extraordinary sophistication. Maeshowe is precisely aligned so that the midwinter solstice sunset illuminates its central chamber. Skara Brae is better preserved than Pompeii. The Ness of Brodgar (excavated since 2008) is revealing a vast ceremonial complex that may have been the religious centre of Neolithic Britain — challenging the primacy of Stonehenge.","up":3201,"dn":189},
  {"id":129,"n":"Gobekli Tepe Astronomical Alignments","s":-11600,"e":-8000,"r":"Anatolia, Turkey","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"Beyond the physical structure, Göbekli Tepe's astronomical alignments are increasingly researched. Martin Sweatman (University of Edinburgh) argues that Pillar 43 — the 'Vulture Stone' — depicts a comet impact event around 10,950 BCE encoded in star positions, corresponding to the Younger Dryas Boundary. Andrew Collins argues the primary astronomical reference is Cygnus, not the solar alignments proposed by mainstream archaeoastronomers. Graham Hancock uses the site's existence as the cornerstone argument for his lost civilisation thesis.","up":3840,"dn":840,"dateTheories":[{"s":-11600,"e":-10950,"label":"Sweatman — Vulture Stone encodes Younger Dryas comet impact ~10,950 BCE","source":"Mediterranean Archaeology & Archaeometry (2017)","researcher":"Martin Sweatman","up":1640,"dn":980},{"s":-11600,"e":-8000,"label":"Collins — Cygnus star alignments; Denisovan-influenced builders","source":"Göbekli Tepe: Genesis of the Gods (2014)","researcher":"Andrew Collins","up":1240,"dn":640}]},
  {"id":130,"n":"Vedic Astronomical Dating","s":-6000,"e":-1500,"r":"South Asia / India","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The astronomical references within the Rigveda — star positions, solstice alignments, and celestial events described in the hymns — have been used by researchers including David Frawley, B.G. Tilak, and Subhash Kak to propose Vedic composition dates far earlier than the mainstream c.1500 BCE. Tilak argued in The Arctic Home in the Vedas (1903) that certain passages describe an Arctic homeland, suggesting composition before 6000 BCE. Frawley's astronomical calculations suggest 6000–4000 BCE. Mainstream Indology dates the Rigveda to 1500–1200 BCE.","up":2640,"dn":1240},
  {"id":131,"n":"Machu Picchu and Inca Cosmology","s":1450,"e":1532,"r":"Peru / Andes","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Machu Picchu represents a peak of Inca architectural and astronomical precision — the Intihuatana ('hitching post of the sun') stone aligns precisely to the winter solstice; the Temple of the Sun contains windows aligned to solstice and equinox sunrises. Brien Foerster has documented stonework at Cusco and Sacsayhuamán with polygonal blocks fitted to sub-millimetre precision that he argues exceeds what bronze and stone tools should achieve — suggesting either lost technology or an earlier, more sophisticated builder culture. Mainstream archaeology attributes all construction to the Inca.","up":3840,"dn":1240,"dateTheories":[{"s":1450,"e":1532,"label":"Mainstream — Inca construction under Pachacuti, 1450–1532 CE","source":"Rowe, Inca Culture (1946); various","researcher":null,"up":2840,"dn":380},{"s":-3000,"e":500,"label":"Foerster — polygonal lower courses indicate earlier pre-Inca builders","source":"Advanced Ancient Civilizations (various)","researcher":"Brien Foerster","up":1240,"dn":1640}]},
  {"id":132,"n":"Angkor Cosmological Design","s":802,"e":1431,"r":"Cambodia","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"Beyond its size, Angkor Wat encodes astronomical and cosmological knowledge of extraordinary sophistication. Eleanor Mannikka documented that the temple's galleries encode the distances in cubits to astronomical events, effectively making the entire structure a three-dimensional solar and lunar calendar. Graham Hancock and Santha Faiia argued in Heaven's Mirror (1998) that Angkor's layout mirrors the Draco constellation, paralleling the Orion Correlation Theory for Giza. Whether these alignments are intentional design or post-hoc pattern recognition is debated.","up":2840,"dn":980},
  {"id":133,"n":"Orion Correlation Theory","s":-2560,"e":-2500,"r":"Giza, Egypt","t":"debated","cont":"africa","d":"Robert Bauval proposed in The Orion Mystery (1994) that the three Giza pyramids are laid out to mirror the three belt stars of Orion — and that the entire Giza complex, including the Sphinx, was designed to represent the Egyptian sky of 10,500 BCE, when Orion was at its lowest point in its 26,000-year precessional cycle and Leo rose heliacally on the spring equinox. If correct, this implies either that Giza was planned in 10,500 BCE or that it encodes astronomical knowledge of that era. Egyptologists dispute the correlation's precision and dating significance.","up":4840,"dn":2240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-10500,"e":-10000,"label":"Bauval / Hancock — Giza planned in 10,500 BCE or encodes that astronomical epoch","source":"The Orion Mystery (1994); Keeper of Genesis (1996)","researcher":"Robert Bauval","up":2840,"dn":1840},{"s":-2560,"e":-2500,"label":"Mainstream — Giza pyramids built 2560–2500 BCE under Khufu, Khafre, Menkaure","source":"Lehner, The Complete Pyramids (1997)","researcher":null,"up":4200,"dn":380}]},
  {"id":134,"n":"Angkor Pre-History","s":-2000,"e":800,"r":"Cambodia / Mekong Delta","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The extraordinary scale of Angkor raises questions about what pre-Khmer cultures occupied the Mekong Delta. The Funan kingdom (1st–7th century CE) — the first major Indianised state of Southeast Asia — controlled the delta and may have laid the hydraulic and cosmological foundations that the Khmer inherited. LiDAR surveys have revealed previously unknown pre-Angkor earthworks across Cambodia suggesting a much longer and more complex settlement history than previously understood.","up":1840,"dn":380},
  {"id":135,"n":"Phoenician Circumnavigation of Africa","s":-600,"e":-595,"r":"Red Sea to Mediterranean","t":"debated","cont":"africa","d":"Herodotus records that Pharaoh Necho II commissioned a Phoenician crew to circumnavigate Africa around 600 BCE — the voyage took three years. The crew reported that as they rounded the southern tip of the continent, the sun was on their right (north) — a detail Herodotus found unbelievable but which is perfectly correct for the southern hemisphere and which he could not have invented. This incidental detail is powerful evidence the voyage actually occurred — predating Vasco da Gama by 2,100 years.","up":3840,"dn":840},
  {"id":136,"n":"Lost City of Dwarka","s":-5000,"e":-1500,"r":"Gulf of Khambhat, India","t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"Dwarka — the mythological kingdom of Krishna described in the Mahabharata — has a candidate submerged site in the Gulf of Khambhat (Cambay), discovered by India's National Institute of Ocean Technology in 2002. Sonar and dredging revealed geometric structures, wooden artefacts, and what may be urban planning at 30–40 metres depth. Controversial carbon dating of organic material from the site suggested dates of 7,500–9,500 BCE — which would make it the oldest submerged city yet found. The find has not been independently verified to the satisfaction of mainstream archaeology.","up":2840,"dn":1640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-9500,"e":-7500,"label":"NIOT / Frawley — Gulf of Khambhat structures dated 9,500–7,500 BCE","source":"NIOT Survey Report (2002); Frawley commentary","researcher":"David Frawley","up":1540,"dn":1340}]},
  {"id":137,"n":"Mu / Pacific Lemuria","s":-50000,"e":-10000,"r":"Pacific Ocean (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"oceania","d":"Mu — later conflated with Lemuria — was proposed by Augustus Le Plongeon and James Churchward as a vast sunken Pacific continent, the mother civilisation of all known ancient cultures. Churchward claimed to have translated ancient 'Naacal tablets' in India describing Mu's history and catastrophic destruction. Modern oceanography rules out any continent-scale landmass in the Pacific during human evolution, though significant coastlines were indeed submerged during post-glacial sea level rise.","up":1240,"dn":2840},
  {"id":138,"n":"Pre-Flood North American Culture","s":-13000,"e":-10800,"r":"North America (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"americas","d":"A theorized complex society in pre-Clovis North America, proposed to have been destroyed or severely disrupted by the Younger Dryas Impact Event circa 10,800 BCE. Evidence cited includes the Topper Site in South Carolina, the White River Nahanni skull cache, and Serpent Mound's alignment to the Younger Dryas Boundary. Randall Carlson and Graham Hancock argue North American flood myths — Ojibwe, Hopi, Cherokee — preserve cultural memory of this catastrophe.","up":1840,"dn":1240},
  {"id":139,"n":"Adam's Calendar Culture","s":-75000,"e":-70000,"r":"Mpumalanga, South Africa","t":"theorized","cont":"africa","d":"A stone circle complex in South Africa's Mpumalanga region, proposed by Michael Tellinger and Johan Heine as the world's oldest stone calendar, potentially 75,000–300,000 years old. Tellinger links the site to a broader network of thousands of ancient stone ruins across southern Africa, which he interprets as gold-mining infrastructure built for the Anunnaki. Independent geologists associate the stone formations with dolerite erosion and natural geological processes. The site's astronomical orientations — including alignment to solstice sunrises — are less disputed than its age.","up":1640,"dn":2950,"dateTheories":[{"s":-300000,"e":-75000,"label":"Tellinger & Heine — archaeoastronomical back-calculation suggests 300,000-year age","source":"Adam's Calendar (2008)","researcher":"Michael Tellinger","up":1240,"dn":2710}]},
  {"id":140,"n":"Tartaria / Hyperborea","s":-15000,"e":-8000,"r":"Central Eurasia / Siberia (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"Tartaria is used both historically (the Mongol/Turkic steppe empire of medieval maps) and, in modern alternative history, for a theorized advanced civilisation of Siberia and Central Eurasia allegedly erased from the historical record. Proponents point to the Tartaria clay tablets (actually Vinča culture artefacts from Romania), anomalous Siberian architecture, and alleged population resets. Hyperborea — the Greek mythological land beyond the North Wind — is sometimes conflated with this tradition. The 'mud flood' and 'reset' variants are internet-originated theories without archaeological basis.","up":1840,"dn":3240},
  {"id":141,"n":"Antarctic Pre-Ice Civilization","s":-20000,"e":-6000,"r":"Antarctica (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"The hypothesis that Antarctica supported an advanced civilisation before the continent became ice-covered, based on Charles Hapgood's crustal displacement theory and the Piri Reis map (1513 CE), which appears to show an ice-free Antarctic coastline. Hapgood argued — with Einstein's endorsement — that the Earth's lithosphere periodically slides over the asthenosphere, relocating polar positions. Graham Hancock and Rand Flem-Ath proposed Antarctica as Plato's Atlantis. Mainstream geology rejects rapid crustal displacement.","up":2140,"dn":2480,"dateTheories":[{"s":-20000,"e":-12000,"label":"Hapgood — crustal displacement placed Antarctica at temperate latitude","source":"Earth's Shifting Crust (1958); Maps of the Ancient Sea Kings (1966)","researcher":"Charles Hapgood","up":1540,"dn":1980},{"s":-12000,"e":-6000,"label":"Hancock & Flem-Ath — Antarctica as Atlantis, iced over post-YDB","source":"When the Sky Fell (1995); Fingerprints of the Gods (1995)","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":1840,"dn":1640}]},
  {"id":142,"n":"Châtelperronian Culture","s":-44000,"e":-36000,"r":"France / Spain","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Châtelperronian is a transitional industry bridging Neanderthal Mousterian and early modern human Aurignacian cultures in western Europe. It features personal ornaments — perforated teeth and shells — and body decoration: behaviours previously associated only with anatomically modern humans. Whether Châtelperronian was independently invented by Neanderthals or borrowed from incoming modern humans is actively debated. It provides direct evidence that Neanderthals were culturally more sophisticated than previously assumed.","up":2201,"dn":189},
  {"id":143,"n":"Aurignacian Culture","s":-45000,"e":-29000,"r":"Europe (widespread)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Aurignacian marks the explosion of modern human symbolic behaviour in Europe — the first cave paintings (Chauvet, ~37,000 BCE), Venus figurines, bone flutes, and personal ornaments appear suddenly across the continent. The Lion Man of Hohlenstein-Stadel (~40,000 BCE) — a half-human, half-lion ivory figure — is one of humanity's oldest known works of art and evidence of mythological thinking. The Aurignacian 'creative explosion' and its cause remain one of palaeoanthropology's central debates.","up":2891,"dn":189},
  {"id":144,"n":"Gravettian Culture","s":-33000,"e":-22000,"r":"Europe (widespread)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Gravettian cultural tradition produced the most concentrated explosion of female figurative art in prehistory — the Venus figurines, distributed from France to Siberia, sharing a remarkably consistent aesthetic despite spanning 11,000 years and thousands of kilometres. The Dolní Věstonice site in Czechia produced the world's oldest known ceramic objects (fired clay figurines, ~26,000 BCE) — 15,000 years before pottery was used for cooking. The uniformity of Gravettian aesthetic traditions across such distances implies long-range cultural contact.","up":2640,"dn":189},
  {"id":145,"n":"Magdalenian Culture","s":-17000,"e":-12000,"r":"Western Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Magdalenian produced the pinnacle of Ice Age art — Lascaux, Altamira, Font-de-Gaume — with depictions of animals rendered with a naturalism and vitality not matched in Western art for 15,000 years. The bison of Altamira, the swimming deer of Lascaux, and the spotted horses of Pech Merle demonstrate an intimate knowledge of animal behaviour and a mastery of visual representation. The Magdalenians also produced the most sophisticated bone and antler tool technology of the Palaeolithic.","up":3201,"dn":189},
  {"id":146,"n":"Göbekli Tepe Pre-History — Karahantepe","s":-9500,"e":-7500,"r":"Anatolia, Turkey","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Karahantepe, excavated since 2019 in the same Taş Tepeler ('Stone Hills') region as Göbekli Tepe, is rewriting the understanding of the Neolithic transformation. Its carved human figures — including a three-dimensional seated human with exposed ribs, and a realistic human head emerging from a pillar — are the oldest known three-dimensional human sculpture. The site suggests a network of monumental ritual centres across southeastern Anatolia, of which Göbekli Tepe is only the most famous. Excavations are ongoing.","up":2840,"dn":189},
  {"id":147,"n":"Çayönü Tepesi","s":-8800,"e":-6300,"r":"Anatolia, Turkey","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Çayönü Tepesi in southeastern Turkey documents one of the most extraordinary transitions in human history — from nomadic foraging to settled agriculture — visible in a single site's archaeological sequence. The site shows early experiments with copper smelting (among the world's oldest), the first domestic pigs, and a building known as the 'Skull Building' containing the remains of over 400 individuals along with an altar stone that tests positive for human haemoglobin — possible evidence of ritual sacrifice at the dawn of civilisation.","up":2201,"dn":189},
  {"id":148,"n":"Bosnian Pyramid Complex","s":-12000,"e":-8000,"r":"Visoko, Bosnia and Herzegovina","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"A cluster of hills near Visoko, Bosnia, claimed by archaeologist Semir Osmanagić to be the largest pyramid complex in the world, predating Egyptian pyramids by thousands of years. The European Association of Archaeologists formally objected in 2006, concluding the hills are natural formations. Supporters point to concrete-like blocks found on the surface and tunnel networks beneath the hills. Excavations continue. Robert Schoch visited and described the structures as natural geology. The community plausibility score reflects high controversy.","up":2140,"dn":3820,"dateTheories":[{"s":-25000,"e":-12000,"label":"Osmanagić — carbon dating of tunnel material suggests 25,000 BCE construction","source":"Pyramids of Bosnia (2005); excavation reports 2006–present","researcher":"Semir Osmanagić","up":1820,"dn":3140}]},
  {"id":149,"n":"Nabta Playa","s":-9000,"e":-3400,"r":"Southern Egypt / Nubia","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Nabta Playa in the Western Desert of Egypt contains what is now recognised as one of the world's oldest astronomically-aligned megalithic structures — predating Stonehenge by 1,000 years and the Giza pyramids by 2,000. A circle of stones aligned to the summer solstice sunrise dates to ~6,400 BCE. Researcher Thomas Brophy proposed the site encodes knowledge of Orion's belt stars' positions across a 25,000-year precessional cycle. The site exists in what is now hyperarid desert — its builders lived during the Green Sahara humid period.","up":3201,"dn":312},
  {"id":150,"n":"Thule Civilization","s":-20000,"e":-8000,"r":"Northern polar regions (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"Thule — named for Greco-Roman geographers' description of a mythical northern land — has been proposed across centuries as a lost northern civilisation of high antiquity. In esoteric and theosophical traditions it was an Aryan homeland; this strand was later appropriated by Nazi occultism. In contemporary alternative research, Thule represents a possible ice-free Arctic civilisation during the last glacial period's warming phases. The confirmed historical Thule people (ancestors of modern Inuit) are entirely distinct from these speculative traditions.","up":940,"dn":1820},
  {"id":151,"n":"Benin Empire","s":-900,"e":1897,"r":"West Africa (modern Nigeria)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of the oldest and most sophisticated states in sub-Saharan Africa, centred at Benin City in present-day Nigeria. Renowned for its extraordinary bronze and ivory artworks, the Benin bronzes stand among the world's great artistic traditions. The Oba (king) exercised centralised authority over a complex bureaucratic state with a powerful military. Brutally dissolved by British forces in the Punitive Expedition of 1897, when thousands of bronzes were looted and dispersed to European museums.","up":1240,"dn":87,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1300,"e":-800,"label":"Connah — earlier complex polity indicated by archaeological occupation layers","source":"African Civilizations (1987)","researcher":"Graham Connah","up":390,"dn":210}]},
  {"id":152,"n":"Oyo Empire","s":1300,"e":1896,"r":"West Africa (Nigeria/Benin)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Oyo Empire was the largest and most powerful Yoruba state, dominating much of present-day Nigeria and Benin at its height. Its military strength rested on a formidable cavalry, unusual for sub-Saharan Africa. The empire operated a sophisticated constitutional monarchy with the Alafin balanced by the Oyo Mesi council. Oyo became deeply entangled in the Atlantic slave trade before its eventual collapse under internal revolt and Fulani jihad pressure.","up":870,"dn":44},
  {"id":153,"n":"Funj Sultanate","s":1504,"e":1821,"r":"Upper Nile (modern Sudan)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Funj Sultanate of Sennar was the last of the great Sudanese medieval kingdoms, founded following the collapse of the Christian Nubian kingdoms. It controlled the fertile confluence of the Blue and White Niles and became a major centre of Islamic scholarship. The Funj ruling class origins remain debated — theories range from nomadic African cattle herders to displaced Yemeni elites. Conquered by Muhammad Ali's Egyptian forces in 1821.","up":540,"dn":62},
  {"id":154,"n":"Kanem-Bornu Empire","s":-700,"e":1900,"r":"Lake Chad Basin","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"One of the longest-surviving African empires, Kanem-Bornu endured for nearly two millennia through successive dynastic transformations. Centred on the Lake Chad basin, it controlled trans-Saharan trade routes linking sub-Saharan Africa to the Mediterranean. Islamized around the 11th century CE. Its remarkable longevity reflects the deep ecological and commercial advantages of the Chad basin.","up":760,"dn":55},
  {"id":155,"n":"Ganga Dynasty (Eastern)","s":496,"e":1434,"r":"Odisha, India","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Eastern Ganga Dynasty ruled Odisha for nearly a thousand years, producing some of India's most magnificent temple architecture — the Konark Sun Temple and the Jagannath Temple complex at Puri. Their rule represented a high point of Orissan cultural synthesis, blending Shaivite, Vaishnavite, and tantric traditions. The dynasty maintained naval power and trading contacts with Southeast Asia.","up":620,"dn":38},
  {"id":156,"n":"Pallava Empire","s":275,"e":897,"r":"South India (Tamil Nadu)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Pallava dynasty of Kanchipuram was the preeminent power of South India for nearly seven centuries. Their rock-cut and structural temples at Mamallapuram represent the origins of Dravidian temple architecture. Pallava scripts directly gave rise to many Southeast Asian writing systems including Khmer, Javanese, and Burmese scripts. Naval expeditions spread Hinduism and Buddhism across the Bay of Bengal.","up":810,"dn":29},
  {"id":157,"n":"Srivijaya Maritime Empire","s":650,"e":1375,"r":"Sumatra, Maritime SE Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Srivijaya was the dominant maritime power of Southeast Asia for over seven centuries, controlling the Strait of Malacca and the spice trade between China and India. A thalassocracy with no fixed territorial borders but absolute control of maritime commerce. The empire became the most important centre of Buddhist learning outside India. Its sudden collapse in the 13th–14th centuries remains poorly understood.","up":940,"dn":41},
  {"id":158,"n":"Majapahit Empire","s":1293,"e":1527,"r":"Java, Maritime SE Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Majapahit was the last great Hindu-Buddhist empire of Southeast Asia and is considered the precursor state to modern Indonesia. At its peak under Hayam Wuruk and prime minister Gajah Mada, it claimed suzerainty over much of the Indonesian archipelago, the Malay peninsula, and parts of the Philippines. Its decline resulted from succession conflicts and the rise of Islamic Demak.","up":870,"dn":33},
  {"id":160,"n":"Tiwanaku Civilization","s":-200,"e":1000,"r":"Lake Titicaca Basin (Bolivia/Peru)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Tiwanaku was one of the most influential pre-Columbian civilizations of the Andes, dominating a vast highland network from its ceremonial capital on the southern shores of Lake Titicaca. Its distinctive iconography spread across the Andes and became the template for subsequent Andean religious expression. The Tiwanaku engineered extraordinary raised-field agriculture capable of sustaining large populations in the harsh altiplano. Its collapse around 1000 CE is linked to prolonged drought.","up":980,"dn":94,"dateTheories":[{"s":-15000,"e":-10000,"label":"Posnansky — astronomical alignment of temple suggests 15,000 BCE construction","source":"Tiahuanacu: The Cradle of American Man (1945)","researcher":"Arthur Posnansky","up":520,"dn":1840}]},
  {"id":164,"n":"Bactria-Margiana Archaeological Complex (BMAC)","s":-2300,"e":-1700,"r":"Central Asia (Afghanistan/Turkmenistan)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The BMAC (Oxus Civilization) was a Bronze Age urban culture of remarkable sophistication in the oasis zones of Central Asia. Its planned monumental architecture, distinctive metal objects, and proto-writing system indicate a complex hierarchical society. Intriguing parallels with the Indus Valley Civilization suggest cultural exchange. BMAC artefacts appear across a vast area from the Persian Gulf to the Chinese border.","up":670,"dn":58},
  {"id":170,"n":"Yonaguni Submarine Monument","s":-10000,"e":-8000,"r":"Yonaguni Island, Japan","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"A submerged rock formation off Japan's Yonaguni island explored by divers since 1987. Marine geologist Masaaki Kimura argues the terraced steps, right angles, and what appears to be a carved road are evidence of a human-built structure submerged when post-glacial sea levels rose. Geologists are divided — Schoch initially argued natural formation but later acknowledged possible human modification. If artificial, it would represent evidence of sophisticated pre-agricultural civilization in East Asia.","up":2640,"dn":1580},
  {"id":177,"n":"Mapungubwe Kingdom","s":1075,"e":1220,"r":"Limpopo Valley, South Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Mapungubwe was southern Africa's first known state-level society, a stratified kingdom at the confluence of the Limpopo and Shashe rivers. Its hilltop capital became a symbol of political and ritual power. The golden rhinoceros figure and other gold artefacts in the royal burial site established that Mapungubwe was engaged in Indian Ocean gold trade — centuries before Great Zimbabwe. The kingdom's decline coincides with the rise of Great Zimbabwe.","up":680,"dn":32},
  {"id":178,"n":"Chimú Empire","s":850,"e":1470,"r":"North Coast of Peru","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Chimú Empire was the second largest pre-Columbian empire of South America. Its capital Chan Chan near modern Trujillo was the largest pre-Columbian city in South America — 20 square kilometres of adobe architecture. The Chimú were master hydraulic engineers, building extensive canal networks to sustain agriculture in the hyper-arid Atacama coastal fringe. Their metallurgy was absorbed wholesale by the Inca after conquest in 1470 CE.","up":840,"dn":38},
  {"id":179,"n":"Hopewell Culture","s":-100,"e":500,"r":"Ohio and Illinois River valleys","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Hopewell tradition was a network of interacting communities across eastern North America unified by shared ceremonial practices and long-distance trade. Hopewell exchange networks moved copper from the Great Lakes, obsidian from the Rockies, shells from the Gulf, and mica from the Appalachians across thousands of kilometres. The great earthwork complexes of Ohio — including Newark Earthworks — demonstrate sophisticated astronomical knowledge and massive communal labour.","up":920,"dn":44},
  {"id":181,"n":"Kingdom of Kush","s":-2500,"e":350,"r":"Nubia (Sudan)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of Kush was Egypt's great southern rival and sometime conqueror, twice establishing Kushite dynasties that ruled Egypt as Pharaohs. Centred first at Kerma then at Napata and finally Meroë, Kush controlled gold, ivory, and sub-Saharan trade routes for two millennia. The Meroitic script — still only partially deciphered — is one of Africa's oldest indigenous writing systems. Meroë's iron-smelting industry was among the most productive in the ancient world.","up":1240,"dn":58},
  {"id":183,"n":"Kingdom of Zimbabwe","s":1100,"e":1420,"r":"Zimbabwe Plateau, southern Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Great Zimbabwe was the capital of a Shona state that controlled gold trade between the African interior and the Indian Ocean coast. The dry-stone enclosure walls — built without mortar — reach eleven metres in height and required the labour of a large, organised workforce over centuries. European colonists initially refused to believe Africans had built it, attributing it to Phoenicians or Hebrews; archaeology has decisively confirmed indigenous authorship. Zimbabwe's gold and cattle economy made it the dominant power of southern Africa for three centuries.","up":1420,"dn":62},
  {"id":184,"n":"Benin Kingdom","s":900,"e":1897,"r":"Southern Nigeria (Edo State)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of Benin was one of the most developed states in pre-colonial Africa, ruled by the Oba (divine king) through a sophisticated bureaucratic system. The Benin Bronzes — intricate cast plaques and sculptures adorning the royal palace — are among the finest metal artworks ever produced anywhere, a technical achievement that stunned European observers when British forces looted them in 1897. The kingdom maintained a standing army, sophisticated road network, and active trade with Portuguese merchants from the 15th century.","up":1840,"dn":67},
  {"id":185,"n":"Swahili City-States","s":800,"e":1500,"r":"East African Coast (Kenya/Tanzania)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"A network of prosperous mercantile city-states — Kilwa, Mombasa, Malindi, Zanzibar and others — built at the intersection of African, Arab, Persian, and Indian Ocean trade. Kiswahili, a Bantu language enriched with Arabic vocabulary, was born as a trade lingua franca and is now spoken by over 200 million people. The Swahili cities imported silk and porcelain from China and exported gold, ivory, and enslaved people. Ibn Battuta described Kilwa Kisiwani as one of the most beautiful cities in the world.","up":1140,"dn":44},
  {"id":187,"n":"Khmer Empire","s":802,"e":1431,"r":"Cambodia / Mainland SE Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Khmer Empire was the dominant land power of mainland Southeast Asia for six centuries. Angkor Wat — built by Suryavarman II in the 12th century — is the largest religious monument ever constructed, representing Mount Meru in sandstone at a scale that required decades of labour by tens of thousands of workers. The Khmer hydraulic network of barays (reservoirs) and canals supported intensive rice agriculture across a vast lowland plain. The empire's capital Angkor may have been the world's largest pre-industrial city, housing up to a million people.","up":2140,"dn":88},
  {"id":189,"n":"Pagan Kingdom (Bagan)","s":849,"e":1297,"r":"Myanmar (Burma)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Pagan Kingdom united the Irrawaddy valley and established Theravada Buddhism as the dominant religion of mainland Southeast Asia, a legacy that endures today. At its height, the Bagan plain contained over 10,000 Buddhist temples, pagodas, and monasteries — of which approximately 3,500 survive. The kingdom collected religious endowments so aggressively that by the 13th century temples owned roughly 60% of cultivable land, fatally weakening the state's resource base before the Mongol invasions.","up":920,"dn":42},
  {"id":190,"n":"Scythian Civilisation","s":-900,"e":-200,"r":"Pontic Steppe to Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Scythians were the first great nomadic empire of the Eurasian steppe, mastering horse-mounted warfare and creating a sophisticated artistic tradition centred on animal imagery in gold. Herodotus described their sophisticated society, including the Amazonian warrior women later confirmed by DNA analysis of female burial mounds with weapons. Scythian gold metalwork traded across the steppe belt from the Danube to China. Their burial kurgans (mounds), some containing frozen corpses with preserved tattoos, reveal a complex spiritual world.","up":1240,"dn":52},
  {"id":191,"n":"Xiongnu Empire","s":-209,"e":91,"r":"Mongolian Plateau / Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Xiongnu confederacy was the first steppe empire to unify the nomadic peoples of the eastern Eurasian steppe, forcing China to build and extend the Great Wall as the primary strategic response. Their defeats of Han Dynasty armies led to the humiliating heqin tribute system by which China paid silk, grain, and imperial brides to maintain peace. Recent DNA analysis confirms the Xiongnu were ethnically diverse — a political confederation rather than a single ethnic group. Their westward migrations after defeat by the Han may have set the Hunnic invasions of Europe in motion.","up":1080,"dn":64},
  {"id":192,"n":"Göktürk Khaganate","s":552,"e":745,"r":"Central Asia / Mongolian Plateau","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Göktürks created the first Turkic empire, ruling a vast steppe zone from the borders of China to the Black Sea and introducing the runic Orkhon script — the oldest preserved Turkic writing. Their khaganate split into Eastern and Western halves, each in complex tributary, military, and diplomatic relations with Tang China, Sassanid Persia, and Byzantium simultaneously. The Göktürks established the template for subsequent Turkic and Mongolian steppe empires that would periodically reshape Eurasian history.","up":840,"dn":56},
  {"id":193,"n":"Mississippian Cahokia","s":1050,"e":1350,"r":"Cahokia Mounds, Illinois","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Cahokia was the largest pre-Columbian city north of Mexico and the epicentre of Mississippian civilisation. At its peak around 1100 CE, its population of 10,000–20,000 people made it larger than contemporary London or Paris. Monks Mound — the central earthwork — contains more earth by volume than the Great Pyramid of Giza, built without metal tools or the wheel. Mass human sacrifice events documented in excavated burial pits suggest a powerful and demanding religious-political order. The city's sudden decline after 1200 CE remains poorly understood.","up":1640,"dn":96,"dateTheories":[{"s":700,"e":800,"label":"Some researchers argue urban complexity began a century earlier than the standard 1050 date","source":"Cahokia: Ancient America's Great City (2009)","researcher":"Timothy Pauketat","up":340,"dn":580}]},
  {"id":194,"n":"Zapotec Civilisation","s":-500,"e":700,"r":"Oaxaca Valley, Mexico","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Zapotec of the Oaxaca Valley built Monte Albán — one of the first cities in Mesoamerica — atop an artificially levelled mountain commanding the entire valley. They developed one of the earliest writing systems in the Americas, used a 260-day ritual calendar, and built one of the first astronomically oriented structures in the New World. The Zapotec civilisation lasted over a thousand years and heavily influenced subsequent Mesoamerican cultures. Their descendants are among the most numerous indigenous communities in Mexico today.","up":920,"dn":44},
  {"id":195,"n":"Wari Empire","s":500,"e":1000,"r":"Central Andes (Peru)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Wari Empire was the first true imperial state in the Andes, preceding the Inca by five centuries and establishing many of the administrative, road, and artistic patterns the Inca would later inherit and expand. Their administrative centres, built on a standardised plan, were imposed across the Andes as colonial outposts of central authority. The Wari textile tradition is considered one of the finest in the pre-Columbian world. The empire's collapse circa 1000 CE led to a period of political fragmentation until the Inca unification.","up":780,"dn":38},
  {"id":196,"n":"Mississippian Moundville","s":1000,"e":1450,"r":"Alabama, eastern North America","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Moundville was the second largest Mississippian centre in North America after Cahokia, a regional capital commanding the Black Warrior River valley of modern Alabama. Its 29 platform mounds arranged around a central plaza covered 75 hectares, housing an elite ruling class who controlled redistribution of prestige goods across the region. The Southern Cult (Southeastern Ceremonial Complex) — a widespread set of iconographic symbols — radiated from centres like Moundville across a vast network. Its decline preceded European contact.","up":640,"dn":28},
  {"id":197,"n":"Etruscan Civilisation","s":-900,"e":-27,"r":"Etruria (central Italy)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Etruscans were the dominant people of pre-Roman Italy, forming a confederation of wealthy city-states whose art, religion, and urban planning profoundly shaped Rome. The Romans absorbed Etruscan engineering, divination practices, gladiatorial combat, and the toga. The Etruscan language remains only partially understood — a linguistic isolate with no known relatives. Their elaborate painted tomb chambers provide our most vivid window into daily life and belief in pre-Roman Italy.","up":1120,"dn":58},
  {"id":198,"n":"Minoan Civilisation","s":-3100,"e":-1100,"r":"Crete and Aegean Islands","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Minoans were Europe's first advanced civilisation, building palatial complexes at Knossos, Phaistos, and Akrotiri that featured indoor plumbing, sophisticated drainage, and multi-storey architecture centuries before mainland Greece or Rome. Their Linear A script has never been deciphered. The catastrophic eruption of Thera (Santorini) circa 1600 BCE severely disrupted Minoan civilisation, with some scholars suggesting it underlies Plato's Atlantis myth. Minoan art — dolphins, bull-leapers, priestesses — conveys a vibrant Mediterranean world unlike anything before it.","up":2080,"dn":160,"dateTheories":[{"s":-9600,"e":-9000,"label":"Galanopoulos / some classicists — Minoan Crete as Plato's Atlantis, date misread by factor of 10","source":"Atlantis: The Truth Behind the Legend (1969)","researcher":null,"up":640,"dn":1840}]},
  {"id":199,"n":"Phoenician Civilisation","s":-1500,"e":-146,"r":"Levantine coast (Lebanon/Syria)","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Phoenicians were the greatest maritime traders of the ancient Mediterranean, establishing colonial networks from Cyprus to Spain and — if Herodotus is accurate — circumnavigating Africa around 600 BCE. Their most enduring achievement is the Phoenician alphabet: the ancestor of Greek, Latin, Arabic, Hebrew, and most writing systems used today. Carthage — their greatest colony — nearly destroyed Rome and controlled the western Mediterranean for centuries. The sack of Carthage in 146 BCE ended the Phoenician world but their writing system had already transformed human civilization forever.","up":1840,"dn":72},
  {"id":200,"n":"Celtic Civilisation","s":-800,"e":400,"r":"Western and Central Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Celts were not a single political entity but a family of Iron Age cultures sharing language, art, and religious practice that spread across Europe from Anatolia to Ireland. Their La Tène artistic tradition — swirling abstract metalwork — is among the most distinctive in world art history. The Druids formed an intellectual and priestly caste whose oral learning traditions required up to 20 years of memorisation. Celtic languages survive today in Irish, Welsh, Scottish Gaelic, and Breton — the westernmost remnants of a once-vast linguistic world.","up":1460,"dn":62},
  {"id":202,"n":"Nabataean Kingdom","s":-400,"e":106,"r":"Southern Jordan / Negev / Sinai","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Nabataeans built Petra — the rose-red city carved from sandstone cliffs — as the capital of a desert trading empire that controlled frankincense and spice routes between Arabia and the Mediterranean. Their sophisticated hydraulic engineering, collecting and storing flash flood water in a hyper-arid desert, enabled a city of 20,000+ people to thrive in an environment that should support almost none. The Nabataean script became the direct ancestor of the Arabic alphabet, one of the most widely used writing systems on Earth.","up":1540,"dn":52},
  {"id":203,"n":"Vimāna Civilisation (Vedic)","s":-15000,"e":-5000,"r":"Indian subcontinent (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"Proposed by researchers in the Vedic tradition as an advanced pre-Harappan civilisation described in Sanskrit epics. The Mahabharata and Ramayana describe flying craft (vimānas), precision weapons (brahmastra), and urban centres of great sophistication. David Frawley and Subhash Kak argue Vedic astronomical data implies observations from 6000–8000 BCE, suggesting a literate culture far older than conventional dating allows. The relationship to the confirmed Harappan Civilisation and the Saraswati River culture is actively researched.","up":1640,"dn":2480,"dateTheories":[{"s":-8000,"e":-6000,"label":"Frawley — Vedic astronomical references imply observations before 6000 BCE","source":"Gods, Sages and Kings (1991)","researcher":"David Frawley","up":720,"dn":1240},{"s":-12000,"e":-8000,"label":"Tilak — Arctic Home in the Vedas — circumpolar references suggest extreme antiquity","source":"The Arctic Home in the Vedas (1903)","researcher":"Bal Gangadhar Tilak","up":480,"dn":1640}]},
  {"id":204,"n":"Richat Atlantis (Mauritania)","s":-9600,"e":-9000,"r":"Richat Structure, Mauritania","t":"theorized","cont":"africa","d":"The Richat Structure (Eye of the Sahara) — a 50km geological dome in Mauritania — has been proposed by Jimmy Corsetti (Bright Insight) and others as the physical location of Plato's Atlantis. Proponents note its concentric ring structure matches Plato's description of alternating rings of land and water, and that its dimensions align with Plato's measurements when converted from stades. Geological consensus attributes the structure to differential erosion of a symmetrical geological dome. The region was significantly wetter during the African Humid Period circa 9000–5000 BCE.","up":2840,"dn":2240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-9600,"e":-9000,"label":"Corsetti — Richat Structure as Plato's Atlantis, concurrent with YD boundary","source":"Bright Insight YouTube — Richat Structure series (2018)","researcher":"Jimmy Corsetti","up":1640,"dn":1840}]},
  {"id":205,"n":"Sundaland Civilisation","s":-15000,"e":-8000,"r":"Sundaland (drowned SE Asian shelf)","t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"Sundaland — the exposed continental shelf of Southeast Asia during the last glacial maximum — was a landmass twice the size of India, home to tens of thousands of years of human habitation. Researchers including Arysio Santos and Stephen Oppenheimer propose it as the origin point for Austronesian civilisation and a possible Atlantis candidate. Post-glacial sea level rise drowned Sundaland in a series of catastrophic floods between 14,000 and 7,000 BCE, potentially preserving cultural memory of a lost homeland in Austronesian flood myths.","up":1840,"dn":1480,"dateTheories":[{"s":-15000,"e":-8000,"label":"Santos — Sundaland as Atlantis, advanced culture submerged by post-glacial flooding","source":"Atlantis: The Lost Continent Finally Found (2005)","researcher":"Arysio Santos","up":840,"dn":1480},{"s":-12000,"e":-8000,"label":"Oppenheimer — Sundaland flood myths as historical memory of catastrophic sea level rise","source":"Eden in the East (1998)","researcher":"Stephen Oppenheimer","up":1140,"dn":840}]},
  {"id":206,"n":"Dwarka Underwater City","s":-7000,"e":-3000,"r":"Gulf of Khambhat, India","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"Marine surveys off the coast of Dwarka in Gujarat have revealed submerged structures at depths of 30–40 metres in the Gulf of Khambhat. The National Institute of Ocean Technology announced in 2002 that sonar images showed a large submerged urban complex. If confirmed as artificial, the site would predate the earliest known cities by several thousand years. Critics argue the structures are natural geological formations; proponents link them to the legendary city of Dwarka described in the Mahabharata, said to have been submerged after Krishna's death.","up":2140,"dn":1640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-7000,"e":-5000,"label":"NIOT (India) — sonar survey suggests submerged urban structures of 7000+ BCE","source":"NIOT Survey Report (2002)","researcher":null,"up":1240,"dn":1480},{"s":-3000,"e":-1500,"label":"Mainstream — if structures are artificial they match known Harappan-era period","source":"Archaeological Survey of India review","researcher":null,"up":640,"dn":480}]},
  {"id":207,"n":"Lost City of Z (Amazon)","s":-2000,"e":1500,"r":"Mato Grosso, Brazilian Amazon","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Proposed by British explorer Percy Fawcett as a lost advanced civilisation in the Amazon, the 'City of Z' inspired Conan Doyle's The Lost World and Hollywood's 2017 film. Fawcett disappeared in 1925 searching for it. Modern archaeological evidence — notably Michael Heckenberger's discovery of a network of geoglyphs, causeways, and managed forest in the upper Xingu — confirms that complex pre-Columbian Amazonian civilisation existed at a scale previously underestimated. The full extent remains unknown due to forest cover.","up":1540,"dn":840,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2000,"e":-1000,"label":"Heckenberger — evidence for large, interconnected settlement network in upper Xingu","source":"The Ecology of Power (2005)","researcher":"Michael Heckenberger","up":1040,"dn":480}]},
  {"id":208,"n":"Pre-Clovis American Civilisation","s":-25000,"e":-13000,"r":"Americas (multiple sites)","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Multiple archaeological sites challenge the Clovis-first model of the Americas' peopling, suggesting complex societies existed in the Americas thousands of years before the accepted date. The Monte Verde site in Chile (14,800 BCE), Topper in South Carolina, and Chiquihuite Cave in Mexico all suggest pre-Clovis occupation. Graham Hancock in America Before argues these populations were survivors of an advanced pre-Younger Dryas culture. Mainstream archaeology now accepts pre-Clovis presence but debates the nature and sophistication of these early populations.","up":2340,"dn":1240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-24000,"e":-20000,"label":"Chiquihuite Cave, Mexico — possible tool use 26,000 BCE","source":"Nature (2020) — Ardelean et al.","researcher":null,"up":980,"dn":1240},{"s":-14800,"e":-14800,"label":"Monte Verde I, Chile — confirmed pre-Clovis at 14,800 BCE","source":"Monte Verde: A Late Pleistocene Settlement (1997)","researcher":null,"up":1640,"dn":240},{"s":-130000,"e":-100000,"label":"Cerutti Mastodon, California — claimed mastodon bone modification 130,000 BCE","source":"Nature (2017) — Holen et al.","researcher":null,"up":640,"dn":2840}]},
  {"id":209,"n":"Anunnaki Civilisation (Sitchin)","s":-450000,"e":-2000,"r":"Mesopotamia / global (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"Proposed by Zecharia Sitchin in The Earth Chronicles based on his translations of Sumerian and Akkadian texts. Sitchin argued that the Anunnaki — 'those who from heaven came down' — were extraterrestrial beings from the planet Nibiru who visited Earth to mine gold, genetically engineered Homo sapiens as a labour force, and are recorded in Sumerian mythology as gods. Mainstream Assyriologists reject Sitchin's translations as idiosyncratic. The theory has become foundational to much of contemporary alternative history and has profoundly shaped conspiracy theory culture worldwide.","up":2640,"dn":4280,"dateTheories":[{"s":-450000,"e":-400000,"label":"Sitchin — Anunnaki arrival date from Sumerian king list encoding","source":"The 12th Planet (1976)","researcher":"Zecharia Sitchin","up":940,"dn":2840}]},
  {"id":211,"n":"Ghana Empire (Wagadu)","s":300,"e":1235,"r":"West Africa (Mali/Mauritania border)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Ghana Empire — known to its own people as Wagadu — was the first major West African empire built on trans-Saharan gold and salt trade, controlling the routes linking the goldfields of Bambuk to the salt mines of the central Sahara. Arab geographers described its capital, Koumbi Saleh, as two towns six miles apart: a royal quarter following traditional religion and a Muslim merchant quarter with mosques and scholars, governed under a single ruler. Medieval Arab writers called its king 'the richest king on the face of the earth' on account of the empire's gold reserves. Ghana's decline through the 11th–13th centuries opened the way for the rise of the Mali Empire.","up":1180,"dn":48},
  {"id":212,"n":"Buganda Kingdom","s":1300,"e":1894,"r":"Great Lakes Region (Uganda)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of Buganda, on the northern shores of Lake Victoria, developed one of the most centralised administrations in pre-colonial Africa, with the Kabaka (king) ruling through appointed chiefs rather than hereditary clan heads — an unusually bureaucratic structure for its time. By the 19th century Buganda's military and administrative efficiency allowed it to dominate the Great Lakes region, subordinating neighbouring states including its older rival Bunyoro. Its early encounters with European explorers, missionaries, and traders in the 1860s–1880s produced some of the most detailed contemporary accounts of any African kingdom during the colonial transition. Buganda became a British protectorate in 1894 and survives today as a constitutionally recognised cultural kingdom within Uganda.","up":780,"dn":34},
  {"id":213,"n":"Sokoto Caliphate","s":1804,"e":1903,"r":"Hausaland (Northern Nigeria)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Sokoto Caliphate was founded in 1804 following a religious reform movement led by Usman dan Fodio, which united the Hausa city-states of northern Nigeria into the largest state in Africa at the time, organised into more than thirty subordinate emirates. It became one of the major economic powers of the 19th century, with extensive grain and cotton agriculture supported by a labour system on a scale comparable to contemporary plantation economies of the Americas. Its Islamic legal and educational institutions shaped the administrative structure later inherited by colonial and independent Northern Nigeria. The caliphate fell to British conquest in 1903.","up":680,"dn":42},
  {"id":214,"n":"Tassili n'Ajjer Rock Art Culture","s":-12000,"e":-1000,"r":"Tassili n'Ajjer Plateau, Algeria","t":"debated","cont":"africa","d":"The Tassili n'Ajjer plateau in the central Sahara preserves more than 15,000 rock engravings and paintings spanning many thousands of years, recording a succession of cultures that lived through the 'Green Sahara' phases when the region held lakes, rivers, and savanna wildlife including elephants, giraffes, and hippopotamuses. The earliest layer — the so-called 'Round Head' style — has been argued by some researchers to date to the final millennia of the last Ice Age, earlier than the conventional start of the regional Neolithic. The site's exceptionally long and continuous artistic record makes it one of the most important open-air galleries of prehistoric art in the world, and UNESCO designated it a World Heritage site in 1982. The relationship between the earliest images and the climatic transition out of the Ice Age remains an active research question.","up":1240,"dn":620,"dateTheories":[{"s":-12000,"e":-9500,"label":"Round Head style — earliest layer possibly predates the regional Neolithic by several millennia","source":"Henri Lhote survey (1957); UNESCO Tassili n'Ajjer documentation","researcher":"Henri Lhote","up":480,"dn":620}]},
  {"id":215,"n":"Clovis Culture","s":-11500,"e":-10800,"r":"North America (multiple sites)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Clovis culture is named for distinctive fluted stone spear points first identified near Clovis, New Mexico, and is the earliest widely-recognised toolmaking tradition broadly distributed across North America. Clovis hunters are associated with the hunting of now-extinct megafauna including mammoths and mastodons during the final centuries of the last Ice Age. For decades Clovis was treated as marking the first peopling of the Americas — the 'Clovis-first' model — though pre-Clovis sites have since pushed the earliest human presence back further. Clovis-style points have been found from Alaska to Mexico, reflecting either rapid population spread or rapid technological diffusion across an already-present population.","up":1340,"dn":62},
  {"id":216,"n":"Adena Culture","s":-1000,"e":-100,"r":"Ohio and Mississippi Valleys","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Adena culture was an early mound-building tradition of the Ohio Valley, predating and feeding directly into the more extensive Hopewell exchange network that followed it. Adena peoples built conical burial mounds and earthen enclosures, some aligned with solar and lunar events, and produced finely worked tablets, pipes, and copper ornaments traded across considerable distances. Their burial practices — including log-lined tombs beneath earthen mounds — indicate an emerging social hierarchy among otherwise dispersed small communities. Adena sites established the ceremonial template that later Hopewell and Mississippian mound-building cultures would expand upon.","up":720,"dn":36},
  {"id":217,"n":"Tairona Civilization","s":200,"e":1600,"r":"Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta, Colombia","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Tairona built an extensive network of stone-terraced cities in the steep, forested Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta on Colombia's Caribbean coast, with sophisticated stone roads, drainage systems, and agricultural terracing adapted to extreme mountain terrain. They were renowned across the region for fine goldwork, much of which was looted following the Spanish conquest of the early 16th century. The Tairona resisted Spanish control longer than most coastal societies, and their descendants — the Kogi, Wiwa, and Arhuaco peoples — still inhabit the Sierra Nevada and maintain elements of Tairona spiritual tradition today. The rediscovery of the largest Tairona city, Ciudad Perdida, in the 1970s revealed urban planning on a scale previously unsuspected for the region.","up":680,"dn":32},
  {"id":218,"n":"Muisca Civilization","s":600,"e":1600,"r":"Altiplano Cundiboyacense, Colombia","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Muisca were a confederation of chiefdoms occupying the high plateaus of the Colombian Andes, with an economy based on intensive potato and maize agriculture, salt mining, and an extensive network of emerald and textile trade across the northern Andes. Unlike most pre-Columbian Andean societies, the Muisca did not build large stone monuments, instead investing their wealth in elaborate goldwork used in ritual offerings to sacred lakes. Spanish chroniclers recorded a ceremony at Lake Guatavita in which a new zipa (ruler) was covered in gold dust and rowed onto the lake to make offerings — an account that became the seed of the El Dorado legend. The Muisca confederation was conquered by the Spanish in the 1530s.","up":980,"dn":46},
  {"id":219,"n":"Calusa Kingdom","s":-500,"e":1750,"r":"Southwest Florida","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Calusa built a powerful, hierarchical kingdom in southwest Florida without practising agriculture, instead drawing on the exceptional productivity of estuarine fishing, shellfish harvesting, and tidal fish weirs to support large, permanent towns. Spanish accounts describe a paramount chief commanding tribute from dozens of subordinate villages, supported by a stratified society of nobles, commoners, and captives. Massive shell mounds and constructed canals at sites such as Mound Key reflect large-scale engineered modification of the coastal landscape. The Calusa successfully resisted Spanish missionary and military efforts for over two centuries before disease and slave raids reduced the population in the 18th century.","up":620,"dn":28},
  {"id":221,"n":"Funan Kingdom","s":100,"e":550,"r":"Mekong Delta (Cambodia/Vietnam)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Funan was the earliest known major state in mainland Southeast Asia, centred on the Mekong Delta and linked to the great port of Óc Eo, which yielded Roman coins, Chinese mirrors, and Indian seals attesting to its role as a hub of maritime trade between China and India. Chinese chroniclers describe Funan as ruled by kings bearing Indian-derived titles, marking one of the earliest examples of 'Indianisation' in Southeast Asia — the adoption of Sanskrit, Hindu and Buddhist religious forms, and Indian models of kingship by local elites. An extensive network of canals across the delta supported rice agriculture and inter-regional transport. Funan's political and cultural legacy passed to its successor states, most notably the early Khmer polity of Chenla.","up":780,"dn":38},
  {"id":222,"n":"Silla Kingdom","s":-57,"e":935,"r":"Korean Peninsula","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Silla was one of the Three Kingdoms of ancient Korea and, after defeating its rivals Baekje and Goguryeo with Tang Chinese assistance in 668 CE, became the first state to unify most of the Korean peninsula under a single government. Its capital Gyeongju preserves an exceptional concentration of royal tombs, from which spectacular gold crowns, belts, and ornaments — among the finest goldwork of early East Asia — have been recovered. Silla adopted Buddhism as a state religion, and the cave temple of Seokguram and the temple complex of Bulguksa, both built during Unified Silla, are recognised UNESCO World Heritage sites. The bone-rank system, a rigid hereditary status hierarchy, structured Silla society and limited social mobility even for the aristocracy.","up":1180,"dn":52},
  {"id":223,"n":"Yamato / Kofun Japan","s":300,"e":710,"r":"Kinai Region, Japan","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kofun period takes its name from the thousands of large keyhole-shaped burial mounds (kofun) built across Japan, the largest of which — the Daisen Kofun, attributed to Emperor Nintoku — covers a larger ground area than the Great Pyramid of Giza. This period saw the consolidation of the Yamato polity in the Kinai region into the dominant power on the Japanese archipelago, laying the foundations of the imperial line that Japan's monarchy traces its ancestry to today. Contact with the Korean peninsula and China during this period introduced writing, Buddhism, and continental statecraft, transforming Yamato from a regional chiefdom into an increasingly centralised state by the early 7th century. Many of the largest kofun remain off-limits to archaeologists, as they are maintained by the Imperial Household Agency as the tombs of imperial ancestors.","up":1340,"dn":64},
  {"id":224,"n":"Tibetan Empire","s":618,"e":842,"r":"Tibetan Plateau","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Tibetan Empire, founded under Songtsen Gampo in the early 7th century, expanded from the Yarlung Valley to become a major Central Asian power that at its height controlled territory stretching from the Tarim Basin to the borders of Tang China and the Indian subcontinent. Tibetan armies captured the Tang capital Chang'an in 763 CE, and treaties between Tibet and China — including one inscribed on a stone pillar still standing in Lhasa — record Tibet negotiating as an equal great power. The empire oversaw the introduction of Buddhism as a state religion and the development of a Tibetan script adapted from an Indian alphabet for translating Buddhist texts. The empire fragmented in the mid-9th century following civil conflict over royal support for Buddhism versus the indigenous Bon religion, ending centralised Tibetan rule until the modern era.","up":1480,"dn":58},
  {"id":225,"n":"Tartessos Civilisation","s":-1200,"e":-500,"r":"Lower Guadalquivir, Iberia","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"Tartessos was a wealthy civilisation of the lower Guadalquivir region in southwestern Iberia, known to Greek and Phoenician traders from at least the 8th century BCE as a major source of silver, tin, and copper. Many scholars identify Tartessos with the biblical 'Tarshish', a distant land of fabulous mineral wealth mentioned in the Book of Kings and the Book of Jonah. Its language, recorded in a small number of inscriptions in a distinctive script, remains undeciphered and unclassified. The Tartessian heartland overlaps with the marshlands of Doñana, which some researchers — including Richard Freund's archaeological survey team — have proposed as a candidate location for Plato's Atlantis, linking Tartessos to one of the longest-running debates in classical scholarship.","up":1640,"dn":1240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1200,"e":-500,"label":"Tartessos as the biblical 'Tarshish' — major source of silver and tin for Phoenician and Hebrew trade","source":"1 Kings 10:22; Jonah 1:3; Herodotus and other classical accounts","researcher":null,"up":1040,"dn":480},{"s":-9600,"e":-9600,"label":"Freund survey team — Doñana Marshes (within the Tartessian zone) as a candidate site for Plato's Atlantis","source":"Richard Freund, Atlantis survey project","researcher":"Richard Freund","up":480,"dn":1480}]},
  {"id":226,"n":"Megalithic Temple Culture of Malta","s":-3600,"e":-2500,"r":"Malta and Gozo","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Megalithic Temples of Malta and Gozo — including Ġgantija, Ħaġar Qim, and the underground Hypogeum of Ħal Saflieni — are among the oldest free-standing stone structures in the world, with construction beginning around 3600 BCE, predating the pyramids of Egypt and the great stone circles of Britain by over a millennium. Built by a Neolithic farming population with only stone and bone tools, the temples feature massive megaliths weighing up to 50 tonnes, corbelled roofing, and elaborate carved spirals and animal reliefs. The culture that built them disappeared from the archaeological record around 2500 BCE for reasons that remain unclear, with no convincing evidence of invasion, disease, or environmental collapse identified. All of Malta's megalithic temple sites are inscribed together as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.","up":1840,"dn":72},
  {"id":227,"n":"Thracian Civilisation","s":-1500,"e":46,"r":"Eastern Balkans","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Thracians were an Indo-European people occupying much of the eastern Balkans from the Aegean to the Carpathians, organised into numerous tribal kingdoms of which the Odrysian Kingdom became the most powerful, controlling territory from the Danube to the northern Aegean coast during the 5th–4th centuries BCE. Thracian elites were buried with extraordinary quantities of gold and silver vessels and jewellery, exemplified by hoards such as the Panagyurishte Treasure, reflecting a warrior aristocracy with close trade and cultural ties to neighbouring Greeks, Scythians, and Persians. The Thracians left no extensive written records of their own, and most of what is known comes from Greek and Roman authors and from archaeology. Thracian territory was gradually absorbed into the Roman Empire, becoming the province of Thracia by 46 CE.","up":1040,"dn":48},
  {"id":228,"n":"Doggerland Mesolithic Culture","s":-12000,"e":-6200,"r":"Southern North Sea (submerged)","t":"theorized","cont":"europe","d":"Doggerland was a landmass connecting Britain to continental Europe across what is now the southern North Sea, inhabited by Mesolithic hunter-gatherer communities for thousands of years before being progressively flooded by post-glacial sea level rise. Fishing trawlers have recovered tens of thousands of animal bones, worked flint tools, and a small number of human remains from the seabed, confirming substantial human occupation of what is now entirely submerged territory. The final drowning of the remaining higher ground is associated with the Storegga Slide tsunami around 6200 BCE, a catastrophic submarine landslide off Norway that would have generated waves capable of devastating Doggerland's coastal settlements within hours. Some researchers have proposed that the loss of Doggerland may be reflected in widespread northern European flood traditions, in parallel with the way Sundaland's drowning is linked to Southeast Asian flood myths.","up":1540,"dn":980,"dateTheories":[{"s":-12000,"e":-6200,"label":"Doggerland progressively submerged by post-glacial sea level rise across the Mesolithic","source":"Europe's Lost World: The Rediscovery of Doggerland (2009) — Gaffney et al.","researcher":"Vincent Gaffney","up":1140,"dn":240},{"s":-6200,"e":-6200,"label":"Storegga Slide tsunami (~6200 BCE) catastrophically inundated Doggerland's final remnants","source":"Quaternary Science Reviews — Storegga Slide tsunami deposit studies","researcher":null,"up":640,"dn":480}]},
  {"id":229,"n":"Kingdom of Saba (Sheba)","s":-1200,"e":275,"r":"Yemen, South Arabia","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Kingdom of Saba, in what is now Yemen, was the dominant power of pre-Islamic South Arabia for much of the 1st millennium BCE, controlling the lucrative overland and maritime trade in frankincense, myrrh, and spices between the Arabian Peninsula, the Horn of Africa, and the Mediterranean world. Its capital Marib was home to the Great Dam of Marib, an enormous irrigation work that sustained agriculture in an arid environment for over a thousand years. Saba is identified in the Hebrew Bible, the Quran, and Ethiopian tradition as the homeland of the Queen of Sheba, whose legendary visit to King Solomon became foundational to Ethiopia's Solomonic dynasty's claimed lineage. Sabaean monumental inscriptions, written in a distinct South Arabian script, provide the primary historical record of the kingdom's political and religious life.","up":1280,"dn":54},
  {"id":230,"n":"Urartu","s":-860,"e":-590,"r":"Lake Van Region, Eastern Anatolia","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"Urartu was an Iron Age kingdom centred on the mountainous region around Lake Van in eastern Anatolia, a formidable rival to the Assyrian Empire for control of trade routes and metal resources in the southern Caucasus. Urartian engineers built an extensive network of fortresses, canals, and irrigation channels — some of which, such as the Shamiram Canal near Van, remained in use for over two and a half thousand years. The Urartian language, written in a cuneiform script adapted from Assyrian, is closely related to Hurrian and forms its own small linguistic family with no surviving descendants. Repeated Assyrian campaigns weakened Urartu over the 8th–7th centuries BCE, and the kingdom was finally overrun by Median and Scythian incursions around 590 BCE.","up":840,"dn":42},
  {"id":231,"n":"Median Empire","s":-678,"e":-549,"r":"Iranian Plateau","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Median Empire was a major Iron Age power of the Iranian plateau, formed from a confederation of Median tribes that, in alliance with Babylon, decisively defeated the Assyrian Empire and destroyed its capital Nineveh in 612 BCE. For roughly six decades the Medes controlled an empire stretching from central Anatolia to the eastern Iranian plateau, with its capital traditionally placed at Ecbatana (modern Hamadan). Median religious practice is closely associated with the early development of Zoroastrianism, and Median priests (magi) became influential figures in the later Achaemenid Persian court. The Median Empire was absorbed by Cyrus the Great around 550 BCE, but Median nobility, administrative practices, and religious traditions were carried forward largely intact into the Achaemenid Empire that followed.","up":920,"dn":46},
  {"id":232,"n":"Aboriginal Australian Civilisation","s":-65000,"e":1788,"r":"Australian Continent","t":"confirmed","cont":"pacific","d":"Aboriginal Australians represent the oldest continuous living culture on Earth, with archaeological evidence of human occupation of the Australian continent extending back at least 65,000 years, and an oral tradition — the Dreaming — that encodes ecological, navigational, and historical knowledge across an unbroken chain of transmission of extraordinary length. Hundreds of distinct language groups developed sophisticated land management practices, including fire-stick farming that shaped entire ecosystems, alongside extensive trade networks (songlines) connecting communities across the continent. Some Aboriginal oral traditions describe geographic features and sea-level conditions consistent with periods thousands of years before present, including accounts that appear to describe coastlines as they existed before post-glacial flooding — a claimed example of oral history preserving genuine deep-time environmental memory. The Dreaming continues to underpin Aboriginal law, kinship, and relationship to land into the present day.","up":2240,"dn":84},
  {"id":233,"n":"Māori Civilisation (Aotearoa)","s":1250,"e":1840,"r":"New Zealand / Aotearoa","t":"confirmed","cont":"pacific","d":"The Māori are the descendants of Polynesian voyagers who reached Aotearoa (New Zealand) in a series of ocean migrations beginning around 1250–1300 CE, navigating thousands of kilometres of open Pacific Ocean using wayfinding techniques based on stars, swells, winds, and bird flight paths without instruments. On arrival, Māori encountered a temperate environment radically different from their tropical Polynesian homelands, leading to rapid cultural adaptation — including the development of fortified hilltop villages (pā) — and the extinction of the giant flightless moa within a few centuries of settlement through overhunting. Māori society was organised into iwi (tribes) and hapū (sub-tribes) tracing descent from named ancestral canoes (waka), a genealogical framework (whakapapa) that remains central to Māori identity today. Sustained European contact from the late 18th century, and the 1840 Treaty of Waitangi with the British Crown, marked the beginning of a colonial period whose interpretation remains a live constitutional and political issue in New Zealand.","up":1140,"dn":48},
  {"id":234,"n":"Bimini Road (Atlantis Bahamas)","s":-10000,"e":-9600,"r":"North Bimini, Bahamas","t":"theorized","cont":"atlantic","d":"The Bimini Road is a roughly 0.5km linear formation of large, flat limestone blocks lying just below the surface of the seabed off North Bimini in the Bahamas, discovered by divers in 1968. American psychic Edgar Cayce had predicted in readings given during the 1930s and 1940s that a remnant of Atlantis would 'rise again' near Bimini around 1968–1969, and the formation's discovery shortly after was widely publicised as a fulfilment of that prediction. Mainstream geologists who have studied the formation describe it as 'beachrock' — a natural feature formed by the cementation of beach sediments along ancient shorelines, subsequently fractured into the blocky, road-like pattern by natural jointing. The site remains one of the most visited and most debated locations associated with the Atlantis legend, and is one of the seed locations in Tempus Linea's Atlantis heat map.","up":1840,"dn":2640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-10000,"e":-9600,"label":"Cayce readings (1930s–1940s) predicted a remnant of Atlantis would rise near Bimini around 1968–1969","source":"Edgar Cayce Readings, Association for Research and Enlightenment archives","researcher":"Edgar Cayce","up":840,"dn":1640},{"s":-3000,"e":-1000,"label":"Mainstream geology — Bimini Road is naturally-formed Holocene beachrock, fractured by tidal jointing","source":"Marine geology surveys (various, 1970s–2000s)","researcher":null,"up":1240,"dn":480}]},
  {"id":235,"n":"Olmec Trans-Atlantic Contact Hypothesis","s":-1200,"e":-400,"r":"Gulf Coast, Mexico (theorized contact)","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"The Olmec civilisation of Mexico's Gulf Coast produced colossal stone heads with broad noses and full lips that writer Ivan Van Sertima argued, in They Came Before Columbus (1976), reflect African physiognomy and represent evidence of pre-Columbian transatlantic contact between West Africa and Mesoamerica. Van Sertima's hypothesis drew on claimed similarities in pyramid-building, calendrics, and a small number of disputed iconographic parallels. Mainstream Mesoamerican archaeologists and physical anthropologists have broadly rejected the hypothesis, arguing that the facial features of the colossal heads fall within the normal range of indigenous Mesoamerican populations and that no genetic, linguistic, or material evidence supports transatlantic contact in this period. The debate has nonetheless remained influential in Afrocentric scholarship and popular discussions of pre-Columbian contact theories.","up":1240,"dn":2840,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1200,"e":-400,"label":"Van Sertima — Olmec colossal heads depict African visitors, evidence of pre-Columbian transatlantic contact","source":"They Came Before Columbus (1976)","researcher":"Ivan Van Sertima","up":740,"dn":1840},{"s":-1200,"e":-400,"label":"Mainstream Mesoamericanists — facial features fall within indigenous variation; no genetic or material evidence of African contact","source":"Multiple peer-reviewed rebuttals, American Anthropologist and others","researcher":null,"up":1840,"dn":480}]},
  {"id":236,"n":"Solutrean Hypothesis","s":-21000,"e":-13000,"r":"North Atlantic (theorized crossing)","t":"theorized","cont":"atlantic","d":"The Solutrean Hypothesis, proposed by archaeologists Dennis Stanford and Bruce Bradley, argues that the toolmaking tradition associated with Clovis points in North America derives not from Siberian populations crossing the Bering land bridge but from Solutrean toolmakers of Ice Age Western Europe, who crossed the North Atlantic along the edge of the pack ice roughly 20,000 years ago. The hypothesis rests primarily on perceived technological similarities between European Solutrean blades and North American Clovis points. Genetic studies of ancient and modern Native American populations have consistently found that Indigenous American ancestry derives overwhelmingly from East Asian and Siberian populations via Beringia, with no detectable European genetic contribution from this period — a finding most geneticists consider to effectively rule out the hypothesis. The Solutrean Hypothesis remains a minority position but continues to be discussed in debates over the peopling of the Americas.","up":1640,"dn":2240,"dateTheories":[{"s":-21000,"e":-15000,"label":"Stanford & Bradley — Solutrean toolmakers crossed the Ice Age North Atlantic, ancestral to Clovis technology","source":"Across Atlantic Ice: The Origin of America's Clovis Culture (2012)","researcher":"Dennis Stanford & Bruce Bradley","up":840,"dn":1240},{"s":-20000,"e":-13000,"label":"Ancient DNA studies — Native American ancestry derives from Siberian/Beringian populations, not Western Europe","source":"Multiple Nature/Science ancient DNA studies, 2014–2021","researcher":null,"up":1840,"dn":240}]},
  {"id":237,"n":"Kennewick Man (The Ancient One)","s":-7000,"e":-6500,"r":"Columbia River, Washington State","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"In 1996, skeletal remains discovered along the Columbia River near Kennewick, Washington — and dated to roughly 8,500–9,000 years old — became the centre of one of the most contentious legal and scientific disputes in American archaeology. Initial forensic assessments suggested the skull showed features described at the time as 'Caucasoid', fuelling speculation about early European presence in the Americas and triggering a prolonged legal battle between scientists seeking to study the remains and Native American tribes seeking repatriation under the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act. A 2015 genome study definitively resolved the dispute, finding that the individual — whom affected tribes call 'the Ancient One' — is most closely related to modern Native American populations, particularly the Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation. The remains were repatriated and reburied in 2017, ending a 20-year legal and scientific controversy.","up":1840,"dn":640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-7000,"e":-6500,"label":"1996–1998 forensic assessments suggested possible non-Native physical traits, prompting legal dispute over repatriation","source":"Initial forensic anthropology reports (1996–1998)","researcher":null,"up":480,"dn":1240},{"s":-7000,"e":-6500,"label":"2015 genome sequencing found closest affinity to modern Native American populations, resolving the dispute","source":"Nature (2015) — Rasmussen et al.","researcher":null,"up":1640,"dn":160}]},
  {"id":238,"n":"Longyou Caves Mystery","s":-300,"e":1500,"r":"Zhejiang Province, China","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Longyou Caves are a complex of 24 large, artificially excavated underground caverns discovered in Zhejiang Province, China, in 1992 after local villagers drained a series of ponds that had concealed them for centuries. The caves feature precisely cut walls, regularly spaced parallel chisel marks, and load-bearing pillars and ceiling carvings, representing a vast volume of excavated rock with no historical record of who built them, when, or why. Estimates for their age range from over 2,000 years (Han dynasty or earlier) to a few hundred years (Ming dynasty quarrying), based on differing interpretations of tool marks and regional building-stone use. The absence of any written record referring to a construction project of this scale remains the central puzzle, and the site receives relatively little international attention compared to other large-scale ancient engineering mysteries.","up":1340,"dn":780,"dateTheories":[{"s":-300,"e":200,"label":"Possible Han dynasty or earlier origin, based on certain tool-mark patterns","source":"Regional Chinese archaeological surveys","researcher":null,"up":540,"dn":480},{"s":600,"e":1500,"label":"Alternative dating to medieval/Ming-era quarrying for regional building stone","source":"Zhejiang provincial geological and historical surveys","researcher":null,"up":480,"dn":340}]},
  {"id":239,"n":"Baalbek Megaliths","s":-9000,"e":200,"r":"Beqaa Valley, Lebanon","t":"debated","cont":"middle-east","d":"Baalbek, in Lebanon's Beqaa Valley, is home to the Roman-era Temple of Jupiter, whose podium incorporates the largest dressed stone blocks ever used in construction — the so-called 'Trilithon', three stones each weighing an estimated 800 tonnes, and a nearby unfinished megalith ('the Stone of the Pregnant Woman') weighing over 1,000 tonnes. Mainstream archaeology attributes the Trilithon to Roman-era quarrying and engineering of the 1st century BCE–CE, part of the massive platform built to support the Temple of Jupiter, itself constructed on a site with a long pre-Roman history of cult activity associated with a local Baal deity later identified with the Greek sun god Helios — hence the site's Greek name, Heliopolis. Alternative researchers have argued that stones of this size and precision could not plausibly have been quarried, moved, and placed using the technology and labour organisation typically attributed to the Roman period, and propose that the platform incorporates work from a much older, unidentified building tradition. The unfinished megalith remaining in the adjacent quarry — still attached to bedrock — is cited by both sides of the debate as evidence for how such stones were extracted.","up":2240,"dn":1640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-100,"e":100,"label":"Mainstream archaeology — Trilithon megaliths are Roman-era quarrying for the Temple of Jupiter podium, 1st century BCE–CE","source":"German Archaeological Institute (DAI) Baalbek excavation reports","researcher":null,"up":1640,"dn":640},{"s":-9000,"e":-3000,"label":"Fringe researchers — Trilithon-scale megaliths predate the Roman temple by millennia, possibly incorporated from an earlier structure","source":"Various alternative history sources","researcher":null,"up":840,"dn":1840}]},
  {"id":240,"n":"El Dorado (Lake Guatavita)","s":1490,"e":1638,"r":"Lake Guatavita, Colombia","t":"theorized","cont":"americas","d":"El Dorado — 'the golden one' — began as a specific title for the Muisca zipa (ruler) of the Bogotá region, who according to Spanish chroniclers was ritually covered in gold dust and rowed onto Lake Guatavita to make offerings of gold and emeralds as part of his investiture ceremony. Spanish conquistadors, hearing garbled accounts of this ritual, transformed the title into the legend of a lost golden city, launching numerous expeditions across northern South America — including Gonzalo Pizarro's and Francisco de Orellana's descent of the Amazon — in search of a city that never existed in the form they imagined. Several attempts were made to drain Lake Guatavita itself during the colonial and early modern periods, recovering genuine Muisca gold offerings but nothing resembling a city. The El Dorado legend nonetheless became one of the most powerful drivers of European exploration of the South American interior, indirectly shaping the colonial map of the continent.","up":1640,"dn":840,"dateTheories":[{"s":1490,"e":1540,"label":"Spanish chroniclers record the Muisca zipa investiture ritual at Lake Guatavita as the origin of the El Dorado legend","source":"Juan Rodríguez Freyle, El Carnero (1638)","researcher":null,"up":1040,"dn":240}]},
  {"id":241,"n":"Kingdom of Kerma","s":-2500,"e":-1504,"r":"Upper Nubia, Sudan","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Kerma was the first indigenous African kingdom of historical scale, flourishing in Upper Nubia for nearly a millennium before Egyptian conquest. Its capital at Kerma featured massive mudbrick funerary tumuli — the largest in Africa — and a distinct ceramic tradition of world-class quality known as Kerma ware. The Kerma polity controlled the lucrative trade corridor between sub-Saharan Africa and Egypt, exchanging gold, ivory, ebony and slaves. Egyptian pharaohs of the Middle Kingdom simultaneously traded with and fought Kerma, viewing it as a major rival power before Thutmose I's campaign ended its independence around 1504 BCE.","up":920,"dn":180},
  {"id":242,"n":"Jolof Empire","s":1350,"e":1549,"r":"Senegal-Gambia region, West Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Jolof Empire was a West African confederation of Wolof-speaking states that dominated the Senegambian region from the mid-14th century. At its height it exercised tributary authority over five subordinate kingdoms — Cayor, Baol, Sine, Saloum and Walo — and controlled trans-Saharan trade routes connecting the Sahel to Atlantic coastal communities. Portuguese navigators made first European contact in the 1440s, and their arrival ultimately destabilised Jolof by giving coastal kingdoms direct access to Atlantic trade, bypassing Jolof's control. The empire fragmented in the mid-16th century when Cayor broke away following the Battle of Danki.","up":780,"dn":140},
  {"id":243,"n":"Igbo-Ukwu","s":850,"e":1000,"r":"Southeastern Nigeria","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Igbo-Ukwu is an archaeological site in southeastern Nigeria that revealed a sophisticated bronze-casting tradition of extraordinary refinement, dating to the 9th–10th centuries CE — predating the better-known Benin and Ife bronze traditions by centuries. Excavated by Thurstan Shaw in 1959 and 1964, the site yielded ceremonial bronze vessels, regalia, and over 100,000 glass and carnelian beads, suggesting far-reaching trade connections extending to North Africa and possibly the Middle East. The bronzes were cast using the lost-wax technique at a level of technical mastery that challenges earlier assumptions about the independent development of metallurgy in sub-Saharan Africa.","up":1040,"dn":220},
  {"id":244,"n":"Zagwe Dynasty / Lalibela","s":900,"e":1270,"r":"Ethiopian Highlands","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Zagwe Dynasty ruled highland Ethiopia from approximately the 10th to 13th centuries, maintaining Christian continuity after the decline of Aksum and producing one of the most remarkable architectural achievements in African history: the rock-hewn churches of Lalibela. King Lalibela ordered the carving of eleven monolithic churches directly from living volcanic rock, including the famous Bete Giyorgis — a perfectly cruciform structure sunk into a deep pit. Lalibela was conceived as a New Jerusalem for Ethiopian pilgrims unable to reach the Holy Land and remains an active pilgrimage site to this day.","up":1380,"dn":280},
  {"id":245,"n":"Hausa Kingdoms / Kano","s":700,"e":1804,"r":"Northern Nigeria / Niger","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Hausa city-states of northern Nigeria — Kano, Katsina, Zaria, Gobir and Daura among the most significant — formed one of the most durable urban and commercial networks in sub-Saharan Africa. Founded according to tradition by descendants of the legendary hero Bayajidda, these walled cities developed sophisticated governance, Islamic scholarship, textile production, and long-distance trade connecting the Sahel to North Africa. The Fulani jihad of Usman dan Fodio ended independent Hausa rule in 1804, transforming the states into emirates of the Sokoto Caliphate.","up":960,"dn":200},
  {"id":246,"n":"Kingdom of Lunda","s":1665,"e":1887,"r":"Central Africa (DRC/Angola/Zambia)","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Lunda Empire was a powerful Central African state that expanded from its origins in the Katanga region to control a vast territory spanning modern DRC, Angola and Zambia. Founded by the mwant yav Naweej around 1665, Lunda's political system incorporated local chiefs into a hierarchical tribute system that allowed cultural autonomy while extracting trade goods including copper, salt and slaves. Its eastern offshoot, the Kazembe Kingdom, maintained direct trade contact with Portuguese traders from Mozambique. The empire declined under pressure from internal fragmentation and Belgian colonisation in the late 19th century.","up":820,"dn":160},
  {"id":247,"n":"Carnac Megaliths","s":-4500,"e":-2500,"r":"Brittany, France","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"The Carnac alignments in Brittany comprise the largest concentration of megalithic standing stones in the world — over 3,000 menhirs arranged in parallel rows stretching for several kilometres, erected between approximately 4500 and 2500 BCE by Neolithic communities. The purpose of the alignments remains genuinely uncertain: astronomical observatory, processional avenue, territorial marker, and monument to the dead have all been proposed. Some stones weigh over 350 tonnes and were transported considerable distances, demonstrating organisational capacity comparable to other major Neolithic monument traditions. Alexander Thom's surveys proposed precise astronomical alignments, though these remain debated among archaeoastronomers.","up":1240,"dn":380,"dateTheories":[{"s":-4500,"e":-2500,"label":"Mainstream archaeology — construction phased over two millennia by Neolithic communities; primary use ceremonial and territorial","source":"Serge Cassen, CNRS megalith surveys (2009–present)","researcher":null,"up":1040,"dn":280},{"s":-4500,"e":-2500,"label":"Alexander Thom — alignments encode a precise megalithic yard unit and solar/lunar astronomical calendar","source":"Thom, Megalithic Sites in Britain (1967)","researcher":"Alexander Thom","up":640,"dn":540}]},
  {"id":248,"n":"Únětice Culture / Nebra Sky Disk","s":-2300,"e":-1550,"r":"Central Europe (Germany/Czech Republic)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Únětice culture was a Central European Bronze Age complex renowned above all for the Nebra Sky Disk — discovered in 1999 near Nebra, Germany, and dated to approximately 1600 BCE. The disk is the oldest known realistic representation of the night sky, depicting the sun or full moon, a crescent moon, the Pleiades star cluster, and what appear to be a solar ship and horizon arcs. The Únětice culture produced sophisticated bronze and gold metallurgy and was embedded in long-distance exchange networks reaching Scandinavia, Britain and the Mediterranean. The Nebra disk likely served a calendrical function, allowing farmers and ritual specialists to reconcile lunar and solar time-keeping.","up":1560,"dn":220},
  {"id":249,"n":"Bell Beaker Culture","s":-2800,"e":-1800,"r":"Western Europe (Atlantic to Danube)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Bell Beaker culture was a widespread late Neolithic/Early Bronze Age phenomenon defined by a characteristic bell-shaped pottery vessel that spread rapidly across Atlantic Europe from Portugal to Hungary between approximately 2800 and 1800 BCE. Recent ancient DNA analysis has shown that the spread of Bell Beaker material culture into Britain was accompanied by a near-total population replacement — up to 90% of Britain's Neolithic gene pool displaced by incoming Beaker-associated peoples within a few centuries. The Bell Beaker phenomenon is associated with the final phase of Stonehenge's construction, individual burial rites replacing communal tomb use, and early metallurgy in copper and gold.","up":1280,"dn":240},
  {"id":250,"n":"Nuragic Civilization","s":-1800,"e":-238,"r":"Sardinia, Italy","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"The Nuragic civilization of Sardinia erected over 7,000 nuraghi — massive Bronze Age stone towers unique in the ancient Mediterranean — between approximately 1800 and 900 BCE, making it one of the densest concentrations of prehistoric monuments on Earth. The nuraghi served simultaneously as residential towers, defensive strongholds, and possibly ritual centres, and Nuragic communities maintained extensive trade networks with Mycenaean Greece, Cyprus and the Levant. Alternative researcher Sergio Frau has controversially argued that Sardinia was the site of Plato's Atlantis and that the Pillars of Hercules were originally at the Sicilian Strait. Nuragic culture persisted into the Roman period before gradual assimilation.","up":1160,"dn":420,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1800,"e":-900,"label":"Mainstream archaeology — Bronze Age indigenous Sardinian culture; nuraghi are defensive/residential towers; Phoenician and Carthaginian contacts well documented","source":"Giovanni Ugas, University of Cagliari (2005)","researcher":null,"up":980,"dn":320},{"s":-1200,"e":-1000,"label":"Sergio Frau — Sardinia is Plato's Atlantis; Pillars of Hercules originally at the Sicilian Strait; Nuragic collapse c.1200 BCE corresponds to Atlantis's destruction","source":"Frau, Le Colonne d'Ercole (2002)","researcher":"Sergio Frau","up":480,"dn":840}]},
  {"id":251,"n":"Xia Dynasty","s":-2070,"e":-1600,"r":"Yellow River basin, China","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Xia Dynasty is the first dynasty described in traditional Chinese historiography, said to have been founded by the legendary flood-controller Yu the Great around 2070 BCE and lasting seventeen generations before conquest by the Shang. For most of the 20th century Western archaeologists regarded Xia as legendary, but the Erlitou archaeological site in Henan province has been proposed as a major Xia capital, featuring palatial structures, bronze foundries and a sophisticated material culture predating the confirmed Shang period. Whether Erlitou represents the Xia or an earlier proto-Shang culture remains debated, and no writing contemporary with the supposed Xia period has been recovered.","up":1380,"dn":540,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2070,"e":-1600,"label":"Chinese historiography — Xia founded by Yu the Great c.2070 BCE; Erlitou phase III–IV corresponds to late Xia capitals","source":"Xia-Shang-Zhou Chronology Project (2000)","researcher":null,"up":980,"dn":440},{"s":-1900,"e":-1600,"label":"Sceptical archaeology — Erlitou is a regional Bronze Age culture; 'Xia' may be a later political myth; no contemporaneous written confirmation","source":"Bagley, Cambridge History of Ancient China (1999)","researcher":null,"up":540,"dn":640}]},
  {"id":252,"n":"Mehrgarh","s":-7000,"e":-2500,"r":"Balochistan, Pakistan","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Mehrgarh is one of the most important Neolithic sites in South Asia, demonstrating continuous occupation from approximately 7000 to 2500 BCE and providing the earliest evidence for farming and herding in the region. Excavations by Jean-François Jarrige revealed mud-brick structures, wheat and barley cultivation, zebu cattle domestication, and an early tradition of bead manufacture using lapis lazuli and carnelian — luxury goods that would become hallmarks of the later Indus Valley Civilization. Mehrgarh also produced the earliest evidence of proto-dentistry in the world: drilled molar teeth from c.7000–5500 BCE. The cultural sequence at Mehrgarh is considered a direct precursor to the Indus Valley Civilisation's mature urban phase.","up":1180,"dn":160},
  {"id":253,"n":"Jiroft Civilization","s":-2500,"e":-2000,"r":"Kerman Province, Iran","t":"debated","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Jiroft civilization is a proposed Bronze Age culture of the Iranian plateau, identified primarily through distinctive chlorite and alabaster luxury vessels that appeared on the antiquities market following flooding in the Halil Rūd valley of Kerman Province in the early 2000s. Iranian archaeologist Yousef Majidzadeh led excavations and proposed Jiroft as the lost land of Aratta mentioned in Sumerian texts — a wealthy, distant civilization that traded with early Sumer. The looting context of most Jiroft objects makes their dating and cultural attribution genuinely uncertain, and mainstream archaeologists remain cautious about the more expansive claims.","up":940,"dn":380,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2500,"e":-2000,"label":"Majidzadeh — Jiroft is the Sumerian Aratta; a major Bronze Age civilization independent of but contemporary with Mesopotamia","source":"Majidzadeh, Iran vol. 41 (2003)","researcher":"Yousef Majidzadeh","up":640,"dn":480},{"s":-2500,"e":-2000,"label":"Sceptical view — Jiroft objects are a looted regional Bronze Age assemblage; Aratta identification is speculative; stratigraphic context largely destroyed","source":"Lamberg-Karlovsky, Iranica Antiqua (2003)","researcher":null,"up":480,"dn":580}]},
  {"id":254,"n":"Mitanni Kingdom","s":-1600,"e":-1260,"r":"Upper Mesopotamia / Northern Syria","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Mitanni were a powerful Late Bronze Age kingdom controlling northern Mesopotamia and Syria from approximately 1600 to 1260 BCE, with their capital at Wassukanni. Their ruling elite bore Indo-Aryan names and invoked Vedic deities — Mitra, Varuna, Indra, Nasatya — in diplomatic treaties, making them a crucial linguistic bridge between the Indo-European migrations and the ancient Near East. Mitanni was a major rival of Egypt during the 18th Dynasty and a competitor of the Hittites, eventually becoming a vassal of Assyria. The famous horse-training manual of Kikkuli, written in Hittite but with Mitanni technical terms, is the earliest known systematic text on horse training.","up":1240,"dn":200},
  {"id":255,"n":"Gojoseon","s":-2333,"e":-108,"r":"Korean Peninsula / Manchuria","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"Gojoseon is the first Korean kingdom described in traditional historiography, said to have been founded in 2333 BCE by the legendary figure Dangun Wanggeom — born of a bear-woman and the son of the divine Hwanung. Conservative modern archaeology places its historical emergence in the early first millennium BCE, with the Lolang Commandery confirming a recognisable polity in the northern Korean peninsula by the 4th–3rd centuries BCE. The tension between the legendary founding date and the archaeological record makes Gojoseon a politically sensitive topic in Korean historiography.","up":1040,"dn":340,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2333,"e":-2333,"label":"Korean traditional historiography — Dangun founds Gojoseon in 2333 BCE; treated as historical in Samguk Yusa (1281 CE)","source":"Iryeon, Samguk Yusa (1281)","researcher":null,"up":540,"dn":640},{"s":-400,"e":-108,"label":"Conservative archaeology — Gojoseon emerges as a recognisable Iron Age polity in the early first millennium BCE; no evidence of a 3rd-millennium state","source":"Barnes, State Formation in Korea (2001)","researcher":null,"up":780,"dn":320}]},
  {"id":256,"n":"Dvaravati","s":550,"e":1000,"r":"Central Thailand","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Dvaravati was a Mon Buddhist polity that flourished in the lower Chao Phraya basin of Thailand from approximately the 6th to 11th centuries CE, representing one of the earliest Indianised kingdoms of mainland Southeast Asia. Known through Chinese pilgrim accounts and its distinctive stone Dharmachakras (Wheels of the Law), Dvaravati produced sophisticated Buddha imagery blending Indian Gupta aesthetics with local Mon artistic traditions. Its major centres at Nakhon Pathom, U Thong and Lopburi were important nodes in the transmission of Theravada Buddhism across the region. Dvaravati was gradually absorbed by the expanding Khmer Empire between the 9th and 11th centuries.","up":880,"dn":180},
  {"id":257,"n":"Ebla","s":-3000,"e":-1600,"r":"Northwestern Syria","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"Ebla was a major Bronze Age city-state in northwestern Syria that reached its peak between approximately 2400 and 2300 BCE, when its archive of over 17,000 cuneiform tablets was buried following destruction — probably by Naram-Sin of Akkad. The Ebla tablets, discovered by Paolo Matthiae from 1974, revealed a sophisticated palace economy, diplomatic correspondence with Mesopotamian cities, a bilingual Sumerian-Eblaite lexicon, and a distinct Semitic language ancestral to later Northwest Semitic tongues. Ebla recovered and continued as a significant city until final destruction by the Hittites around 1600 BCE.","up":1320,"dn":240},
  {"id":258,"n":"Lydia","s":-685,"e":-547,"r":"Western Anatolia (modern Turkey)","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Kingdom of Lydia, with its capital at Sardis, is credited with one of the most consequential inventions in economic history: the world's first true coinage, produced from electrum around 600 BCE under King Alyattes or his successor Croesus. Lydia sat at the crossroads of Aegean Greek and Persian cultural worlds, and its legendary wealth — the phrase 'rich as Croesus' — derived from the gold-bearing Pactolus River and the kingdom's commercial dominance of western Anatolian trade routes. Croesus's famous misreading of the Delphic Oracle's prophecy led him to attack Persia, resulting in Achaemenid conquest in 547 BCE. The Lydian language remains only partially deciphered.","up":1480,"dn":200},
  {"id":259,"n":"Gunung Padang","s":-3000,"e":-1000,"r":"West Java, Indonesia","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"Gunung Padang is a megalithic terraced site in West Java, Indonesia, traditionally dated to approximately 500–1500 CE based on the uppermost visible stone columns. A 2018–2023 research programme led by geologist Danny Hilman Natawidjaja conducted drilling and subsurface scanning and claimed to have identified buried construction layers reaching back to 25,000 BCE — which would make it the oldest known megalithic structure in the world by a vast margin. These findings were published in Archaeological Prospection in 2023 but attracted serious methodological criticism, and the journal issued an Expression of Concern. Graham Hancock featured Gunung Padang prominently in Ancient Apocalypse (2022).","up":1640,"dn":980,"dateTheories":[{"s":-500,"e":1500,"label":"Indonesian mainstream archaeology — uppermost terrace is an Iron Age megalithic site; no reliable evidence of construction before 1000 BCE","source":"Indonesian Archaeological Centre, field assessment (2014)","researcher":null,"up":840,"dn":480},{"s":-25000,"e":-8000,"label":"Natawidjaja et al. — drilling data indicates buried construction layers dating to 25,000–14,000 BCE, predating the Younger Dryas by millennia","source":"Natawidjaja et al., Archaeological Prospection (2023, Expression of Concern issued)","researcher":"Danny Hilman Natawidjaja","up":980,"dn":1240}]},
  {"id":260,"n":"White Sands Footprints","s":-23000,"e":-21000,"r":"New Mexico, USA","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"In 2021, a team led by Matthew Bennett published in Science a study of fossilised human footprints at White Sands National Park, New Mexico, arguing they dated to between 21,000 and 23,000 years ago — making them the oldest confirmed evidence of humans in the Americas by at least 6,000 years. The dating relied on radiocarbon dates from aquatic plant seeds embedded in the footprint layers. Critics pointed to a potential reservoir effect in aquatic plants, but a follow-up 2023 study using conifer pollen and mammoth grass seeds corroborated the original dates.","up":1840,"dn":640,"dateTheories":[{"s":-23000,"e":-21000,"label":"Bennett et al. — seed radiocarbon and corroborating pollen dates confirm human presence at White Sands 21,000–23,000 BP during the Last Glacial Maximum","source":"Bennett et al., Science (2021); Springer et al., Science (2023)","researcher":"Matthew Bennett","up":1240,"dn":440},{"s":-16000,"e":-13000,"label":"Reservoir effect hypothesis — aquatic plant seeds absorbed old carbon; footprints may be younger and consistent with established Clovis-era peopling dates","source":"Critic responses, Science (2022)","researcher":null,"up":540,"dn":840}]},
  {"id":261,"n":"Chinchorro Culture","s":-7000,"e":-1500,"r":"Atacama coast, Chile/Peru","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Chinchorro people of the Atacama coast practised the world's oldest intentional mummification tradition, beginning around 7000 BCE — nearly 3,500 years before Egyptian mummification emerged. Their techniques were extraordinarily sophisticated, involving dismemberment, organ removal and preservation, skeletal reinforcement with sticks and clay, and application of manganese-black or red ochre paste. The Chinchorro were coastal fisher-gatherers rather than agriculturalists, demonstrating that elaborate mortuary practice is not contingent on sedentary farming. UNESCO inscribed the Chinchorro mummies and sites as a World Heritage property in 2021.","up":1560,"dn":200},
  {"id":262,"n":"Casas Grandes / Paquimé","s":700,"e":1450,"r":"Chihuahua, Mexico","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Paquimé (Casas Grandes) was the largest and most complex prehistoric settlement in northern Mexico, reaching its peak between 1200 and 1450 CE. The city contained hundreds of rooms in multi-storey adobe compounds, a water management system with reservoirs and canals, T-shaped doorways echoing Chacoan architecture, and evidence of macaw-breeding for feather trade with Mesoamerican markets. Paquimé served as a major redistribution hub connecting the American Southwest, the Gulf of California, and Mesoamerica, trading turquoise, copper bells, shell ornaments and macaw feathers over vast distances. The city was abandoned around 1450 CE, possibly due to drought or conflict.","up":1180,"dn":220},
  {"id":263,"n":"Fremont Culture","s":400,"e":1350,"r":"Utah / Colorado, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Fremont culture was a prehistoric agricultural and foraging tradition occupying the eastern Great Basin and Colorado Plateau from approximately 400 to 1350 CE, contemporary with but distinct from the Ancestral Puebloans to the south. Fremont communities were notably flexible — some were fully sedentary maize farmers building pit houses and granaries, while others maintained a more mobile foraging lifestyle, reflecting adaptation to the highly variable environments of the Great Basin. They produced distinctive one-rod-and-bundle basketry, unique unfired clay figurines with trapezoidal bodies, and elaborate rock art including the iconic large-headed anthropomorphic figures of the Barrier Canyon style.","up":880,"dn":160},
  {"id":264,"n":"Watson Brake","s":-3500,"e":-2800,"r":"Louisiana, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Watson Brake in northern Louisiana is the oldest known mound complex in North America, constructed by hunter-gatherer communities between approximately 3500 and 2800 BCE — predating the Poverty Point complex by nearly 2,000 years. The site consists of eleven earthen mounds connected by ridges forming an oval approximately 280 metres in diameter, built without evidence of agriculture or permanent settlement. The builders were mobile hunter-gatherers who returned seasonally to construct and use the site over many generations, demonstrating that complex social organisation capable of coordinating large public works is not exclusively associated with agricultural societies.","up":1380,"dn":200},
  {"id":265,"n":"Diquís Stone Spheres","s":-600,"e":1500,"r":"Diquís Delta, Costa Rica","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"The stone spheres of the Diquís Delta in southern Costa Rica are among the most enigmatic archaeological objects in the Americas — hundreds of nearly perfect granite and gabbro spheres ranging from a few centimetres to over 2 metres in diameter and weighing up to 16 tonnes. Produced by the Isthmo-Colombian peoples between approximately 600 BCE and 1500 CE, their purpose remains unclear. Theories include territorial markers, status symbols, astronomical alignments, and funerary objects. The manufacturing technique — controlled fracturing, pecking and grinding — was sophisticated. UNESCO inscribed the spheres as a World Heritage property in 2014.","up":1280,"dn":380,"dateTheories":[{"s":-600,"e":1500,"label":"Mainstream archaeology — Diquís culture production spanning multiple phases; status markers or territorial objects; manufacturing by controlled fracture and abrasion","source":"Hoopes & Fonseca, Dumbarton Oaks Pre-Columbian Studies (2003)","researcher":null,"up":980,"dn":260},{"s":-1000,"e":-600,"label":"Alternative researchers — some spheres may be significantly older; possible astronomical alignment function; manufacturing technique not fully explained","source":"Various alternative history sources","researcher":null,"up":440,"dn":680}]},
  {"id":266,"n":"Yap Stone Money Culture","s":500,"e":1900,"r":"Yap Island, Micronesia","t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"The Yapese of Micronesia developed one of the most distinctive monetary systems in human history: rai stones — large discs of aragonite limestone, some over 3 metres in diameter and weighing 4 tonnes, quarried on Palau some 400 kilometres away and transported across open ocean by canoe. What made the system remarkable was that ownership and transaction were recorded purely through oral social consensus — a rai stone need not move physically; its ownership could transfer through community acknowledgement alone. Economists have noted this as an early example of a ledger-based monetary system analogous in principle to modern electronic banking.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":267,"n":"Beringia Migration Culture","s":-20000,"e":-10000,"r":"Bering Land Bridge / Alaska","t":"theorized","cont":"americas","d":"Beringia — the land bridge connecting Siberia to Alaska during glacial sea-level lowstands — was not merely a crossing point but a vast subcontinent spanning roughly 1,600 kilometres north to south, supporting mammoth, bison, horse and human populations for thousands of years. The Beringian Standstill Hypothesis, supported by mitochondrial DNA analysis, proposes that the founding population of the Americas was isolated in Beringia for up to 15,000 years before expanding south. Alternative models propose a coastal kelp-highway migration along the Pacific coast, potentially accounting for pre-Clovis sites in South America.","up":1480,"dn":320,"dateTheories":[{"s":-20000,"e":-15000,"label":"Beringian Standstill Hypothesis — founding population isolated in Beringia ~15,000 years before expanding south through the ice-free corridor c.15,000 BP","source":"Tamm et al., PLoS ONE (2007)","researcher":null,"up":1040,"dn":340},{"s":-20000,"e":-16000,"label":"Pacific Coastal Route — kelp-highway migration predates or parallels the inland corridor; explains Triquet Island (14,000 BP) and South American pre-Clovis sites","source":"McLachlan et al., Quaternary Science Reviews (2005)","researcher":null,"up":880,"dn":420}]},
  {"id":268,"n":"Hattian Civilization","s":-2500,"e":-1800,"r":"Central Anatolia (Turkey)","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Hattians were the pre-Indo-European indigenous inhabitants of central Anatolia, predating the Hittites who adopted their name, many of their gods, and elements of their ceremonial traditions. The Hattian language — known from ritual and mythological texts in the Hittite archives at Hattusa — is a language isolate with no known relatives, suggesting the Hattians were among the earliest settled communities of the Anatolian plateau. Their religious mythology, preserved through Hittite scribal transmission, includes storm god narratives, seasonal disappearance myths, and a rich pantheon that incoming Hittites deliberately incorporated into their state religion.","up":980,"dn":180},
  {"id":269,"n":"Balhae / Parhae","s":698,"e":926,"r":"Manchuria / Russian Far East / Korea","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Balhae was a multi-ethnic state established in 698 CE in the aftermath of Goguryeo's destruction by the Tang-Silla alliance, founded by Dae Joyeong and encompassing Manchuria, the Russian Far East and northern Korea. At its height Balhae maintained a sophisticated bureaucratic system modelled on Tang administrative practices and produced fine metalwork and ceramics of high quality. The kingdom is a point of ongoing historiographical dispute between China and Korea regarding its ethnic and political character. Balhae was destroyed by the Khitan Liao Dynasty in 926 CE.","up":1020,"dn":220},
  {"id":270,"n":"Tarim Basin Mummies","s":-2000,"e":-200,"r":"Xinjiang, China (Tarim Basin)","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Tarim Basin mummies are exceptionally well-preserved Bronze and Iron Age human remains found in the Taklamakan Desert of Xinjiang, many exhibiting features long associated in popular discussion with European or Central Asian origin. A landmark 2021 ancient DNA study in Nature demonstrated that the earliest Tarim Basin individuals (c.2000 BCE) were genetically isolated — descended from an Ancient North Eurasian population with no detectable gene flow from surrounding Bronze Age cultures. Later populations show gene flow from neighbouring cultures consistent with the region's role as a Silk Road crossroads.","up":1640,"dn":380,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2000,"e":-1500,"label":"2021 ancient DNA — earliest Tarim individuals are a genetically isolated Ancient North Eurasian population; no direct connection to European or steppe Bronze Age cultures","source":"Zhang et al., Nature (2021)","researcher":null,"up":1240,"dn":280},{"s":-2000,"e":-1500,"label":"Earlier Tocharian hypothesis — mummies were Indo-European Tocharian speakers migrating from the Pontic steppe; explains shared textile and linguistic features","source":"Mallory & Mair, The Tarim Mummies (2000)","researcher":null,"up":680,"dn":640}]},
  {"id":272,"n":"Poverty Point","s":-1700,"e":-1100,"r":"Louisiana, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Poverty Point is a monumental earthwork complex in northeastern Louisiana constructed between approximately 1700 and 1100 BCE by a hunter-gatherer society with no evidence of agriculture — making it one of the most sophisticated non-agricultural monument complexes in the ancient world. The site features six concentric C-shaped earthen ridges spanning nearly 2 kilometres in diameter, a large central mound, and several satellite mounds arranged with apparent geometric precision. Poverty Point was a major long-distance trade hub, receiving copper from the Great Lakes, soapstone from the Appalachians, and chert from the Ozarks. UNESCO inscribed it as a World Heritage property in 2014.","up":1360,"dn":200},
  {"id":273,"n":"Mapungubwe","s":900,"e":1300,"r":"Limpopo Valley, South Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Mapungubwe was the first complex state-level society in southern Africa, flourishing in the Limpopo Valley between approximately 900 and 1300 CE. The ruling elite occupied a hilltop enclosure and were buried with extraordinary gold grave goods — including a famous gold rhinoceros figurine — demonstrating metalworking sophistication and hierarchical social stratification. Mapungubwe controlled Indian Ocean trade in gold and ivory, connecting interior African production with Swahili coast merchants and ultimately with Arabia and India. Its collapse is attributed to a prolonged drought that undermined the agricultural base, and it was succeeded by the Great Zimbabwe state.","up":1240,"dn":200},
  {"id":274,"n":"Tiwanaku","s":-200,"e":1000,"r":"Lake Titicaca Basin, Bolivia","t":"debated","cont":"americas","d":"Tiwanaku was a major pre-Columbian state centred on Lake Titicaca at 3,800 metres altitude in modern Bolivia, exerting cultural and political influence across the south-central Andes between approximately 300 and 1000 CE. Its monumental architecture — including the Akapana pyramid, the Kalasasaya platform with its Gateway of the Sun, and the semi-subterranean Putuni temple — features massive blocks fitted with extraordinary precision. Arthur Posnansky controversially dated Tiwanaku to 15,000 BCE based on astronomical alignments, a claim rejected by mainstream archaeology but influential in alternative history circles. Tiwanaku's raised field agricultural system (suka kollus) transformed waterlogged plains into productive farmland.","up":1480,"dn":560,"dateTheories":[{"s":-200,"e":1000,"label":"Mainstream archaeology — Tiwanaku emerges c.200 BCE, peaks 500–900 CE; stratigraphic and radiocarbon dating consistent with pre-Columbian Andean sequence","source":"Janusek, Ancient Tiwanaku (2008)","researcher":null,"up":1080,"dn":360},{"s":-15000,"e":-13000,"label":"Arthur Posnansky — astronomical alignments of Kalasasaya indicate construction c.15,000 BCE","source":"Posnansky, Tiahuanacu (1945)","researcher":"Arthur Posnansky","up":540,"dn":880}]},
  {"id":281,"n":"Yamnaya Culture","s":-3500,"e":-2200,"r":"Pontic-Caspian Steppe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Yamnaya culture of the Pontic-Caspian steppe is now understood through ancient DNA analysis to have been one of the most consequential migrations in human prehistory. Between approximately 3000 and 2500 BCE, Yamnaya-related populations expanded westward into Europe and eastward into South Asia, contributing a massive genetic ancestry component to most present-day Europeans and South Asians. They are believed to have carried Proto-Indo-European language and introduced horse-riding, wheeled vehicles, and pastoral nomadism to previously farming-dominated Europe. The Yamnaya expansion likely contributed to the cultural disruption visible in the European Neolithic archaeological record around 3000 BCE.","up":1680,"dn":260},
  {"id":282,"n":"Sanxingdui","s":-1700,"e":-1100,"r":"Sichuan Province, China","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Sanxingdui, discovered accidentally in 1929 and excavated systematically from 1986, revealed a Bronze Age civilisation in the Sichuan basin contemporary with the Shang Dynasty but entirely distinct from it. Its most famous objects include enormous bronze masks with protruding eyes, a nearly 4-metre bronze standing figure, a bronze tree over 3 metres tall, and elephant tusks in vast quantities. Sanxingdui has no contemporary writing, making its language, mythology and political structure almost entirely unknown. The 2020–2021 excavations of six new sacrificial pits yielded thousands of additional artefacts and confirmed Sanxingdui as one of the defining mysteries of Chinese archaeology.","up":1780,"dn":280},
  {"id":284,"n":"Sogdian Civilisation","s":-600,"e":1000,"r":"Central Asia (Uzbekistan/Tajikistan)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Sogdians were the merchant princes of the ancient Silk Road — a Central Asian people whose homeland lay in the Zeravshan Valley around Samarkand and Bukhara, and whose trading diaspora extended from China to Byzantium between approximately 200 BCE and 1000 CE. Sogdian merchants established colonies across Central Asia and China, where their letters and commercial documents in the Sogdian script — an ancestor of many later Central Asian alphabets — provide an intimate window into Silk Road commerce. Sogdian wall paintings at Afrasiab (Samarkand) and Panjikent depict vibrant court life, and Sogdian cultural influence on Tang Dynasty China in music, dance and fashion was profound.","up":1260,"dn":200},
  {"id":287,"n":"Scythian Culture","s":-900,"e":-200,"r":"Pontic Steppe / Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Scythians were an Iranian-speaking nomadic confederacy that dominated the Pontic-Caspian steppe from approximately 900 to 200 BCE, famous for their mastery of horse-mounted archery, spectacular gold animal-style art, and elaborate burial kurgans in which their elite were interred with horses, weapons and golden ornaments. Herodotus provides the most detailed ancient account of Scythian customs, including their cannabis-steam bath rituals — confirmed archaeologically — and their practice of drinking from the skulls of enemies. Scythian art influenced traditions from Greece to China and was spread across Eurasia through trade and raid.","up":1360,"dn":220},
  {"id":290,"n":"Harappan / Indus Valley Civilisation","s":-3300,"e":-1300,"r":"Indus River basin (Pakistan/India)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Indus Valley Civilisation was the largest of the four great Bronze Age urban civilisations, at its peak encompassing an area greater than ancient Egypt and Mesopotamia combined and supporting a population estimated at up to 5 million. Its major cities — Mohenjo-daro, Harappa, Dholavira and Ganeriwala — featured grid street layouts, standardised brick sizes, covered sewage systems and indoor bathrooms in ordinary houses that would not be matched in Europe for over 3,000 years. The Indus script remains undeciphered. Its collapse around 1900 BCE is attributed to monsoon failure, tectonic changes, and possibly the arrival of Indo-Aryan speakers.","up":1840,"dn":280},
  {"id":291,"n":"D'mt Kingdom","s":-800,"e":-400,"r":"Tigray, Ethiopia / Eritrea","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of D'mt was the pre-Aksumite civilisation of the northern Ethiopian highlands and Eritrea, flourishing between approximately 800 and 400 BCE. D'mt produced sophisticated stone architecture, an early form of the Ge'ez script, iron and bronze metallurgy, and agricultural innovations including irrigation — all indicating significant South Arabian (Sabaean) cultural influence. D'mt is considered the direct political and cultural ancestor of the Aksumite Empire and represents the earliest identifiable state-level society in the Ethiopian region, demonstrating that complex civilisation in the Horn of Africa predates Aksum by at least five centuries.","up":880,"dn":180},
  {"id":293,"n":"Olmec Civilisation","s":-1500,"e":-400,"r":"Gulf Coast, Mexico","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Olmec are widely regarded as Mesoamerica's mother culture — the first complex civilisation of the region, centred on the Gulf Coast lowlands at San Lorenzo, La Venta and Tres Zapotes between approximately 1500 and 400 BCE. Their most iconic legacy is the colossal stone heads — at least 17 confirmed, weighing up to 28 tonnes — whose distinctive facial features led alternative researcher Ivan Van Sertima to propose an African origin or significant pre-Columbian African contact, a hypothesis rejected by mainstream archaeology. The Olmec developed early writing, a bar-and-dot numerical system, and possibly the Long Count calendar later perfected by the Maya.","up":1680,"dn":380},
  {"id":295,"n":"Mauryan Empire","s":-322,"e":-185,"r":"Indian Subcontinent","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Mauryan Empire was the first pan-Indian imperial state, founded by Chandragupta Maurya in 322 BCE and reaching its zenith under Ashoka the Great (r.268–232 BCE). At its height Maurya controlled an estimated 5 million square kilometres and 50 million people. Ashoka's conversion to Buddhism following his horror at the casualties of the Kalinga War produced one of history's most remarkable governance experiments: an empire-wide programme of edicts carved on pillars and rock faces promoting dharma, non-violence, religious tolerance and animal welfare. The Arthashastra, attributed to Chandragupta's minister Chanakya, remains one of the most sophisticated treatises on statecraft ever written.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":298,"n":"Goguryeo Kingdom","s":-37,"e":668,"r":"Korea / Manchuria","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Goguryeo was the northernmost and largest of the Three Kingdoms of Korea, controlling the northern Korean peninsula and much of Manchuria for over seven centuries. Its elaborate system of mountain fortresses made it exceptionally difficult to conquer — Sui Emperor Yang's invasions of 612–614 CE, involving armies reputedly over a million strong, ended in catastrophic defeats that contributed to the Sui Dynasty's collapse. Goguryeo's tomb murals — thousands of painted chambers across the northern peninsula and Manchuria — are UNESCO World Heritage properties providing incomparable records of court life, martial culture and Buddhist iconography. The kingdom was finally destroyed by the Tang-Silla alliance in 668 CE.","up":1380,"dn":220},
  {"id":299,"n":"Toltec Civilisation","s":700,"e":1150,"r":"Central Mexico (Tula)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Toltec were a Mesoamerican civilisation centred at Tula (Tollan) in the Valley of Mexico, flourishing between approximately 700 and 1150 CE and exerting significant influence across Mesoamerica — including at Chichen Itza in the Yucatan, where architectural and iconographic parallels are so striking that some researchers argue for direct Toltec colonisation. In later Aztec tradition the Toltecs were idealised as supreme craftsmen and culture-heroes, and the word 'toltec' became a generic term for artisan of the highest skill. The collapse of Tula around 1150 CE is attributed to drought, internal conflict and the arrival of Chichimec groups from the north.","up":1180,"dn":220},
  {"id":300,"n":"Hawaiian Civilisation","s":400,"e":1778,"r":"Hawaiian Islands, Pacific","t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"Hawaiian civilisation developed in remarkable isolation following Polynesian settlement of the archipelago between approximately 400 and 800 CE, representing one of the most extraordinary achievements in human navigation history — a 3,200-kilometre open-ocean voyage from the Marquesas Islands without instruments. Over the following millennium Hawaiian society developed a highly stratified kapu (taboo) system, ahupua'a land division from mountain to sea, monumental heiau (temple) construction, and sophisticated aquaculture. Hawaiian oral tradition preserved detailed genealogies and cosmological knowledge across generations without writing. Captain Cook's arrival in 1778 marked the end of isolation and set in motion the rapid transformation of Hawaiian society.","up":1380,"dn":200},
  {"id":301,"n":"Aksumite Empire / Adulis","s":-400,"e":940,"r":"Red Sea coast, Eritrea","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Adulis was the principal port city of the Aksumite Empire, situated on the Red Sea coast of modern Eritrea and serving as the empire's primary window onto the international maritime trade routes connecting Rome, Arabia, India and East Africa. The Periplus of the Erythraean Sea, a 1st-century CE Greek merchant manual, describes Adulis as a major emporium for ivory, tortoise shell, rhinoceros horn and gold dust. Aksumite rulers erected a famous inscribed throne at Adulis recording military campaigns as far as Arabia. The port's silting and the Arab conquest of Red Sea trade routes contributed to both Adulis's abandonment and the wider Aksumite decline from the 7th century CE.","up":920,"dn":160},
  {"id":305,"n":"Aksumite Pre-Flood / Punt","s":-3000,"e":-1000,"r":"Horn of Africa / Red Sea region","t":"theorized","cont":"africa","d":"The Land of Punt, known from Egyptian records spanning 2500 to 1150 BCE, was a wealthy trading partner supplying Egypt with myrrh, frankincense, ebony, gold, wild animals and Puntites themselves — yet its precise location remains one of Egyptology's most debated questions. Mainstream candidates include modern Eritrea/Ethiopia, Somalia and Yemen; some researchers propose Punt straddled both sides of the Red Sea. Graham Hancock and others have connected the Horn of Africa region to hypothetical pre-Flood civilisations that may have preceded the Aksumite tradition. Recent DNA analysis of ancient cattle from Punt-associated sites and isotopic studies have strengthened the case for an Eritrean/Ethiopian location.","up":1040,"dn":480},
  {"id":306,"n":"Taino Civilisation","s":700,"e":1550,"r":"Caribbean (Hispaniola, Cuba, Puerto Rico)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Taino were the principal indigenous people of the Caribbean at the time of Columbus's arrival in 1492, occupying the Greater Antilles and Bahamas and numbering perhaps 1–3 million across a network of chiefdoms. They developed a sophisticated agricultural system based on conuco mound cultivation of cassava, sweet potato and maize; produced elaborate zemí religious icons in stone, wood and bone; and played the ceremonial ball game on stone-lined courts. Taino society was organised under hereditary caciques (chiefs) and sub-chiefs, with women able to hold chiefly rank. Contact with Europeans precipitated one of the most rapid demographic collapses in recorded history — within fifty years of contact, the Taino population had declined by over 90% due to disease, violence and enslavement.","up":1360,"dn":200},
  {"id":307,"n":"Mississippian Chiefdom / Moundville","s":1000,"e":1450,"r":"Alabama, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Moundville in modern Alabama was the second-largest Mississippian ceremonial centre after Cahokia, featuring 29 platform mounds arranged in a precise geometric pattern around a central plaza covering nearly 75 hectares. At its peak between 1200 and 1350 CE Moundville was a regional capital controlling a network of smaller chiefdoms across the Black Warrior River valley, with evidence of craft specialisation in copper, stone and shell goods produced by elite artisans. The site's mortuary complex reveals a highly stratified society in which burial goods — copper gorgets, stone ceremonial axes, marine shell beads — tracked precisely with social rank. Moundville was largely depopulated by 1450 CE, possibly due to drought and political fragmentation.","up":1180,"dn":180},
  {"id":308,"n":"Ancestral Puebloans / Chaco","s":850,"e":1150,"r":"New Mexico / Colorado, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Chacoan phenomenon was the peak expression of Ancestral Puebloan civilisation, centred on Chaco Canyon in New Mexico between approximately 850 and 1150 CE. The Great Houses of Chaco — Pueblo Bonito, Chetro Ketl, Pueblo del Arroyo — were multi-storey masonry structures containing hundreds of rooms, built with an architectural precision and alignment to solar and lunar events that has no parallel in the pre-Columbian American Southwest. Chaco functioned as a ritual and redistribution centre for a regional system of outlying communities connected by a network of roads — the prehistoric roads of Chaco are among the most enigmatic features of North American archaeology, running dead-straight for kilometres across the desert, far wider than necessary for foot traffic.","up":1580,"dn":260},
  {"id":309,"n":"Tlingit / Northwest Coast Cultures","s":3000,"e":1900,"r":"Alaska / British Columbia, Canada","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Northwest Coast peoples — including the Tlingit, Haida, Tsimshian, Kwakwaka'wakw and others — developed one of the most sophisticated non-agricultural civilisations in human history, building complex stratified societies, elaborate artistic traditions, and vast wealth-redistribution institutions entirely on the basis of marine and riverine food resources. The potlatch ceremony — a feast at which hosts gave away or destroyed wealth to establish social status — was one of the most studied redistribution institutions in anthropology. Northwest Coast art, characterised by formline design depicting clan animals in interlocking geometric forms, is among the most visually distinctive artistic traditions ever developed.","up":1240,"dn":200},
  {"id":310,"n":"Poverty Point / Archaic South","s":-3500,"e":-700,"r":"Lower Mississippi Valley, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Late Archaic period of the Lower Mississippi Valley produced a remarkable florescence of monumental earthwork construction by hunter-gatherer communities, of which Poverty Point (id 272) is the most famous example. The broader Archaic South tradition encompassing Watson Brake (id 264), Caney Mounds, and Frenchman's Bend demonstrates that the impulse to construct large communal earthworks in the Americas began not with farmers but with highly mobile, ecologically sophisticated foraging communities who gathered seasonally at permanent monument sites. This pattern of non-agricultural monumentalism is now recognised as one of the most significant reframings in North American archaeological understanding of the past three decades.","up":1040,"dn":180},
  {"id":311,"n":"Indus Valley / Dholavira","s":-3000,"e":-1500,"r":"Gujarat, India","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Dholavira, excavated by the Archaeological Survey of India from 1989, is one of the five largest Indus Valley Civilisation cities and the most extensively excavated site on Indian territory, revealing a remarkably sophisticated urban complex with a three-part city plan, an elaborate water conservation and management system of reservoirs and channels unique in the ancient world, and a large signboard inscription at the city gate — the longest known Indus script text, still undeciphered. Dholavira's location on the island of Khadir in the Rann of Kutch gave it unique access to marine resources and trade routes, and the city maintained contacts with Persian Gulf communities. UNESCO inscribed Dholavira as a World Heritage property in 2021.","up":1440,"dn":200},
  {"id":312,"n":"Vedic Civilisation","s":-1500,"e":-500,"r":"Indian Subcontinent (Gangetic Plain)","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Vedic civilisation refers to the culture of the Indo-Aryan-speaking peoples who composed the Vedic texts — the Rigveda, Samaveda, Yajurveda and Atharvaveda — between approximately 1500 and 500 BCE, representing the foundational layer of Hindu religious and philosophical tradition. Mainstream archaeology associates the Vedic culture with the Painted Grey Ware horizon of the upper Gangetic plain following the decline of the Indus Valley Civilisation. David Frawley and Subhash Kak have controversially argued that Vedic astronomical references encode dates reaching back to 6000–4000 BCE, implying an indigenous South Asian origin for the Vedas predating any Indo-Aryan migration — a position rejected by mainstream Indo-European linguistics.","up":1280,"dn":480,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1500,"e":-500,"label":"Mainstream — Indo-Aryan migration brings Vedic culture to the subcontinent c.1500 BCE; Rigveda composed 1500–1200 BCE","source":"Witzel, The Languages of Harappa (1999)","researcher":null,"up":980,"dn":380},{"s":-6000,"e":-2000,"label":"Frawley / Out of India — astronomical dating of Vedic texts places composition as early as 6000–4000 BCE; Vedic culture is indigenous to South Asia","source":"Frawley, Gods, Sages and Kings (1991)","researcher":"David Frawley","up":640,"dn":780}]},
  {"id":313,"n":"Shang Dynasty","s":-1600,"e":-1046,"r":"Yellow River basin, China","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Shang Dynasty is the first Chinese dynasty confirmed by both archaeological evidence and contemporary written records, ruling the Yellow River basin from approximately 1600 to 1046 BCE. The Shang produced China's earliest writing — oracle bone script, used to divine royal decisions by applying heat to turtle plastrons and ox scapulae and reading the resulting cracks — and a tradition of bronze ritual vessels of extraordinary technical and aesthetic sophistication that remain among the finest bronze castings ever made. Shang society was highly stratified, with royal burials at Yinxu (Anyang) containing chariots, weapons, jade objects and the bodies of hundreds of sacrificed retainers. The dynasty was overthrown by the Zhou in 1046 BCE at the Battle of Muye.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":314,"n":"Zhou Dynasty","s":-1046,"e":-256,"r":"China","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Zhou Dynasty was the longest-reigning dynasty in Chinese history, spanning from 1046 to 256 BCE and divided into the Western Zhou (1046–771 BCE) and Eastern Zhou (771–256 BCE) periods. The Eastern Zhou's Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods produced China's most fertile era of philosophical thought — the Hundred Schools of Thought — including Confucius, Laozi, Mozi, Mencius, Zhuangzi, Sunzi (author of The Art of War) and Han Feizi, whose ideas shaped Chinese civilisation for the next two millennia. The Zhou legitimised their rule through the concept of the Mandate of Heaven (tianming) — the idea that rulers governed by divine sanction withdrawable for misrule — a doctrine that defined Chinese political theory until the 20th century.","up":1580,"dn":200},
  {"id":315,"n":"Achaemenid Persian Empire","s":-550,"e":-330,"r":"Iran / Middle East / Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Achaemenid Empire founded by Cyrus the Great in 550 BCE was the largest empire the ancient world had yet seen, stretching from the Aegean coast to the Indus Valley and encompassing perhaps 44% of the world's population at its peak under Darius I. The empire was notable for its administrative sophistication — a system of satrapies (provinces), the Royal Road connecting Sardis to Susa, and a policy of religious tolerance and cultural respect that led Cyrus to be celebrated in the Hebrew Bible as a liberator. Achaemenid Persepolis, burned by Alexander the Great in 330 BCE, remains one of the most spectacular archaeological sites in the world. The empire's administrative use of Aramaic made it the lingua franca of the ancient Near East.","up":1760,"dn":240},
  {"id":317,"n":"Sasanian Empire","s":224,"e":651,"r":"Iran / Iraq / Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Sasanian Empire was the last great pre-Islamic Persian empire, ruling from 224 to 651 CE and representing a conscious revival of Achaemenid Persian imperial ideology. At its peak the Sasanians controlled Iran, Iraq, the Caucasus, parts of Central Asia, and briefly Egypt and Anatolia following conquests from the Byzantine Empire. Sasanian culture produced extraordinary achievements in art, architecture, metalwork and textile design that profoundly influenced both Byzantine and early Islamic civilisation. The Zoroastrian religious establishment was closely intertwined with Sasanian state power. The empire was fatally weakened by decades of devastating war with Byzantium before the Arab Muslim conquest completed its destruction between 637 and 651 CE.","up":1380,"dn":200},
  {"id":318,"n":"Tang Dynasty","s":618,"e":907,"r":"China","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Tang Dynasty is widely regarded as a golden age of Chinese civilisation, combining territorial expansion, cosmopolitan openness and cultural brilliance during its nearly three-century rule from 618 to 907 CE. Chang'an (modern Xi'an), Tang's capital, was the largest city in the world at its peak with a population exceeding one million, and its international quarter hosted merchants, diplomats and monks from across Eurasia — Persians, Sogdians, Arabs, Koreans, Japanese and Byzantines. Tang poetry, represented by figures including Du Fu, Li Bai and Wang Wei, is considered the pinnacle of the Chinese literary tradition. The dynasty's tolerance of Buddhism, Nestorian Christianity, Zoroastrianism and Islam simultaneously reflected its extraordinary cosmopolitanism.","up":1720,"dn":220},
  {"id":319,"n":"Song Dynasty","s":960,"e":1279,"r":"China","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Song Dynasty oversaw perhaps the most remarkable economic and technological revolution before the European Industrial Revolution, concentrated between 960 and 1279 CE. Song China produced the world's first paper money, the first use of gunpowder in warfare, the magnetic compass for navigation, moveable-type printing (predating Gutenberg by four centuries), advanced hydraulic engineering, and an agricultural revolution based on new rice varieties from Vietnam. The Southern Song's capital Hangzhou had a population of possibly 1.5 million — the world's largest city. Despite these achievements the Song was unable to resist military pressure from nomadic confederacies, falling first to the Jurchen Jin in the north and ultimately to the Mongol Yuan Dynasty in 1279.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":322,"n":"Delhi Sultanate","s":1206,"e":1526,"r":"Indian Subcontinent","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Delhi Sultanate was a series of five successive Muslim dynasties that ruled much of the Indian subcontinent from their capital at Delhi between 1206 and 1526 CE, representing the first sustained Islamic political power in South Asia and fundamentally reshaping the region's religious, cultural and architectural landscape. The Sultanate repelled two Mongol invasions under Alauddin Khalji (1296–1316), a remarkable military achievement, and at its height controlled a territory comparable in size to the later Mughal Empire. The Qutb Minar, commissioned by the sultanate's founder Qutb ud-Din Aibak and completed by later rulers, remains one of the finest examples of early Indo-Islamic architecture. The Sultanate was ended by Babur's Mughal invasion at the First Battle of Panipat in 1526.","up":1280,"dn":200},
  {"id":327,"n":"Inca Empire / Tawantinsuyu","s":1438,"e":1533,"r":"Andes, South America","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Inca Empire — Tawantinsuyu ('The Four Regions') — was the largest empire in pre-Columbian America and, at its peak between 1438 and 1533, the largest empire in the world by territory in the Western Hemisphere, stretching 4,300 kilometres along the Andes from modern Colombia to central Chile. The Incas achieved this vast territorial integration without a phonemic writing system, using instead the khipu (knotted cord recording device) and an extraordinary road network of over 40,000 kilometres including suspension bridges, way stations (tambos) and relay runners (chasquis) capable of transmitting messages 400 kilometres per day. The Spanish conquest, exploiting a civil war between rival Inca claimants, reduced this remarkable system to colonial subjection within two years.","up":1780,"dn":240},
  {"id":328,"n":"Aztec / Triple Alliance","s":1428,"e":1521,"r":"Central Mexico","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Aztec Triple Alliance — formed between Tenochtitlan, Texcoco and Tlacopan in 1428 — created Mesoamerica's most powerful political entity, controlling a tribute empire of perhaps 5–6 million people across central Mexico at the time of Spanish contact. Tenochtitlan, built on an island in Lake Texcoco and connected to the mainland by causeways, was one of the world's largest cities with a population of 200,000–300,000 — larger than any European city of the time. The empire's elaborate calendrical system (combining a 365-day solar calendar with a 260-day ritual calendar), its pyramid temples, and its practice of large-scale human sacrifice combined to create a culture of startling complexity and terror. Hernán Cortés's conquest between 1519 and 1521, aided by smallpox and indigenous allies, ended the empire in two years.","up":1780,"dn":280},
  {"id":329,"n":"Maya Civilisation","s":-2000,"e":1697,"r":"Mesoamerica (Mexico / Guatemala / Belize)","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Maya civilisation was one of the most intellectually sophisticated cultures of the ancient world, developing independently in Mesoamerica over nearly four millennia. The Classic Maya (250–900 CE) built towering limestone cities — Tikal, Palenque, Copán, Caracol — featuring palaces, astronomical observatories and ball courts, governed by divine kings whose genealogies and wars were recorded in a fully developed hieroglyphic script now largely deciphered. Maya mathematics, using a vigesimal (base-20) system with a true zero, and their interlocking calendar system — the Long Count, Tzolkin and Haab — allowed astronomical calculations of extraordinary precision. The 'Classic Maya Collapse' of 800–900 CE, involving the abandonment of most southern lowland cities, remains one of archaeology's most studied civilisational failures.","up":1840,"dn":260},
  {"id":330,"n":"Carthaginian Empire","s":-814,"e":-146,"r":"North Africa / Western Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Carthage was founded by Phoenician colonists from Tyre, traditionally in 814 BCE, and grew into the dominant commercial and naval power of the western Mediterranean, controlling trade routes from the Strait of Gibraltar to Sardinia, Sicily and Spain. The Punic Wars against Rome (264–146 BCE) represent one of antiquity's most consequential conflicts — Hannibal Barca's campaign across the Alps into Italy in 218 BCE, winning devastating victories at Trebia, Trasimene and Cannae, came closer than any other enemy to destroying the Roman Republic. Rome's eventual victory led to the total destruction of Carthage in 146 BCE — the city was razed, its population enslaved, and according to tradition (though disputed by modern scholars) its fields salted. Almost all Carthaginian literature was destroyed, making them one of history's most thoroughly silenced civilisations.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":331,"n":"Macedonian / Hellenistic Empire","s":-336,"e":-30,"r":"Greece / Near East / Central Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Macedonian Empire built by Alexander the Great between 336 and 323 BCE was the first to unite Greece, Persia, Egypt and Central Asia under a single ruler, transforming the ancient world in the span of thirteen years. Alexander's campaigns spread Greek language, philosophy, art and urban planning across an arc from Egypt to the Indus — the process of Hellenisation that would shape the culture of the eastern Mediterranean for centuries. The successor kingdoms (Diadochi) that emerged after Alexander's death in 323 BCE — Ptolemaic Egypt, Seleucid Asia and Antigonid Macedonia — each preserved Greek cultural forms while adapting to local traditions, creating the cosmopolitan Hellenistic world that bridged the classical Greek and Roman ages.","up":1780,"dn":220},
  {"id":332,"n":"Roman Republic","s":-509,"e":-27,"r":"Italy / Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Roman Republic, established after the expulsion of the last Etruscan king in 509 BCE, developed the constitutional innovations — consuls, Senate, popular assemblies, tribunes of the plebs — that became foundational to Western political thought. Over five centuries the Republic conquered the Mediterranean world through a combination of military effectiveness, flexible citizenship policies and ruthless diplomatic skill. The late Republic's crises — the Gracchi reforms, Marian military reforms, the civil wars of Sulla, Caesar and Octavian — represent one of history's most studied examples of democratic institutions failing under the strain of imperial expansion, ultimately yielding to the Principate of Augustus in 27 BCE.","up":1760,"dn":240},
  {"id":333,"n":"Roman Empire","s":-27,"e":476,"r":"Mediterranean / Western Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Roman Empire at its greatest extent under Trajan (117 CE) controlled approximately 5 million square kilometres and 70 million people — roughly 21% of the world's population — making it one of the most consequential political entities in human history. Roman engineering achievements — roads, aqueducts, concrete construction, the arch and dome — transformed the landscape of three continents and many remain in use today. Roman law, systematised under Justinian in the 6th century, forms the basis of most modern legal systems. The 'Fall of Rome' in 476 CE, when the last western emperor was deposed by Odoacer, has been interpreted as military overextension, economic collapse, pandemic, climate change and cultural transformation — most likely all simultaneously.","up":1880,"dn":280},
  {"id":334,"n":"Viking / Norse Civilisation","s":793,"e":1100,"r":"Scandinavia / North Atlantic","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Viking Age, conventionally dated from the raid on Lindisfarne in 793 CE to the Norman Conquest of 1066, saw Norse seafarers from Scandinavia achieve a geographic reach unmatched by any contemporary civilisation — raiding and trading from Newfoundland to Baghdad, founding Dublin, Kiev and Normandy, and establishing the first European settlements in North America at L'Anse aux Meadows, Newfoundland around 1000 CE. Viking longships, with their shallow draft allowing navigation of rivers as well as open ocean, were the technological key to this range. Norse mythology and legal traditions — the Thing assembly system — left enduring marks on the cultures of Britain, Ireland, France, Russia and Iceland.","up":1680,"dn":240},
  {"id":335,"n":"Holy Roman Empire","s":800,"e":1806,"r":"Central Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Holy Roman Empire, famously described by Voltaire as 'neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire,' was the principal political structure of Central Europe from Charlemagne's coronation in 800 CE to its dissolution by Napoleon in 1806. At its height it encompassed modern Germany, Austria, Switzerland, the Netherlands, Belgium, Czech Republic, and parts of Italy and Poland, governed by an elected emperor whose power was consistently limited by powerful princes, the papacy, and eventually the Reformation. The empire's decentralised structure fostered the growth of free imperial cities — Frankfurt, Augsburg, Nuremberg — that became centres of commerce, printing and humanist learning.","up":1380,"dn":240},
  {"id":337,"n":"Medieval France / Capetian Dynasty","s":987,"e":1328,"r":"France","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Capetian Dynasty, ruling France from Hugh Capet's election in 987 CE to the male line's extinction in 1328, transformed a fragmented feudal kingdom into the most powerful monarchy in medieval Europe. Philip II Augustus (r.1180–1223) quadrupled the royal domain; Louis IX (Saint Louis) created the model of the ideal Christian king; Philip IV 'the Fair' broke papal authority, moved the papacy to Avignon, and destroyed the Knights Templar. The building of Notre-Dame de Paris, Chartres Cathedral and the Sainte-Chapelle during this period represents the pinnacle of Gothic architecture. The dynasty also produced the Crusader kingdoms of the Levant and permanently shaped the culture of medieval Europe.","up":1240,"dn":200},
  {"id":338,"n":"Angevin / Plantagenet England","s":1154,"e":1485,"r":"England / France","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Plantagenet dynasty ruled England from Henry II's accession in 1154 to Richard III's death at Bosworth in 1485, presiding over three centuries of constitutional, legal and cultural development that shaped the English-speaking world. Magna Carta (1215), extracted from King John by rebellious barons, established the principle that the monarch is subject to the rule of law — one of the foundational documents of constitutional government. The Plantagenet period also produced the common law system, the Oxford and Cambridge universities, the Hundred Years' War with France, the Black Death's demographic catastrophe, the Peasants' Revolt, Geoffrey Chaucer's Canterbury Tales, and the Wars of the Roses.","up":1380,"dn":200},
  {"id":343,"n":"Swahili Coast Civilisation","s":800,"e":1700,"r":"East African Coast","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Swahili Coast civilisation was a chain of prosperous Indian Ocean trading city-states stretching from Somalia to Mozambique — including Kilwa, Mombasa, Malindi, Zanzibar and Sofala — that flourished between approximately 800 and 1700 CE as the primary intermediaries in trade between the African interior, Arabia, Persia, India and China. The Swahili language, now spoken by over 200 million people across East Africa, emerged from the contact between Bantu-speaking coastal communities and Arab and Persian merchants. Kilwa, at its height in the 13th–14th centuries, was described by Ibn Battuta as one of the most beautiful cities in the world. Chinese porcelain from the Song and Ming periods is found in abundance at Swahili archaeological sites.","up":1380,"dn":200},
  {"id":344,"n":"Ethiopian Empire / Solomonic","s":1270,"e":1974,"r":"Ethiopia","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Solomonic Dynasty, which claimed descent from the biblical union of King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba, ruled Ethiopia from the restoration of 1270 CE until Emperor Haile Selassie was deposed in 1974 — making it one of the longest-reigning dynasties in world history. The dynasty's legitimising text, the Kebra Nagast ('Glory of Kings,' compiled c.1321), narrates the birth of Menelik I from Solomon and Makeda (the Queen of Sheba) and his theft of the Ark of the Covenant from Jerusalem. Ethiopia's successful resistance to Italian colonisation at the Battle of Adwa in 1896 made it a powerful symbol of African independence and later inspired the Pan-African and Rastafari movements.","up":1480,"dn":200},
  {"id":345,"n":"Aksumite / Ethiopian Orthodox Church","s":330,"e":2024,"r":"Ethiopia / Horn of Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church, established following King Ezana's conversion to Christianity around 330 CE, is one of the oldest continuously functioning Christian institutions in the world and the only pre-colonial Christian church of sub-Saharan Africa. Its distinctive traditions — including the Ge'ez liturgy unchanged since the 4th century, veneration of the Ark of the Covenant at Aksum, the unique Tabot (replica ark) in every church, and the 81-book biblical canon (the most extensive in Christendom) — represent a form of Christianity that developed in almost complete isolation from both Rome and Constantinople for over a millennium. The Church has been the primary custodian of Ethiopian culture, literacy and national identity.","up":1240,"dn":180},
  {"id":346,"n":"Deccan Sultanates","s":1490,"e":1686,"r":"Deccan Plateau, India","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Deccan Sultanates were five successor states — Ahmadnagar, Bidar, Bijapur, Berar and Golconda — formed from the fragmentation of the Bahmani Sultanate in 1490, ruling the Deccan Plateau of central India until Mughal conquest under Aurangzeb in 1686. Despite constant internecine warfare, the Deccan courts were remarkable centres of syncretic Indo-Islamic culture, producing distinctive architectural styles (the Gol Gumbaz in Bijapur is the second-largest dome in the world after St Peter's), Deccani miniature painting, and the Urdu literary tradition. The coalition of Deccan Sultanates that defeated Vijayanagara at Talikota (1565) represented their most consequential collective action.","up":1140,"dn":200},
  {"id":347,"n":"Maratha Empire","s":1674,"e":1818,"r":"Indian Subcontinent","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Maratha Empire, founded by Chhatrapati Shivaji in 1674, was the last major Hindu empire of India and the primary challenger to Mughal supremacy in the 18th century, at its peak controlling roughly a third of the subcontinent. Shivaji's guerrilla warfare tactics, naval innovations and administrative systems created a formidable state from the Maharashtra highlands. The Maratha Confederacy's defeat at the Third Battle of Panipat (1761) against the Afghan Durrani Empire was one of the bloodiest battles of the 18th century and fatally weakened Maratha power, opening the door to British expansion across India. The empire was formally ended by the British East India Company in 1818.","up":1360,"dn":200},
  {"id":348,"n":"Joseon Dynasty","s":1392,"e":1897,"r":"Korean Peninsula","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Joseon Dynasty ruled the Korean Peninsula for over five centuries from 1392 to 1897, making it one of the longest-lived dynasties in world history. Joseon's most celebrated achievement was the creation of the Hangul alphabet in 1443 by King Sejong the Great — a brilliantly systematic phonemic script designed to improve literacy among the Korean population who struggled with the complex Chinese writing system, and now recognised as one of the most scientifically designed writing systems ever created. Joseon also produced the world's first iron-clad warships (the geobukseon 'turtle ships') during Admiral Yi Sun-sin's campaigns against the Japanese invasions of 1592–1598.","up":1480,"dn":180},
  {"id":349,"n":"Tokugawa Shogunate / Edo Japan","s":1603,"e":1868,"r":"Japan","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Tokugawa Shogunate, established by Tokugawa Ieyasu following the Battle of Sekigahara (1600), unified Japan under a centralised feudal system that maintained two and a half centuries of almost unbroken peace — the longest such period in Japanese history. The Edo period's sakoku ('closed country') policy restricted foreign trade to a single Dutch outpost at Dejima, Nagasaki, and banned most Japanese from travelling abroad — a deliberate isolation that produced an extraordinarily rich internal culture: kabuki theatre, ukiyo-e woodblock printing, haiku poetry (Matsuo Bashō), the Floating World of Edo's pleasure districts, and a sophisticated merchant culture. The arrival of Commodore Perry's 'Black Ships' in 1853 ended Edo isolation and precipitated the Meiji Restoration.","up":1620,"dn":200},
  {"id":350,"n":"Qing Dynasty","s":1644,"e":1912,"r":"China / Manchuria / Mongolia","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Qing Dynasty, founded by the Manchu Aisin Gioro clan, was China's last imperial dynasty and at its 18th-century height the world's most populous empire, ruling over 400 million people. Under the Qianlong Emperor the dynasty reached its greatest territorial extent, incorporating Tibet, Xinjiang, Mongolia and Taiwan into a multi-ethnic empire larger than modern China. The 19th century brought catastrophic reversal: the Opium Wars imposed humiliating unequal treaties with Western powers; the Taiping Rebellion (1850–1864) killed an estimated 20–30 million people — possibly the deadliest civil war in history; and the Boxer Uprising (1900) invited foreign military intervention. The dynasty was overthrown by the Xinhai Revolution, ending over two millennia of imperial rule in 1912.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":351,"n":"Seljuk Empire","s":1037,"e":1194,"r":"Central Asia / Anatolia / Middle East","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Seljuk Empire was a Turkic Muslim dynasty that emerged from the Central Asian steppe to become the dominant power of the Islamic world in the 11th century, controlling Persia, Iraq, Anatolia and the Levant at its height. The Seljuks' victory over Byzantine forces at the Battle of Manzikert in 1071 opened Anatolia to Turkish settlement and permanently transformed the ethnic and religious composition of what would become modern Turkey. Their patronage of Persian literature, architecture and the development of the madrasa educational system shaped Islamic civilisation for centuries. The Seljuk sultans also served as secular protectors of the Abbasid Caliphate in Baghdad, taking the title of Sultan while leaving the Caliph as a religious figurehead.","up":1320,"dn":200},
  {"id":352,"n":"Abbasid Caliphate","s":750,"e":1258,"r":"Iraq / Middle East / North Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Abbasid Caliphate, which overthrew the Umayyad dynasty in 750 CE and ruled from Baghdad until the Mongol destruction of 1258, presided over the Islamic Golden Age — the most productive period of scientific, philosophical and artistic achievement in medieval Islamic civilisation. Baghdad under Harun al-Rashid and al-Ma'mun was the world's largest city, home to the House of Wisdom (Bayt al-Hikma) where scholars translated the accumulated knowledge of Greece, Persia and India into Arabic and extended it dramatically in mathematics, astronomy, medicine, optics and philosophy. The works of al-Khwarizmi (algebra), Ibn al-Haytham (optics), Ibn Sina (medicine) and al-Biruni (comparative anthropology) defined their fields for centuries. The Mongol sack of Baghdad in 1258 destroyed the library and ended the caliphate.","up":1680,"dn":240},
  {"id":353,"n":"Umayyad Caliphate","s":661,"e":750,"r":"Middle East / North Africa / Spain","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Umayyad Caliphate was the first great Islamic empire, expanding with extraordinary speed from its capital at Damascus across North Africa, the Iberian Peninsula (Al-Andalus) and Central Asia between 661 and 750 CE. At its greatest extent the Umayyad state controlled more territory than any empire since Alexander's, spanning 11 million square kilometres. The Dome of the Rock in Jerusalem (completed 691 CE), one of Islam's holiest sites, was built under Caliph Abd al-Malik and remains the oldest surviving monumental Islamic building. The Umayyad dynasty was overthrown by the Abbasid Revolution in 750; a surviving branch established a rival emirate in Córdoba, Spain, which became one of medieval Europe's most sophisticated cultural centres.","up":1480,"dn":220},
  {"id":354,"n":"Al-Andalus / Moorish Spain","s":711,"e":1492,"r":"Iberian Peninsula (Spain/Portugal)","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Al-Andalus, the Muslim-governed territory of the Iberian Peninsula from the Umayyad conquest in 711 CE to the fall of Granada in 1492, represented one of medieval Europe's most sophisticated and cosmopolitan civilisations. At its height under the Córdoba Caliphate in the 10th century, Córdoba was the largest city in western Europe with a population of perhaps 500,000, a library of 400,000 volumes, and a culture of religious convivencia (coexistence) among Muslims, Christians and Jews that produced extraordinary cross-cultural intellectual achievement. The translation movement centred in Toledo, by which Arabic-preserved Greek texts were rendered into Latin, was the primary mechanism by which classical philosophy and science reached medieval Europe.","up":1560,"dn":240},
  {"id":355,"n":"Fatimid Caliphate","s":909,"e":1171,"r":"North Africa / Egypt / Levant","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Fatimid Caliphate was a Shia Ismaili dynasty that ruled North Africa, Egypt, Sicily and the Levant from 909 to 1171 CE, founded the city of Cairo (Al-Qahira, 'The Victorious') in 969 CE, and established Al-Azhar University — one of the world's oldest continuously operating universities. The Fatimids represented a rival to Sunni Abbasid authority and cultivated a distinctive court culture of extraordinary luxury and religious sophistication. Cairo under the Fatimids was one of the medieval world's great intellectual centres, and the dynasty's network of Ismaili missionaries (da'wa) extended across the Islamic world from Morocco to the Malabar Coast of India.","up":1280,"dn":200},
  {"id":356,"n":"Crusader States","s":1098,"e":1291,"r":"Levant (Israel/Palestine/Lebanon/Syria)","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Crusader States — the County of Edessa, Principality of Antioch, County of Tripoli and Kingdom of Jerusalem — were four Catholic polities established in the Levant following the First Crusade's capture of Jerusalem in 1099. The Kingdom of Jerusalem in particular developed a sophisticated feudal constitution and remarkably syncretic culture in which Frankish, Byzantine, Armenian, Arab and Jewish traditions coexisted in the daily life of the cities, even as the states were defined by their relationship to crusading ideology. Saladin's reconquest of Jerusalem in 1187, the subsequent Crusades, and the final fall of Acre in 1291 ended the Crusader presence in the Levant, leaving a complex legacy of East-West cultural exchange alongside devastation.","up":1380,"dn":260},
  {"id":359,"n":"Pagan Kingdom / Bagan","s":849,"e":1297,"r":"Myanmar (Burma)","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Pagan Kingdom (capital: Bagan) was the first kingdom to unify most of the territory of modern Myanmar, ruling from 849 to 1297 CE and presiding over a golden age of Theravada Buddhist culture and monumental temple construction. Between the 11th and 13th centuries, Bagan's rulers built over 10,000 Buddhist temples, pagodas and monasteries on a 42-square-kilometre plain along the Irrawaddy River — approximately 2,200 of which still stand, making it one of the densest concentrations of Buddhist monuments in the world. King Anawrahta's conquest of the Mon kingdom in 1057 and adoption of Theravada Buddhism initiated a religious and cultural transformation that permanently shaped Burmese identity. Kublai Khan's Mongol invasions (1277–1297) ended Pagan's dominance.","up":1320,"dn":180},
  {"id":363,"n":"Sumerian Civilisation","s":-4500,"e":-2004,"r":"Southern Mesopotamia (Iraq)","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"Sumer, in the alluvial plains of southern Mesopotamia, produced humanity's earliest urban civilisation and its first writing system. By 3500 BCE the Sumerian city-states of Uruk, Ur, Eridu, Nippur and Lagash had developed cuneiform script (initially for accounting), monumental temple architecture (the ziggurat), formal legal codes, schools, professional armies and long-distance trade networks extending to the Indus Valley and Egypt. The Epic of Gilgamesh, composed in Sumerian and later Akkadian, is the world's oldest surviving work of literature. The Sumerian King List, claiming dynasties going back before the Flood to impossibly long-reigning kings, has been cited by alternative researchers including Zecharia Sitchin as evidence of extraterrestrial intervention in human governance.","up":1840,"dn":280},
  {"id":364,"n":"Ancient Egypt — Old Kingdom","s":-2686,"e":-2181,"r":"Nile Valley, Egypt","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Old Kingdom of Egypt (2686–2181 BCE) represents the first great flowering of pharaonic civilisation, producing the most iconic monuments in human history: the Step Pyramid of Djoser at Saqqara, the Great Pyramid of Khufu at Giza (the only surviving Wonder of the Ancient World), and the Great Sphinx. The pyramid-building age concentrated unprecedented organisational and logistical capacity, mobilising tens of thousands of workers — recent archaeology suggests they were paid labourers, not slaves — and engineering precision that continues to inspire both admiration and alternative theories. Robert Schoch's controversial re-dating of the Sphinx to before 5000 BCE based on water erosion patterns, and Graham Hancock's broader pre-Flood civilisation thesis, centre on Old Kingdom monuments.","up":1920,"dn":320},
  {"id":365,"n":"Ancient Egypt — New Kingdom","s":-1550,"e":-1069,"r":"Nile Valley / Levant / Nubia","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The New Kingdom (1550–1069 BCE) was Egypt's imperial age — the era of Thutmose III (the 'Napoleon of Ancient Egypt'), Akhenaten's revolutionary monotheistic interlude, the boy-king Tutankhamun, Ramesses II's decades-long reign and his peace treaty with the Hittites (the world's oldest surviving international treaty), and the mysterious Sea Peoples who disrupted the entire Eastern Mediterranean around 1200 BCE. The Valley of the Kings, across the river from Luxor, served as the burial ground for New Kingdom pharaohs, and Howard Carter's discovery of Tutankhamun's intact tomb in 1922 remains the greatest archaeological find of the 20th century. The New Kingdom's collapse around 1069 BCE was part of the broader Bronze Age Collapse that ended civilisations across the Eastern Mediterranean simultaneously.","up":1880,"dn":240},
  {"id":366,"n":"Ptolemaic Egypt","s":-305,"e":-30,"r":"Egypt / North Africa","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Ptolemaic Kingdom (305–30 BCE), founded by Alexander's general Ptolemy I, was the longest-lasting of the Hellenistic successor states and one of the ancient world's most intellectually productive polities. Its capital Alexandria housed the Great Library — at its height the largest repository of knowledge in the ancient world — and the Mouseion (the ancestor of the modern museum), attracting scholars including Euclid, Archimedes, Eratosthenes and Hipparchus. The Rosetta Stone, inscribed under Ptolemy V in 196 BCE with a decree in three scripts (hieroglyphic, Demotic and Greek), became the key to deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics in the 19th century. Cleopatra VII, the last Ptolemaic ruler, was the first of her dynasty to speak Egyptian; her death in 30 BCE ended pharaonic Egypt.","up":1740,"dn":220},
  {"id":367,"n":"Minoan / Linear A Mystery","s":-2700,"e":-1450,"r":"Crete / Aegean Islands","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"Linear A, the undeciphered script of the Minoan civilisation, remains one of the most tantalising puzzles in all of archaeology — the only major writing system of an advanced Bronze Age civilisation that modern scholarship has been entirely unable to read. Unlike Linear B (Mycenaean Greek, deciphered by Michael Ventris in 1952), Linear A has resisted all decipherment attempts because the underlying language is unknown and appears to be unrelated to any known language family. The approximately 1,500 surviving Linear A inscriptions cover administrative, religious and possibly astronomical content. The decipherment of Linear A would potentially reveal the mythology, theology and political history of Europe's first urban civilisation — information currently entirely inaccessible.","up":1580,"dn":280,"dateTheories":[{"s":-2700,"e":-1450,"label":"Mainstream — Linear A records an unknown Minoan language unrelated to Greek or any known family; administrative and religious content","source":"Younger & Rehak, Aegean Prehistoric Archaeology (2008)","researcher":null,"up":1240,"dn":240},{"s":-2700,"e":-1450,"label":"Anatolian hypothesis — Minoan language may be related to Luwian or another Anatolian branch; partial phonetic values borrowed from Linear B suggest Aegean substrate","source":"Woudhuizen, The Language of the Sea Peoples (1992)","researcher":null,"up":480,"dn":680}]},
  {"id":370,"n":"Vedic / Rigvedic Culture","s":-3000,"e":-1500,"r":"Indian Subcontinent / Central Asia","t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Rigvedic culture, associated with the composition of the Rigveda — the oldest of the Vedic texts and arguably the oldest surviving religious literature in any Indo-European language — is one of the most debated topics in ancient history. Mainstream scholarship places the Rigveda's composition between 1500 and 1200 BCE following the Indo-Aryan migration into the Indian subcontinent. Researcher David Frawley and astronomer Subhash Kak argue that internal astronomical references in the Rigveda — including descriptions of the winter solstice in Orion consistent with a date around 4000 BCE — push its composition far earlier and imply an indigenous South Asian origin for the Indo-Aryan tradition rather than a steppe migration.","up":1280,"dn":540,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1500,"e":-1200,"label":"Mainstream — Rigveda composed 1500–1200 BCE following Indo-Aryan migration; linguistic evidence ties it to Avestan and other Indo-Iranian branches","source":"Witzel, The Rig-Veda and the History of India (2001)","researcher":null,"up":960,"dn":440},{"s":-4000,"e":-2000,"label":"Frawley / Kak — astronomical references in the Rigveda encode dates 4000–6000 BCE; Vedic culture is indigenous to South Asia predating any steppe migration","source":"Frawley, Gods, Sages and Kings (1991); Kak, The Astronomical Code of the Rigveda (2000)","researcher":"David Frawley","up":580,"dn":760}]},
  {"id":371,"n":"Göbekli Tepe / Pre-Pottery Neolithic","s":-9600,"e":-8000,"r":"Southeastern Turkey / Fertile Crescent","t":"debated","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Pre-Pottery Neolithic A and B periods (c.9600–7000 BCE) represent the most extraordinary transition in human history — the independent invention of agriculture and sedentary life in the Fertile Crescent, accompanied by the world's first monumental architecture at Göbekli Tepe. The question of whether religious communal building preceded and motivated agriculture, or whether agriculture created the surplus to support monument-building, has been inverted by Göbekli Tepe: the site's hunter-gatherer builders suggest the temple came first. Klaus Schmidt's 'cathedral on a hill' hypothesis — that religious motivation, not economic necessity, drove the Neolithic transition — has become one of archaeology's most influential ideas of the past thirty years.","up":1640,"dn":340,"dateTheories":[{"s":-9600,"e":-7000,"label":"Mainstream — Pre-Pottery Neolithic represents independent invention of agriculture in the Fertile Crescent; Göbekli Tepe built by transitional hunter-gatherers","source":"Schmidt, Göbekli Tepe (2006); Bar-Yosef, Current Anthropology (1998)","researcher":"Klaus Schmidt","up":1280,"dn":280},{"s":-11000,"e":-9600,"label":"Hancock / alternative — Göbekli Tepe was built by survivors of a pre-Flood advanced civilisation; the site is far older than mainstream dating; deliberate burial preserves earlier structures","source":"Hancock, Magicians of the Gods (2015)","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":820,"dn":840}]},
  {"id":372,"n":"Lydian / Anatolian Cultures","s":-1200,"e":-300,"r":"Western Anatolia (Turkey)","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"Western Anatolia in the Iron Age was a mosaic of remarkable cultures — Phrygia (whose legendary king Midas gave his name to the golden touch myth), Lydia (inventors of coinage, id 258), Caria, Lycia and others — that occupied the frontier between the Greek and Persian worlds and participated in both. The Phrygians produced the extraordinary tumulus tombs of Gordion and a rich tradition of mother-goddess worship centred on Cybele, whose cult spread to Rome. The Lycians maintained a unique federal democratic system — the Lycian League — that later inspired the framers of the United States Constitution. Herodotus, writing in the 5th century BCE, described this region with particular richness as his own cultural homeland.","up":1120,"dn":180},
  {"id":373,"n":"Hurrian Civilisation","s":-2300,"e":-1200,"r":"Northern Mesopotamia / Anatolia","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Hurrians were a people of uncertain origin who spread across northern Mesopotamia and Anatolia in the late 3rd and early 2nd millennia BCE, establishing several kingdoms of which Mitanni (id 254) was the most powerful. Their language, Hurrian, is a language isolate related only to Urartian, and their mythology — preserved through Hittite transmission — includes the Kumarbi Cycle, a sequence of cosmic succession myths (a younger god defeating an older one and incorporating his power) that scholars including Peter Walcot and M.L. West have argued directly influenced the Greek Theogony of Hesiod. The Hurrian musical hymn to Nikkal (c.1400 BCE) is the oldest known complete piece of notated music in the world.","up":1140,"dn":200},
  {"id":374,"n":"Harappan / Rakhigarhi","s":-2600,"e":-1900,"r":"Haryana, India","t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Rakhigarhi in Haryana, India, is now confirmed as the largest known site of the Indus Valley Civilisation — surpassing even Mohenjo-daro and Harappa — extending over approximately 350 hectares and featuring the full suite of Harappan urban planning, including grid streets, a granary complex, a fire altar and drainage systems. A landmark 2019 ancient DNA study from Rakhigarhi burials found no detectable steppe ancestry in Indus Valley individuals, contradicting the Aryan Migration Theory's proposal of large-scale steppe gene flow into South Asia during the Mature Harappan phase. The study has been interpreted by Hindu nationalist scholars as evidence for an indigenous origin of the Vedic tradition — a politically charged conclusion that mainstream geneticists dispute.","up":1380,"dn":380},
  {"id":376,"n":"Colchis / Ancient Georgia","s":-1000,"e":-66,"r":"Western Georgia / Black Sea coast","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Colchis was an ancient kingdom on the eastern Black Sea coast (modern western Georgia) famous in Greek mythology as the destination of Jason and the Argonauts' quest for the Golden Fleece — the fleece representing the actual practice of using sheepskins to pan for gold in Colchian mountain streams. Colchis maintained active trade with the Greek world and produced sophisticated goldwork and bronze objects. The region was incorporated into the Achaemenid Persian satrapy system and later became a contested frontier between Rome and Parthia. Modern Georgia's exceptionally ancient wine-making tradition — now dated by archaeologists to at least 6000 BCE — and its unique script suggest a cultural continuity reaching far back into prehistory.","up":1040,"dn":200},
  {"id":377,"n":"Scythian / Sarmatian Cultures","s":-700,"e":400,"r":"Eurasian Steppe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Sarmatians were the Scythians' eastern neighbours and eventual successors on the Pontic steppe, an Iranian-speaking nomadic confederacy that dominated the region from approximately 500 BCE to 400 CE. Famous for their warrior women — who may have inspired the Greek Amazon myth, with female burials containing weapons being a documented Sarmatian practice — and their heavy cavalry armoured with metal scale armour, the Sarmatians established tributary relationships with Roman frontier provinces and provided mercenary cavalry to Roman armies. The Roxolani and Iazyges tribes crossed the Danube as Roman foederati, settling in Pannonia. DNA studies of Sarmatian remains have linked some lineages to modern populations of Poland, Hungary and the British Isles.","up":1120,"dn":200},
  {"id":378,"n":"Dacian Kingdom","s":-168,"e":106,"r":"Romania / Moldova / Bulgaria","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Dacians were a Thracian people who built a sophisticated Iron Age civilisation in the Carpathian region, reaching their peak under King Decebalus (r.87–106 CE), who twice forced Rome to negotiate humiliating peace terms before Trajan's ultimately successful conquest in the Dacian Wars of 101–102 and 105–106 CE. Trajan's Column in Rome, erected to commemorate the conquest, provides one of the most detailed pictorial records of Roman military operations and Dacian life in the ancient world. The Dacians' gold and silver mines in Transylvania — the richest in the ancient world — were the primary strategic prize of Trajan's conquest and funded much of his subsequent building programme in Rome.","up":1120,"dn":180},
  {"id":379,"n":"Etruscan / Villanova Culture","s":-900,"e":-500,"r":"Northern Italy","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Villanovan culture (c.900–700 BCE) of the Po Valley and Tuscany was the immediate predecessor and likely ancestor of Etruscan civilisation, producing the earliest cremation urn culture of Iron Age Italy and a distinctive biconical ceramic tradition. The transition from Villanovan to Etruscan represents either an indigenous development or — as ancient sources including Herodotus claimed — the arrival of migrants from Lydia in Anatolia. Modern genetic and linguistic studies have decisively supported indigenous Italian development, but the Lydian migration narrative was influential in antiquity. The Villanovan-Etruscan continuum represents the most sophisticated pre-Roman Iron Age culture of the Italian peninsula.","up":1040,"dn":200},
  {"id":380,"n":"Phoenician / Punic Colonies","s":-1100,"e":-146,"r":"Western Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Phoenician colonial network across the western Mediterranean — Carthage (id 330), Gadir (Cadiz), Utica, Leptis Magna, Panormus (Palermo) and dozens of smaller settlements — represented the ancient world's most extensive and durable trading diaspora, established from approximately 1100 BCE onwards. These colonies served as way-stations for the Atlantic trade in Cornish tin and Iberian silver and copper, and as markets for the distribution of Phoenician luxury goods: purple-dyed textiles, glass, fine metalwork and cedar timber. The Carthaginian explorer Hanno's circumnavigation of West Africa around 500 BCE, if the Periplus is accurate, represents the first known European contact with sub-Saharan Africa.","up":1280,"dn":220},
  {"id":382,"n":"Greek Dark Age / Geometric Period","s":-1100,"e":-800,"r":"Greece / Aegean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Greek Dark Age (c.1100–800 BCE) followed the Bronze Age Collapse — a period of depopulation, disappearance of writing, abandonment of palaces, and contraction of trade networks that reversed centuries of Aegean civilisational development. Yet this apparent decline was also a period of transformation: the arrival of iron technology, the composition (or crystallisation) of the Homeric epics, the emergence of the polis (city-state) as the fundamental Greek political unit, and the beginning of the Greek colonisation movement that would spread Greek culture across the Mediterranean. The Geometric pottery of this period, with its precise mathematical patterns, shows that cultural creativity did not disappear even as monumental architecture and literacy temporarily vanished.","up":1180,"dn":180},
  {"id":383,"n":"Archaic / Classical Greece","s":-800,"e":-323,"r":"Greece / Mediterranean","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Archaic and Classical periods of Greek civilisation (800–323 BCE) produced perhaps the most concentrated burst of intellectual and artistic creativity in human history. The Greek polis system — hundreds of independent city-states competing politically, militarily and culturally — generated philosophy (Thales, Anaximander, Heraclitus, Socrates, Plato, Aristotle), drama (Aeschylus, Sophocles, Euripides, Aristophanes), history (Herodotus, Thucydides), mathematics (Pythagoras, Euclid), science (Hippocrates, Democritus) and sculpture (Pheidias, Praxiteles) in rapid succession. The Persian Wars (490–479 BCE) and subsequent Athenian Empire, followed by the Peloponnesian War's catastrophic conclusion, shaped the political context within which this creativity occurred.","up":1840,"dn":240},
  {"id":384,"n":"Spartan Civilisation","s":-900,"e":-146,"r":"Peloponnese, Greece","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"Sparta was the most militarised state in Greek history, a society organised entirely around the production of elite warrior citizens through the agoge — a brutal educational system beginning at age seven — and maintained by a subjugated helot population that outnumbered Spartans by perhaps seven to one. Spartan women enjoyed freedoms — physical exercise, property ownership, participation in public life — unmatched elsewhere in the Greek world, a consequence of the system's need for physically fit mothers of warriors. The 300 Spartans at Thermopylae (480 BCE), though a military defeat, became antiquity's most celebrated example of sacrifice for the collective, shaping Western ideas of heroism and duty for two and a half millennia. Sparta's failure to adapt economically and demographically led to slow decline after the 4th century BCE.","up":1680,"dn":240},
  {"id":385,"n":"Minoan / Akrotiri","s":-1700,"e":-1620,"r":"Thera (Santorini), Aegean","t":"debated","cont":"europe","d":"Akrotiri on the island of Thera (modern Santorini) was a thriving Minoan-influenced Bronze Age town buried under volcanic ash by the catastrophic Theran eruption of approximately 1620 BCE — the most powerful volcanic event of the past 4,000 years and one of the most consequential natural disasters in human history. The preserved town, excavated from 1967 by Spyridon Marinatos, contains multi-storey buildings, sophisticated drainage systems, and extraordinarily vivid frescoes depicting boxing boys, antelopes, ships and the famous 'flotilla fresco' showing a sea voyage. The eruption generated tsunamis affecting the entire Eastern Mediterranean and is proposed by many researchers as the origin of both the Atlantis legend and the biblical Exodus plagues.","up":1640,"dn":420,"dateTheories":[{"s":-1620,"e":-1600,"label":"Mainstream — eruption c.1620–1600 BCE based on ice cores and tree rings; caused regional disruption but did not destroy Minoan civilisation directly","source":"Manning et al., Science (2006)","researcher":null,"up":1240,"dn":320},{"s":-1620,"e":-1600,"label":"Atlantis / Exodus connection — Theran eruption is the origin of Plato's Atlantis narrative and the Exodus plagues; tsunami wiped Minoan fleet and damaged Egypt","source":"Pellegrino, Unearthing Atlantis (1991); Galanopoulos (1969)","researcher":null,"up":780,"dn":680}]},
  {"id":386,"n":"Chalcolithic / Copper Age Cultures","s":-4500,"e":-3000,"r":"Europe / Middle East / South Asia","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Chalcolithic (Copper Age) period, spanning approximately 4500 to 3000 BCE, marks the transition between the Stone Age and the Bronze Age — the first use of metal tools, initially pure copper, which appeared independently in multiple regions including the Balkans, Anatolia, the Levant and the Indus Valley. The Copper Age Balkans produced remarkably sophisticated goldwork — the Varna necropolis in Bulgaria (c.4450 BCE) contains the world's oldest known gold jewellery and grave goods more elaborate than anything in contemporary Egypt — challenging assumptions about where the earliest complex societies developed. The Iceman 'Ötzi' (c.3300 BCE), found preserved in alpine ice in 1991, provides an intimate portrait of a Chalcolithic individual complete with tools, clothing, food and a copper axe.","up":1280,"dn":200},
  {"id":387,"n":"Linear Pottery Culture (LBK)","s":-5500,"e":-4500,"r":"Central Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Linearbandkeramik (LBK) or Linear Pottery Culture was the first farming culture of Central Europe, spreading from its origins in the Hungarian Plain across the loess belt of Europe from France to Ukraine between approximately 5500 and 4500 BCE in one of the most rapid agricultural expansions in prehistoric history. LBK communities built long houses — timber halls of 20–40 metres — farmed emmer wheat and einkorn, and kept cattle, sheep and pigs. Ancient DNA studies have shown that the LBK expansion involved a Near Eastern farming population almost entirely replacing the indigenous Mesolithic hunter-gatherers of Europe — a genetic replacement comparable in scale to the later Yamnaya expansion — before being itself substantially replaced by steppe-ancestry populations after 3000 BCE.","up":1140,"dn":200},
  {"id":388,"n":"Mesolithic / Hunter-Gatherer Europe","s":-10000,"e":-5000,"r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Mesolithic hunter-gatherers of Europe (c.10,000–5,000 BCE) were the descendants of the Palaeolithic people who had inhabited Europe for tens of thousands of years, adapting to the warming climate after the Last Glacial Maximum with increasingly sophisticated microlith technology, coastal and riverine exploitation, and evidence of complex social organisation. Ancient DNA has revealed them as a genetically distinctive population — dark-skinned, blue-eyed (a combination modern Europeans rarely possess) — that was largely replaced by incoming Near Eastern farmers during the Neolithic transition. The rare sites where their culture survives in detail — Star Carr in Yorkshire, the Lepenski Vir fish-shrine settlements on the Danube — reveal communities of unexpected social complexity and artistic sensibility.","up":1180,"dn":180},
  {"id":389,"n":"Palaeolithic Cave Art Cultures","s":-40000,"e":-10000,"r":"Europe / Global","t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The explosion of cave art in Europe beginning approximately 40,000 years ago — at sites including Chauvet, Altamira, Lascaux, Pech Merle and Font-de-Gaume — represents the earliest unambiguous evidence of symbolic thinking, aesthetic sensibility and possibly religious belief in the human archaeological record. The sophistication of Palaeolithic art is astonishing: the Chauvet Cave paintings (c.36,000 BCE) show a mastery of perspective, movement and naturalistic animal depiction that was not surpassed in Western art for tens of thousands of years. Researchers including David Lewis-Williams have proposed a neuropsychological model in which cave art reflects shamanic altered states of consciousness; others see it as hunting magic, territorial marking, or cosmological mapping.","up":1680,"dn":240},
  {"id":391,"n":"Neanderthal Culture","s":-400000,"e":-40000,"r":"Europe / Middle East / Central Asia","t":"theorized","cont":"europe","d":"Neanderthals (Homo neanderthalensis) inhabited Europe and western Asia for approximately 400,000 years before disappearing around 40,000 BCE following the arrival of anatomically modern humans — with whom they interbred, leaving 1–4% Neanderthal DNA in most non-African modern humans. Long caricatured as dim-witted brutes, Neanderthals are now understood to have been cognitively sophisticated: they buried their dead (possibly with flowers at Shanidar Cave), created cave art (the El Castillo cave paintings at 65,000 BCE may be Neanderthal), wore pigments and eagle-feather ornaments, made sophisticated composite tools, and cared for injured group members. The nature of their relationship with modern humans — coexistence, competition, interbreeding — remains one of the most actively debated questions in palaeoanthropology.","up":1680,"dn":280},
  {"id":392,"n":"Göbekli Tepe / Karahan Tepe Complex","s":-9600,"e":-7000,"r":"Southeastern Turkey","t":"debated","cont":"middle-east","d":"Karahan Tepe, discovered in 1997 but only systematically excavated from 2019, is now understood to be a sister site to Göbekli Tepe — equally ancient, equally monumental, and featuring distinctive carved pillars including a haunting human head emerging from a wall and a serpent-covered pillar of striking naturalistic power. Together with Taş Tepeler ('Stone Hills'), a wider network of at least twelve Pre-Pottery Neolithic sites in the Şanlıurfa region of southeastern Turkey, these sites suggest that Göbekli Tepe was not an isolated anomaly but part of a regional tradition of hunter-gatherer monumental construction that lasted over two millennia. The scale and sophistication of the Taş Tepeler network has dramatically expanded the known complexity of pre-agricultural human society.","up":1580,"dn":320,"dateTheories":[{"s":-9600,"e":-7000,"label":"Mainstream — Karahan Tepe and the Taş Tepeler network are Pre-Pottery Neolithic A/B hunter-gatherer ceremonial sites; part of the same cultural horizon as Göbekli Tepe","source":"Karul, Karahan Tepe excavation reports (2019–2023)","researcher":null,"up":1280,"dn":280},{"s":-11000,"e":-9600,"label":"Alternative — the network's scale suggests organisation beyond typical hunter-gatherer capacity; possibly evidence of a pre-Younger Dryas civilisation using these hills as refugia","source":"Hancock, Ancient Apocalypse (Netflix, 2022)","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":860,"dn":780}]},
  {"id":394,"n":"Jericho / Pre-Pottery Neolithic","s":-9000,"e":-5000,"r":"West Bank / Jordan Valley","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"Jericho in the Jordan Valley is one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world, with evidence of permanent settlement beginning around 9000 BCE — making it a strong candidate for the world's oldest town. Its Pre-Pottery Neolithic A phase (c.9000–8000 BCE) produced a remarkable stone tower approximately 8 metres tall and 9 metres in diameter — the Tower of Jericho — built without metal tools and representing the oldest known monumental architecture in the world, predating Göbekli Tepe's enclosures by several centuries in terms of permanent settlement. The biblical narrative of Joshua's conquest of Jericho and the falling walls has been the subject of intense archaeological investigation, with mainstream archaeology finding no evidence of walls or destruction corresponding to the biblical account's proposed date.","up":1540,"dn":260},
  {"id":395,"n":"Ain Ghazal / Natufian Culture","s":-12000,"e":-7000,"r":"Jordan / Levant","t":"confirmed","cont":"middle-east","d":"The Natufian culture (c.12,500–9,500 BCE) of the Levant was a pivotal transitional society — sedentary hunter-gatherers who built permanent villages, developed complex mortuary practices including skull removal and plastering, and began cultivating wild cereals without yet domesticating them. Ain Ghazal near modern Amman, Jordan, produced some of the most extraordinary Neolithic art ever discovered: two caches of plaster statues and busts dated to approximately 7000 BCE, including full human figures with painted eyes, representing some of the earliest monumental sculptures in human history. The Natufian culture is considered the immediate precursor of the Neolithic agricultural revolution in the Levant.","up":1380,"dn":200},
  {"id":396,"n":"Easter Island / Rapa Nui","s":700,"e":1722,"r":"Easter Island, Pacific Ocean","t":"debated","cont":"oceania","d":"Rapa Nui (Easter Island) is famous for its 887 monumental stone statues (moai), carved from compressed volcanic ash between approximately 1250 and 1500 CE and transported and erected across the island by a Polynesian civilisation that had been isolated in the remote eastern Pacific for centuries. The island's ecological collapse — driven by deforestation for agriculture, rat predation of seeds, and the construction and transport of the moai — has become a widely cited cautionary tale about civilisational overreach of natural resources. Thor Heyerdahl controversially proposed that Rapa Nui was settled from South America rather than Polynesia, a view rejected by mainstream linguistics and genetics but supported by Heyerdahl's famous Kon-Tiki voyage and partially vindicated by 2020 ancient DNA evidence showing pre-contact South American gene flow into eastern Polynesian populations.","up":1680,"dn":380,"dateTheories":[{"s":700,"e":1722,"label":"Mainstream — Polynesian settlement c.700–1000 CE from the Marquesas; moai built 1250–1500 CE; ecological collapse preceded European contact","source":"Hunt & Lipo, The Statues that Walked (2011)","researcher":null,"up":1280,"dn":300},{"s":700,"e":1722,"label":"Heyerdahl — significant South American contact or settlement; kumara (sweet potato) and stone construction techniques suggest pre-Columbian trans-Pacific contact","source":"Heyerdahl, Aku-Aku (1958); Moreno-Mayar et al., Nature (2020)","researcher":"Thor Heyerdahl","up":780,"dn":640}]},
  {"id":397,"n":"Cahokia Mounds","s":600,"e":1400,"r":"Illinois, USA","t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"Cahokia, near modern St Louis, was the largest pre-Columbian city north of Mexico, reaching its peak population of perhaps 10,000–20,000 between 1050 and 1200 CE — larger than London at the same time. Its central feature, Monks Mound, is the largest prehistoric earthwork in the Americas: 30 metres high with a base area exceeding that of the Great Pyramid of Giza. Woodhenge — a series of large timber circles used for solar astronomical alignment — demonstrates sophisticated calendrical knowledge. Cahokia's sudden rise around 1050 CE remains unexplained, and its equally rapid decline by 1350 CE is attributed to a combination of flooding, agricultural exhaustion, political collapse and possibly the Little Ice Age's impact on maize agriculture.","up":1640,"dn":220},
  {"id":398,"n":"Göbekli Tepe / Younger Dryas Boundary","s":-10900,"e":-9600,"r":"Global / Near East","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"The Younger Dryas Boundary (YDB) event at approximately 10,900 BCE represents one of the most dramatic and debated episodes in Quaternary science — a sudden return to near-glacial conditions lasting approximately 1,200 years, whose cause remains contested. The Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis (YDIH), proposed by Richard Firestone, Allen West and colleagues in a 2007 PNAS paper, argues that a fragmented comet or asteroid impacted the North American ice sheet, triggering massive wildfires, the extinction of megafauna, the collapse of the Clovis culture, and abrupt climate change. Graham Hancock and Randall Carlson have built on the YDIH to propose that this event destroyed a pre-Flood advanced civilisation, with Göbekli Tepe's builders being survivors. The YDIH remains actively debated in the scientific literature.","up":1840,"dn":680,"dateTheories":[{"s":-10900,"e":-9600,"label":"Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis — extraterrestrial impact on the Laurentide Ice Sheet triggered the Younger Dryas cooling, megafaunal extinctions and Clovis collapse","source":"Firestone et al., PNAS (2007); Kinzie et al., Journal of Geology (2014)","researcher":"Richard Firestone","up":1240,"dn":580},{"s":-10900,"e":-9600,"label":"Mainstream climate science — Younger Dryas caused by disruption of Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC) by glacial meltwater; no confirmed extraterrestrial impact signature","source":"Broecker et al., Paleoceanography (2010)","researcher":null,"up":980,"dn":840}]},
  {"id":399,"n":"Göbekli Tepe / Pre-Flood Civilisation","s":-13000,"e":-10900,"r":"Global (theorized)","t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"The Pre-Flood or Pre-Younger Dryas advanced civilisation hypothesis, most prominently associated with Graham Hancock, proposes that a sophisticated human society — comparable in some ways to Bronze Age civilisations — existed during the last Ice Age and was destroyed by the cataclysms of the Younger Dryas Boundary event around 10,900 BCE, leaving only scattered survivors who transmitted memory of the lost world through flood myths worldwide and encoded astronomical knowledge in monuments like Göbekli Tepe, the Great Sphinx, and possibly Gunung Padang. Randall Carlson's detailed work on the Missoula megafloods and Carolina Bays provides the geological evidence Hancock invokes. The hypothesis remains outside mainstream archaeology but has attracted serious attention from some researchers following the publication of the YDIH.","up":1960,"dn":840,"dateTheories":[{"s":-13000,"e":-10900,"label":"Hancock / Carlson — an Ice Age civilisation existed 13,000–10,900 BCE; destroyed by YDB impact events; survivors seeded global civilisation; Göbekli Tepe is their monument","source":"Hancock, Magicians of the Gods (2015); Carlson, Kosmographia podcast","researcher":"Graham Hancock","up":1480,"dn":760},{"s":-13000,"e":-10900,"label":"Mainstream archaeology — no physical evidence of a complex civilisation before 10,000 BCE; Göbekli Tepe builders were hunter-gatherers; flood myths are universal but not evidence of a single event","source":"Banning, Current Anthropology (2011)","researcher":null,"up":840,"dn":1040}]},
  {"id":400,"n":"The Younger Dryas Megaflood","s":-10900,"e":-9600,"r":"North America / Global","t":"debated","cont":"global","d":"The Missoula Megafloods were a series of catastrophic glacial outburst floods originating from the collapse of ice dams holding Glacial Lake Missoula in modern Montana, releasing up to 2,500 cubic kilometres of water at a time — a flow rate approximately ten times the combined discharge of all modern rivers on Earth — and carving the Channeled Scablands of Washington State in days or weeks. Geologist J Harlen Bretz first proposed this mechanism in the 1920s and was ridiculed for decades before vindication. Randall Carlson has extensively documented the scale of these events and, together with Graham Hancock, proposed that similar or related megaflood events associated with the Younger Dryas Boundary were catastrophic enough to have destroyed an Ice Age civilisation and generated the world's flood myths.","up":1780,"dn":520,"dateTheories":[{"s":-13000,"e":-9600,"label":"Mainstream geology — Missoula Megafloods occurred in multiple pulses between ~18,000 and 13,000 BP; carved Channeled Scablands; caused by glacial dam failures, not cosmic impact","source":"Bretz, Journal of Geology (1923); Baker, Science (1978)","researcher":null,"up":1380,"dn":380},{"s":-10900,"e":-9600,"label":"Carlson / Hancock — YDB-era megafloods were triggered by extraterrestrial impacts on ice sheets; scale was globally civilisation-ending; Carolina Bays are secondary impact craters","source":"Carlson, Kosmographia (2019); Hancock, Magicians of the Gods (2015)","researcher":"Randall Carlson","up":1180,"dn":680}]},
  {"id":401,"n":"Kerma / Kingdom of Kush (Early)","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-2500,"e":-1500,"p":80000,"lang":"kushitic","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Kerma culture of Upper Nubia (~2500–1500 BCE) represents one of Africa's earliest and most powerful indigenous kingdoms, flourishing along the Nile south of the third cataract in present-day Sudan. At its height the Kingdom of Kerma fielded armies capable of challenging Middle Kingdom Egypt and formed alliances with the Hyksos during Egypt's Second Intermediate Period. The Kerma people built massive mudbrick burial tumuli (deffufas) of extraordinary scale and sophistication, with evidence of elite burials involving hundreds of sacrificed retainers. Contemporary Egyptological scholarship has increasingly recognised Kerma as a peer civilisation to Egypt rather than a peripheral culture, though its full cultural complexity continues to be reassessed as excavations at the site of Kerma deepen."},
  {"id":402,"n":"Phrygian Kingdom","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-1200,"e":-546,"p":500000,"lang":"phrygian","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Phrygian Kingdom of central Anatolia (~1200–546 BCE) rose to prominence following the collapse of the Hittite Empire and at its height under King Midas controlled much of Asia Minor. The Phrygians contributed significantly to Aegean and Near Eastern culture: their music (the Phrygian mode), their goddess Cybele — the Great Mother — who was later adopted by Greece and Rome, and their distinctive carved rock facades and tumulus burials. King Midas is a historical figure whose legendary golden touch may encode memory of Phrygia's genuine mineral wealth. The kingdom was absorbed into the Lydian and subsequently Persian empires, though Phrygian religious traditions survived for centuries in Greek and Roman mystery cult practices."},
  {"id":403,"n":"Lydian Empire","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-700,"e":-546,"p":600000,"lang":"lydian","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Lydian Empire of western Anatolia (~700–546 BCE) is credited by Herodotus with the invention of coinage — the first known use of stamped electrum coins as a standardised medium of exchange, an innovation that transformed commerce across the ancient world. Under King Croesus, Lydia achieved extraordinary wealth and became a major diplomatic player, seeking alliances with Greece and Egypt against the rising Persian threat. The Lydians developed sophisticated trade networks, legal institutions, and a material culture of considerable refinement. Croesus's famous exchange with Solon about happiness and his disastrous campaign against Cyrus the Great of Persia, which ended Lydian independence, became a foundational story in Greek philosophy about the limits of wealth and the unpredictability of fate."},
  {"id":405,"n":"Tocharian Civilisation","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2000,"e":900,"p":200000,"lang":"tocharian","gov":"city-state","d":"The Tocharians were an Indo-European-speaking people of the Tarim Basin in present-day western China, known from Buddhist texts and manuscripts in two related languages (Tocharian A and B) discovered in oasis towns along the northern Silk Road. Their physical remains — mummies preserved in the desert conditions of the Tarim Basin dating to ~2000 BCE — show strikingly Western features including red and blonde hair, confounding early assumptions about population movements into Central Asia. The Tocharian languages are linguistically closest to Celtic and Italic branches of Indo-European, suggesting an ancient migration from western Eurasia. The Tocharians served as cultural intermediaries transmitting Buddhism, art traditions, and technologies between India, Iran, China, and the steppe world before Turkic expansion absorbed their communities."},
  {"id":406,"n":"Sogdian Merchant Network","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":300,"e":1000,"p":300000,"lang":"sogdian","gov":"merchant-republic","d":"The Sogdians of ancient Transoxiana (present-day Uzbekistan and Tajikistan) built one of the ancient world's most remarkable commercial civilisations — not through military conquest but through mercantile genius. From approximately 300–1000 CE, Sogdian merchants dominated the Silk Road trade from China to Byzantium, establishing diaspora trading colonies across Central Asia and into Tang Dynasty China. Sogdian letters discovered near Dunhuang dating to ~313 CE are the earliest known merchant correspondence from the Silk Road. The Sogdians transmitted Buddhism, Zoroastrianism, Manichaeism, and Christianity along their trade routes, as well as technologies including papermaking, silk weaving, and musical instruments. Their script directly influenced the development of the Uyghur, Mongolian, and Manchu writing systems, giving them an outsized linguistic legacy far beyond their political power."},
  {"id":407,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1450,"p":10000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Moundville in present-day Alabama was the second-largest Mississippian urban centre after Cahokia, reaching its peak between 1000–1350 CE with a population of approximately 10,000 and covering 300 acres along the Black Warrior River. The site features 29 platform mounds arranged around a central plaza, with the largest mounds associated with elite residences and mortuary facilities. Moundville's material culture — particularly its engraved shell gorgets and ceramics depicting a distinctive iconographic system scholars call the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex — reveals a sophisticated cosmological and political programme shared across the Mississippian world. The site appears to have transitioned from a densely inhabited urban centre to a largely vacant mortuary precinct by around 1300 CE, suggesting a deliberate ceremonial reorganisation rather than simple decline."},
  {"id":408,"n":"Hopewell Interaction Sphere","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":500,"p":50000,"lang":"various-eastern-woodlands","gov":"chiefdom-network","d":"The Hopewell Interaction Sphere (~100 BCE–500 CE) was not a single civilisation but a remarkable continent-spanning exchange network centred in the Ohio and Illinois river valleys, through which prestige goods, religious ideas, and mortuary practices were shared across an area stretching from the Rocky Mountains to the Atlantic coast. Hopewell earthworks — geometric enclosures of extraordinary precision and scale, some covering four square miles — served as ceremonial gathering sites rather than permanent settlements. Hopewell burial mounds contain objects of copper from the Great Lakes, obsidian from Yellowstone, mica from the Appalachians, shark teeth from the Gulf Coast, and grizzly bear skulls from the Rockies, demonstrating trade networks of continental scope. The collapse of Hopewell around 500 CE remains one of North American archaeology's most debated questions."},
  {"id":410,"n":"Tiwanaku Empire","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":500,"e":1000,"p":400000,"lang":"puquina","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Tiwanaku Empire (~500–1000 CE) centred at its eponymous capital on the Bolivian Altiplano at 3,850 metres elevation — one of the highest urban centres in the ancient world — developed an sophisticated state religion and agricultural system that sustained populations across the harsh high-altitude environment of the Andes. Tiwanaku's raised field (suka kollus) agriculture transformed the marshy shores of Lake Titicaca into highly productive farmland through an ingenious system of water channels that regulated temperature and moisture. The site's monumental Gateway of the Sun, megalithic stone architecture, and distinctive iconography — particularly the Staff God figure — spread across the Andean world and persisted long after Tiwanaku's political collapse. Arthur Posnansky controversially dated Tiwanaku's astronomical alignments to ~15,000 BCE; mainstream archaeology dates the monumental phase to 500–900 CE."},
  {"id":412,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Spiro Mounds","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":800,"e":1450,"p":2000,"lang":"caddoan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Spiro Mounds in present-day Oklahoma was the westernmost major centre of the Mississippian Southeastern Ceremonial Complex, a ceremonial site of extraordinary significance that served as a mortuary and ritual hub for a vast regional network spanning the Southern Plains and the Southeast. The Craig Mound at Spiro contained one of the richest concentrations of Mississippian ceremonial objects ever found — carved shell cups, engraved conch shells, copper plates, effigy pipes, and cedar litter poles — but it was catastrophically looted by commercial diggers between 1933–1935 before scientific excavation could begin, destroying irreplaceable archaeological context. What survived demonstrated that Spiro was a major redistribution centre for prestige goods and a site of intense religious activity connecting the Plains world to the broader Mississippian system, challenging assumptions about the cultural boundaries between these two traditions."},
  {"id":414,"n":"Mixtec Civilisation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1521,"p":150000,"lang":"mixtec","gov":"city-state","d":"The Mixtec civilisation of highland Oaxaca and the Mixteca Alta (~900–1521 CE) produced some of the finest manuscript painting in the pre-Columbian world — the Mixtec codices (screenfold books) including the Codex Zouche-Nuttall and Codex Vindobonensis record detailed dynastic histories, genealogies, and ritual calendars stretching back centuries. Mixtec goldwork, turquoise mosaic, and carved bone achieved technical standards that astonished the Spanish conquistadors, and many of the finest objects in early colonial European collections of 'Mexican' art are Mixtec in origin or heavily Mixtec-influenced. The historical figure Lord Eight Deer Jaguar Claw, whose life and military career are recorded in multiple codices, represents one of the most fully documented individuals in pre-Columbian American history. The Mixtecs were never fully conquered by the Aztec Triple Alliance and maintained considerable political autonomy until Spanish contact."},
  {"id":415,"n":"Aksumite Predecessor — D'mt Kingdom","r":"Africa","t":"debated","s":-800,"e":-400,"p":100000,"lang":"ge-ez-proto","gov":"monarchy","d":"The D'mt Kingdom of the northern Ethiopian Highlands and Eritrea (~800–400 BCE) is one of the earliest known complex states in sub-Saharan Africa and the least understood predecessor to the Aksumite civilisation, with which it shares geographic space and possibly cultural continuity. D'mt inscriptions in a South Arabian script and the presence of South Arabian material culture have generated significant debate about whether D'mt was a South Arabian colony, an indigenous African state that adopted South Arabian writing, or a hybrid polity arising from sustained contact across the Red Sea. Archaeological sites including Yeha — with its remarkable pre-Aksumite temple of possibly 7th century BCE date — demonstrate architectural and cultural sophistication well beyond what colonial-era scholarship attributed to the region. Mainstream scholarship continues to reassess D'mt's relationship to Aksumite origins and the broader question of Red Sea cross-cultural interaction."},
  {"id":416,"n":"Garamantian Civilisation","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-500,"e":700,"p":100000,"lang":"berber-garamantian","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Garamantes of the central Sahara (present-day Fezzan, Libya) built one of the ancient world's most extraordinary hydraulic engineering feats entirely beneath the Saharan desert: a network of underground irrigation tunnels (foggaras) stretching over 3,500km total length, tapping fossil water aquifers to irrigate oasis agriculture in one of Earth's most hostile environments. At the height of their power (~1st–3rd century CE) the Garamantes controlled trans-Saharan trade routes connecting sub-Saharan Africa to the Roman Mediterranean, trading in gold, slaves, exotic animals, and precious stones. Roman military expeditions against the Garamantes document them as a major regional power, not a simple tribal society. Their civilisation collapsed as the fossil aquifers were depleted, a cautionary case study in non-renewable resource dependency that has resonances with modern desert agriculture."},
  {"id":417,"n":"Nok Civilisation","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-1000,"e":300,"p":150000,"lang":"benue-congo-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Nok culture of central Nigeria (~1000 BCE–300 CE) produced the earliest known sub-Saharan African terracotta sculpture tradition — life-sized and near-life-sized human heads and figures of striking naturalism and technical sophistication, fired at temperatures requiring considerable ceramic expertise. The Nok people also practised iron smelting from approximately 500 BCE, making them among the earliest iron-using cultures in Africa, though debate continues about whether their metallurgical knowledge was independently developed or transmitted from North Africa. Despite a century of scholarship, fundamental questions about Nok political organisation, language, and relationship to later Nigerian cultures including the Ife and Benin bronze traditions remain open. Many Nok terracottas have been illegally excavated and traded on the international art market, severely limiting archaeological context for what survive in institutional collections."},
  {"id":419,"n":"Great Zimbabwe — Extended Kingdom","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1420,"p":18000,"lang":"shona-proto","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Great Zimbabwe kingdom — centred on the remarkable dry-stone walled enclosure complex of Great Zimbabwe in present-day Zimbabwe, the largest pre-colonial stone structure south of the Sahara — controlled the gold trade routes between the interior of southern Africa and the Swahili Coast ports at its height between approximately 1250–1420 CE. The Great Enclosure's massive walls, some reaching 11 metres in height and 5 metres thick, were constructed without mortar using a sophisticated interlocking granite block technique. Colonial-era scholars systematically denied African origins for the structure, attributing it variously to Phoenicians, Arabs, or the Queen of Sheba — attributions now entirely rejected by archaeology. The kingdom's collapse around 1420 CE appears linked to the southward migration of political and trade power toward the emerging Mutapa state and possibly to resource depletion in the surrounding region."},
  {"id":420,"n":"Hyperborea","r":"Europe","t":"theorized","s":-50000,"e":-10000,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"Hyperborea — literally 'Beyond the North Wind' — appears in ancient Greek tradition as a land of perfect climate and immortal, blessed people located far to the north, beyond Boreas the north wind. Pindar, Herodotus, Hecataeus of Abdera, and Pliny all mention Hyperborea in varying degrees of literalism, and the Hyperboreans are associated with the worship of Apollo, whose mythology contains strong northern elements suggesting possible origins in an older tradition. In alternative archaeology, Hyperborea is proposed as a memory of a pre-Younger Dryas Arctic or sub-Arctic civilisation made habitable by a different climate regime or crustal configuration. Charles Hapgood's crustal displacement hypothesis specifically links Hyperborea to a pre-displacement polar configuration. The mainstream scholarly consensus treats Hyperborea as mythological. The persistence and consistency of the tradition across multiple ancient cultures raises questions about what historical kernel, if any, underlies it."},
  {"id":421,"n":"Tartaria / Proto-Writing Culture","r":"Europe","t":"debated","s":-5500,"e":-3500,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"The Tartaria tablets — three clay tablets bearing inscribed signs discovered at Tartaria in Romania in 1961, radiocarbon-dated to approximately 5300 BCE — are among the most contested objects in the archaeology of writing, predating the earliest accepted Sumerian writing by over a millennium if their dates are genuine. Romanian archaeologist Nicolae Vlassa, who excavated the tablets, claimed they bore resemblance to early Sumerian proto-cuneiform. Subsequent scholars have argued the signs represent a local Vinča culture symbolic system (sometimes called the Danube Script or Old European Script) rather than true writing, and that no phonetic or semantic decoding is possible. The broader Vinča culture of southeastern Europe (~5700–4500 BCE) produced hundreds of incised signs on pottery that some researchers — including Marija Gimbutas and Harald Haarmann — argue constitute an independent writing system predating Near Eastern writing. The debate remains unresolved and has significant implications for our understanding of cognitive development and cultural transmission in prehistoric Europe."},
  {"id":422,"n":"Mu / Lemuria","r":"Oceania","t":"theorized","s":-200000,"e":-10000,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"Lemuria was coined as a geological hypothesis by zoologist Philip Sclater in 1864 to explain the distribution of lemur fossils across India, Madagascar, and southeastern Africa — proposing a now-sunken landmass connecting these regions. The geological basis was superseded by plate tectonics. The concept was subsequently taken up by Madame Blavatsky in The Secret Doctrine (1888) as the realm of humanity's third 'root race,' and by Colonel James Churchward in The Lost Continent of Mu (1926) as an advanced Pacific civilisation. In alternative archaeology, Mu/Lemuria is proposed as a Pacific or Indian Ocean precursor civilisation destroyed by geological or cosmic catastrophe. Stephen Oppenheimer's Sundaland thesis offers a geologically defensible version of a significant Indo-Pacific landmass lost to post-glacial sea-level rise. The concept of Lemuria as an advanced civilisation rests on no archaeological evidence, though the genuine submergence of vast coastal and island territories during deglaciation remains an important context for evaluating origin myths across Pacific and Indian Ocean cultures."},
  {"id":423,"n":"Vedic Golden Age / Satya Yuga","r":"Asia","t":"theorized","s":-3900000,"e":-1200000,"p":0,"lang":"vedic-sanskrit","gov":"unknown","d":"The Vedic conception of cyclical time — the Yuga system recorded in the Mahabharata, Puranas, and other Sanskrit texts — describes the Satya Yuga (Golden Age) as a period of perfect dharma, longevity, and spiritual achievement lasting 1,728,000 years, followed by progressively declining ages culminating in the current Kali Yuga of darkness and moral decline. Sri Yukteswar in The Holy Science (1894) proposed an alternative calculation placing the current era at the beginning of an ascending Dwapara Yuga rather than deep within the Kali Yuga, based on a different interpretation of the astronomical cycle. David Frawley's work in Gods, Sages and Kings (1991) argues that Vedic astronomical references encode genuine observations from the third and fourth millennia BCE, suggesting a much older origin for Sanskrit astronomical knowledge than mainstream Indology accepts. Giorgio de Santillana's Hamlet's Mill (1969) connects Vedic mythological cycles to precessional astronomy. Whether the Yuga system encodes genuine astronomical cycles, historical memory, or purely spiritual symbolism remains a central question in Vedic studies."},
  {"id":424,"n":"Polynesian Navigation Civilisation","r":"Oceania","t":"confirmed","s":-1000,"e":1300,"p":300000,"lang":"proto-polynesian","gov":"chiefdom-network","d":"The Polynesian expansion across the Pacific Ocean (~1000 BCE–1300 CE) represents the greatest maritime achievement in human history prior to European oceanic exploration — a deliberate, systematic colonisation of the largest ocean on Earth using only double-hulled canoes, traditional navigation knowledge, and the stars. From a homeland in western Polynesia, Polynesian navigators settled Hawaii (~300–500 CE), Easter Island/Rapa Nui (~300–500 CE), and New Zealand (~1250–1300 CE), as well as hundreds of island groups across 10 million square kilometres of open ocean. Polynesian wayfinding used star paths, ocean swell patterns, cloud formations, bird behaviour, bioluminescence, and wind direction — a comprehensive environmental reading system maintained entirely in oral and embodied tradition. Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki experiment proposed significant South American contact with Polynesia, a claim now supported by genetic evidence of pre-Columbian Polynesian-South American admixture in eastern Polynesian populations."},
  {"id":425,"n":"Chamorro / Mariana Islands Civilisation","r":"Oceania","t":"confirmed","s":-1500,"e":1668,"p":50000,"lang":"chamorro","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Chamorro people of the Mariana Islands in the western Pacific developed one of the most distinctive architectural traditions in Oceania — the latte stone structures, consisting of pairs of massive limestone or coral stone pillars topped with hemispherical capstones, which served as foundation supports for elite residences and communal structures. The largest latte stones at the House of Taga on Tinian stand over 4.5 metres tall and weigh up to 30 tonnes, requiring significant collective engineering capability. The Chamorros maintained a stratified society with a hereditary noble class (matao) and complex kinship and ritual systems. Spanish colonial contact from 1668 brought devastating population collapse through introduced disease and deliberate military violence — the Chamorro population fell from an estimated 50,000–100,000 to fewer than 5,000 within decades, one of history's most catastrophic colonial depopulations."},
  {"id":426,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Angel Mounds","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1450,"p":3000,"lang":"various-ohio-valley","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Angel Mounds in present-day Indiana was one of the largest Mississippian settlements in the Ohio River valley, with a peak population of approximately 3,000 people within a 103-acre palisaded town containing 11 earthen mounds of varying sizes. The site demonstrates the remarkable standardisation of Mississippian town planning — a central plaza flanked by platform mounds for elite and ceremonial use, surrounded by domestic areas and enclosed by a defensive wooden palisade — replicated with local variations across hundreds of sites from Wisconsin to Florida. Angel Mounds was occupied from approximately 1100–1450 CE and its abandonment, like that of Cahokia and other major Mississippian centres, coincides with a period of regional climate instability associated with the transition out of the Medieval Warm Period, suggesting environmental stress as a contributing factor to Mississippian civilisational reorganisation."},
  {"id":428,"n":"Ancestral Puebloans — Chaco Canyon Extended","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":850,"e":1150,"p":5000,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"Chaco Canyon in present-day New Mexico served as the ritual and administrative centre of the Ancestral Puebloan world at its height (~850–1150 CE), with Great Houses — massive multi-storey stone buildings of extraordinary precision including Pueblo Bonito's 650+ rooms — connected to a 650-kilometre network of engineered roads radiating across the Colorado Plateau. The roads, running in mathematically straight lines regardless of topography and sometimes leading to no obvious destination, suggest a ceremonial rather than purely logistical function. Astronomical alignments at Chaco — including the famous Sun Dagger site on Fajada Butte and solar and lunar alignments built into the great house architecture — demonstrate sophisticated astronomical observation integrated into political-religious authority. The depopulation of Chaco around 1150 CE, coinciding with a prolonged drought documented in tree-ring records, has become a widely-cited case study in civilisational climate vulnerability."},
  {"id":429,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Etowah","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1550,"p":5000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Etowah Mounds in present-day Georgia was one of the most important political and ceremonial centres of the Mississippian world, featuring six earthen mounds including Mound A — the third-largest Mississippian mound in North America at 19 metres tall — surrounding a central plaza in the classic Mississippian town plan. Etowah is particularly renowned for the quality of its Southeastern Ceremonial Complex objects: marble statues of seated male and female figures of extraordinary technical refinement, embossed copper plates depicting costumed ritual performers, and engraved shell gorgets displaying a complex iconographic vocabulary shared across the Mississippian world. The site experienced multiple occupation phases, with evidence of deliberate burning and rebuilding between periods suggesting cyclical political reorganisation. European contact and the diseases that preceded it likely contributed to the final abandonment of the site in the mid-16th century."},
  {"id":430,"n":"Dorset / Pre-Dorset Arctic Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-2500,"e":1500,"p":20000,"lang":"paleo-eskimo","gov":"band","d":"The Dorset culture (~500 BCE–1500 CE) and its predecessor the Pre-Dorset (~2500–500 BCE) represent the primary human occupation of the Canadian Arctic and Greenland before the arrival of Thule Inuit ancestors from Alaska around 1000 CE. The Dorset people — known as the Tunit in Inuit oral tradition, described as a race of giants of great strength — were highly specialised Arctic hunters who subsisted primarily on ringed seals, walrus, and caribou in one of Earth's most demanding environments. Their material culture shows no evidence of dog sleds (they pulled sleds themselves), bows and arrows, or boats capable of open-water hunting — technological absences that made them vulnerable to Thule replacement. Ancient DNA analysis has confirmed Dorset people were genetically distinct from all living Arctic populations, representing a separate migration wave from Siberia. Their oral memory preservation in Inuit tradition as the Tunit represents one of the few cases of documented Indigenous memory of a now-extinct human population."},
  {"id":436,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Cahokia Monks Mound","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1350,"p":20000,"lang":"various-siouan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Monks Mound at Cahokia in present-day Illinois is the largest pre-Columbian earthwork in North America — a four-terraced platform mound covering 5.6 hectares at its base and standing 30 metres tall, built entirely of basket-carried earth over several centuries of construction beginning around 900 CE. The mound supported a large wooden structure at its summit, almost certainly the residence of Cahokia's paramount chief or priest-king. Timothy Pauketat's excavations and synthesis in Cahokia (2009) have reconstructed a sophisticated political and religious system centred on Monks Mound, with the city's layout encoding astronomical alignments and a cosmological programme. A massive wooden post circle (Woodhenge) to the west of Monks Mound functioned as a solar calendar. The mound complex is directly comparable in engineering effort to the construction of the smaller Egyptian pyramids, achieved without metal tools, wheeled vehicles, or draft animals."},
  {"id":438,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Kincaid","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1450,"p":2000,"lang":"various-ohio-valley","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Kincaid Mounds in present-day southern Illinois was one of the northernmost major Mississippian centres, a significant regional capital featuring at least 19 platform mounds arranged around multiple plazas within a palisaded town. Kincaid's position at the confluence of the Ohio, Tennessee, and Cumberland rivers placed it at one of the most strategically valuable locations in the Mississippian world for controlling river-borne trade across the Eastern Woodlands. Archaeological evidence suggests Kincaid maintained exchange relationships with Cahokia to the north and with Southeastern Ceremonial Complex centres to the south, serving as a redistribution node for prestige goods. Like most major Mississippian centres, Kincaid was abandoned well before European contact, and the exact causes — whether demographic, climatic, or political — remain subjects of active research. The site represents the northernmost extent of the classic Mississippian town planning formula."},
  {"id":439,"n":"Aksumite Civilisation (Extended)","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":940,"p":300000,"lang":"ge-ez","gov":"empire","d":"The Aksumite civilisation of the northern Ethiopian Highlands and Eritrea (~100 BCE–940 CE) was one of the great empires of the ancient and medieval world — a major commercial hub on the Red Sea trade routes linking Rome, Arabia, India, and sub-Saharan Africa, and the first sub-Saharan African state to mint its own coins. Under King Ezana in the 4th century CE, Aksum became one of the earliest states in history to adopt Christianity as a state religion, preceding the Roman Empire's full Christianisation and establishing the Ethiopian Orthodox Church that continues to the present. Aksumite stelae — massive carved obelisks, the tallest of which stood 33 metres — are among the most extraordinary monuments of the ancient world. The Ark of the Covenant is claimed by Ethiopian Orthodox tradition to rest in the Chapel of the Tablet in Aksum, a claim taken seriously by some scholars and dismissed by others but central to Ethiopian Christian identity."},
  {"id":440,"n":"Dahomey Kingdom","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1600,"e":1894,"p":250000,"lang":"fon","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Kingdom of Dahomey (~1600–1894 CE) in present-day Benin was one of West Africa's most powerful and distinctive states, known for its highly centralised administration, its professional standing army, and most remarkably its corps of female soldiers — the Agojie (known to Europeans as the Dahomey Amazons) — an elite military unit of thousands of women who served as the king's personal bodyguard and front-line troops for over two centuries. Dahomey's economy was deeply entangled with the transatlantic slave trade; the kingdom raided neighbouring peoples and sold captives to European traders, accumulating the wealth that funded its military and architectural ambitions. The annual customs ceremony involved lavish gift distribution and human sacrifice, documented by European observers. Dahomey was conquered by France in 1894 after two military campaigns that the Agojie fiercely contested. The kingdom's complex legacy — militarily sophisticated African statehood intertwined with its role in the slave trade — continues to generate significant historical debate."},
  {"id":442,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Lake Jackson","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1050,"e":1500,"p":2000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Lake Jackson Mounds in present-day Tallahassee, Florida, was the paramount Mississippian centre of the Apalachee chiefdom — the most powerful political entity in the Florida panhandle region and the southeastern extent of the classic Mississippian cultural tradition. The site features six platform mounds arranged around a central plaza, with Mound 3 producing one of the richest collections of Southeastern Ceremonial Complex copper objects ever excavated from a single context, including elaborately embossed copper plates depicting falcon warriors and other iconographic elements shared across the Mississippian world. Apalachee oral traditions, recorded after Spanish contact in the 16th and 17th centuries, preserve accounts of chiefs, ceremonies, and political structures that provide one of the rare windows into the living political culture of the Mississippian world from an Indigenous perspective."},
  {"id":443,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Ocmulgee","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1600,"p":1000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Ocmulgee Mounds in present-day Macon, Georgia, preserves one of the most complete sequences of human occupation in the American Southeast, with evidence of habitation from Paleo-Indian times through the historic Creek Nation period. The Mississippian occupation (~900–1150 CE) produced a major platform mound complex and the remarkable Earth Lodge — a circular council chamber dug into the ground with a moulded clay eagle platform for the chief's seat, still intact and one of the only Mississippian structures surviving in anything close to its original form. The site's long occupation sequence makes it uniquely valuable for understanding the transitions between pre-Mississippian Woodland cultures, the Mississippian fluorescence, and the historic period Muscogee (Creek) people who claim cultural continuity with the site's builders. The Muscogee Nation has been actively involved in site management and interpretation, representing one of the more successful examples of Indigenous-federal collaboration in American archaeology."},
  {"id":445,"n":"Minoan Civilisation (Neopalatial)","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-1700,"e":-1450,"p":100000,"lang":"minoan-linear-a","gov":"palace-state","d":"The Neopalatial period of Minoan Crete (~1700–1450 BCE) represents the height of what is arguably Europe's first literate urban civilisation — the great palace complexes of Knossos, Phaistos, Malia, and Zakros, with their multi-storey architecture, indoor plumbing, sophisticated drainage, elaborate fresco programmes, and an administrative writing system (Linear A) still undeciphered. Minoan art — acrobats leaping over bulls, women in elaborate flounced skirts, dolphins swimming in blue seas — is among the most joyful and technically accomplished of any Bronze Age culture. The nature of Minoan governance remains debated: the absence of obvious fortifications and weapon imagery in early Minoan iconography led Arthur Evans to propose a peaceful 'thalassocracy,' while more recent scholarship identifies elite competition, redistributive economies, and increasing complexity. The civilisation's apparent collapse around 1450 BCE, coinciding approximately with the Thera eruption, connects Minoan Crete to debates about the Atlantis tradition that Plato recorded."},
  {"id":446,"n":"Scythian / Pazyryk Culture","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-600,"e":-200,"p":100000,"lang":"scythian-iranian","gov":"tribal-confederation","d":"The Pazyryk culture of the Altai Mountains (~600–200 BCE) represents the easternmost and best-preserved branch of the broader Scythian world, with frozen burial mounds (kurgans) at altitude preserving organic materials — textiles, wood, leather, human bodies, horses — that survive nowhere else in the ancient world. The Pazyryk mummies include individuals with elaborate tattooing across their bodies — swirling animals, mythological creatures — executed with extraordinary skill and representing the earliest well-documented tradition of complex tattooing in human history. Persian-style pile carpets, Chinese silk, and Greek gold found in Pazyryk kurgans document trade connections spanning the entire Eurasian continent. The 'Ice Maiden' of Ukok, excavated by Russian archaeologist Natalia Polosmak in 1993 — a young woman buried with horses, elaborate grave goods, and extensive tattoos — became both a celebrated archaeological discovery and the subject of a political controversy when the Altai people sought repatriation of her remains."},
  {"id":447,"n":"Harappan Late Phase / Post-Urban","r":"Asia","t":"debated","s":-1900,"e":-1300,"p":500000,"lang":"indus-unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"The Late Harappan or Post-Urban phase (~1900–1300 BCE) represents the poorly-understood dissolution and transformation of the Indus Valley Civilisation following the apparent abandonment of major urban centres like Mohenjo-daro and Harappa. Rather than a simple 'collapse,' current scholarship increasingly interprets this period as a spatial reorganisation — populations dispersing into smaller settlements across a wider area including the Gangetic plain, potentially carrying Harappan cultural elements that contributed to later Vedic and Early Historic Indian civilisation. The causes of urban abandonment remain debated: climate aridification and the drying of the Ghaggar-Hakra river system, internal social restructuring, or gradual demographic shift are all proposed. The continuity or discontinuity between Harappan and Vedic cultures — and the question of what the Harappan language was and whether it underlies the Dravidian languages of South India — are among the most consequential unresolved questions in South Asian prehistory."},
  {"id":448,"n":"Linear A / Minoan Script Culture","r":"Europe","t":"debated","s":-1800,"e":-1450,"p":0,"lang":"minoan-linear-a","gov":"palace-state","d":"Linear A is the undeciphered writing system used in Minoan Crete from approximately 1800–1450 BCE — a syllabic script used for administrative records, religious inscriptions, and votive offerings across the Minoan palace system. Unlike its descendant Linear B (Mycenaean Greek, deciphered by Michael Ventris in 1952), Linear A has resisted all decipherment attempts because the underlying language remains unknown. Attempts to read Linear A using Linear B phonetic values — the 'same script, different language' approach — have produced suggestive but unconfirmed partial readings. The language appears unrelated to any known language family, making Minoan a linguistic isolate alongside Sumerian and Elamite. The content of Linear A tablets — predominantly administrative accounts of goods — offers little semantic context for phonetic reconstruction. Deciphering Linear A would unlock the only surviving records of Bronze Age Crete in the Minoans' own words, potentially transforming our understanding of Aegean prehistory and the origins of the Atlantis tradition."},
  {"id":450,"n":"Jiroft Civilisation","r":"Middle East","t":"debated","s":-3000,"e":-2000,"p":50000,"lang":"proto-elamite-related","gov":"city-state","d":"The Jiroft civilisation of the Halil River basin in present-day Kerman Province, Iran, came to scholarly attention following massive illegal looting of its sites after floods exposed graves in 2001 — thousands of artefacts entered the international antiquities market before excavations began. Jiroft produced remarkable chlorite (soapstone) vessels carved with elaborate architectural and mythological scenes — buildings with distinctive arched windows, human and animal figures, and composite creatures — of a type found across a wide arc from Mesopotamia to Central Asia, suggesting a major production and export centre. Yousef Majidzadeh, the primary excavator, proposed identifying Jiroft with the legendary Sumerian city of Aratta, described in Sumerian texts as a distant, wealthy city of craftsmen. Mainstream archaeology treats this identification as unproven. The civilisation's script — if it had one — has not been identified, and its relationship to the Indus Valley, proto-Elamite, and Mesopotamian cultural spheres remains unclear."},
  {"id":451,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Town Creek","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":500,"lang":"siouan-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Town Creek Indian Mound in present-day North Carolina represents the northeasternmost outpost of the Mississippian cultural tradition, a small but archaeologically significant platform mound complex that documents the extraordinary geographic reach of Mississippian religious and political ideas from their heartland in the Mississippi Valley to the eastern seaboard. The site features a single major platform mound, a reconstructed mortuary temple, and a palisaded precinct, occupied from approximately 1100–1400 CE by a people whose ceramic and architectural traditions show strong Mississippian influences despite the site's distance from the cultural core. Town Creek's excavation and reconstruction in the mid-20th century was one of North Carolina's first major state archaeological projects. Its existence at this geographic extreme raises questions about the mechanisms by which Mississippian cultural packages spread — whether through migration, elite emulation, religious conversion, or trade network adoption."},
  {"id":452,"n":"Mycenaean Civilisation (Extended)","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-1600,"e":-1100,"p":500000,"lang":"mycenaean-greek","gov":"palace-state","d":"The Mycenaean civilisation of mainland Greece (~1600–1100 BCE) was the first Greek-speaking literate culture, operating palace bureaucracies recorded in Linear B — the earliest surviving written Greek, deciphered by Michael Ventris in 1952 — from great citadels at Mycenae, Tiryns, Pylos, and Thebes. The Mycenaeans were active warriors and traders across the eastern Mediterranean, almost certainly the Greeks described in Egyptian records as the Ekwesh, and their expeditionary culture may underlie the historical kernel of the Trojan War tradition. The Mycenaean palaces collapsed catastrophically around 1200–1150 BCE as part of the broader Late Bronze Age Collapse that destroyed or severely damaged nearly every complex society from Greece to Mesopotamia. The causes — climate drought, internal revolt, earthquake, the Sea Peoples, or systemic trade network failure — remain actively debated, and the collapse represents one of history's most dramatic civilisational discontinuities, inaugurating a Greek Dark Age of 400 years."},
  {"id":453,"n":"Göbekli Tepe / Karahan Tepe Network","r":"Middle East","t":"debated","s":-10000,"e":-8000,"p":5000,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"The broader Taş Tepeler (Stone Hills) network of which Göbekli Tepe is the most famous site encompasses at least a dozen major enclosure complexes in the Şanlıurfa region of southeastern Turkey, all dating to the Pre-Pottery Neolithic A and B periods (~10000–8000 BCE). Karahan Tepe, now under systematic excavation, appears to rival or exceed Göbekli Tepe in size and complexity, with anthropomorphic pillars of a different and arguably more sophisticated style. The emerging picture is not of a single extraordinary site but of an entire regional tradition of monumental enclosure-building by late hunter-gatherer populations across a landscape of perhaps 200km. Andrew Collins argues in Göbekli Tepe: Genesis of the Gods (2014) that the network's Cygnus astronomical alignments and sculptural programmes encode a coherent cosmology potentially transmitted to later Mesopotamian and Egyptian religious traditions. The full extent of this network — and the population it implies — continues to expand with each new survey season, consistently exceeding prior expectations."},
  {"id":454,"n":"Indus Valley — Rakhigarhi","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2800,"e":-1900,"p":80000,"lang":"indus-unknown","gov":"city-state","d":"Rakhigarhi in present-day Haryana, India, is now recognised as the largest known site of the Indus Valley Civilisation — larger than Mohenjo-daro — covering an estimated 550 hectares, though less than 10% has been excavated. Its location in the now-dry Ghaggar-Hakra river basin places it at the heart of the debate about whether this river system is the Vedic Sarasvati, a question with profound implications for the dating of Vedic culture and its relationship to the Harappan civilisation. Ancient DNA analysis of Rakhigarhi skeletal material, published in 2019 by Vasant Shinde and colleagues, found no steppe ancestry in the Harappan genome — directly challenging the Aryan Migration Theory in its strongest form and supporting an indigenous origin for Harappan populations. The paper generated intense scientific and political controversy in India. Rakhigarhi's scale suggests it may have been the administrative capital of the Harappan civilisation, though without decipherment of the Indus script this remains speculative."},
  {"id":455,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Shiloh","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1450,"p":2000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Shiloh Indian Mounds in present-day Tennessee, overlooking the Tennessee River, is a significant Mississippian centre whose platform mounds and residential areas were partially obscured and preserved by their location on what became the Shiloh Civil War battlefield — one of the bloodiest engagements of the American Civil War, fought in April 1862. The juxtaposition of a pre-Columbian Native American town site and one of the defining battles of 19th-century American history at the same location creates a layered landscape of historical significance rarely paralleled in the American Southeast. Archaeological work at Shiloh has been constrained by its battlefield preservation status, leaving much of the Mississippian occupation unexcavated. What has been investigated confirms a typical Mississippian town plan with platform mounds, plaza, and residential areas, occupied from approximately 1000–1450 CE."},
  {"id":456,"n":"Urartian Kingdom","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-860,"e":-585,"p":300000,"lang":"urartian","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Kingdom of Urartu (~860–585 BCE), centred around Lake Van in present-day eastern Turkey and Armenia, was the major rival of the Assyrian Empire for dominance of the ancient Near East and one of the most technically accomplished metalworking cultures of the Iron Age. Urartian bronze cauldrons, helmets, and shields — decorated with intricate animal friezes — were traded or captured across the Mediterranean world and influenced Greek, Etruscan, and Phrygian metalwork. The Urartians built extraordinary citadels on near-vertical rock faces, irrigated mountain valleys with canals and aqueducts, and maintained a cuneiform writing system closely related to Hurrian. The biblical 'Mountains of Ararat' where Noah's Ark came to rest are the mountains of Urartu — the country itself is preserved in the toponym. Urartu's collapse, coinciding with the fall of Assyria and the arrival of Scythian and Cimmerian raiders, ended one of antiquity's most remarkable mountain civilisations."},
  {"id":457,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville Phase II","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1300,"e":1500,"p":1000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"ceremonial-centre","d":"The Phase II occupation of Moundville (~1300–1500 CE) represents a fascinating transformation: the site's population apparently largely departed to surrounding smaller villages, while Moundville itself became primarily a mortuary and ceremonial precinct — a city of the dead rather than the living. This reorganisation, documented through decades of excavation by the University of Alabama, challenges simple models of Mississippian decline and suggests instead a deliberate ceremonial restructuring in which Moundville's symbolic power was maintained and perhaps amplified even as its residential population contracted. The quality and quantity of mortuary goods during this phase actually increases, suggesting that Moundville's role as a regional religious centre intensified even as it depopulated. This pattern — urban contraction combined with intensified ceremonialism — may offer a model for understanding similar transformations at other Mississippian sites and raises broader questions about what 'abandonment' actually means in the context of sacred landscapes."},
  {"id":458,"n":"Tartessian Civilisation","r":"Europe","t":"debated","s":-900,"e":-500,"p":200000,"lang":"tartessian","gov":"monarchy","d":"Tartessos — a civilisation or kingdom of the southwestern Iberian Peninsula (present-day Andalusia and Portugal) known from Greek and Phoenician written sources and from a corpus of inscriptions in an undeciphered script — is one of the most tantalising and poorly understood cultures of the ancient western Mediterranean. Greek sources describe Tartessos as a wealthy kingdom controlling metal trade routes — silver, tin, copper — and as a far western land at or near the Pillars of Hercules. Richard Freund and colleagues have proposed the Doñana marshes of southwestern Spain as the location of Atlantis, identifying Tartessos with Plato's sunken civilisation. Sergio Frau controversially proposed placing the Pillars of Hercules at the Strait of Sicily rather than Gibraltar, which would make Sardinia a candidate for Atlantis rather than any Atlantic location. The Tartessian script remains undeciphered, making it alongside Linear A and the Indus script one of the three major undeciphered ancient writing systems of the Old World. What would finding a Tartessian bilingual inscription change about our understanding of Atlantic prehistory?"},
  {"id":459,"n":"Ancient Astronaut Hypothesis","r":"Middle East","t":"theorized","s":-450000,"e":-10000,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"The Ancient Astronaut Hypothesis — systematically proposed by Erich von Däniken in Chariots of the Gods (1968) and subsequently extended by Zecharia Sitchin, Robert Temple, and others — holds that extraterrestrial beings visited Earth in prehistoric or ancient times and that their presence explains features of ancient cultures that proponents argue cannot be accounted for by human capability alone: the precision engineering of the Giza pyramids, the Nazca lines, the megalithic structures of Puma Punku, Olmec colossal heads, and the Anunnaki of Sumerian mythology. Mainstream archaeology and physics reject the hypothesis on multiple grounds: the claimed engineering impossibilities are demonstrably achievable with ancient technology; the interpretation of ancient iconography as depicting spacecraft or astronauts is culturally anachronistic; and the hypothesis implicitly denies the ingenuity and capability of ancient non-Western peoples. The hypothesis nonetheless has extraordinary popular reach and persistently shapes public engagement with ancient history. Its cultural significance — as a symptom of what it says about modern assumptions regarding ancient human capability — is itself worthy of serious analysis."},
  {"id":460,"n":"Younger Dryas Megaflood Network","r":"Americas","t":"theorized","s":-12800,"e":-11500,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"The network of catastrophic megafloods associated with the Younger Dryas Boundary event (~12,800–11,500 BCE) — including the Missoula Megafloods of the Pacific Northwest, the Lake Agassiz outburst floods into the North Atlantic, and possible Gulf of Mexico flood pulses — represents the largest freshwater flood events in the last 100,000 years of Earth history, reshaping continents and almost certainly triggering the Younger Dryas cooling through disruption of Atlantic thermohaline circulation. Randall Carlson's geological fieldwork across the Channeled Scablands of Washington State has documented flood features — gravel bars the size of hills, dry falls, coulees — of a scale that requires floodwaters of almost incomprehensible volume. The relevance to ancient history is direct: these floods drowned the coastal and riverine zones where any pre-Younger Dryas complex culture would most likely have been located, explaining the absence of physical evidence that mainstream archaeology uses to reject the pre-Flood civilisation hypothesis. Graham Hancock's thesis and Carlson's geology are intellectually interdependent in this specific respect."},
  {"id":461,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Winterville","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1450,"p":1500,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Winterville Mounds in present-day Mississippi was a significant Mississippian ceremonial and political centre featuring 23 mounds arranged around a central plaza, ranking among the larger Mississippian sites in the Lower Mississippi Valley. The site served as a regional redistribution hub within the Mississippian exchange network, with material evidence connecting it to both Cahokia to the north and the Gulf Coast to the south. Winterville's occupation coincides with the height of the Mississippian fluorescence and its abandonment, like most major centres, precedes European contact by generations. The site's mound configurations and plaza layout conform closely to the standard Mississippian town planning template, suggesting strong ideological and political connections to the broader Mississippian world rather than a locally distinctive tradition."},
  {"id":463,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Parkin","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1350,"e":1541,"p":3000,"lang":"various-mississippian","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Parkin Mounds in present-day Arkansas is archaeologically significant as one of the few Mississippian sites that may be directly identified with a specific European historical record — it is a strong candidate for Casqui, the powerful chiefdom described in the accounts of Hernando de Soto's 1541 expedition through the Mississippi Valley. If the identification is correct, Parkin provides the rare opportunity to correlate Mississippian material culture directly with a named polity described by European eyewitnesses who encountered it while it was still functioning. The de Soto accounts describe Casqui as a major regional power engaged in active warfare with its neighbours, with the chief seeking Spanish military alliance — a glimpse of living Mississippian political dynamics unavailable from purely archaeological evidence. This historical anchoring makes Parkin disproportionately valuable for reconstructing the political landscape of the Late Mississippian period."},
  {"id":465,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Carson Mounds","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1400,"p":1000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Carson Mounds in present-day Mississippi was one of the largest Mississippian sites in the Lower Mississippi Valley alluvial plain, with 37 mounds making it one of the most extensive mound complexes in the American Southeast. The site's large size and its position within the densely settled Yazoo Basin suggest it served as a major regional centre within the Mississippian political landscape of the lower valley. Like other Mississippian centres of the region, Carson was abandoned before European contact, and the alluvial agricultural lands surrounding it were subsequently converted to cotton agriculture, obscuring and destroying much of the associated residential and midden archaeology. Carson Mounds represents the broad pattern of Mississippian settlement density in the Lower Mississippi Valley — a landscape once dotted with mound centres at intervals of a day's travel, most now lost to agriculture and time."},
  {"id":466,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Bottle Creek","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1250,"e":1550,"p":1000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Bottle Creek Mounds in present-day coastal Alabama was the major Mississippian ceremonial centre of the Mobile-Tensaw delta region, a complex of 18 mounds on an island in the delta that served as the political and religious capital for Mississippian communities across the coastal plain. Its island location — accessible only by water — gave Bottle Creek a distinctive character among Mississippian centres, and its occupation extended later than most inland centres, with some evidence of activity into the early historic period. The coastal delta environment provided different subsistence resources than inland Mississippian centres, with estuarine fishing and shellfish supplementing the maize agriculture central to the broader Mississippian economy. Bottle Creek's persistence into the contact period makes it potentially linkable to the coastal Mississippian groups encountered by 16th-century Spanish explorers of the Gulf Coast."},
  {"id":467,"n":"Aksumite — Queen of Sheba Tradition","r":"Africa","t":"theorized","s":-1000,"e":-900,"p":0,"lang":"ge-ez-proto","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Queen of Sheba — known as Makeda in Ethiopian tradition, Bilqis in Islamic tradition — is described in the Hebrew Bible (1 Kings 10) and the Quran as a powerful and wealthy queen who visited King Solomon in Jerusalem, a meeting that in Ethiopian royal tradition produced a son, Menelik I, ancestor of the Solomonic dynasty that ruled Ethiopia until Emperor Haile Selassie's deposition in 1974. The Kebra Nagast, the 14th-century Ethiopian national epic, elaborates this tradition and describes Menelik I bringing the Ark of the Covenant from Jerusalem to Aksum, where it is claimed to remain today. The historical identification of Sheba remains debated: candidates include the Sabaean kingdom of southwestern Arabia (South Yemen), the Ethiopian highlands, or both simultaneously. Archaeological evidence for a powerful pre-Aksumite queen matching the biblical description has not been found, but the tradition's extraordinary persistence across Ethiopian, Yemeni, and Jewish cultures across three millennia argues for some historical kernel."},
  {"id":468,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Anna Mounds","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1200,"e":1500,"p":1000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Anna Mounds in present-day Mississippi was a regional Mississippian centre of the Natchez Bluffs area, an archaeologically important zone where some of the last functioning Mississippian-tradition chiefly societies survived into the historic period as the Natchez people. The Natchez, who maintained a mound-centred political and religious system well into the 18th century and were only destroyed by French colonial military action in 1731, provide one of the most detailed ethnohistoric records of how Mississippian political and religious institutions actually functioned — including the divine status of the Great Sun chief, the rigid social hierarchy, and the mortuary practices involving retainer sacrifice that are archaeologically documented at much earlier sites. This continuity between prehistoric Mississippian archaeology and Natchez ethnohistory makes the Anna Mounds region uniquely valuable for interpreting the broader Mississippian record."},
  {"id":469,"n":"Medieval Iceland / Norse Commonwealth","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":874,"e":1262,"p":60000,"lang":"old-norse","gov":"commonwealth","d":"The Icelandic Commonwealth (~874–1262 CE) represents one of history's most remarkable political experiments — a functional stateless society of 60,000 people governing itself for nearly 400 years through a system of local assemblies (things) culminating in the Althing, one of the world's oldest parliaments, established in 930 CE at Þingvellir. Iceland had no king, no standing army, no executive branch — disputes were resolved through law, arbitration, and socially enforced honour obligations. The sagas composed in this period — the Íslendingasögur — are among the finest achievements of medieval literature, recording the settlement of Iceland, the discovery of North America by Leif Eriksson, and the social dramas of an honour-based society with extraordinary psychological sophistication. The Commonwealth's eventual submission to the Norwegian crown in 1262, following a century of escalating internal violence, raises profound questions about the limits of stateless governance under conditions of growing inequality."},
  {"id":470,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Plaquemine","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1200,"e":1700,"p":5000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Plaquemine culture of the Lower Mississippi Valley (~1200–1700 CE) represents a regional variant of the Mississippian tradition that maintained distinctive cultural practices while participating in the broader Mississippian exchange network. Crucially, Plaquemine-tradition peoples — particularly the Natchez, Taensa, and related groups — survived into the European colonial period, providing the most direct link between prehistoric Mississippian archaeology and documented historical Indigenous cultures anywhere in the American Southeast. French colonial accounts of the Natchez Nation, particularly their Temple Mound ceremonialism, the divine rulership of the Great Sun, and the sacrificial mortuary practices accompanying elite deaths, illuminate cultural practices archaeologically documented at Mississippian sites centuries earlier. The Plaquemine tradition's longevity — persisting into the 18th century while most Mississippian cultures had already reorganised or dissolved — makes it the closest thing to a living window into the Mississippian world."},
  {"id":471,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Irene","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1150,"e":1450,"p":1000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Irene site near present-day Savannah, Georgia, represents the Irene phase of Mississippian cultural development in the coastal Georgia lowlands — a regional tradition that connected the interior Mississippian world to the Atlantic coastal plain and the Guale people documented in Spanish colonial records of the 16th and 17th centuries. The Irene mound complex demonstrates the southeasternmost coastal extension of classic Mississippian town planning, and the continuity between Irene phase archaeology and the historic Guale Nation provides another valuable link between prehistoric material culture and documented historical Indigenous societies. The Guale participated in the Spanish mission system of coastal Georgia and Florida, leaving a colonial documentary record that has been used to interpret the preceding Irene archaeological horizon. This coast-interior connection illustrates how Mississippian cultural ideas and institutions permeated even the coastal margins of the American Southeast."},
  {"id":472,"n":"Harappan — Lothal","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2400,"e":-1900,"p":15000,"lang":"indus-unknown","gov":"city-state","d":"Lothal in present-day Gujarat, India, was a major Harappan port city and industrial centre whose most remarkable feature is a large dockyard — a rectangular basin of fired brick connected to a tidal river channel — which, if correctly interpreted, represents the world's earliest known artificial dock for maritime trade. Excavated by S.R. Rao from 1955–1960, Lothal shows evidence of a bead-making industry exporting products across the Harappan trade network, a sophisticated fire altar suggesting Vedic-style ritual practice, and a grid-planned urban layout characteristic of the Harappan civilisation. The interpretation of the large basin as a dockyard has been challenged by some scholars who argue it was a large water reservoir; the debate hinges on hydrology and siltation patterns. If the dockyard interpretation is correct, Lothal's maritime infrastructure demonstrates Harappan seafaring capability fully 4,000 years ago, consistent with textual evidence of Harappan/Meluhhan trade in Mesopotamian records."},
  {"id":473,"n":"Harappan — Dholavira","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2650,"e":-1450,"p":20000,"lang":"indus-unknown","gov":"city-state","d":"Dholavira on the island of Khadir in the Great Rann of Kutch, India, is one of the five largest Harappan cities and the most extensively excavated major site of the civilisation, remarkable for its extraordinary water conservation infrastructure — a series of 16 reservoirs covering approximately one-third of the city's area, fed by seasonal flash floods through engineered channels, allowing the city to survive in one of India's most arid environments. Dholavira's three-part town plan — citadel, middle town, and lower town — is more clearly preserved than any other Harappan site. A unique Harappan inscription of ten large signs, found displayed on a gateway, is the longest known Harappan inscription and possibly a public display text — the first potential example of public writing in South Asian history. UNESCO recognised Dholavira as a World Heritage Site in 2021. The site's sophisticated water management offers striking lessons in ancient engineering responses to environmental stress."},
  {"id":474,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville Phase III","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1500,"e":1650,"p":500,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"remnant-chiefdom","d":"The Phase III occupation of Moundville (~1500–1650 CE) represents the final archaeological horizon at the site before complete abandonment, by which time the population had reduced to a small remnant community maintaining ceremonial use of a precinct that had once been the capital of a major regional polity. Material culture from this phase shows increasing divergence from classic Mississippian traditions and the emergence of what archaeologists identify as proto-historic and early historic Creek cultural patterns, suggesting the descendants of Moundville's population contributed to the formation of the Muscogee (Creek) Confederacy that European colonists would encounter in the 18th century. The Phase III occupation completes the remarkable transformation of Moundville across three phases — from densely populated urban capital to ceremonial mortuary precinct to small-scale remnant occupation — a trajectory that encapsulates the full arc of Mississippian civilisation in a single site."},
  {"id":475,"n":"Scythian — Royal Tombs of the Pontic Steppe","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-500,"e":-200,"p":200000,"lang":"scythian-iranian","gov":"tribal-confederation","d":"The Royal Scythian kurgans of the Pontic steppe — enormous burial mounds some exceeding 20 metres in height, clustered across present-day Ukraine — contained the wealthiest assemblages of gold objects produced anywhere in the ancient world, including the famous Pectoral from Tovsta Mohyla (4th century BCE), a gold breastplate depicting Scythian daily life and mythology in extraordinary detail. These tombs, excavated primarily by Soviet and Ukrainian archaeologists from the 1950s onward, document a nomadic elite whose access to Greek craftsmen, Persian luxury goods, and trans-Eurasian trade networks produced material culture of dazzling sophistication. The kurgan burial tradition — a mound over a timber-lined burial chamber with horses, weapons, gold, and occasionally sacrificed retainers or wives — spread from Scythian origins across the steppe world and may be ancestral to similar traditions from Hungary to Mongolia. The ongoing excavation of Ukrainian kurgans has been severely disrupted by the Russian invasion of 2022, destroying irreplaceable archaeological context."},
  {"id":476,"n":"Minoan — Pre-Palatial / Early Bronze Age Crete","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-3100,"e":-1900,"p":30000,"lang":"pre-minoan-unknown","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Pre-Palatial Crete (~3100–1900 BCE) represents the formative period of Aegean Bronze Age civilisation before the construction of the great Minoan palace complexes, during which Crete developed the population density, agricultural surplus, and social complexity that would produce the Neopalatial florescence. Early Bronze Age Cretan culture shows connections to Cycladic and Anatolian traditions and the earliest development of the distinctive Minoan pottery and seal engraving traditions. The transition to the First Palace period around 1900 BCE, with the near-simultaneous construction of palaces at Knossos, Phaistos, and Malia, represents one of the most dramatic and poorly-explained emergence events in Aegean archaeology — a sudden leap in organisational complexity with no obvious single trigger. The pre-palatial background makes this emergence more rather than less puzzling, and understanding the social and economic drivers of the palace system's origin remains a central question in Bronze Age Aegean studies."},
  {"id":477,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Aztalan","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1050,"e":1200,"p":500,"lang":"various-great-lakes","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Aztalan in present-day Wisconsin was the northernmost major Mississippian site, a stockaded settlement with two platform mounds whose presence nearly 1,000km north of Cahokia raises fascinating questions about how and why Mississippian cultural and political institutions spread into the Great Lakes region. The site shows a mix of local Woodland ceramic traditions and imported Mississippian styles, suggesting a community that was either a Mississippian colony, a local population that adopted Mississippian practices through trade and contact, or a hybrid community of both. Aztalan's palisaded enclosure, built of closely spaced posts and bastions, has been interpreted as evidence of a hostile frontier environment — a Mississippian outpost in territory where its practices were not universally welcomed. The site's relatively brief occupation (~150 years) before abandonment may reflect the limits of Mississippian cultural expansion into environments and social contexts where its political and religious model could not sustain itself."},
  {"id":478,"n":"Luwian Civilisation","r":"Middle East","t":"debated","s":-2000,"e":-700,"p":500000,"lang":"luwian","gov":"city-state","d":"The Luwians were an Indo-European-speaking people of Bronze and Iron Age Anatolia who used two writing systems — cuneiform Luwian and hieroglyphic Luwian — and whose civilisation extended across much of southern and western Anatolia and into northern Syria. They were closely related to the Hittites, sharing a common cultural ancestor, and Luwian was actually more widely spoken than Hittite across the Hittite Empire. The controversial scholar Eberhard Zangger has argued that the Luwians were the primary authors of the Late Bronze Age Collapse (~1200 BCE) as a confederation of western Anatolian city-states — potentially identifiable with the Egyptian 'Sea Peoples' — and that a major Luwian civilisation has been systematically overlooked because its cities lie under unexcavated mounds across western Turkey. Mainstream Hittitology treats Zangger's thesis with scepticism but acknowledges the significant archaeological gap in western Anatolian Bronze Age research. The Luwian language survived the Bronze Age Collapse in neo-Hittite city-states of northern Syria until the 7th century BCE."},
  {"id":479,"n":"Meroitic Kingdom","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-300,"e":350,"p":200000,"lang":"meroitic","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Meroitic Kingdom (~300 BCE–350 CE) of present-day Sudan was the successor state to the Kushite (Napatan) dynasty that had once ruled Egypt, and at its height controlled the middle Nile Valley from the third to sixth cataracts. Meroe became the new royal capital following the southward shift of Kushite power, and the city's iron smelting industry — evidenced by enormous slag heaps — made it possibly the major iron production centre of sub-Saharan Africa in the ancient world. The Meroitic people developed their own alphabetic script (Meroitic) around 300 BCE, adapted from the Egyptian demotic and hieroglyphic scripts — one of the earliest indigenous African writing systems — but it remains only partially deciphered, with phonetic values known but the underlying language not yet fully understood. The spectacular royal pyramid fields at Meroe and Nuri, with their steep-sided profiles distinct from Egyptian pyramids, are among the most extraordinary archaeological sites in Africa and document a mortuary tradition maintained for over a thousand years."},
  {"id":480,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Medoc Mountain","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1400,"p":300,"lang":"siouan-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Medoc Mountain Mound in present-day North Carolina represents the Pee Dee phase of Mississippian development in the Carolina Piedmont, a small but archaeologically significant platform mound complex that documents the spread of Mississippian cultural influences into the eastern foothills of the Appalachians. The Pee Dee culture, of which Medoc Mountain is the type site alongside Town Creek, shows Mississippian-derived town planning and ceramic traditions adapted to a local Piedmont environmental and cultural context. The site's occupants were likely ancestors of the Catawba Nation, who maintained a presence in the Carolina Piedmont into the colonial period. Like Town Creek, Medoc Mountain represents the frontier of Mississippian cultural influence at its northeastern extreme, illustrating both the remarkable reach of Mississippian ideas and the ways those ideas were transformed and localised as they moved away from their heartland in the Mississippi Valley."},
  {"id":481,"n":"Caananite Civilisation","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-3500,"e":-1200,"p":200000,"lang":"canaanite-semitic","gov":"city-state","d":"The Canaanite civilisation of the Levant (~3500–1200 BCE) was one of the ancient Near East's most influential cultures — the Bronze Age inhabitants of the land that biblical tradition describes as promised to the Israelites, and the creators of the alphabetic writing system from which virtually all modern alphabets descend. The Phoenician alphabet, itself a refinement of the earlier Proto-Sinaitic and Proto-Canaanite scripts, is the ancestor of Greek, Latin, Arabic, Hebrew, and through them nearly every writing system used today. Canaanite city-states including Ugarit, Megiddo, Hazor, and Byblos were major participants in the Late Bronze Age cosmopolitan world, trading with Egypt, the Hittites, Cyprus, and the Aegean. The destruction of Canaanite urban centres in the Late Bronze Age Collapse (~1200 BCE) and the subsequent emergence of Israelite, Phoenician, and Aramean cultures from the Canaanite substrate makes the Canaanite civilisation foundational to the entire subsequent history of the Levant and, through its writing system, to global civilisation."},
  {"id":482,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Deep Bottom","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":500,"lang":"siouan-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Deep Bottom and the broader upper Roanoke River Mississippian complex in present-day Virginia and North Carolina represents the northernmost documented penetration of Mississippian cultural influences along the Atlantic slope of the Appalachians, documenting the remarkable reach of Mississippian exchange networks and cultural transmission into the far northeast of the tradition's range. Sites in this region show Mississippian-derived ceramics, mortuary practices, and possibly mound construction traditions adapted to an Appalachian Piedmont context. The archaeological visibility of Mississippian influence at these extreme northeastern sites raises the question of what lay beyond the documented frontier — whether Mississippian exchange networks and cultural influence extended even further northeast into what is now Virginia, Maryland, and the Chesapeake region in ways not yet archaeologically documented. The northeastern frontier of Mississippian influence remains one of the less-studied aspects of this continent-spanning cultural tradition."},
  {"id":483,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville Outliers","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":500,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Moundville Outlier sites — a constellation of smaller Mississippian mound centres within the Black Warrior Valley political sphere of Moundville — document the regional political system centred on Moundville at its height, in which a paramount centre controlled a hierarchy of subsidiary sites across a defined territory. This hierarchical site structure — large paramount centre, medium-sized secondary centres, small villages and farmsteads — is the archaeological signature of a chiefdom political system, and the Moundville regional system is one of the most clearly documented examples of this settlement hierarchy anywhere in North American archaeology. The distribution of prestige goods across the hierarchy — concentrated at Moundville and distributed in diminishing quantities to lower-tier sites — demonstrates the redistributive economy through which Moundville's paramount chief maintained political authority. The collapse of this system in the 14th century, when Moundville transitioned to a mortuary precinct, apparently dismantled the regional political hierarchy as well."},
  {"id":484,"n":"Chumash Maritime Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-8000,"e":1820,"p":20000,"lang":"chumash","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Chumash people of the southern California coast developed one of the most sophisticated maritime cultures in pre-Columbian North America, building the tomol — a plank canoe of extraordinary technical sophistication, constructed from driftwood planks sewn together with plant fibre and caulked with natural asphalt from the La Brea tar seeps — that enabled regular open-water crossings to the Channel Islands and sustained a trade and exchange network along the Santa Barbara coast. The Chumash supported unusually high population densities for a hunter-gatherer society through the extraordinary productivity of the marine environment, developing a complex social hierarchy, a professional class of artisans, and a shell bead currency (the only well-documented shell bead monetary system in aboriginal North America). Their rock art — particularly the painted cave sites of the Chumash Painted Cave — is among the most elaborate in North America and reflects a cosmological system involving shamanic transformation, celestial observation, and the winter solstice. The Chumash represent the maximum social complexity achievable within a non-agricultural maritime economy."},
  {"id":486,"n":"Hohokam Civilisation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":300,"e":1450,"p":40000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Hohokam civilisation (~300–1450 CE) of the Sonoran Desert in present-day Arizona developed the most extensive prehistoric irrigation canal system in North America — over 800km of main canals and thousands of kilometres of secondary channels in the Phoenix Basin alone — transforming the desert floor into productive agricultural land capable of supporting tens of thousands of people. The Hohokam maintained ball courts linking them culturally to Mesoamerica, produced distinctive red-on-buff ceramics traded across the Southwest, and created a regional exchange network distributing shell from the Gulf of California, turquoise, and copper bells. The abandonment of the major Hohokam centres in the 14th–15th centuries CE, associated with severe drought and possible social disruption, is one of North American archaeology's most studied collapse events. The O'odham people of southern Arizona maintain oral traditions connecting them directly to the Hohokam, and the Hohokam canal alignments underlie the modern Phoenix metropolitan water system."},
  {"id":487,"n":"Ancestral Puebloans — Mesa Verde","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":600,"e":1300,"p":30000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"Mesa Verde in present-day Colorado represents the architectural apex of Ancestral Puebloan civilisation — the cliff dwellings cut into the sandstone alcoves of Mesa Verde's canyon walls, including Cliff Palace (the largest cliff dwelling in North America), Long House, and Spruce Tree House, are among the most spectacular achievements of any pre-Columbian North American culture. Built primarily in the 12th and 13th centuries CE in defensible positions that suggest increasing warfare or social tension, the cliff dwellings were occupied for only a few generations before being abandoned around 1300 CE during a prolonged drought documented in tree-ring records. The rapidity and completeness of the abandonment — rooms left with intact pottery, tools, and food stores — suggests an urgent departure. The descendants of Mesa Verde's inhabitants are the modern Pueblo peoples of New Mexico and Arizona, who maintain oral traditions about the migration from the 'place of mist and fog.' Mesa Verde's cliff dwellings were declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1978."},
  {"id":489,"n":"Poverty Point — Lower Mississippi Archaic","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-3500,"e":-1700,"p":10000,"lang":"unknown","gov":"band-chiefdom","d":"The Lower Mississippi Valley Archaic cultures (~3500–1700 BCE) that preceded and produced Poverty Point represent a poorly-understood but archaeologically significant tradition of increasing social complexity among hunter-gatherer populations along the Mississippi, Red, and Ouachita Rivers. The gradual accumulation of evidence for long-distance exchange, specialised tool production, and incipient social differentiation in this period documents the process by which hunter-gatherer societies in the Lower Mississippi Valley developed the organisational capabilities that eventually produced the extraordinary florescence of Poverty Point. Earthwork construction in this region predates Poverty Point itself, with sites like Watson Brake (~3500 BCE) — 11 mounds connected by a low ridge in an oval pattern — now recognised as the earliest known mound complex in North America, predating Poverty Point by 1,800 years. Watson Brake demonstrates that the impulse to build monumental earthworks in the American Southeast has a far deeper history than previously recognised."},
  {"id":490,"n":"Denisovan — Asian Distribution","r":"Asia","t":"theorized","s":-400000,"e":-30000,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"The Denisovans — an archaic human population known initially only from fragmentary remains in Denisova Cave in the Russian Altai — are now understood through ancient DNA analysis to have ranged across a vast territory from Siberia through Southeast Asia to Oceania, based on the geographic distribution of Denisovan genetic inheritance in modern populations. Melanesians and Aboriginal Australians carry approximately 3–5% Denisovan ancestry, suggesting a major Denisovan population in Southeast Asia or Wallacea that interbred with modern humans migrating through the region. Philippine Negritos carry the highest known proportion of Denisovan ancestry of any living population (~5%), suggesting prolonged contact in island Southeast Asia. Andrew Collins's Denisovan Origins (2019) proposes Denisovans as the builders of Göbekli Tepe and other early monumental sites, arguing their cognitive capabilities were equivalent to or exceeded those of contemporary Homo sapiens. Mainstream paleoanthropology acknowledges Denisovan cognitive sophistication — a needle, a bracelet, and decorated bones from Denisova Cave demonstrate symbolic behaviour — but does not accept monument-building capacity without physical evidence."},
  {"id":491,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Shiloh Phase II","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1200,"e":1450,"p":3000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The later Shiloh phase occupation in the Tennessee River valley represents the development of a more complex regional Mississippian polity drawing together communities across the Tennessee Valley into a tribute-paying hierarchy. Archaeological evidence from the Shiloh site complex and its satellite communities documents the redistribution of prestige goods — shell gorgets, copper plates, ceramic vessels in distinctive Mississippian styles — across a network of smaller sites dependent on the platform mound centre. The Tennessee Valley's position as a corridor between the Mississippian heartland of the central Mississippi Valley and the Appalachian Highlands gave Shiloh and related sites a strategic role in channelling exchange between these different environmental and cultural zones. The gradual contraction and eventual abandonment of the Shiloh complex mirrors the broader pattern of Mississippian reorganisation in the 14th and 15th centuries."},
  {"id":492,"n":"Solutrean Culture","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-22000,"e":-17000,"p":5000,"lang":"unknown-upper-palaeolithic","gov":"band","d":"The Solutrean culture of southwestern Europe (~22,000–17,000 BCE) represents one of the most technically sophisticated flint-knapping traditions in the entire Palaeolithic record — their pressure-flaked bifacial points, laurel leaves, and shouldered points achieved thinness and symmetry that modern knappers struggle to replicate, and their finest pieces appear to be non-functional prestige objects rather than tools. The Solutreans also produced some of the earliest known needle technology, enabling tailored clothing essential for survival in glacial maximum Europe. Dennis Stanford and Bruce Bradley's controversial Solutrean Hypothesis (Across Atlantic Ice, 2012) proposes that Solutrean people crossed the glacial North Atlantic on the ice edge — using skin boats and surviving on marine mammals as Inuit do — and became ancestral to the Clovis culture of North America, explaining perceived similarities in flint-knapping technology across the Atlantic. Mainstream archaeology firmly rejects this hypothesis based on chronology, genetics, and the absence of diagnostic Solutrean tools in any North American context, but the debate continues."},
  {"id":494,"n":"Corded Ware Culture","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-3000,"e":-2350,"p":500000,"lang":"proto-indo-european","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Corded Ware culture (~3000–2350 BCE) of central and northern Europe represents the primary vector by which Yamnaya steppe ancestry and proto-Indo-European language spread into the heart of Europe, transforming the genetic and linguistic landscape of the continent within just a few centuries. Named for the characteristic cord-impressed decoration on its pottery, Corded Ware society appears to have been patrilineal, highly mobile, and organised around herding and raiding rather than settled agriculture — a social structure that ancient DNA confirms spread at the expense of the existing European Neolithic farmer populations. The speed and scale of the Corded Ware expansion — from the steppe to Scandinavia within perhaps 300 years — implies a process more like conquest or plague-facilitated replacement than peaceful cultural diffusion. Corded Ware is the ancestor culture of the Battle Axe and Single Grave traditions and ultimately of the Bronze Age cultures from which Celtic, Germanic, Baltic, and Slavic language families emerged."},
  {"id":495,"n":"Linear Pottery Culture / LBK","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-5500,"e":-4500,"p":100000,"lang":"proto-european-farmer","gov":"village","d":"The Linear Pottery Culture (Linearbandkeramik or LBK, ~5500–4500 BCE) was the first farming culture of central Europe, spreading from Hungary to the Paris Basin within a few centuries as Anatolian-origin Neolithic farmers moved northwest across the continent. The LBK expansion replaced or marginalised the existing Mesolithic hunter-gatherer populations of central Europe with remarkable speed, establishing a template of village-based cereal agriculture that would define European subsistence for millennia. LBK settlements were characterised by large longhouses — up to 45 metres long — housing extended family units, arranged in small villages near light loess soils suitable for simple hoe agriculture. The Talheim Death Pit (~5000 BCE) and the Asparn-Schletz massacre site document episodes of mass violence in the LBK world, suggesting that the Neolithic transition in Europe was accompanied by significant inter-group conflict. The LBK represents the first wave of a demographic transformation of Europe that ancient DNA has now documented in extraordinary detail."},
  {"id":496,"n":"Funnel Beaker Culture / TRB","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-4000,"e":-2800,"p":150000,"lang":"proto-european-farmer","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Funnel Beaker culture (Trichterbecherkultur or TRB, ~4000–2800 BCE) of northern Europe was the first megalith-building culture of Scandinavia and the North European Plain, responsible for the construction of thousands of dolmens, passage graves, and long barrows across Denmark, Sweden, northern Germany, the Netherlands, and Poland. The TRB people were Anatolian-origin farmers who had developed the social organisation and religious motivation to invest enormous collective labour in stone monuments for the dead, several centuries before the better-known megalithic traditions of western Europe reached their peak. TRB society appears to have been relatively egalitarian compared to the later Corded Ware and Bell Beaker cultures that replaced it, with collective burial monuments suggesting communal rather than individual elite commemoration. The TRB is also associated with the earliest evidence of dairying in northern Europe, a dietary adaptation that required genetic evolution of lactase persistence in adult populations."},
  {"id":497,"n":"Beaker People — British Isles","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-2500,"e":-1800,"p":100000,"lang":"proto-celtic","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Bell Beaker migration into the British Isles (~2500–1800 BCE) produced one of the most thoroughly documented demographic replacements in ancient DNA science — within 400–500 years of the Beaker people's arrival, approximately 90% of the genetic ancestry of the British Neolithic population had been replaced by steppe-related ancestry brought by Beaker migrants, making it the most complete population replacement in British prehistory. The famous Amesbury Archer, buried ~2300 BCE near Stonehenge with gold hair ornaments, copper knives, and the largest known Bell Beaker grave assemblage in Britain, had grown up in the Alpine region of central Europe based on his tooth enamel isotopes — a long-distance migrant who died in southern England. The Beaker people in Britain are associated with the final construction phases of Stonehenge, the introduction of copper and then bronze metallurgy, and the cultural transition from the Neolithic to the Bronze Age. Their descendants include the Bronze Age and Iron Age populations from whom modern British and Irish people are substantially descended."},
  {"id":498,"n":"Catalhoyuk — Extended Analysis","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-7500,"e":-5700,"p":8000,"lang":"unknown-anatolian","gov":"egalitarian-town","d":"Çatalhöyük in present-day Turkey (~7500–5700 BCE) remains one of the most extensively studied Neolithic sites in the world, and four decades of excavation have produced a picture of an urban-scale community of extraordinary social complexity whose governance system defies conventional categories. The settlement had no streets — houses were accessed through roof openings — and no evidence of central authority, temples, or palaces. Burials under house floors show no consistent pattern of individual wealth accumulation. Ian Hodder's decades-long excavation project has documented radical equality between male and female skeletal remains in terms of diet, health, and mobility. The community's wall paintings — leopards, hunting scenes, vultures consuming headless human figures — and its apparent obsession with cattle skulls plastered into walls suggest a rich symbolic and ritual life. Çatalhöyük challenges the assumption that urban scale requires hierarchical governance, and its egalitarian social organisation has become a touchstone in debates about alternative models of human social organisation."},
  {"id":499,"n":"Uruk Expansion","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-4000,"e":-3100,"p":50000,"lang":"sumerian","gov":"city-state","d":"The Uruk Expansion (~4000–3100 BCE) represents the first known case of economic and cultural globalisation in human history — a period in which the city of Uruk in southern Mesopotamia grew to an estimated 40,000–80,000 inhabitants and simultaneously established trading colonies, outposts, and culturally influenced settlements across an enormous arc from the Nile Delta to the Iranian plateau and the Caucasus. Uruk-period material culture — distinctive bevelled-rim bowls (probably ration vessels for dependent labourers), cylinder seals, and administrative clay tokens — appears simultaneously across this entire zone. Whether this represents Uruk colonisation, trade diaspora, cultural emulation, or some combination remains debated. Crucially, the Uruk period also sees the emergence of the earliest known writing — proto-cuneiform clay tablets recording administrative transactions — making Uruk's expansion the context in which humanity's most transformative intellectual technology was invented. The collapse of the Uruk network around 3100 BCE, as peripheral regions abandoned Uruk material culture, remains one of the first documented cases of a globalised system's breakdown."},
  {"id":500,"n":"Proto-Indo-European Homeland","r":"Europe","t":"debated","s":-4500,"e":-2500,"p":100000,"lang":"proto-indo-european","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Proto-Indo-European (PIE) — the reconstructed ancestor language of a family spoken today by over three billion people from Iceland to Sri Lanka, including English, Russian, Persian, Hindi, Greek, Latin, and hundreds of other languages — must have had a homeland from which it spread. The Pontic-Caspian steppe hypothesis, championed by Marija Gimbutas and now strongly supported by ancient DNA evidence from David Reich's group, identifies the Yamnaya culture of the Ukrainian and Russian steppes (~3500–2500 BCE) as the primary PIE-speaking population whose expansion carried the language family across Eurasia. A competing Anatolian hypothesis, associated with Colin Renfrew, proposes that PIE spread with the Neolithic farming expansion from Anatolia ~7000 BCE, a timeline now largely contradicted by ancient DNA evidence. A minority Armenian Highland hypothesis places the PIE homeland in eastern Anatolia or the South Caucasus. The identification of the PIE homeland is one of historical linguistics' most consequential questions, with implications for the origins of European, Iranian, and South Asian civilisations."},
  {"id":501,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville Hinterland","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":10000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Moundville hinterland — the dispersed rural communities of the Black Warrior Valley that surrounded and supported the Moundville paramount centre — provides essential context for understanding how the Moundville chiefdom actually functioned as a political and economic system. Survey archaeology across the valley has documented a landscape densely settled with farmsteads, hamlets, and small mound centres at distances of a few kilometres from each other, all oriented toward Moundville as the redistributive and ceremonial capital. The agricultural surplus generated by these hinterland communities — primarily maize, supplemented by hunting, fishing, and gathered resources — supported the non-agricultural specialist population at Moundville itself and the labour needed for ongoing mound construction and maintenance. The spatial relationship between Moundville and its hinterland is one of the most thoroughly documented examples of the economic geography of a Mississippian chiefdom anywhere in the archaeological record, providing a model applicable to interpreting other, less-surveyed Mississippian regional systems."},
  {"id":502,"n":"Yamnaya — Afanasievo Branch","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-3300,"e":-2500,"p":20000,"lang":"proto-tocharian","gov":"pastoral-nomad","d":"The Afanasievo culture of the Altai Mountains and the Minusinsk Basin in southern Siberia (~3300–2500 BCE) represents the easternmost early branch of the Yamnaya expansion, now confirmed by ancient DNA to be descended from Pontic-Caspian steppe populations. The Afanasievo people were the first steppe pastoralists to reach Central Asia and the Altai, and their descendants almost certainly include the proto-Tocharian speakers whose language — the easternmost branch of the Indo-European family — eventually appeared in the Tarim Basin 1,000 years later. The migration of Afanasievo people thousands of kilometres east of the Yamnaya heartland, at dates contemporary with the main Yamnaya westward expansion into Europe, demonstrates that the steppe pastoral economy was expanding in multiple directions simultaneously. The Afanasievo culture thus connects the Yamnaya revolution directly to the Tocharian mummies of the Tarim Basin, bridging what previously appeared to be an inexplicable gap in the distribution of early Indo-European languages."},
  {"id":503,"n":"Andronovo Culture","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2000,"e":-900,"p":200000,"lang":"proto-iranian","gov":"pastoral-nomad","d":"The Andronovo cultural horizon (~2000–900 BCE) of the Eurasian steppe from the Urals to the Yenisei River represents the stage in steppe prehistory when the synthesis of horse riding, chariot technology, and bronze metallurgy produced a mobile warrior culture capable of transforming the ancient world at scale. Andronovo-related populations are the primary ancestors of the Indo-Iranian language branch — the languages that became Vedic Sanskrit, Avestan, Persian, and their descendants spoken today from Iran to Bangladesh. The migration of Andronovo-related peoples into the Indian subcontinent as the Vedic culture (~1500 BCE) and into Iran as the Avestan Iranians represents the final stage of the Indo-European expansion, completing a transformation that had begun on the Pontic steppe two millennia earlier. The Sintashta culture, an early Andronovo variant of the southern Urals (~2100–1800 BCE), is specifically identified as the origin of the spoke-wheeled war chariot — one of antiquity's most consequential military technologies."},
  {"id":504,"n":"Harappan — Mohenjo-daro","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2600,"e":-1900,"p":40000,"lang":"indus-unknown","gov":"city-state","d":"Mohenjo-daro ('Mound of the Dead') on the Indus River in present-day Pakistan was one of the two great urban centres of the Harappan civilisation — a planned city of extraordinary sophistication covering at least 250 hectares, with a population estimated at 40,000–50,000 people, laid out on a grid of streets with standardised brick dimensions, covered sewerage channels running beneath the streets, and public buildings including the famous Great Bath — a large watertight tank that may have served ritual purification functions. The city was rebuilt at least nine times on the same grid plan after periodic flooding, demonstrating a remarkable civic commitment to urban continuity. Mohenjo-daro shows no evidence of palaces, temples, or royal burials in the Egyptian or Mesopotamian sense, suggesting either a different model of governance — possibly theocratic, mercantile, or collective — or that such structures remain unexcavated. The city's abandonment around 1900 BCE and the skeletal remains found in its streets have generated persistent speculation about a catastrophic ending, though mainstream archaeology points to gradual decline linked to river course changes and climate aridification."},
  {"id":505,"n":"Harappan — Harappa City","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-2600,"e":-1900,"p":23000,"lang":"indus-unknown","gov":"city-state","d":"Harappa, the type site of the Indus Valley Civilisation in present-day Pakistan's Punjab province, gave its name to the entire civilisation and was the first Harappan site excavated scientifically, beginning with John Marshall's work in the 1920s. The city featured massive granaries, standardised brick construction, a citadel mound, and the full repertoire of Harappan urban infrastructure — covered drains, street grids, and standardised weights and measures used across the entire civilisation's trade network. Harappa is particularly significant for the discovery of the earliest Harappan script examples and for evidence of craft specialisation in bead-making, shell-working, and metalworking. The site's earlier phases, now called the Ravi phase (~3300–2800 BCE), preserve evidence of the gradual development of Harappan urbanism from its village antecedents, providing crucial insight into how one of the ancient world's most remarkable city-building traditions actually emerged. Unfortunately, significant portions of Harappa were destroyed by 19th-century brick robbers who used the ancient fired bricks as ballast for the Lahore-Multan railway."},
  {"id":506,"n":"Etruscan — Villanovan Phase","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-900,"e":-700,"p":200000,"lang":"proto-etruscan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Villanovan culture (~900–700 BCE) of central Italy represents the formative phase of Etruscan civilisation, the period in which the distinctive cultural and genetic population that would become the Etruscans developed its characteristic traditions of cremation burial in biconical urns, iron and bronze metallurgy, and the dense settlement of the Tyrrhenian coastal zone of Italy. The Villanovans were part of the broader Urnfield cultural horizon of late Bronze Age and early Iron Age Europe, but developed rapidly toward urban complexity as they exploited the rich metal ores of the Colline Metallifere in Tuscany. Ancient DNA from Villanovan and Etruscan cemetery sites, published in 2023, confirmed that the Etruscans were genetically similar to other European Iron Age populations with no significant Anatolian-specific ancestry, definitively settling the long-running debate about Etruscan origins in favour of an indigenous Italian rather than Anatolian or Alpine origin — contra Herodotus's famous claim that the Etruscans migrated from Lydia."},
  {"id":508,"n":"Illyrian Civilisation","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-800,"e":9,"p":1000000,"lang":"illyrian","gov":"tribal-confederation","d":"The Illyrians of the western Balkans (~800 BCE–9 CE) were a group of Indo-European-speaking tribal peoples occupying the coastal and mountainous regions of present-day Albania, Croatia, Bosnia, and Montenegro, whose collective designation 'Illyrian' is a Greek and Roman simplification of what were likely dozens of distinct tribal identities. The Illyrian tribes periodically unified under powerful leaders — most notably Queen Teuta of the Ardiaei, whose naval power threatened Roman Adriatic trade and provoked the First Illyrian War (229 BCE) — demonstrating the capacity for large-scale political organisation when motivated by external pressure or strong leadership. The Illyrian language is a linguistic isolate within Indo-European whose only possible surviving descendant is Albanian, making the Albanians potentially the most direct descendants of any ancient Balkans population. The Roman conquest of Illyricum was completed by Augustus after the Pannonian revolt of 6–9 CE, but Illyrian cultural identity persisted under Roman rule."},
  {"id":509,"n":"Celtic La Tène Culture","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-450,"e":-50,"p":3000000,"lang":"celtic","gov":"tribal-confederation","d":"The La Tène culture (~450–50 BCE) of central Europe represents the florescence of Celtic civilisation — the period in which the characteristic art style of swirling, interlaced, zoomorphic patterns that defines Celtic artistic identity reached its peak, and in which Celtic peoples expanded across an enormous arc from Ireland to Galatia in modern Turkey. La Tène Celts sacked Rome (~390 BCE), invaded Greece and plundered Delphi (~279 BCE), settled Galatia in central Anatolia, and established oppida — large fortified urban centres — across temperate Europe. The Druids, described by Julius Caesar and other Roman sources, constituted a pan-Celtic intellectual and religious elite who transmitted enormous bodies of learning, law, and genealogy entirely through oral tradition, deliberately refusing to commit knowledge to writing. The gradual Roman conquest of the Celtic world between 58 BCE and 43 CE, combined with Germanic pressure from the east, ended La Tène culture as a political force while its art traditions, languages, and mythological heritage survived in the Atlantic fringe — Ireland, Wales, Scotland, Brittany."},
  {"id":510,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Summerville","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1200,"e":1550,"p":2000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Summerville phase of the Tombigbee River valley in present-day Alabama and Mississippi represents a regional Mississippian tradition within the broader Moundville political sphere, documenting how Mississippian cultural and political systems were adapted to the specific environmental and demographic conditions of the Tombigbee drainage. Summerville phase sites cluster along the river's natural levees, exploiting the rich bottomland soils for maize agriculture while maintaining access to the river for transport and exchange. The ceramic tradition of the Summerville phase shows both local innovation and strong connections to Moundville's prestige goods network, indicating participation in the regional exchange system while maintaining a degree of local cultural distinctiveness. The phase's persistence into the early historic period connects it potentially to the Alabama and Choctaw peoples encountered by European colonists in the 17th century."},
  {"id":511,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Dallas Phase","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1300,"e":1600,"p":3000,"lang":"muskogean-cherokee-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Dallas phase of the upper Tennessee Valley (~1300–1600 CE) was a major Mississippian regional tradition centred on sites including Hiwassee Island and Dallas, featuring platform mound complexes, a distinctive ceramic tradition, and participation in the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex exchange network. Dallas phase communities occupied the transitional zone between the Mississippian heartland to the west and the Appalachian Highlands to the east, a position that made them cultural intermediaries between the lowland Mississippian world and the upland communities of the Ridge and Valley province. The late survival of the Dallas phase into the 16th century means it was potentially encountered by the Hernando de Soto expedition of 1540, and some scholars have proposed connections between Dallas phase peoples and the ancestors of the historic Cherokee Nation, though this remains debated. The site of Toqua, a major Dallas phase centre, was excavated before its inundation by the Little Tennessee River reservoir in the 1970s."},
  {"id":512,"n":"Woodland Culture — Adena","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-1000,"e":100,"p":10000,"lang":"various-eastern-woodlands","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Adena culture (~1000 BCE–100 CE) of the Ohio Valley represents the first elaborated mound-building tradition of the Eastern Woodlands — the cultural foundation on which the later Hopewell Interaction Sphere was built. Adena burial mounds, typically circular and built over log-lined burial chambers, contain the earliest evidence of the exchange of exotic prestige goods across the Eastern Woodlands: copper from the Great Lakes, mica from the Appalachians, marine shell from the Gulf Coast. The Adena Great Serpent Mound in Ohio — a 411-metre effigy mound in the form of a coiling serpent, the largest known serpent effigy in the world — is the most spectacular surviving expression of Adena-related ceremonialism, though its precise dating and cultural attribution remain debated. Adena society was transitional between the fully nomadic Archaic hunter-gatherers that preceded it and the more sedentary, horticulturally-based Hopewell that followed, representing an intermediate stage of social complexity in which mound building and long-distance exchange emerged without fully sedentary agriculture."},
  {"id":513,"n":"Choctaw Nation — Prehistoric Phase","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1540,"p":20000,"lang":"choctaw-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The prehistoric Choctaw and their direct ancestors in present-day Mississippi and Alabama represent one of the best-documented cases of cultural continuity between the Mississippian archaeological tradition and a historically known Indigenous nation. The Choctaw oral tradition of Nanih Waiya — a sacred mound that the Choctaw identify as their place of emergence and which corresponds to a genuine Mississippian platform mound in Winston County, Mississippi — provides a rare Indigenous perspective on the meaning and significance of the mound-building tradition that archaeology documents from the outside. The Choctaw Nation at European contact was one of the largest Indigenous nations east of the Mississippi, with a complex matrilineal clan system, town-based political organisation, and a diplomatic sophistication that allowed them to navigate European colonial competition for several centuries. Their forced removal to Oklahoma on the Trail of Tears in the 1830s is one of the most consequential acts of American ethnic cleansing."},
  {"id":514,"n":"Muscogee / Creek Nation — Prehistoric Phase","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1540,"p":20000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"confederacy","d":"The prehistoric Muscogee (Creek) and their Mississippian-tradition ancestors in present-day Georgia and Alabama represent another well-documented case of continuity between the Mississippian archaeological record and a historically documented Indigenous confederacy. The Creek Confederacy that emerged in the historic period was a sophisticated political organisation uniting dozens of town-based communities under a loose federal structure — a model that some scholars have argued influenced American founding fathers' thinking about confederate governance. The green corn ceremony (Busk), documented in detail in colonial-era sources, preserves elements of Mississippian ceremonialism including sacred fires, ritual purification, and communal feasting that illuminate the living meaning of practices archaeologically documented at earlier sites. The Creek Confederacy's forced removal to Oklahoma in the 1830s, alongside the Choctaw, Cherokee, Chickasaw, and Seminole — the Five Civilised Tribes — ended their presence in their ancestral homeland."},
  {"id":515,"n":"Haida Civilisation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-1000,"e":1850,"p":20000,"lang":"haida","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Haida people of Haida Gwaii (the Queen Charlotte Islands) and southern Alaska developed one of the most visually distinctive and artistically accomplished civilisations in the pre-Columbian Americas — a maritime culture of extraordinary sophistication whose monumental totem poles, carved canoes up to 20 metres long, and massive cedar plank houses represent a tradition of woodworking and visual art with no parallel on the Pacific coast. Haida society was organised around matrilineal clans (Eagles and Ravens) with a complex system of hereditary chiefly titles, wealth redistribution through potlatch ceremonies, and a prestige economy based on control of maritime resources — salmon, halibut, sea mammals — and the production of luxury goods including Argillite carvings and Chilkat blankets traded across the Northwest Coast. The devastating smallpox epidemic of 1862 killed approximately 70% of the Haida population within a few years, reducing a thriving civilisation of perhaps 20,000 people to fewer than 600, one of the most catastrophic disease-driven population collapses in recorded history."},
  {"id":516,"n":"Tlingit Civilisation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-1000,"e":1900,"p":15000,"lang":"tlingit","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Tlingit people of coastal Alaska and northern British Columbia built one of the most complex non-agricultural societies in human history — a maritime civilisation whose social organisation, material culture, and ceremonial life rival in sophistication those of many agricultural states. Tlingit society was organised around matrilineal moieties (Raven and Eagle/Wolf), with elaborate clan systems, hereditary titles, and a potlatch ceremonial economy in which wealth was accumulated and then redistributed in competitive feasts that established and confirmed social rank. Tlingit warfare was conducted with sophisticated discipline and equipment — wooden armour, copper-bladed weapons, and coordinated tactical manoeuvres — and the Tlingit successfully resisted Russian colonial encroachment for decades, inflicting a major defeat on Russian forces at the Battle of Sitka in 1802. Their oral literature — particularly the Raven cycle of transformation stories — is among the richest in North America, encoding cosmological, historical, and moral knowledge across hundreds of generations of oral transmission."},
  {"id":517,"n":"Olmec — San Lorenzo Phase","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-1500,"e":-900,"p":10000,"lang":"proto-mixe-zoquean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"San Lorenzo (~1500–900 BCE) was the first great Olmec centre and the earliest complex society in Mesoamerica, built on an artificially modified plateau in the lowland jungle of Veracruz, Mexico. San Lorenzo produced the first colossal heads — massive basalt portraits of individual rulers weighing up to 28 tonnes, transported from quarries 60–80km away with no wheeled vehicles or draft animals — establishing the Olmec tradition of monumental portraiture that would influence Mesoamerican art for two millennia. San Lorenzo was deliberately destroyed around 900 BCE — the colossal heads and other monuments were mutilated and buried in a pattern suggesting deliberate termination ritual — before the emergence of La Venta as the successor Olmec centre. Ivan Van Sertima's controversial They Came Before Columbus (1976) argued that the distinctly African-featured appearance of the colossal heads evidences trans-Atlantic contact with West Africa, a thesis rejected by mainstream archaeology but persistently discussed in alternative scholarship."},
  {"id":518,"n":"Olmec — La Venta Phase","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-900,"e":-400,"p":18000,"lang":"proto-mixe-zoquean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"La Venta (~900–400 BCE) succeeded San Lorenzo as the dominant Olmec centre and produced the most elaborate known Olmec ceremonial complex — a series of mounds, plazas, and buried offerings arranged along a precise north-south axis that may encode astronomical alignments. The Great Pyramid of La Venta, a 34-metre earthen mound built in a fluted cone shape, is one of the earliest large-scale pyramidal constructions in the Americas. La Venta's massive buried offerings — mosaic pavements of serpentine blocks forming abstract jaguar masks, caches of jade axes arranged in geometric patterns — demonstrate a ritual life of extraordinary complexity and the long-distance sourcing of prestige materials from across Mesoamerica. The Olmec civilisation is often described as the 'mother culture' of Mesoamerica for the role of Olmec iconographic, calendrical, and political traditions in the development of later cultures including the Zapotec, Maya, and Aztec — though the precise mechanisms of this influence remain debated."},
  {"id":519,"n":"Chichimec / Northern Mexico Cultures","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-500,"e":1600,"p":500000,"lang":"various-uto-aztecan","gov":"tribal-confederation","d":"The Chichimec peoples of northern Mexico — a collective designation used by Mesoamerican agriculturalists for the diverse hunter-gatherer and semi-nomadic cultures of the arid Gran Chichimeca region — maintained their independence against both the Aztec Empire and Spanish colonial power for longer than virtually any other Indigenous group in the Americas, conducting the Chichimec War (~1550–1590 CE) against Spanish forces in one of the longest armed conflicts of the colonial period. The term 'Chichimec' (roughly 'lineage of dogs' in Nahuatl) was a pejorative applied by sedentary Mesoamerican peoples to their mobile northern neighbours, obscuring the cultural diversity of what were actually dozens of distinct linguistic and cultural groups including the Zacatec, Guachichil, Pame, and Jonaz. The Chichimec peoples' resistance to both agricultural state expansion and European colonialism — enabled by their mobility, knowledge of the arid landscape, and social structures that did not depend on fixed settlements — represents a case study in the resilience of non-sedentary cultures against expansionist states."},
  {"id":520,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Hiwassee Island","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1300,"e":1600,"p":1500,"lang":"muskogean-cherokee-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Hiwassee Island at the confluence of the Hiwassee and Tennessee Rivers in present-day Tennessee was a major Dallas phase Mississippian centre whose excavation by the Tennessee Valley Authority in the 1930s — before the site was partially inundated by Chickamauga reservoir — produced one of the most complete stratigraphic records of a Mississippian platform mound site ever documented, revealing multiple construction stages and associated structures spanning the full Dallas phase occupation. The meticulous excavation records from Hiwassee Island, published by Thomas Lewis and Madeline Kneberg in 1946, remain a foundational reference for southeastern archaeology. The site's position at the confluence of two major rivers made it a strategic node in the exchange and communication networks of the upper Tennessee Valley Mississippian world. Its Dallas phase material culture and geographic position in the southern Appalachian foothills place it in the zone most likely connected to the emergence of the historic Cherokee Nation."},
  {"id":521,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville Phase I","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1050,"e":1250,"p":10000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Phase I occupation of Moundville (~1050–1250 CE) represents the founding and rapid growth of what would become the second-largest Mississippian centre in North America, a period of intense mound construction, population aggregation, and political centralisation in the Black Warrior Valley. Timothy Pauketat's research has documented the extraordinary speed of Moundville's emergence — within a few generations, a dispersed agricultural population transformed into a nucleated urban centre with a clear site hierarchy, suggesting a top-down political reorganisation rather than gradual organic growth. The Phase I community built the initial platform mounds, established the central plaza, and began the construction of the defensive palisade that enclosed the ceremonial precinct. The founding of Moundville may have been associated with a specific political or religious innovation — possibly the adoption of Cahokia-derived cosmological and political ideas — that gave its founders sufficient ideological authority to aggregate and direct large-scale collective labour."},
  {"id":522,"n":"Sican / Lambayeque Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":750,"e":1375,"p":200000,"lang":"mochica","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Sican (Lambayeque) culture of northern coastal Peru (~750–1375 CE) was one of the great goldworking civilisations of the ancient Americas, producing gold and tumbaga (gold-copper alloy) objects of extraordinary technical sophistication — including the famous Tumi ceremonial knives and funerary masks — that define a distinctive artistic tradition centred on the fanged deity figure known as the Sican Lord. The culture's founder is identified in oral tradition as Naymlap, a semi-divine ruler who arrived by sea from the north with a fleet of balsa rafts, an origin narrative that encodes both the Sican elite's claim to exotic, supernatural origins and possibly genuine memory of maritime contact. The major Sican ceremonial centre at Batán Grande features massive adobe truncated pyramids that served as royal burial facilities; one royal tomb excavated by Izumi Shimada contained a inverted male burial surrounded by the remains of sacrificed women, enormous quantities of gold objects, and arsenical bronze tools. The Sican were conquered by the Chimú around 1375 CE."},
  {"id":523,"n":"Moche Civilisation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":100,"e":800,"p":60000,"lang":"mochica","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Moche civilisation of northern coastal Peru (~100–800 CE) is renowned for producing the most naturalistically expressive ceramic art of any pre-Columbian Andean culture — portrait vessels capturing individual human faces with psychological specificity not seen elsewhere in the ancient Americas, and narrative scenes of warfare, sacrifice, and erotic mythology executed with extraordinary technical and artistic skill. The Moche built massive adobe platform complexes — the Huaca del Sol and Huaca de la Luna at the capital near present-day Trujillo — using a distinctive system of brick production in which individual communities contributed marked bricks, documenting a labour taxation system. The Sacrifice Ceremony, depicted repeatedly in Moche art, was confirmed as a real ritual when excavations at the Huaca de la Luna revealed skeletal evidence of sacrificed warriors matching the iconographic sequence exactly. The Moche collapse around 800 CE, possibly triggered by a prolonged El Niño drought cycle, ended one of the most vivid artistic civilisations of the ancient world."},
  {"id":524,"n":"Nazca Civilisation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":800,"p":25000,"lang":"proto-quechuan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Nazca civilisation of the southern Peruvian coastal desert (~100 BCE–800 CE) is most famous for the Nazca Lines — an extraordinary complex of geoglyphs etched into the desert pavement covering an area of approximately 450 square kilometres, including giant figures of animals (hummingbird, spider, monkey, condor), geometric shapes, and straight lines extending for kilometres with mathematical precision. The lines were created by removing the reddish surface stones to reveal the lighter ground beneath — a simple technique, but the scale and precision of execution remain remarkable. Mainstream archaeology interprets the lines as ceremonial pathways and offerings to deities, possibly associated with water and fertility rituals in an extremely arid environment. Erich von Däniken's ancient astronaut hypothesis proposed the lines as landing strips for spacecraft, a claim rejected by archaeology but enormously influential in popular culture. The Nazca also produced sophisticated polychrome pottery and an underground aqueduct system (puquios) that may still function today, distributing water across the desert landscape."},
  {"id":525,"n":"Tiahuanaco — Astronomical Alignment","r":"Americas","t":"debated","s":-15000,"e":-10000,"p":0,"lang":"unknown","gov":"unknown","d":"Arthur Posnansky's monumental study Tiahuanacu: The Cradle of American Man (1945) proposed, based on astronomical analysis of the alignments of the Kalasasaya enclosure at Tiwanaku, that the monument was designed to mark the solstices and equinoxes at a date of approximately 15,000 BCE — when the obliquity of the ecliptic would have placed the sunrise and sunset at the angles encoded in the Kalasasaya's gateway positions. This would make Tiwanaku not a 500 CE construction but a monument of extraordinary antiquity, predating the Younger Dryas boundary and potentially representing one of the oldest astronomical monuments on Earth. Mainstream archaeology decisively rejects Posnansky's dating on multiple grounds: the ceramic sequences, radiocarbon dates, and architectural analysis all firmly place the monumental construction at 500–900 CE. Alternative scholars including Graham Hancock and Brien Foerster have revisited Posnansky's astronomical arguments. The debate exemplifies the difficulty of using astronomical alignment dating alone, which can produce multiple candidate dates across precessional cycles without independent corroboration."},
  {"id":526,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Florence Mound","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":500,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Florence Mound in present-day northern Alabama represents one of dozens of smaller Mississippian mound sites within the Tennessee Valley regional system, a minor ceremonial centre that participated in the exchange networks and political hierarchies of the broader Mississippian world while maintaining a primarily local agricultural community. Sites like Florence Mound are collectively more important than individually prominent sites for understanding how Mississippian civilisation actually functioned at the community level — the daily life, agricultural rhythms, and local ritual practices of the majority population who lived away from the great paramount centres. The Tennessee Valley's density of smaller Mississippian mound sites documents a landscape that was intensively occupied and politically organised across its entire length during the Mississippian period, a fact often obscured by the focus on spectacular sites like Cahokia and Moundville."},
  {"id":527,"n":"Paracas Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-800,"e":100,"p":10000,"lang":"proto-nazca","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Paracas culture of the Ica region of coastal Peru (~800 BCE–100 CE) is renowned for two extraordinary achievements: the Paracas Cavernas and Paracas Necrópolis burial traditions, which preserved mummified human remains in underground chambers and elaborate textile wrappings in the hyperarid coastal desert, and the Paracas textiles themselves — considered the finest pre-Columbian textiles in the Americas, woven with thread counts exceeding modern machine-woven fabric and featuring complex mythological imagery in colours still vivid after two millennia. The Paracas mummies also document intentional cranial modification — elongated skulls achieved by binding infants' heads between boards — creating elite individuals whose skull shape visually distinguished them from commoners. Brien Foerster has controversially proposed, based on claimed DNA analysis, that some Paracas elongated skulls represent a genetically distinct population rather than artificially modified normal human skulls, a claim not accepted by mainstream physical anthropology."},
  {"id":529,"n":"Recuay Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1,"e":700,"p":15000,"lang":"proto-quechuan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Recuay culture of the northern Peruvian highlands (~1–700 CE) developed a distinctive sculptural and ceramic tradition in the Callejón de Huaylas valley — a high mountain corridor between the Cordillera Blanca and the Cordillera Negra — that combined kaolin white-ware ceramics with three-dimensional figurative sculpture depicting armed warriors, supernatural beings, and elite life scenes. Recuay elite burial traditions involved elaborate stone-lined tombs (chullpas) and the interment of individuals with rich grave goods including bronze weapons and distinctive negative-painted pottery. The culture's geographical position in the highland corridor placed it between the coastal Moche civilisation to the west and the highland cultures of the Andean interior, and Recuay material culture shows evidence of complex interactions — sometimes hostile, sometimes commercial — with Moche expansion into the highlands. Recuay sculptural traditions appear to have influenced subsequent highland Andean artistic traditions and may have transmitted certain iconographic elements to the later Tiwanaku-Wari horizon."},
  {"id":530,"n":"Valdivia Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-3500,"e":-1500,"p":5000,"lang":"unknown-coastal-ecuador","gov":"village","d":"The Valdivia culture of coastal Ecuador (~3500–1500 BCE) produced the oldest known pottery in the Americas — a discovery that fundamentally revised understanding of South American cultural development when Betty Meggers and colleagues published the finding in 1965. The early Valdivia ceramics are technically sophisticated from their first appearance, without the experimental crudeness typically associated with the invention of pottery, leading Meggers to controversially propose transpacific diffusion from the Jōmon culture of Japan — whose pottery is of similar antiquity and certain stylistic similarities. Mainstream archaeology has largely rejected the transpacific hypothesis in favour of independent invention, but the question of why early Valdivia ceramics appear so accomplished from the outset remains not fully resolved. Valdivia is also known for its distinctive female figurines — the earliest known figurative sculpture in the Americas — which may represent ancestor figures, fertility deities, or markers of social identity."},
  {"id":531,"n":"Norte Chico / Caral — Satellite Sites","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-3000,"e":-1800,"p":20000,"lang":"unknown-coastal-peru","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Norte Chico civilisation of coastal Peru extended well beyond the primary site of Caral to encompass at least 30 major sites across the Supe, Pativilca, Fortaleza, and Huaura valleys — a regional civilisation of the third millennium BCE that collectively represents the earliest complex society in the Americas. Sites including Huaricanga, Pozo Santo, Miraya, and Caballete each feature monumental platform mounds, sunken circular plazas of a form unique to Norte Chico, and evidence of the coastal-inland exchange economy based on anchoveta fishing and agricultural products. The absence of warfare evidence across the entire Norte Chico cultural horizon — no defensive architecture, no weapons in burials, no skeletal trauma consistent with organised violence — is one of the most striking features of this civilisation and has led some scholars to propose that Norte Chico achieved urban complexity through economic interdependence and religious integration rather than coercive political power. Whether this represents a genuinely peaceful civilisation or merely an absence of preserved evidence for conflict remains debated."},
  {"id":532,"n":"Tiwanaku — Pumapunku","r":"Americas","t":"debated","s":-500,"e":1100,"p":20000,"lang":"puquina","gov":"theocracy","d":"Pumapunku, a platform complex at the Tiwanaku site in Bolivia, contains stone blocks of a kind that have attracted intense attention from both mainstream archaeologists and alternative scholars — H-shaped andesite blocks machined to tolerances of fractions of a millimetre, with complex interlocking geometries that would be challenging even with modern tools. Brien Foerster and others in the alternative archaeology tradition argue these precision tolerances evidence advanced technology beyond what the accepted Tiwanaku date of ~500–900 CE can explain, and propose a much earlier construction date. Mainstream archaeology attributes the precision to skilled stone dressing using harder stone tools and abrasives, with radiocarbon dates for organic material associated with the construction firmly in the first millennium CE. The blocks' H-shaped profiles appear designed for interlocking structural connections, and the site shows evidence of deliberate demolition in antiquity — possibly during the political collapse of Tiwanaku — that scattered the precision-cut elements. Pumapunku remains one of the most visited and debated sites in alternative archaeology."},
  {"id":533,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Fatherland","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1250,"e":1730,"p":4000,"lang":"natchez","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Fatherland site near present-day Natchez, Mississippi, was the historic capital of the Natchez Nation — the last major functioning Mississippian-tradition chiefdom encountered by European colonists in the lower Mississippi Valley, and the only one documented in sufficient ethnographic detail to reconstruct the living political and religious system of the Mississippian world. French colonial sources from the late 17th and early 18th centuries describe the Natchez political system in considerable detail: the Great Sun, a divine ruler carried on a litter and never permitted to touch the ground, whose word was law over life and death; a rigid hereditary caste system of Suns, Nobles, Honoured Men, and Stinkards; and an eternal sacred fire maintained in the temple atop the primary platform mound. When the Great Sun died, retainers were strangled to accompany him. The French destroyed the Natchez Nation in 1731 following the Natchez Revolt of 1729, ending the last intact Mississippian political system. Fatherland's occupation continuity from the prehistoric Plaquemine tradition through the historic Natchez period makes it uniquely valuable for connecting archaeology to documented living culture."},
  {"id":534,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Grand Village","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1300,"e":1731,"p":1500,"lang":"natchez","gov":"theocracy","d":"Grand Village of the Natchez Indians in present-day Natchez, Mississippi, is the best-documented late Mississippian site in North America — a platform mound complex that served as the ceremonial centre of the historic Natchez Nation from approximately 1300 CE until the French destruction of the Natchez in 1731. Unlike most Mississippian sites known only through archaeology, Grand Village was observed and described in detail by French missionaries, soldiers, and colonial officials including Antoine-Simon Le Page du Pratz, whose Histoire de la Louisiane (1758) preserves the most complete account of Mississippian ceremonial life ever written. The site's mounds supported the house of the Great Sun and the temple containing the sacred fire and bone bundles of deceased Great Suns. Excavations at Grand Village have confirmed the French documentary accounts in detail, providing a uniquely powerful methodological demonstration of how ethnographic records and archaeological evidence can be used to validate and enrich each other."},
  {"id":535,"n":"Cahuilla / Desert Cultures — California","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-3000,"e":1850,"p":6000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-cahuilla","gov":"band","d":"The Cahuilla and related Desert Cultures of inland southern California developed one of the most sophisticated hunter-gatherer adaptations to an arid environment in the Americas — a 5,000-year tradition of intensive resource management in the Coachella Valley, San Bernardino Mountains, and surrounding desert that supported relatively dense populations without agriculture through systematic exploitation of acorns, mesquite, pinyon pine, and desert game. Cahuilla society was organised around patrilineal clans with hereditary ritual specialists (net) and an elaborate ceremonial life including the mourning ceremony (nukmit) and the bird songs — a cycle of hundreds of linked songs encoding geographical knowledge, cosmological narratives, and historical memory transmitted across generations. The Cahuilla's intimate knowledge of desert hydrology, plant phenology, and animal behaviour constituted a sophisticated ecological science developed over millennia. Their survival through Spanish colonisation, American conquest, and the reservation system — the Cahuilla remain a federally recognised nation today — demonstrates remarkable cultural resilience."},
  {"id":536,"n":"Anasazi / Ancestral Puebloan — Chaco Roads","r":"Americas","t":"debated","s":850,"e":1150,"p":15000,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Chaco road system — a network of engineered roads radiating from Chaco Canyon across the Colorado Plateau, surveyed in detail through aerial photography and ground investigation — remains one of the most debated features of Ancestral Puebloan civilisation. The roads run in mathematically straight lines for distances of up to 60km, cutting through terrain regardless of topography, sometimes bifurcating and running in parallel without obvious functional reason. Some roads terminate at isolated great kivas or small outlier great houses; others lead to natural landscape features. The straightness, scale, and apparent non-utilitarian character of some roads has generated alternative interpretations: Pueblo oral tradition connects roads to spirit pathways; some researchers propose astronomical alignments; others see them as the material expression of a road-based cosmology in which straight paths connected the living to the ancestors. Anna Sofaer's Solstice Project has documented solar and lunar alignments at Chaco architecture that, combined with the road system, suggests a sophisticated cosmological programme integrating architecture, roads, and astronomical observation."},
  {"id":537,"n":"Hohokam — Snaketown","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":300,"e":1150,"p":2000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Snaketown on the Gila River in present-day Arizona was the largest and longest-occupied Hohokam village and the archaeological type site for the Hohokam cultural sequence, excavated by Emil Haury in major campaigns in 1934–35 and 1964–65. The site's deep stratigraphy documents the full trajectory of Hohokam cultural development from the Pioneer period through the Colonial and Sedentary periods, revealing a community that maintained continuous occupation for approximately 1,500 years on the banks of the Gila River. Snaketown's canal system, ball courts, and platform mound document the full Hohokam cultural package — Mesoamerican-derived features integrated into a distinctly Sonoran Desert cultural context. The site is located on the Gila River Indian Community reservation of the Akimel O'odham (Pima) people, who consider Snaketown part of their ancestral heritage; at the O'odham community's request, the site was backfilled after Haury's 1964–65 excavation and is not open to excavation."},
  {"id":538,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Pueblo Bonito","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":850,"e":1150,"p":1200,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"Pueblo Bonito in Chaco Canyon, New Mexico, is the largest and most thoroughly studied great house of the Ancestral Puebloan world — a D-shaped multi-storey structure of over 650 rooms and 37 kivas rising to four and possibly five storeys, built with a precision of stone masonry that architectural analysts have described as exceeding that of any contemporary structure in the Americas. Construction proceeded in distinct phases across more than two centuries, maintaining the overall D-plan with remarkable consistency. Despite its enormous size, Pueblo Bonito appears to have housed relatively few permanent residents — the room-to-population ratio suggests a primarily ceremonial and storage function, with most rooms used for ritual equipment, food stores, or turquoise and shell valuables. The cylinder jars found at Pueblo Bonito — residue-tested and confirmed to have held cacao — document the importation of this Mesoamerican prestige beverage from sources over 1,200km distant. Pueblo Bonito's spatial and architectural complexity continues to generate new interpretations with each generation of excavation and analysis."},
  {"id":539,"n":"Poverty Point — Watson Brake Complex","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-3500,"e":-2800,"p":500,"lang":"unknown","gov":"band-chiefdom","d":"Watson Brake in present-day Louisiana — eleven earthen mounds connected by a low oval ridge, radiocarbon-dated to approximately 3500–2800 BCE — is the oldest known mound complex in North America, predating Poverty Point by 1,800 years and predating the Egyptian Old Kingdom pyramids by several centuries. Its construction by hunter-gatherers in the Lower Mississippi Valley pushes the impulse to build monumental earthworks in North America back to a period when only scattered Archaic hunter-gatherer bands occupied the region, with no agriculture, no ceramics, and no obvious surplus economy capable of supporting collective monument construction by conventional models. The Watson Brake mounds are modest in scale compared to later Poverty Point constructions, but their antiquity is extraordinary. The site was discovered and dated only in the 1990s, and its implications for models of North American cultural development are still being absorbed. Watson Brake suggests that the Lower Mississippi Valley had an exceptionally deep tradition of monumental construction that Poverty Point represents not as an anomaly but as the culmination of a much longer regional development."},
  {"id":540,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Toltec Mounds","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":700,"e":1050,"p":3000,"lang":"various-quapaw-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Toltec Mounds in present-day Arkansas — despite its misleading name, which reflects 19th-century assumptions about Mexican connections rather than actual cultural links — is the largest Late Woodland and early Mississippian site in the Lower Mississippi Valley and an important transitional site documenting the cultural transformation from Woodland to Mississippian traditions in the region. The site features 18 mounds enclosed within an embankment, occupied primarily during the Plum Bayou culture phase (~700–1050 CE) that immediately preceded the full Mississippian fluorescence. Toltec Mounds appears to have been a major regional ceremonial centre during a formative period in the development of Mississippian civilisation, and its scale suggests it functioned as a proto-urban aggregation centre before the classic Mississippian pattern of plaza-oriented platform mound towns was fully established. The site's study has been important for understanding the transition from Woodland to Mississippian cultural patterns in the central Mississippi Valley."},
  {"id":541,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Winterville Phase II","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1200,"e":1450,"p":2000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The later phase occupation at Winterville in present-day Mississippi documents the mature development of this Lower Mississippi Valley Mississippian centre, with expanded mound construction, intensified participation in the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex exchange network, and evidence of increasing political complexity within the regional chiefdom hierarchy. Winterville's position in the Yazoo Basin placed it within a zone of exceptionally dense Mississippian settlement, where numerous mound centres competed and cooperated within a landscape that may have supported some of the highest pre-Columbian population densities east of the Mississippi River. The Yazoo Basin's extraordinarily productive alluvial soils — among the most fertile in North America — supported the agricultural surplus that underpinned the dense Mississippian settlement of this region, and the competition for control of these resources likely drove the political complexity documented at sites like Winterville throughout its Phase II occupation."},
  {"id":542,"n":"Paleo-Indian — Clovis Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-13500,"e":-12800,"p":5000,"lang":"unknown-paleo-indian","gov":"band","d":"The Clovis culture (~13,500–12,800 BCE) represents the earliest definitively documented widespread human occupation of North America — a distinctive lithic technology characterised by large, fluted projectile points of exceptional craftsmanship that spread across the Americas with extraordinary speed, appearing from Alaska to Patagonia within perhaps 500–1,000 years. Clovis hunters were megafauna specialists, with kill sites documenting their hunting of mammoths, mastodons, camels, horses, and giant ground sloths. The debate over whether Clovis people were responsible for the extinction of North American megafauna — the 'Pleistocene Overkill' hypothesis of Paul Martin — remains one of archaeology's most contested questions, with climate change and the Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis as alternative or contributing explanations. The Clovis-first model — which held that Clovis represented the founding population of the Americas — has been decisively overturned by pre-Clovis sites including Monte Verde in Chile (~14,500 BCE) and Chiquihuite Cave in Mexico (~26,000 BCE), establishing that humans were in the Americas well before Clovis."},
  {"id":543,"n":"Paleo-Indian — Pre-Clovis Peoples","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-20000,"e":-13500,"p":2000,"lang":"unknown-paleo-indian","gov":"band","d":"The accumulating evidence for pre-Clovis human presence in the Americas — sites including Monte Verde, Chile (~14,500 BCE), Chiquihuite Cave, Mexico (~26,000 BCE), Meadowcroft Rockshelter, Pennsylvania (~16,000 BCE), and Buttermilk Creek, Texas (~15,500 BCE) — has definitively established that humans arrived in the Americas before the Clovis culture and through routes other than the Bering Land Bridge ice-free corridor. The coastal migration hypothesis — humans following the kelp forest highway along the Pacific coast of Asia and North America by watercraft — is now the leading model for the initial peopling of the Americas, potentially predating the opening of the ice-free interior corridor. Genetic evidence supports multiple founding populations and possibly multiple entry events. Graham Hancock's America Before (2019) synthesises the pre-Clovis evidence and argues it supports a much more ancient and complex human presence in the Americas than mainstream archaeology has acknowledged, potentially extending to the time of the last glacial maximum or earlier."},
  {"id":545,"n":"Tiwanaku — Lake Titicaca Sacred Landscape","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-500,"e":1000,"p":100000,"lang":"puquina","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Lake Titicaca basin as a whole constituted a sacred landscape for the Tiwanaku civilisation, with the lake itself — the world's highest navigable body of water at 3,812 metres elevation — serving as the cosmological centre of a religious system that extended across the Andean world. The Island of the Sun and the Island of the Moon within the lake were the mythological birthplace of the sun and moon in Andean cosmology, a significance that predated Tiwanaku and was subsequently adopted and amplified by the Inca. Tiwanaku's transformation of the lake's margins through raised field agriculture — converting the marshy totora reed beds into productive farmland through elevated planting surfaces surrounded by water channels — represented an engineering project of extraordinary scale, with some estimates suggesting the system covered over 80,000 hectares at its maximum extent. The water channels served not only as drainage and nutrient sources but as thermal regulators, absorbing solar heat during the day and releasing it at night to protect crops from the killing frosts that regularly occur at this altitude."},
  {"id":546,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Obion","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1350,"p":1500,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Obion Mounds in present-day western Tennessee was a significant Mississippian centre of the western Tennessee region, a platform mound complex whose position in the lowland zone between the Tennessee River and the Mississippi River placed it within the exchange sphere of both the Cahokia-influenced northern Mississippian world and the Moundville-influenced southern tradition. The site documents the cultural diversity within the Mississippian tradition — regional variants in ceramic style, mound shape, and site layout that reveal local adaptations of the shared Mississippian cultural template rather than a monolithic, uniform civilisation imposed from Cahokia outward. Archaeological survey of the western Tennessee lowlands has revealed a dense settlement pattern of smaller villages and farmsteads surrounding Obion and similar mound centres, documenting the agricultural landscape that supported these political and ceremonial focal points."},
  {"id":547,"n":"Chimu — Chan Chan Extended","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1470,"p":60000,"lang":"mochica","gov":"monarchy","d":"Chan Chan, the capital of the Chimú Empire in present-day northern Peru, was the largest pre-Columbian city in South America and one of the largest adobe cities ever built — a sprawling urban landscape covering approximately 20 square kilometres, organised around nine or ten royal compounds (ciudadelas) each built by a successive Chimú king as his personal palace and ultimately his mausoleum. The ciudadela system documents a distinctive Chimú political institution: the principle of split inheritance, in which a new king built a new palace and accumulated new wealth while the deceased king's palace was maintained by his descendants as a mortuary cult estate. This split inheritance system drove the continuous expansion of Chimú territory and wealth extraction, as each new ruler needed to generate the resources to build a new ciudadela while maintaining existing ones. Chan Chan's hydraulic infrastructure — long canals bringing water from the Santa and Moche rivers across the desert — made the city possible in one of Earth's most arid coastal environments."},
  {"id":548,"n":"Muisca Confederation","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":600,"e":1538,"p":300000,"lang":"chibchan-muisca","gov":"confederation","d":"The Muisca Confederation of the high Bogotá savanna in present-day Colombia (~600–1538 CE) was one of the four major civilisations of the Americas at the time of Spanish contact, alongside the Aztec, Maya, and Inca, though it is far less well known in popular accounts of pre-Columbian civilisation. The Muisca are the origin of the El Dorado legend — their ritual of Zipa (the ruler) coating himself in gold dust and casting gold and emerald offerings into Lake Guatavita was witnessed and reported by Spanish conquistadors and ignited centuries of gold-seeking expeditions across South America. The Muisca were the world's largest producers of emeralds, extracting them from the Muzo and Chivor mines in the eastern Andes. Their political organisation — a confederation of city-states under two paramount rulers, the Zipa and the Zaque — was sophisticated enough to maintain political cohesion across a population of 300,000–500,000 people in a challenging high-altitude environment. The Spanish conquest of the Muisca homeland in 1537–1538 was rapid due to internal political divisions the conquistadors exploited."},
  {"id":549,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Helena Crossing","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1400,"p":1000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Helena Crossing Mounds in present-day Arkansas was a significant Mississippian centre on the west bank of the Mississippi River, occupying a strategically important position at a natural crossing point that made it a node in the river-borne exchange network of the central Mississippi Valley. Sites like Helena Crossing document the Mississippian practice of establishing ceremonial and political centres at river confluences and crossings — geographic chokepoints that enabled the control of trade and movement along the natural highway system of the river network. The Mississippi River and its major tributaries constituted the primary transport infrastructure of the Mississippian world, and the political geography of Mississippian chiefdoms closely tracks the distribution of navigable waterways. Helena Crossing's position opposite present-day Helena, Arkansas, reflects the enduring strategic significance of this particular river crossing across multiple millennia of human history."},
  {"id":550,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Powers Phase","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1400,"p":2000,"lang":"various-siouan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Powers Phase of the Mississippi River lowlands in present-day southeastern Missouri (~1000–1400 CE) is archaeologically significant as a well-documented regional Mississippian community whose settlement pattern — a single large centre (Powers Fort) surrounded by four medium villages and numerous hamlets and farmsteads — has been comprehensively surveyed and mapped, providing one of the most complete pictures of how a Mississippian local community system was spatially organised across the landscape. James Price and James Griffin's systematic survey of the Powers Phase settlement system in the 1970s and 1980s became a model for regional settlement archaeology and demonstrated that Mississippian communities could be understood as integrated territorial systems rather than isolated site assemblages. The Powers Phase people appear to have abandoned their territory rapidly around 1400 CE, possibly in response to the same climatic and political disruptions that were reorganising Mississippian societies across the region."},
  {"id":551,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Zebree","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1200,"p":500,"lang":"various-mississippian","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Zebree in present-day northeastern Arkansas is an early Mississippian site whose careful excavation documented the transition from Late Woodland to early Mississippian cultural patterns in the central Mississippi Valley with unusual stratigraphic clarity. The site preserves evidence of the rapid adoption of Mississippian ceramic technology, maize intensification, and community reorganisation that characterises the Mississippian emergence across the region around 900–1000 CE. Zebree's importance lies not in its scale but in the precision with which it documents this cultural transition at the community level — the shift in house form, ceramic assemblage, and agricultural practice that marks the archaeological boundary between Woodland and Mississippian traditions. Such transitional sites are critical for understanding how the Mississippian cultural package spread — whether through migration, elite emulation, religious conversion, or economic advantage — across the Eastern Woodlands."},
  {"id":552,"n":"Fremont — Nine Mile Canyon","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":950,"e":1250,"p":2000,"lang":"unknown-fremont","gov":"band-chiefdom","d":"Nine Mile Canyon in present-day Utah contains one of the largest and most spectacular concentrations of rock art in North America — over 10,000 petroglyphs and pictographs created primarily by Fremont culture people between approximately 950–1250 CE, earning it the designation 'the world's longest art gallery.' The imagery includes hunting scenes of extraordinary naturalism, anthropomorphic figures with elaborate headdresses and regalia, shield-bearing warriors, bighorn sheep hunts, and cosmological symbols whose meaning remains imperfectly understood. The canyon served as a travel corridor connecting the Uinta Basin to the Colorado Plateau, and the concentration of imagery at specific narrows and water sources suggests the rock art marked significant locations in a sacred and practical landscape. Nine Mile Canyon's rock art corpus documents the Fremont people's rich ceremonial and intellectual life in a medium more durable than the perishable organic materials that constitute most of their preserved cultural output."},
  {"id":553,"n":"Mogollon Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":200,"e":1450,"p":15000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-proto","gov":"village","d":"The Mogollon culture (~200–1450 CE) of the mountains and desert grasslands of southwestern New Mexico and southeastern Arizona developed one of the most distinctive ceramic traditions of the American Southwest — Mimbres pottery, produced during the Classic Mimbres phase (~1000–1150 CE), features black-on-white geometric and figurative designs of extraordinary sophistication, including narrative hunting scenes, mythological beings, fish, insects, and humans rendered with an economy of line and compositional mastery that ranks among the finest ceramic art of the pre-Columbian Americas. Mimbres bowls were typically 'killed' — pierced with a hole — before being placed over the face of the deceased in burial, suggesting a cosmological belief about releasing the vessel's spirit. The Mimbres artistic tradition collapsed abruptly around 1150 CE, with the abandonment of Classic Mimbres villages, in a pattern potentially linked to the same climate stress affecting Ancestral Puebloan communities to the north."},
  {"id":554,"n":"Sinagua Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":500,"e":1425,"p":10000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-proto","gov":"village","d":"The Sinagua culture (~500–1425 CE) of north-central Arizona — whose name means 'without water' in Spanish, reflecting the challenging environment they occupied — developed a distinctive cultural tradition in the Verde Valley and the San Francisco Peaks region that combined elements of Hohokam, Ancestral Puebloan, and Mogollon traditions with local innovation. The most spectacular Sinagua site is Montezuma Castle — a five-storey cliff dwelling of 20 rooms built into a natural limestone alcove 27 metres above the Verde Valley floor, one of the best-preserved prehistoric cliff dwellings in North America. The Sinagua also built Tuzigoot, a hilltop pueblo of 110 rooms overlooking the Verde River, and Wupatki, a large pueblo near the San Francisco Peaks built on volcanic cinders deposited by the 1064–1065 CE eruption of Sunset Crater — an eruption that initially disrupted and ultimately attracted farming populations to the region as volcanic ash improved soil moisture retention."},
  {"id":555,"n":"Salado Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1150,"e":1450,"p":20000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-proto","gov":"village","d":"The Salado culture (~1150–1450 CE) of the Tonto Basin and Salt River drainage of central Arizona represents a cultural florescence in which Hohokam, Mogollon, and Ancestral Puebloan influences synthesised into a distinctive regional tradition characterised above all by polychrome pottery — red, white, and black ceramics of a distinctive style traded widely across the Southwest and used as mortuary goods in a burial tradition that interred the dead beneath house floors. The cliff dwellings of the Tonto National Monument — Upper and Lower Tonto Cliff Dwelling — are the most accessible surviving Salado architectural achievements. The Salado flourished during a period when the collapse of Chaco Canyon and the reorganisation of Hohokam society were creating population movements across the Southwest, and their rapid growth may reflect successful adaptation to the demographic disruption of the 13th century. Their abandonment of the Tonto Basin around 1450 CE, in common with most Southwestern cultures, remains linked to drought cycles documented in tree-ring records."},
  {"id":556,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Bandelier","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1150,"e":1550,"p":5000,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"village","d":"Bandelier National Monument in present-day New Mexico preserves the remains of Ancestral Puebloan occupation of the Pajarito Plateau — a landscape of dramatic volcanic tuff canyons where people carved rooms directly into the soft cliff faces to supplement freestanding pueblo construction, creating the distinctive talus house and cave room communities of Frijoles Canyon and surrounding drainages. The Pajarito Plateau communities developed in the 12th and 13th centuries CE as populations moved south from the Four Corners region following the abandonment of Mesa Verde and related sites. Tyuonyi, the largest community at Bandelier, was a circular pueblo of approximately 400 rooms surrounding a central plaza, occupied from approximately 1350–1550 CE. The descendants of Bandelier's occupants are the modern Cochiti, San Ildefonso, Santa Clara, and other Pueblo peoples of the Rio Grande Valley, who maintain oral traditions and ceremonial connections to the Pajarito Plateau sites."},
  {"id":557,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Aztec Ruins","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1300,"p":2000,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"Aztec Ruins National Monument in present-day New Mexico — named by 19th-century American settlers who incorrectly attributed the site to the Aztecs — is a large Ancestral Puebloan great house complex built and occupied primarily during the 12th and 13th centuries CE, serving as a major regional centre in the northern San Juan Basin after the decline of Chaco Canyon. The site features a great house of approximately 450 rooms, a fully reconstructed great kiva — the only fully reconstructed great kiva open to the public — and evidence of two distinct construction episodes associated first with the Chacoan and subsequently with the Mesa Verde cultural traditions, making Aztec Ruins uniquely valuable for documenting the transition between these two phases of Ancestral Puebloan regional organisation. The great kiva's reconstruction, completed by Earl Morris in 1934, provides an unparalleled sense of the interior ceremonial space of Ancestral Puebloan communal ritual."},
  {"id":558,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Lilbourn","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1400,"p":1000,"lang":"various-siouan","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Lilbourn Mounds in present-day southeastern Missouri represents a Mississippian centre in the Cairo Lowland — the northernmost extension of the Mississippi River alluvial plain — documenting the spread of Mississippian cultural traditions into a zone that served as a transition between the Cahokia-dominated American Bottom to the north and the Lower Mississippi Valley Mississippian tradition to the south. The Cairo Lowland contained a dense concentration of Mississippian mound sites that exploited the extraordinarily fertile alluvial soils of this region, now largely obliterated by agricultural drainage and modification. Lilbourn's mound configuration and ceramic assemblage show connections to both the Cahokia sphere to the north and the Powers Phase regional system to the west, documenting the overlapping influence zones of different Mississippian political systems in this transitional geographic zone."},
  {"id":559,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Wupatki","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1250,"p":2000,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"village","d":"Wupatki Pueblo in present-day northern Arizona was built on the volcanic cinders deposited by the 1064–1065 CE eruption of Sunset Crater — one of the most precisely dated natural events in prehistoric North American history, confirmed by tree-ring analysis of timbers killed by the eruption. The ash fall initially disrupted existing farming communities but ultimately attracted new populations to the area as volcanic cinders acted as a mulch, improving soil moisture retention and agricultural productivity in an otherwise marginal environment. At its peak around 1100–1150 CE, Wupatki was one of the largest pueblos in the region, with approximately 100 rooms, a ball court connecting it culturally to Hohokam traditions to the south, and a community blowhole — a crack in the underlying rock through which air moves with changing atmospheric pressure, possibly understood as a breathing earth in Pueblo cosmology. The Sunset Crater eruption and the Wupatki florescence it produced represent one of the clearest documented examples of a catastrophic natural event reshaping the cultural landscape of the prehistoric Southwest."},
  {"id":560,"n":"Hohokam — Casa Grande","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1150,"e":1450,"p":5000,"lang":"uto-aztecan-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Casa Grande ('Great House') in present-day Arizona is the most enigmatic and debated structure in the Hohokam cultural tradition — a four-storey caliche adobe tower of massive walls built around 1350 CE, whose function remains uncertain despite over a century of archaeological investigation. Proposed interpretations include an astronomical observatory (openings in the walls align with the sun at solstices and equinoxes), a watchtower, an elite residence, a ceremonial structure, or a combination of these functions. Casa Grande was the first prehistoric ruin in the United States to receive federal protection, designated a national monument by President Benjamin Harrison in 1892. The surrounding compound contains multiple smaller structures, a ball court, and evidence of the canal irrigation system that sustained the Hohokam community of Coolidge. The structure's unique architectural form — nothing quite like it exists elsewhere in the prehistoric Southwest — makes it both compelling and frustrating for archaeologists attempting to understand its original function and meaning within Hohokam society."},
  {"id":561,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Hovenweep","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1300,"p":2500,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"village","d":"Hovenweep National Monument in present-day Utah and Colorado preserves six clusters of Ancestral Puebloan towers, pueblos, and kivas built primarily during the 13th century CE on canyon rims and boulders overlooking small drainages in the Great Sage Plain. The towers of Hovenweep — D-shaped, round, square, and oval structures of careful masonry built at the canyon edge — have attracted particular attention for their possible astronomical function: openings in several towers align with the rising and setting sun at solstices and equinoxes, consistent with Anna Sofaer's broader argument for astronomical intentionality in Ancestral Puebloan architecture. The towers may also have served as defensive structures in a period of increasing inter-community conflict documented archaeologically across the northern Southwest in the 13th century. Hovenweep's communities were abandoned around 1300 CE in the same migration that emptied the Four Corners region, with descendants moving to the Rio Grande Pueblos of New Mexico."},
  {"id":562,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Moundville Related Sites","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":5000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The constellation of Moundville-related sites in the Black Warrior and Warrior-Tombigbee drainage — including Snow's Bend, Asphalt Plant, and numerous smaller mound sites — collectively document the regional chiefdom system of which Moundville was the paramount centre. Archaeological survey and excavation at these secondary centres has revealed the mechanisms by which Moundville projected political and religious authority across its territory: the distribution of Moundville-style ceramics, the presence of reduced-scale mound construction replicating the Moundville template, and the flow of prestige goods from the paramount centre to subsidiary sites in a redistributive economy that bound the regional system together. The secondary centres served as administrative nodes connecting the agricultural hinterland to the ceremonial capital, collecting tribute, hosting local ceremonies, and providing a graduated hierarchy of political authority between the farming villages and the paramount site."},
  {"id":563,"n":"Hopewell — Newark Earthworks","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":500,"p":3000,"lang":"various-eastern-woodlands","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Newark Earthworks in present-day Ohio constitute the largest known earthwork complex in the world — a system of geometric enclosures covering an area of approximately 10 square miles, including a perfect circle of 1,054 metres diameter, a perfect octagon of 50 hectares, and multiple other precisely constructed geometric forms connected by parallel-walled avenues. The geometric precision of the Newark earthworks — surveyed repeatedly and confirmed to maintain near-perfect geometric form across the entire complex — implies a sophisticated knowledge of geometry, surveying, and large-scale landscape planning. Ray Hively and Robert Horn's analysis demonstrated that the octagon and circle encode accurate predictions of the 18.6-year lunar cycle — specifically the northernmost moonrise and moonset of the lunar standstill cycle. The Newark Earthworks are now bisected by a golf course, roads, and the Ohio State Fairgrounds, making this extraordinary monument one of the most compromised major archaeological sites in North America. The Octagon remains on the golf course, which the Ohio History Connection is working to recover for public access."},
  {"id":564,"n":"Hopewell — Mound City","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":400,"p":1000,"lang":"various-ohio","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Mound City in present-day Ohio — now Hopewell Culture National Historical Park — is a precisely square earthen enclosure of 4.5 hectares containing 23 burial mounds, one of the most important Hopewell ceremonial sites in the Ohio heartland. The mounds at Mound City contained extraordinarily rich assemblages of grave goods documenting the Hopewell exchange network at its most elaborate: copper cutouts from Lake Superior copper, obsidian from Yellowstone, silver from Ontario, grizzly bear teeth from the Rocky Mountains, and mica from the southern Appalachians — prestige materials assembled from sources across the entire North American continent. The site was catastrophically disturbed during World War I when a military training camp was constructed directly over the earthworks, destroying most of the mound deposits. Subsequent excavation by Henry Shetrone in the 1920s recovered significant material from disturbed contexts, but the irreplaceable stratigraphic information lost during the military occupation represents one of American archaeology's greatest losses."},
  {"id":565,"n":"Hopewell — Seip Earthworks","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":400,"p":500,"lang":"various-ohio","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Seip Earthworks in present-day Ohio is one of the most important Hopewell ritual centres in the Scioto River valley, featuring a large circular and oval enclosure system surrounding burial mounds whose excavation in the early 20th century produced some of the most spectacular Hopewell mortuary assemblages ever recovered. The Seip Mound 1 — the primary burial mound within the enclosure — yielded copper breastplates, mica cutouts, pearl ornaments, and effigy platform pipes of extraordinary quality, now among the prized collections of the Ohio History Connection. The Seip earthworks demonstrate the characteristic Hopewell combination of geometric precision in earthwork construction with lavish mortuary investment — a pattern suggesting that the ritual and cosmological authority embodied in the earthwork geometry was directly connected to the social and spiritual power of the elite individuals interred within the mounds. The site is partially preserved and partially destroyed by agriculture."},
  {"id":566,"n":"Mississippian — Lubbub Creek","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1400,"p":1000,"lang":"muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Lubbub Creek Archaeological Complex in present-day Alabama was a Mississippian mound centre on the Tombigbee River whose systematic excavation in the 1970s and early 1980s — prompted by the planned construction of the Tennessee-Tombigbee Waterway — produced one of the most complete datasets for a small Mississippian community ever assembled, documenting the full range of residential, agricultural, and ceremonial activities at a site below the paramount centre level. The Lubbub Creek data have been extensively used to model Mississippian community organisation, agricultural intensification, and the relationship between small mound centres and their surrounding agricultural hinterlands. The site exemplifies the salvage archaeology principle: the threat of destruction by a federal construction project mobilised resources for excavation that would otherwise not have been available, producing scientific knowledge at the cost of the irreplaceable physical site."},
  {"id":567,"n":"Mississippian — Lake George","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1400,"p":3000,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Lake George Mounds in present-day Mississippi was a major Mississippian centre of the Yazoo Basin — the same extraordinarily productive alluvial zone that supported Winterville and Carson Mounds — featuring a large platform mound complex that served as a regional ceremonial and political focal point within the dense Mississippian settlement of the lower Yazoo River drainage. The Yazoo Basin as a whole constituted one of the most densely Mississippian-settled regions in North America, with mound sites distributed at intervals of a few kilometres across the bottomland, suggesting a landscape that was politically organised and economically integrated at a fine spatial scale. Lake George's position within this landscape identifies it as a significant node in the regional exchange and political hierarchy, though its specific role relative to Winterville and other nearby centres involves questions of temporal priority and political dominance that archaeological evidence has not yet fully resolved."},
  {"id":568,"n":"Mississippian — Pocahontas","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1400,"p":500,"lang":"various-mississippian","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Pocahontas Mounds in present-day Mississippi represents another node in the dense network of Mississippian centres across the Yazoo Basin alluvial plain, documenting the fine-grained political and ceremonial landscape of this extraordinarily productive agricultural zone. The distribution of mound sites like Pocahontas across the Yazoo Basin at regular intervals reflects the spatial logic of the Mississippian chiefdom system — each centre serving a surrounding agricultural territory whose surplus supported the ceremonial and political activities at the mound site, with higher-order centres like Winterville and Lake George integrating multiple lower-order centres into a regional hierarchy. Pocahontas and similar smaller Yazoo Basin sites have been less studied than the major centres, but their collective significance for understanding Mississippian settlement systems is considerable, representing the median experience of Mississippian political life rather than the exceptional scale of paramount centres."},
  {"id":569,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Salmon Ruins","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1080,"e":1280,"p":1000,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"Salmon Ruins near present-day Bloomfield, New Mexico, was a Chacoan outlier great house built in a single massive construction episode around 1088–1094 CE — its precisely dated construction documented by dendrochronology of its primary roof beams — making it one of the most precisely dated major prehistoric structures in North America. The site served as a northern Chacoan administrative centre and ritual facility in the San Juan River valley, built according to the standardised Chacoan great house template with core-and-veneer masonry, kivas integrated into the room block, and a tower kiva. After the decline of the Chacoan system around 1130 CE, Salmon Ruins was reoccupied by Mesa Verde-tradition people who modified and extended the structure, creating an unusually clear stratigraphic record of the Chacoan-to-Mesa Verde cultural transition in a single site. A catastrophic fire in the secondary occupation period killed a significant number of children whose remains were found in the tower kiva, one of the most poignant discoveries in Southwestern archaeology."},
  {"id":570,"n":"Mississippian — Ingomar Mounds","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1000,"e":1350,"p":500,"lang":"various-muskogean","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Ingomar Mounds in present-day Mississippi is a small Mississippian platform mound site that — while modest in scale — was the subject of one of the first systematic archaeological investigations of a Mississippian site in the Yazoo Basin, conducted by Calvin Brown in the early 20th century. The documentation of sites like Ingomar established the basic typology of Mississippian mound architecture in the Lower Mississippi Valley and contributed to the recognition of the Mississippian culture as a coherent archaeological tradition spanning the eastern United States. The Yazoo Basin sites collectively — Winterville, Carson, Lake George, Pocahontas, Ingomar, and dozens of others — represent a settlement density that speaks to the extraordinary agricultural productivity of the Mississippi alluvial plain and the political sophistication of the Mississippian peoples who organised and inhabited this landscape for over 500 years."},
  {"id":571,"n":"Woodland Culture — Havana Tradition","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-200,"e":400,"p":15000,"lang":"various-eastern-woodlands","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Havana Hopewell tradition of the Illinois River valley (~200 BCE–400 CE) was one of the two primary centres of Hopewell ceremonialism — alongside the Ohio Hopewell heartland — and the source of much of the ceramic and exchange material that defined the Hopewell Interaction Sphere across the eastern half of North America. Havana Hopewell sites, particularly Dickson Mounds and the Fulton County mound groups, demonstrate the full elaboration of Hopewell mortuary ceremonialism: geometric earthwork enclosures, log-lined burial chambers, and rich assemblages of exotic goods from across the continent. The Illinois River valley's position at the confluence of multiple major waterways — connecting the Great Lakes to the Gulf of Mexico and the Mississippi to the Ohio — gave Havana Hopewell communities unparalleled access to the long-distance exchange networks that defined the Hopewell world. The Havana tradition's decline around 400 CE, in common with Ohio Hopewell, remains poorly explained — the 'Hopewell Collapse' is one of eastern North American archaeology's enduring questions."},
  {"id":572,"n":"Woodland Culture — Kansas City Hopewell","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":700,"p":5000,"lang":"various-plains","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Kansas City Hopewell tradition of the Missouri and Kansas River confluence region represents the westernmost major expression of Hopewell ceremonialism, documenting the extraordinary geographic reach of the Hopewell Interaction Sphere into the eastern margins of the Great Plains. Kansas City Hopewell communities participated in the exchange of platform pipes, copper objects, and exotic materials with the Ohio and Illinois Hopewell heartlands while developing local adaptations appropriate to the prairie-forest ecotone environment they occupied. The westernmost Hopewell sites provide important evidence for the mechanisms of Hopewell interaction — whether through direct travel of individuals, relay exchange along chains of communities, or periodic aggregation events — and for the relationship between Hopewell ceremonialism and the subsistence economies of communities living in diverse environments at the system's margins. Kansas City Hopewell's survival into the 7th century CE, after Ohio and Illinois Hopewell had declined, suggests regional variability in the Hopewell Collapse that complicates simple monocausal explanations."},
  {"id":573,"n":"Mississippian — Orendorf Site","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1050,"e":1200,"p":3000,"lang":"various-illinois","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Orendorf site in present-day western Illinois was one of the largest early Mississippian communities in the central Illinois River valley, occupied during the critical period of Mississippian emergence and expansion in the 11th and 12th centuries CE. The site's large residential population, defensive palisade, and platform mound document the emergence of Mississippian-pattern communities in the northern periphery of the Cahokia sphere — communities that adopted Mississippian cultural practices while adapting them to the environmental and social conditions of the Illinois valley. Orendorf's excavation has contributed to understanding how Mississippian cultural packages spread northward from the Cahokia heartland, and whether this spread involved migration of people, movement of ideas through trade and intermarriage, or the forcible incorporation of existing communities into Cahokia's political sphere. Evidence of violence at some northern Mississippian sites — including burned villages and skeletal trauma — suggests the expansion was not always peaceful."},
  {"id":574,"n":"Mississippian — Cahokia Woodhenge","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1200,"p":0,"lang":"various-siouan","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Woodhenge solar calendar complex at Cahokia — a series of large red cedar post circles reconstructed through postholes excavated adjacent to Monks Mound — represents one of the most sophisticated astronomical instruments of the pre-Columbian Americas. Warren Wittry's identification and Warren Witty and Robert Hall's subsequent analysis of five successive post circles, each slightly larger than the last, demonstrated that the circles were designed so that a person standing at the centre post could observe the sunrise at the solstices and equinoxes in alignment with specific marker posts on the circle's circumference. The circles' sequential construction documents a refinement process over time, suggesting ongoing astronomical observation and calendar improvement. The summer solstice sunrise as seen from Woodhenge aligns over Monks Mound itself, connecting the solar calendar to the political and religious centre of Cahokia in a single sightline. Woodhenge demonstrates that the Cahokia leadership maintained sophisticated astronomical knowledge as an instrument of political authority — controlling the calendar meant controlling the timing of planting, ceremony, and tribute."},
  {"id":575,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Chetro Ketl","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1020,"e":1120,"p":500,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"theocracy","d":"Chetro Ketl in Chaco Canyon, New Mexico, is the second-largest great house in the canyon — a D-shaped structure of approximately 500 rooms and 16 kivas built over a construction period of about a century, featuring an elevated colonnade (the only known colonnade in Ancestral Puebloan architecture) and an enormous enclosed plaza of 1.5 hectares. The colonnade — a row of masonry columns supporting a raised walkway along the south face of the great house — has no known functional precedent in the Southwest and has been interpreted as evidence of direct Mesoamerican architectural influence, possibly from the colonnaded halls of Tula or Teotihuacan. Chetro Ketl's road connections, water control features, and the elaborate great kiva in its plaza document it as one of the primary ritual and administrative facilities of the Chacoan system. Its abandonment around 1120 CE, slightly before Pueblo Bonito, traces the sequence of Chacoan great house disuse that marked the system's collapse."},
  {"id":576,"n":"Woodland Culture — Marksville","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":-100,"e":400,"p":2000,"lang":"various-lower-mississippi","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Marksville culture of the Lower Mississippi Valley (~100 BCE–400 CE) was the southern expression of Hopewell ceremonialism, documenting the extraordinary southward reach of the Hopewell Interaction Sphere to the Gulf Coast region. Marksville site in present-day Louisiana features geometric earthwork enclosures and burial mounds whose contents — copper objects, platform pipes, and exotic ceramic vessels — are unmistakably Hopewell in character despite the site's location nearly 1,000km from the Ohio heartland. The Marksville tradition provides crucial evidence for understanding how the Hopewell Interaction Sphere maintained coherence across such vast distances: the similarity of ritual practice, mortuary treatment, and prestige object styles across communities separated by hundreds of kilometres implies either frequent long-distance travel, relay exchange networks of remarkable efficiency, or the movement of ritual specialists across the system. Marksville's position at the southern end of the Mississippi River valley also connects the Hopewell world to the earlier Poverty Point tradition of the same region, raising questions about long-term cultural continuity in the Lower Mississippi Valley."},
  {"id":577,"n":"Mississippian — Aztalan Phase II","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1100,"e":1200,"p":300,"lang":"various-great-lakes","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The mature occupation of Aztalan in present-day Wisconsin documents what appears to be an intensification of Mississippian practices at this northernmost outpost — a period in which the community's connections to the Cahokia sphere were maintained or strengthened even as the site remained an isolated enclave in a landscape dominated by local Woodland-tradition peoples. The evidence for human sacrifice and possible ritual cannibalism at Aztalan — disarticulated and processed human bones in specific contextual associations — has generated significant debate about whether these represent Mississippian mortuary practices brought from the south, evidence of conflict with local peoples, or misinterpreted refuse. Aztalan's abandonment around 1200 CE, while Cahokia itself was still at or near its peak, suggests that the northernmost Mississippian communities were vulnerable to local pressures that the metropolitan centre itself was insulated from. The site stands as evidence of both the ambition and the limits of Mississippian cultural expansion."},
  {"id":578,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Lowry Pueblo","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":1090,"e":1300,"p":100,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"village","d":"Lowry Pueblo in present-day southwestern Colorado is a Chacoan outlier great house of moderate size — approximately 40 rooms and eight kivas — whose distinctive feature is the painted great kiva, one of the very few Ancestral Puebloan great kivas to preserve significant surviving wall paintings in situ. The paintings, executed in red, white, and black pigments on plaster, depict geometric and possibly cosmological imagery consistent with the broader Ancestral Puebloan ceremonial tradition. Lowry Pueblo was built in stages between approximately 1090 and 1120 CE, with tree-ring dating establishing a precise construction chronology. Its position as a Chacoan outlier in the northern periphery of the system documents the geographic extent of Chacoan political and religious influence and the mechanisms by which standardised great house architecture was replicated across the Colorado Plateau as a visible marker of participation in the Chacoan system."},
  {"id":579,"n":"Mississippian — Coles Creek Culture","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":700,"e":1200,"p":10000,"lang":"various-lower-mississippi","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Coles Creek culture of the Lower Mississippi Valley (~700–1200 CE) represents the immediate predecessor of the full Mississippian tradition in this region — a period of increasing social complexity, mound construction, and platform mound-centred ceremonialism that set the stage for the Mississippian fluorescence but predates the adoption of certain key Mississippian markers, particularly maize intensification and the full elaboration of Southeastern Ceremonial Complex iconography. Coles Creek sites, distributed across the Mississippi and Red River alluvial plains, document the gradual development of ranked society, redistributive chiefdom economies, and monumental earthwork construction in the Lower Mississippi Valley in the centuries before the Classic Mississippian pattern emerged. The relationship between Coles Creek and the subsequent Mississippian tradition in this region is one of continuity and transformation rather than replacement — the Mississippian tradition of the Lower Valley grew from Coles Creek roots rather than being introduced by population movements from the north."},
  {"id":580,"n":"Ancestral Puebloan — Yellow Jacket","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":900,"e":1300,"p":2500,"lang":"proto-puebloan","gov":"village","d":"Yellow Jacket Pueblo in present-day southwestern Colorado was one of the largest Ancestral Puebloan communities of the Mesa Verde region, with an estimated 1,200–1,900 rooms making it comparable in scale to Pueblo Bonito despite its relative obscurity in popular accounts of the Ancestral Puebloan world. The site features multiple great kivas, a great house, and evidence of a community that aggregated population from surrounding smaller sites during the 13th century — the same population consolidation process documented at many Mesa Verde-tradition sites in the period before the final abandonment of the Four Corners region around 1300 CE. Yellow Jacket's scale suggests it briefly served as a regional population centre during the organisational disruption of the late Pueblo III period, drawing people from a wide surrounding area in a pattern of demographic consolidation that immediately preceded the mass migration southward to the Rio Grande and beyond."},
  {"id":581,"n":"Kingdom of Aksum — Axumite Christianity","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":330,"e":650,"p":200000,"lang":"ge-ez","gov":"theocracy","d":"The Aksumite Christianisation under King Ezana (~330 CE) represents one of the earliest and most consequential adoptions of Christianity by a major state, predating even the Roman Empire's full institutional Christianisation. Frumentius, a Syrian-born Christian shipwrecked on the Red Sea coast, became tutor to the Aksumite royal family and was eventually consecrated as the first Bishop of Aksum by Athanasius of Alexandria — establishing the direct connection between the Ethiopian church and the Alexandrian patriarchate that defines Ethiopian Orthodox Christianity to this day. Aksumite Christian material culture — churches, crosses, illustrated manuscripts, and the architectural tradition of monolithic rock-hewn churches that would reach its apex at Lalibela centuries later — represents a unique African Christian civilisational tradition entirely independent of European influence. The Aksumite church's claim to house the original Ark of the Covenant, in the Chapel of the Tablet in Aksum, is the centrepiece of Ethiopian Christian identity and a claim taken seriously by some scholars including Graham Hancock, whose The Sign and the Seal (1992) investigated it at length."},
  {"id":582,"n":"Nok — Iron Age West Africa","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-1000,"e":300,"p":100000,"lang":"benue-congo-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Nok culture's iron smelting tradition, dating to at least 500 BCE and possibly earlier, places West Africa among the earliest iron-using regions in the world and raises enduring questions about whether African iron metallurgy was independently invented or diffused from North Africa or the Middle East. The evidence for independent invention has strengthened with archaeological dating: some Nok iron-smelting contexts predate the period when technology transfer from the north would have been feasible, and the African smelting techniques differ substantially from Near Eastern and European traditions in ways suggesting separate development. The social implications of early iron production in the Nok context — specialised craft production, controlled access to transformative technology, and the prestige associated with metalworking — may explain aspects of the social hierarchy visible in the Nok terracotta tradition, where some figures wear elaborate jewellery and headdresses suggesting elite status. West African iron technology subsequently spread southward with Bantu expansion, transforming agricultural and material capabilities across sub-Saharan Africa."},
  {"id":583,"n":"Bantu Expansion","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":-3000,"e":1000,"p":500000,"lang":"proto-bantu","gov":"chiefdom","d":"The Bantu Expansion — the spread of Bantu-speaking agricultural peoples from a homeland in the Cameroon-Nigeria borderland across virtually all of sub-Saharan Africa over approximately 4,000 years — is one of the most consequential demographic and cultural events in human history, transforming the linguistic, genetic, and agricultural landscape of an entire continent. From perhaps 3000 BCE, Bantu-speaking farmers spread eastward through the Congo Basin and southward along both the eastern and western coasts of Africa, carrying with them iron technology, cattle herding, yam and later sorghum agriculture, and characteristic pottery traditions. The Bantu Expansion displaced, absorbed, or marginalised the previous inhabitants of eastern and southern Africa — primarily Khoisan-speaking hunter-gatherer peoples — whose genetic signature survives in isolated pockets and in the admixed ancestry of some Bantu populations. The speed and geographic scale of the Bantu Expansion, reconstructed through linguistics, genetics, and archaeology, makes it the largest pre-modern expansion of a human cultural tradition across a single landmass."},
  {"id":584,"n":"Aksumite — Lalibela Rock Churches","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1181,"e":1221,"p":20000,"lang":"ge-ez","gov":"theocracy","d":"The eleven monolithic rock-hewn churches of Lalibela in the Ethiopian Highlands — carved entirely from living volcanic rock during the reign of King Lalibela of the Zagwe dynasty (~1181–1221 CE) — constitute one of the most extraordinary architectural achievements in human history: not buildings constructed from quarried stone, but entire churches excavated from the bedrock, complete with windows, columns, drainage systems, and elaborate decorative carving, while remaining connected at their base to the surrounding rock. The largest, Bete Medhane Alem, is the largest monolithic rock-hewn church in the world, approximately 33 metres long and 11 metres tall. Ethiopian Christian tradition attributes the construction to divine intervention — angels working alongside human labourers at night to complete what the workforce could not achieve by day. Alternative scholars including Graham Hancock have examined the Lalibela churches in the context of possible Templar Knight involvement during the Crusader period. UNESCO designated the churches a World Heritage Site in 1978; they remain active places of worship."},
  {"id":585,"n":"Kingdom of Mali — Sundiata Period","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1235,"e":1400,"p":4000000,"lang":"mande","gov":"empire","d":"The Kingdom of Mali under Sundiata Keita (~1235 CE onwards) and his successors — particularly the legendary Mansa Musa, whose 1324–1325 CE pilgrimage to Mecca with a retinue of 60,000 people and 80 camels carrying gold dust so disrupted the Egyptian and Mediterranean gold markets that it caused inflation lasting a decade — was the wealthiest state in the medieval world, controlling the trans-Saharan gold and salt trade routes that were the financial arteries of the medieval Mediterranean economy. The Malian capital of Niani and the great trading cities of Timbuktu and Djenné were centres of Islamic scholarship whose libraries and universities — particularly the Sankore Madrasah at Timbuktu — attracted scholars from across the Muslim world. The Epic of Sundiata, the foundational oral epic of the Mande peoples, is one of Africa's greatest literary works, transmitted across centuries by professional bards (griots) in a tradition that continues to the present. Mansa Musa remains by most estimates the wealthiest individual in recorded human history in inflation-adjusted terms."},
  {"id":586,"n":"Songhai Empire — Askia Period","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1464,"e":1591,"p":5000000,"lang":"songhay","gov":"empire","d":"The Songhai Empire under Askia Muhammad I (~1493–1528 CE) reached its territorial and cultural apex — controlling the largest territory of any West African empire, stretching 2,000km along the Niger River and encompassing the great cities of Timbuktu, Djenné, and Gao. Askia Muhammad, who seized power from Sunni Ali's dynasty and legitimised his rule through a famous pilgrimage to Mecca in 1497, was a devout Muslim who established Islamic law courts, standardised weights and measures, and patronised Islamic scholarship on a scale that made Timbuktu one of the foremost intellectual centres of the 15th–16th century world. The Sankore University at its height may have enrolled 25,000 students and housed a library of one million manuscripts — more books than Europe's largest libraries of the same period. The Songhai Empire was destroyed by a Moroccan invasion in 1591, whose gunpowder weapons proved decisive against Songhai's larger but conventionally armed forces — one of the clearest early examples of gunpowder technology determining the outcome of sub-Saharan African history."},
  {"id":588,"n":"Great Zimbabwe — Mutapa State","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1420,"e":1760,"p":100000,"lang":"shona-karanga","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Mutapa State (Mwenemutapa, ~1420–1760 CE) was the political successor to the Great Zimbabwe kingdom, relocating the centre of power northward to the Zambezi Valley as the southern gold trade routes shifted and as Great Zimbabwe's local resources became depleted. The Mutapa rulers maintained the Great Zimbabwe tradition of divine kingship and gold-based wealth while developing new trade relationships — first with the Swahili coast and subsequently, fatally, with the Portuguese who arrived in the Indian Ocean in 1498. Portuguese attempts to control the Mutapa's gold trade through military pressure and diplomatic manipulation progressively undermined the state's political independence throughout the 16th and 17th centuries. A Portuguese-backed succession dispute in 1629 installed a puppet ruler who ceded nominal sovereignty, though effective Mutapa political authority persisted in reduced form until the late 17th century. The Mutapa State represents the final phase of the Great Zimbabwe civilisational tradition before its absorption into the colonial economy of the Indian Ocean world."},
  {"id":589,"n":"Kuba Kingdom","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1625,"e":1900,"p":150000,"lang":"kuba-bantu","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Kuba Kingdom of the Kasai region in present-day Democratic Republic of Congo (~1625–1900 CE) was renowned across central Africa for the extraordinary quality of its textile art — raffia cloth cut-pile velvets, geometric patterned prestige textiles, and embroidered garments of dazzling complexity that were among the most technically sophisticated textiles produced anywhere in the pre-industrial world. The Kuba political system was notable for its degree of constitutional complexity: a king (nyim) whose power was substantially checked by councils of nobles and age-grade associations, creating a more balanced power structure than the absolute monarchies of many neighbouring states. Kuba oral tradition credits the culture hero Shyaam aMbul aNgoong with introducing embroidery, new crops, and a new political order from outside — some scholars have speculated about connections to the broader Atlantic world through trade networks. Kuba art, particularly the carved wooden prestige objects and ndop royal portrait statues, was among the first African art to be seriously studied by Western artists and directly influenced Picasso and the Cubist movement."},
  {"id":590,"n":"Luba Empire","r":"Africa","t":"confirmed","s":1585,"e":1889,"p":2000000,"lang":"luba-bantu","gov":"empire","d":"The Luba Empire (~1585–1889 CE) of the central Congo region in present-day southeastern DRC was a sophisticated state whose distinctive contribution to African political history was a system of memory devices — the lukasa memory board and the associated mbudye memory specialists — that encoded dynastic history, territorial geography, and political knowledge in material objects read by trained specialists, functioning as an alternative to writing for the storage and transmission of complex political information. Luba royal art — particularly the seated female figures that served as supports for headrests and other prestige objects — is among the most celebrated in African art history for its formal elegance and the sophistication with which it encoded cosmological and political meaning. The Luba system of sacred kingship, in which the king's body was a vessel for divine power that sustained the kingdom's prosperity, was the model that spread across a wide arc of central African states through the diaspora of Luba royals establishing new kingdoms in neighbouring territories."},
  {"id":591,"n":"Mississippian — Kolomoki","r":"Americas","t":"confirmed","s":350,"e":750,"p":2000,"lang":"muskogean-proto","gov":"chiefdom","d":"Kolomoki Mounds in present-day Georgia is one of the oldest and largest platform mound complexes in the American Southeast — built and occupied primarily during the Swift Creek and Weeden Island cultural periods (~350–750 CE), several centuries before the full Mississippian tradition emerged. At its peak, Kolomoki may have been the largest site in the entire eastern United States, with a population of 2,000 or more and a mound complex including the seventh-largest platform mound in North America. The site's early date makes it a crucial link in the developmental sequence from Hopewell to Mississippian, demonstrating the continuity of mound-building and ceremonial traditions in the Southeast across a period of apparent cultural transition. The presence at Kolomoki of Swift Creek and Weeden Island ceramic traditions alongside evidence of long-distance exchange documents the persistence of Hopewell-derived ceremonial practices into the late Woodland period in the deep Southeast, bridging the gap between Hopewell and Mississippian."},
  {"id":592,"n":"Anatolian Neolithic — Göbekli Tepe Predecessors","r":"Middle East","t":"debated","s":-12000,"e":-9600,"p":1000,"lang":"unknown-epipaleolithic","gov":"band","d":"The cultural tradition that produced Göbekli Tepe did not emerge from nothing — the Epipalaeolithic and Pre-Pottery Neolithic A cultures of the Fertile Crescent from which the Göbekli builders emerged had their own long development of symbolic behaviour, communal gathering, and increasingly complex social organisation stretching back to at least 12,000 BCE. Sites like Körtik Tepe, Nevalı Çori, and Jerf el Ahmar document the gradual intensification of sedentism, symbolic art, and communal architecture in the pre-Göbekli Fertile Crescent, providing the cultural substrate from which the extraordinary florescence at Göbekli Tepe and the Taş Tepeler network grew. The question of what specifically triggered the explosive complexity of Göbekli Tepe — whether a sudden social reorganisation, a specific environmental stress, a religious innovation, or the arrival of a distinct population with different cultural capacities — remains at the heart of debates about the Neolithic transition. Alternative scholars including Andrew Collins and Graham Hancock argue that the continuity model is insufficient to explain Göbekli Tepe's sophistication and propose a more ancient cultural ancestry."},
  {"id":593,"n":"Cucuteni-Trypillia — Mega-Site Network","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-4100,"e":-3500,"p":15000,"lang":"unknown-european-farmer","gov":"egalitarian-town","d":"The Cucuteni-Trypillia mega-sites of the Ukrainian-Moldovan-Romanian borderland reached their maximum extent and complexity between approximately 4100–3500 BCE, with sites like Talianky covering up to 450 hectares and possibly housing 15,000–20,000 people — a population comparable to contemporary Uruk in Mesopotamia but organised on entirely different principles, with no evidence of central authority, temples, or elite quarters. The mega-sites appear to have been organised as concentric rings of houses, each ring containing hundreds of identical or near-identical structures suggesting a deliberate egalitarian spatial programme. The regular burning and rebuilding of the entire settlement every 60–80 years — with the new settlement built on the same plan adjacent to or overlapping the ash and debris of the previous — represents a cultural practice with no known parallel anywhere in the world. Whether the burning was ritual, practical, demographic, or epidemiological in motivation remains undetermined. The Trypillia mega-sites may represent the largest human settlements of the 4th millennium BCE — a fact that challenges Mesopotamia-centric accounts of early urbanism."},
  {"id":594,"n":"Linear A — Minoan Administrative System","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-1800,"e":-1450,"p":50000,"lang":"minoan-linear-a","gov":"palace-state","d":"The Linear A administrative system of Minoan Crete — the bureaucratic infrastructure of the palace economies centred on Knossos, Phaistos, Malia, and Zakros — represents one of the earliest known examples of literacy being used primarily as an instrument of economic administration rather than royal propaganda or religious text, a pattern that also characterises the earliest Mesopotamian cuneiform and Egyptian hieratic writing. The Linear A tablets, found primarily in palace contexts, record transactions of agricultural commodities — olive oil, grain, wine, figs, wool — using a numerical and metrological system partially but not fully reconstructable from the related Linear B. The palace economy operated as a redistributive system: agricultural surplus flowed into the palace as taxation or tribute and was redistributed as rations, festival goods, and craft materials. The destruction of the palace archives in the fires that ended each palace period means we have only a fraction of the original Linear A corpus, making decipherment statistically challenging in addition to linguistically so."},
  {"id":595,"n":"Mycenaean — Palace of Nestor","r":"Europe","t":"confirmed","s":-1600,"e":-1180,"p":10000,"lang":"mycenaean-greek","gov":"palace-state","d":"The Palace of Nestor at Pylos in present-day southwestern Greece is the best-preserved Mycenaean palace on the Greek mainland and the site that yielded the largest archive of Linear B tablets in Greece — approximately 1,000 tablets recording the palace's administrative activities in the final months before its destruction around 1180 BCE. The Linear B archive from Pylos, deciphered by Michael Ventris in 1952, provides the most detailed picture of Mycenaean palace economy available: rosters of rowers being mustered, allocations of bronze for spearheads, rations for women textile workers, land tenure records, and — hauntingly — preparations for coastal defence against an unnamed threat in what appear to be the palace's final administrative records before destruction by fire. The Homeric tradition identifies Pylos as the kingdom of the wise king Nestor, one of the Greek heroes at Troy, and the palace's evident sophistication and the wealth of its Linear B archive give some historical plausibility to the Homeric tradition."},
  {"id":596,"n":"Ugarit — Bronze Age Cosmopolitan City","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-2000,"e":-1185,"p":8000,"lang":"ugaritic","gov":"city-state","d":"Ugarit on the Syrian coast was the most cosmopolitan city of the Late Bronze Age international system — a port city whose archives document diplomatic correspondence in Akkadian with Egypt, Hatti, Cyprus, and the Aegean; commercial transactions in multiple languages; and literature in the Ugaritic language itself written in an alphabetic cuneiform script that is one of the direct ancestors of the Phoenician and therefore all subsequent alphabets. The Ugaritic mythological texts — the Baal Cycle, the Epic of Aqhat, the Legend of Keret — are among the oldest examples of Canaanite literature and provide essential background for understanding the development of Hebrew biblical literature, with clear parallels in narrative themes, poetic formulae, and divine epithets between Ugaritic and biblical texts. Ugarit was destroyed around 1185 BCE by the Sea Peoples in what appears to have been a sudden and complete catastrophe — the final Ugaritic letters, found in a kiln still awaiting firing, describe a terrifying enemy attack and desperate requests for military aid that never arrived."},
  {"id":597,"n":"Elam / Proto-Elamite Civilisation","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-3200,"e":-539,"p":200000,"lang":"elamite","gov":"empire","d":"The Elamite civilisation of southwestern Iran (~3200–539 BCE) was one of the oldest and most persistent civilisations of the ancient Near East — a contemporary and frequent rival of Sumer and Akkad, whose capital Susa was among the earliest urban centres in the world and whose Proto-Elamite script (~3200–2900 BCE) is one of the earliest writing systems known, predating or contemporaneous with proto-cuneiform but still undeciphered. The Elamites sacked Ur and captured the famous Law Code of Hammurabi (which is why it was found at Susa rather than Babylon). At the height of Elamite power under the Middle Elamite period (~1500–1100 BCE), the kingdom rivalled Assyria and Babylonia as a major Near Eastern power. Elam was eventually absorbed into the Achaemenid Persian Empire under Cyrus the Great in 539 BCE, but Elamite administrative traditions, the Elamite language (used in official Achaemenid inscriptions alongside Old Persian and Akkadian), and Elamite cultural influences profoundly shaped Persian civilisation."},
  {"id":598,"n":"Mittani Kingdom","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-1500,"e":-1270,"p":300000,"lang":"hurrian","gov":"empire","d":"The Mittani Kingdom (~1500–1270 BCE) of northern Syria and Mesopotamia was a major Bronze Age power whose ruling elite spoke Indo-Aryan — a language closely related to Vedic Sanskrit — while the general population spoke Hurrian, creating one of the most linguistically distinctive ancient Near Eastern states. Mittani horse-training documents written in Hurrian include technical terminology in Indo-Aryan (including names for horse gaits that are cognate with Sanskrit terms), providing crucial linguistic evidence for the eastward spread of Indo-European speakers into the Near East during the second millennium BCE. The Mittani kingdom played a critical diplomatic role in the Late Bronze Age international system, maintaining formal treaty relationships with Egypt and competing with the Hittites for Syrian hegemony. Mittani's diplomatic correspondence in the Amarna Letters documents the sophisticated protocol of Bronze Age international relations — royal marriages, gift exchanges, and carefully calibrated language of brotherhood between great kings. The kingdom was destroyed by a combination of Hittite military pressure and Assyrian expansion around 1270 BCE."},
  {"id":599,"n":"Kassite Babylonia","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-1595,"e":-1155,"p":500000,"lang":"kassite-akkadian","gov":"empire","d":"The Kassite dynasty of Babylonia (~1595–1155 BCE) — a people of uncertain origin who seized control of Babylon following the Hittite raid that ended the Old Babylonian period — ruled Mesopotamia for over 400 years, making it the longest-ruling dynasty in Babylonian history. The Kassites adopted Babylonian culture, language, and religion with remarkable completeness, becoming the custodians of the Mesopotamian literary and scholarly tradition and the patrons under whose rule many foundational Babylonian literary and scientific texts reached their canonical forms, including the Gilgamesh epic's standard version. Kassite Babylonia was a major player in the Late Bronze Age international system, documented extensively in the Amarna Letters exchanging diplomatic correspondence with Egypt, Assyria, and the Mittani. The Kassites introduced the kudurru — carved stone boundary markers documenting land grants, whose complex iconographic programmes document Babylonian religious art at a moment of considerable elaboration. Their dynasty ended when the Elamites raided Babylon and carried off the statue of Marduk."},
  {"id":600,"n":"Civilisation 600 — Milestone Entry","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-3500,"e":-2900,"p":50000,"lang":"proto-cuneiform","gov":"city-state","d":"The Early Dynastic period city-states of southern Mesopotamia (~3500–2900 BCE) represent the transition from the Uruk proto-urban phase to the full elaboration of Sumerian civilisation — the period in which writing developed from proto-cuneiform administrative notation toward a fully expressive system capable of recording literature, law, and mythology; in which cylinder seals became the primary medium of personal and institutional identification; and in which the distinctive Sumerian city-state system — each city ruled by a patron deity through a human king or priest-king — crystallised as the political template that would define Mesopotamian civilisation for two millennia. Cities including Ur, Eridu, Nippur, Lagash, Girsu, Umma, and Shuruppak developed their characteristic monumental architecture — the ziggurat temple platform — and the economic institutions of temple and palace that organised Sumerian society. The earliest known author in human history — Enheduanna, high priestess of the moon god Nanna at Ur and daughter of Sargon of Akkad (~2285–2250 BCE) — composed hymns in this tradition that established literary conventions still recognisable in subsequent millennia."},
  {"id":601,"n":"Phoenician — Tyre and Sidon","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-1200,"e":-64,"p":200000,"lang":"phoenician","gov":"city-state","d":"The Phoenician city-states of Tyre and Sidon on the Lebanese coast (~1200–64 BCE) were the great maritime trading civilisation of the Iron Age Mediterranean — the people who, through their trading diaspora stretching from Cyprus to Spain, spread the Phoenician alphabetic writing system that became the ancestor of virtually every alphabet in use today. Phoenician craftsmen worked for Solomon's Temple in Jerusalem; Phoenician purple dye (from Murex sea snails) was the most expensive textile colourant in the ancient world, costing more per gram than gold; and Phoenician merchant ships navigated the entire Mediterranean and Atlantic coasts. The Phoenician colony of Carthage, founded by Tyre around 814 BCE, became one of the great powers of the ancient Mediterranean. Herodotus records a Phoenician circumnavigation of Africa commissioned by the Egyptian pharaoh Necho II around 600 BCE — sailing from the Red Sea southward and returning through the Pillars of Hercules — a feat not confirmed by other sources but whose navigational plausibility modern scholars increasingly accept."},
  {"id":602,"n":"Neo-Assyrian Empire","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-911,"e":-609,"p":5000000,"lang":"assyrian-akkadian","gov":"empire","d":"The Neo-Assyrian Empire (~911–609 BCE) was the first true world empire in history — a military and administrative system that at its height controlled territory from Egypt and the Levant to Persia and Anatolia, sustaining dominance over this vast area through a combination of extreme military violence (mass deportations, deliberate psychological terror, and the destruction of cities), sophisticated provincial administration, and a professional standing army equipped with iron weapons, siege engines, and cavalry. Assyrian royal inscriptions document military campaigns with meticulous pride in destruction; the Assyrian kings competed to record the numbers of enemies killed, cities razed, and populations deported. The library of Ashurbanipal at Nineveh — over 30,000 clay tablet fragments — was the first systematically collected library in history, preserving the Gilgamesh epic, astronomical observations, medical texts, and religious literature that would otherwise have been lost. The empire's sudden collapse in 609 BCE, when a Babylonian-Median coalition destroyed Nineveh, shocked the ancient world — the apparent invincibility of Assyria had been the defining geopolitical fact of the Near East for three centuries."},
  {"id":604,"n":"Palmyrene Empire","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":260,"e":273,"p":1000000,"lang":"palmyrene-aramaic","gov":"empire","d":"The Palmyrene Empire (~260–273 CE) was one of history's most remarkable short-lived states — an empire carved from the Roman world by the regent Zenobia, ruling on behalf of her son Vaballathus after the assassination of her husband Odaenathus, that at its brief peak controlled Egypt, the Levant, Anatolia, and much of the Roman East. Zenobia — described by Roman sources as beautiful, scholarly, and militarily brilliant — declared independence from Rome, adopted the title Queen of Queens, and styled her court on a synthesis of Roman, Greek, and Egyptian traditions, corresponding with the philosopher Cassius Longinus and presenting herself as a descendant of Cleopatra. The Emperor Aurelian defeated Zenobia's forces in 272 CE and captured Palmyra; Zenobia herself was taken to Rome, where according to some sources she lived out her days in comfortable exile. Palmyra, her capital in the Syrian desert, was one of antiquity's most magnificent cities — its colonnaded street, temples, and funerary towers documented a unique synthesis of Roman and Near Eastern architectural traditions largely destroyed by ISIS in 2015."},
  {"id":605,"n":"Kingdom of Pontus","r":"Middle East","t":"confirmed","s":-302,"e":-64,"p":1000000,"lang":"greek-iranian","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Kingdom of Pontus (~302–64 BCE) on the southern coast of the Black Sea was a Hellenistic state founded by an Iranian dynasty that embraced Greek culture while maintaining connections to Persian royal traditions, producing in Mithridates VI Eupator one of Rome's most formidable and persistent opponents. Mithridates VI — known as Mithridates the Great — fought three wars against Rome across 25 years (~88–63 BCE), at one point controlling most of the Black Sea coast, Anatolia, and Greece, and allegedly building immunity to poisons by consuming small doses daily (giving rise to the word 'mithridate' for an antidote). His pharmacological interests — documented in ancient sources as extensive practical experimentation — made him a foundational figure in the history of toxicology. The Kingdom of Pontus represents the complex cultural synthesis of the Hellenistic world: Greek language and artistic traditions grafted onto Iranian royal ideology in a Black Sea maritime environment, producing a distinctive civilisational hybrid that challenged Rome's eastern expansion for a generation."},
  {"id":606,"n":"Bactrian / Greco-Bactrian Kingdom","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":-256,"e":-125,"p":1000000,"lang":"greek-bactrian","gov":"monarchy","d":"The Greco-Bactrian Kingdom (~256–125 BCE) of present-day Afghanistan and Central Asia was the easternmost expression of Hellenistic civilisation — a Greek state founded by Diodotus I, a governor of Alexander's eastern territories who declared independence from the Seleucid Empire, maintaining Greek language, art, and political forms at the far eastern end of the Greek cultural world for over a century. Greco-Bactrian coinage is among the finest portrait coinage of the ancient world, with individual kings depicted with a psychological realism exceeding anything produced in the contemporary Hellenistic west. The kingdom's successor state, the Indo-Greek Kingdom, extended Greek rule into northwestern India, producing the remarkable Milindapanha — a philosophical dialogue between the Indo-Greek king Menander I and the Buddhist monk Nagasena that represents a genuine intellectual encounter between Greek philosophical tradition and Buddhist thought. Greco-Bactrian and Indo-Greek artistic traditions were a primary conduit through which Greek artistic conventions entered Buddhist art, giving rise to the Gandharan school in which the Buddha is first depicted in human form with distinctly Greek artistic characteristics."},
  {"id":608,"n":"Sogdian Letter Network","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":300,"e":800,"p":50000,"lang":"sogdian","gov":"merchant-diaspora","d":"The Sogdian merchant diaspora along the Silk Road — documented through the remarkable Ancient Sogdian Letters found near Dunhuang in 1907, dating to approximately 313 CE and representing the earliest surviving merchant correspondence from the Silk Road — maintained a commercial and cultural network of extraordinary geographic reach and sophistication. The letters, written on paper and apparently lost when the messenger carrying them was abandoned in the desert, discuss commercial transactions, family matters, political events (including references to a Xiongnu attack on Luoyang in 311 CE — the earliest known reference to this historically significant event), and the difficulties of long-distance communication. The Sogdian network operated through a diaspora model — Sogdian merchants established trading colonies at regular intervals along the Silk Road from Samarkand to the Chinese capital, maintaining cultural identity across generations while adapting to local conditions. Their script was adopted by the Uyghurs, whose script was adopted by the Mongols, whose script was adopted by the Manchus — making the Sogdian writing tradition one of the most consequential in Asian history."},
  {"id":609,"n":"Pala Empire","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":750,"e":1174,"p":5000000,"lang":"bengali-proto","gov":"empire","d":"The Pala Empire (~750–1174 CE) of Bengal and Bihar was the last great Buddhist dynasty of India — a powerful state that patronised the final flourishing of Indian Buddhist culture and the monastic university tradition at Nalanda and Vikramashila before the Muslim conquest of northern India ended Buddhism as a significant Indian religious force. The Nalanda university under Pala patronage was arguably the greatest educational institution of the ancient world, housing up to 10,000 students and 2,000 scholars from across Asia in a vast complex of monasteries, lecture halls, and libraries; the Chinese monk Xuanzang's 7th-century account describes its scale and intellectual vitality in detail. The Pala maritime connections with the Srivijaya Empire of Sumatra facilitated the spread of Mahayana Buddhism into Southeast Asia and subsequently to Japan via China. Pala bronzes — the classical medium of late Indian Buddhist sculpture — achieved a technical and aesthetic refinement that influenced Buddhist artistic traditions across Southeast Asia, Tibet, and East Asia."},
  {"id":610,"n":"Chola Empire — Maritime Phase","r":"Asia","t":"confirmed","s":985,"e":1279,"p":8000000,"lang":"tamil","gov":"empire","d":"The Chola Empire of southern India under Rajaraja I and Rajendra I (~985–1279 CE) achieved the most ambitious maritime military projection in medieval Asian history — naval expeditions that raided the Srivijaya Empire in Sumatra, established diplomatic relations with China, and briefly controlled the Strait of Malacca, projecting Tamil Hindu culture across the Bay of Bengal. The Chola navy, operating thousands of kilometres from its base in Tamil Nadu, represented an unprecedented southern Indian military reach into Southeast Asia. On land, the Chola patronised an extraordinary florescence of Tamil literature, bronze casting, and temple architecture — the Brihadeeswarar Temple at Thanjavur, built by Rajaraja I and completed in 1010 CE, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the great achievements of Indian architectural history, with a vimana tower of 66 metres built entirely of granite. Chola bronze casting — particularly the Nataraja (Shiva as Lord of Dance) figure — achieved an artistic synthesis of cosmic symbolism and technical perfection that has become globally recognised as one of humanity's supreme sculptural achievements."},
  {"id":612,"n":"Zhou Dynasty (Western)","s":-1046,"e":-771,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[34.3,108.9],"d":"The Western Zhou Dynasty succeeded the Shang and governed China from its capital near modern Xi'an, establishing a feudal system of royal domains and vassal states. This era produced foundational texts of Chinese philosophy including early portions of the Book of Songs and the Classic of Documents, which defined ritual propriety and the Mandate of Heaven — the concept that rulers govern legitimately only while virtuous. The Western Zhou period ended in 771 BCE when nomadic Quanrong peoples sacked the capital, forcing the court east to Luoyi and inaugurating the Eastern Zhou period.","v":0},
  {"id":613,"n":"Yayoi Culture","s":-300,"e":300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[33.5,130.5],"d":"The Yayoi culture emerged in the Japanese archipelago from approximately 300 BCE as wet rice agriculture, bronze and iron metallurgy, and weaving techniques arrived from the Korean peninsula and continental Asia. Yayoi communities rapidly replaced or absorbed the preceding Jōmon hunter-gatherer populations across Kyushu and the main islands, establishing nucleated farming villages with granary structures and defended settlements. Genetic and skeletal evidence indicates the Yayoi represented a significant migration event, and Yayoi people are considered the primary ancestral population of most modern Japanese. The period culminated in the emergence of chiefdom confederacies that evolved into the Yamato state.","v":0},
  {"id":614,"n":"Gaya Confederacy","s":42,"e":562,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[35.2,128.1],"d":"The Gaya Confederacy was a loose alliance of polities occupying the southern coastal lowlands of the Korean peninsula between the Baekje and Silla kingdoms. Gaya city-states were renowned producers and exporters of iron — controlling ore-rich deposits that supplied markets as far as Japan and the Chinese commanderies — and their warrior aristocracies were buried in elaborate tumuli containing iron armour, weapons, and distinctive ceramic vessels. Unlike the Three Kingdoms of Korea, Gaya never unified under a single monarchy, and the confederacy was progressively absorbed by Silla during the fifth and sixth centuries, with the last member state falling in 562 CE.","v":0},
  {"id":615,"n":"Baekje Kingdom","s":-18,"e":660,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[36.5,127.1],"d":"Baekje was one of the Three Kingdoms of Korea, occupying the southwestern peninsula and at its height controlling maritime trade routes across the Yellow Sea. The kingdom served as a crucial cultural bridge between China and Japan, transmitting Buddhism, Chinese writing, Confucian statecraft, and skilled artisans — including temple architects, tile-makers, and painters — to the Yamato court in Japan during the fifth and sixth centuries. Baekje maintained a sophisticated bureaucratic state with a Confucian-educated aristocracy and produced distinctive gold filigree jewellery and Buddhist sculpture. The kingdom was destroyed by a Tang-Silla alliance in 660 CE, with its last king captured and its population absorbed.","v":0},
  {"id":616,"n":"Donghu Confederation","s":-700,"e":-209,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[43,119],"d":"The Donghu, meaning 'Eastern Barbarians' in Chinese sources, were a confederation of nomadic and semi-nomadic pastoral peoples occupying the steppe and forest-steppe zones east of the Xiongnu homeland across modern Inner Mongolia and Manchuria. They were contemporaries and rivals of the early Xiongnu and engaged in periodic warfare and tributary relationships with the Chinese Yan and Zhao states along the northern frontier. The Donghu confederacy was shattered around 209 BCE by Xiongnu Chanyu Modu in a decisive military campaign, after which surviving groups splintered into the Wuhuan and Xianbei peoples — the latter of whom would eventually conquer northern China and establish multiple dynasties.","v":0},
  {"id":618,"n":"Rouran Khaganate","s":330,"e":555,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[46,106],"d":"The Rouran Khaganate was a major nomadic empire of the Mongolian steppe that rose to power after the fragmentation of the Xianbei confederacy, dominating Central Asia from the fourth to the mid-sixth century. The Rouran are credited with introducing the title 'khagan' — supreme ruler of nomadic peoples — a political concept adopted by every subsequent steppe empire including the Turks, Mongols, and Avars. They were eventually destroyed by a rebellion of Turkic iron-worker subjects, the Göktürks, who overthrew the Rouran in campaigns around 552–555 CE. The defeated Rouran are frequently proposed as identical to or ancestral to the Avars who subsequently appeared in the European steppe, though this identification remains actively debated.","v":0},
  {"id":620,"n":"Yenisei Kirghiz","s":600,"e":1200,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[51,90],"d":"The Yenisei Kirghiz were a pastoral-nomadic and partly sedentary people of the upper Yenisei River basin in what is now southern Siberia, who rose to brief but remarkable steppe dominance in the ninth century. In 840 CE they destroyed the powerful Uyghur Khaganate in a single decisive campaign, scattering Uyghur populations across Central Asia and briefly becoming the paramount power of the Mongolian steppe — a period some scholars call the Kirghiz Great Power era. Their political influence receded rapidly, but they preserved a distinctive runic inscription tradition related to but distinct from Göktürk script, and their descendants are considered ancestral to the modern Kyrgyz people of Central Asia.","v":0},
  {"id":621,"n":"Kingdom of Mannea","s":-850,"e":-616,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[37,46.5],"d":"Mannea was an ancient kingdom occupying the mountainous region south of Lake Urmia in what is now northwestern Iran, geographically and politically positioned between the competing empires of Assyria, Urartu, and the emerging Median confederacy. Mannean rulers navigated this dangerous geopolitical space through shifting alliances, and Assyrian royal annals record repeated punitive campaigns and tribute-taking expeditions into Mannean territory. The kingdom produced skilled horsemen and metalworkers who participated in the broader Iranian Iron Age cultural zone, and Mannean horse tribute was particularly prized by the Assyrian cavalry. The kingdom was absorbed by the Median Empire around 616 BCE and subsequently vanished from the historical record.","v":0},
  {"id":622,"n":"Land of Magan","s":-3000,"e":-1500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[23.5,58],"d":"Magan was an ancient land mentioned extensively in Sumerian and Akkadian texts as a primary source of copper, diorite stone, and other prestige materials, identified by modern scholars with the Oman Peninsula and the UAE. The Magan copper trade underpinned Mesopotamian bronze production for centuries, with ore sources at sites like Wadi Khalid supplying metal throughout the Gulf network. Archaeological sites including Bat, Al-Ain, and the Hafit tomb culture attest to a sophisticated Bronze Age society capable of organising large-scale resource extraction and maritime trade. Magan traded directly with the Indus Valley civilisation and Dilmun, forming a three-node exchange system that was one of the world's earliest long-distance maritime trade networks.","v":0},
  {"id":623,"n":"Qataban","s":-400,"e":200,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[14.5,45.5],"d":"Qataban was one of the ancient South Arabian kingdoms of the Hadramawt region in modern Yemen, a participant in the lucrative frankincense and myrrh trade that connected the Arabian Peninsula to Egypt, the Levant, and the Mediterranean world. The Qatabanians built their capital at Timna and maintained elaborate irrigation systems in the Wadi Beihan to support agriculture in an otherwise arid environment. Their monumental inscriptions in the Old South Arabian script record kings, rituals, trade regulations, and building dedications, providing a rich documentary record of a society organised around temple institutions and tribal confederacies. The kingdom was absorbed into the expanding Himyarite state around the second century CE.","v":0},
  {"id":624,"n":"Hadramaut Kingdom","s":-800,"e":300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[15.5,49],"d":"The ancient Hadramaut kingdom occupied the eastern portion of what is now Yemen, centred on the Wadi Hadramawt — a fertile valley carved through the vast Rub' al Khali desert that served as the primary inland route for the South Arabian incense trade. The Hadrami capital of Shabwa was a major entrepôt where camel caravans loaded with frankincense converged before the long journey north to Petra and Mediterranean markets. Hadramaut maintained a distinct cultural identity from its western neighbours Saba and Qataban, with its own ruling dynasty and monumental architecture, and its seafarers participated in the Indian Ocean trade network. The ancient kingdom's legacy persists in the modern Yemeni region of Hadhramaut, whose diaspora spread commercial networks across the Indian Ocean from East Africa to Southeast Asia.","v":0},
  {"id":625,"n":"Arzawa","s":-1650,"e":-1180,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","loc":[38,28.5],"d":"Arzawa was a powerful Bronze Age Anatolian kingdom or confederation of kingdoms occupying western Anatolia, known primarily through Hittite royal archives at Hattusa and Egyptian diplomatic correspondence. At its height Arzawa was considered a peer power by both the Hittites and Egyptians — Pharaoh Amenhotep III wrote to the Arzawan king seeking a princess for his harem, using Arzawan as the diplomatic language, suggesting it was a prestige tongue of Bronze Age western Anatolia. The kingdom was destroyed in a major Hittite campaign under Mursili II around 1300 BCE, its population deported and its territories incorporated into the Hittite provincial system. Some scholars propose connections between Arzawa and the later Lydian and Luwian cultural zones of western Anatolia.","v":0},
  {"id":626,"n":"Hattian Culture","s":-2500,"e":-1700,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[40,34.6],"d":"The Hattians were the non-Indo-European pre-Hittite inhabitants of central Anatolia, occupying the region around modern Çorum and Boğazkale before the arrival of the Indo-European Hittite-speaking peoples. Despite being displaced as the political ruling class, Hattian religious texts, myths, rituals, and divine names were absorbed wholesale into Hittite state religion — many Hittite deities, festivals, and priestly functions preserved in Hattusa's archives are fundamentally Hattian in origin. The Hattian language, entirely unrelated to any known language family, survives only in these ritual contexts because it was believed to be the language the gods understood. Their influence on Anatolian and Aegean religious iconography, including certain storm god traditions, may extend far beyond their political disappearance.","v":0},
  {"id":627,"n":"Sea Peoples Network","s":-1200,"e":-1100,"t":"debated","cont":"EU","loc":[36,28],"d":"The Sea Peoples are a loose designation applied to groups of migrants and raiders who appear in Egyptian records during the reigns of Merneptah and Ramesses III, credited with contributing to the Bronze Age Collapse — the catastrophic disintegration of palace economies across the Eastern Mediterranean around 1200 BCE. Egyptian inscriptions at Medinet Habu depict massive combined land-and-sea assaults and name constituent groups including the Peleset, Tjeker, Shekelesh, Denyen, and Weshesh, some of whom scholars identify with the Philistines, Sicilians, Sardinians, and Danaans. Whether the Sea Peoples were a coordinated migration, a loose wave of refugees displaced by prior collapses, or an opportunistic coalition exploiting existing chaos remains hotly debated. Some researchers, including Eric Cline, argue the collapse was multicausal and the Sea Peoples were a symptom rather than the primary cause.","v":0},
  {"id":628,"n":"Pandya Kingdom","s":-600,"e":1345,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[9.5,78.1],"d":"The Pandya Kingdom was one of the three ancient Tamil kingdoms of South India alongside the Chera and Chola dynasties, ruling from their capital Madurai in the deep south of the peninsula for nearly two millennia in various forms. The Pandyas are among the earliest Tamil rulers attested in ancient Greek and Roman sources — Megasthenes and later Pliny the Elder describe a southern Indian kingdom sending embassies to the courts of Alexander and Augustus — and they controlled pearl fisheries in the Gulf of Mannar prized throughout the ancient world. The kingdom is celebrated in the Sangam literary tradition as a patron of Tamil poetry, with the legendary first and second Sangam academies attributed to Pandyan royal patronage. The dynasty reached its greatest territorial extent under Maravarman Sundara Pandya in the thirteenth century before Sultanate invasions ended their dominance.","v":0},
  {"id":629,"n":"Satavahana Empire","s":-230,"e":220,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[17,79.5],"d":"The Satavahana dynasty ruled the Deccan plateau of central India for roughly four centuries, representing one of the most important post-Mauryan powers and a critical link in maritime and overland trade connecting Rome, Arabia, and Southeast Asia. Their ports on the western coast of India participated directly in the Roman-Indian spice and luxury goods trade documented in the Periplus of the Erythraean Sea, and Satavahana lead coins have been found in Roman Egypt. The dynasty was notable for its patronage of Buddhism, funding major stupa complexes at Sanchi, Amaravati, and Nagarjunakonda, and for using Prakrit rather than Sanskrit as its administrative language. The Satavahanas eventually fragmented under pressure from the Shakas, Ikshvakus, and other successor states.","v":0},
  {"id":630,"n":"Kalinga","s":-260,"e":550,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[20.3,85.8],"d":"Kalinga was a powerful ancient kingdom occupying the coastal region of what is now Odisha in eastern India, best known as the site of the Kalinga War of 261 BCE in which Ashoka's Mauryan forces defeated the Kalingan army at enormous human cost — a battle that, according to Ashokan edicts, caused the emperor such remorse that he converted to Buddhism and renounced further conquest. The human toll recorded in Ashoka's own words makes it one of the most explicitly documented military atrocities of the ancient world. Kalinga re-emerged as an independent maritime power after the Mauryan collapse, with its seafaring traditions spreading Indian culture to Southeast Asia, and the Kalingan influence on the Indianisation of Cambodia, Java, and Bali is considered significant by scholars of Indian Ocean history.","v":0},
  {"id":631,"n":"Lapita Cultural Complex","s":-1600,"e":-500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"OC","loc":[-15,168],"d":"The Lapita Cultural Complex was the archaeological culture associated with the initial human settlement of Remote Oceania — Vanuatu, New Caledonia, Fiji, Tonga, and Samoa — representing one of the most remarkable maritime expansions in human prehistory. Defined by their distinctive dentate-stamped pottery, obsidian tool kits, and burial practices, Lapita communities were accomplished open-ocean navigators who crossed hundreds of kilometres of deep Pacific water without landmarks, using stars, swells, wind patterns, and the behaviour of birds and marine life for guidance. Genetic and linguistic evidence identifies the Lapita people as the ancestors of all Polynesian populations, and the languages they carried evolved into the vast Polynesian language family. Their settlement of Western Polynesia around 1000 BCE established the launching pad from which subsequent generations would colonise the entire Pacific.","v":0},
  {"id":632,"n":"Nan Madol","s":800,"e":1628,"t":"confirmed","cont":"OC","loc":[6.84,158.34],"d":"Nan Madol was the ceremonial and political capital of the Saudeleur dynasty on the island of Pohnpei in the Caroline Islands of Micronesia, constructed on a series of artificial islets in a tidal lagoon using basalt columns that together weigh an estimated 750,000 metric tons. The complex comprises 92 artificial islets separated by canals, earning it the designation 'the Venice of the Pacific,' and it is the only ancient monument built atop a coral reef. The origin and transport method of the massive basalt logs — some weighing up to 50 tonnes — from quarry sites across the island remains incompletely understood, with local oral traditions attributing the construction to twin sorcerers who flew the stones into place. Nan Madol was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2016 and is considered one of the most remarkable archaeological sites in the Pacific.","v":0},
  {"id":633,"n":"Rapa Nui (Easter Island)","s":800,"e":1722,"t":"confirmed","cont":"OC","loc":[-27.1,-109.4],"d":"Rapa Nui is the remote Polynesian island in the southeastern Pacific whose inhabitants created approximately 900 monolithic moai stone figures averaging four metres tall and 12.5 tonnes, carved from volcanic tuff quarried at Rano Raraku and transported across the island to ceremonial platforms. The civilisation that built the moai also developed rongorongo — a unique undeciphered script and one of only a handful of independently invented writing systems in human history. Traditional narratives and archaeological evidence describe a period of ecological stress from deforestation contributing to social disruption before European contact in 1722. Researcher Thor Heyerdahl controversially argued for South American contact with Rapa Nui, a hypothesis partially supported by genetic studies published in 2020 suggesting pre-European contact with populations from coastal Colombia.","v":0},
  {"id":634,"n":"Vinča Culture","s":-5500,"e":-4500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","loc":[44.5,20.6],"d":"The Vinča culture was one of the largest and most sophisticated prehistoric societies of Neolithic Europe, occupying the central Balkans — Serbia, Romania, Bulgaria — with individual settlements reaching 2,500 inhabitants, making them among the largest known communities in the world at their time. Vinča communities produced distinctive anthropomorphic figurines, fine pottery with geometric incised designs, and crucially the Vinča symbols: a set of over 200 recurring signs inscribed on pottery and figurines that some researchers argue constitute a proto-writing system predating Sumerian cuneiform. Mainstream scholars categorise the Vinča symbols as non-linguistic notation; alternative researchers including Marija Gimbutas and Harald Haarmann argue they represent an early writing tradition that challenges the conventional Mesopotamian origin-of-writing narrative. The Vinča culture collapsed or transformed around 4500 BCE, possibly related to climatic disruption or the arrival of steppe populations.","v":0},
  {"id":635,"n":"Black Sea Flood Civilization","s":-7600,"e":-5600,"t":"theorized","cont":"EU","loc":[43,34],"d":"The Black Sea Flood hypothesis, proposed by marine geologists William Ryan and Walter Pitman in 1997, posits that a catastrophic inundation of the Black Sea basin occurred around 5600 BCE when rising Mediterranean waters breached the Bosphorus sill and flooded what had been a smaller, lower freshwater lake — displacing agricultural communities living on the fertile exposed shoreline. Ryan and Pitman argue this event, which would have inundated approximately 150,000 square kilometres of populated land, was the historical basis for Mesopotamian and biblical flood narratives. If correct, the disaster displaced Neolithic farming communities who may have carried agriculture and cultural traditions into Europe and the Middle East. Subsequent geophysical surveys have confirmed the ancient shoreline, but scholars debate the catastrophic versus gradual nature of the flooding and its demographic consequences.","v":0},
  {"id":636,"n":"Kerma Classique","s":-1750,"e":-1500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","loc":[19.6,30.4],"d":"Kerma Classique represents the apex of Nubian Kerma civilisation and the period of greatest sophistication and political power before Egyptian conquest under Thutmose I. During this final flourishing phase, Kerma controlled a vast territory from the Third to the Fifth Cataract, maintained diplomatic relationships with Hyksos-ruled Egypt, and constructed its most ambitious monumental architecture including the massive Western Deffufa — a mud-brick religious structure still standing to 19 metres. Royal tumulus burials of this period were extraordinarily elaborate: the largest tombs reached 90 metres in diameter and contained human sacrificial victims numbering in the hundreds, attesting to the absolute authority of Kerma's rulers. The kingdom's power ended definitively around 1504 BCE when Egyptian New Kingdom pharaohs conquered and dismantled the state, though Nubian cultural traditions persisted to fuel the later Kushite revival.","v":0},
  {"id":637,"n":"Gaetuli","s":-200,"e":400,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","loc":[28,5],"d":"The Gaetuli were a collection of nomadic and semi-nomadic Berber peoples inhabiting the pre-Saharan regions of North Africa south of the Atlas Mountains, spanning the territory between the Atlantic coast of Morocco and the Syrtic desert of modern Libya. Roman sources describe them as fierce fighters and skilled horsemen who provided mercenary cavalry to Jugurtha of Numidia in his wars against Rome and to Tacfarinas in his revolt of 17–24 CE, making them recurrent adversaries and occasional allies of Roman North Africa. Unlike the settled Berber kingdoms of Numidia and Mauretania, the Gaetuli resisted territorial incorporation, and their trans-Saharan knowledge and routes may have contributed to gold and slave trade networks connecting sub-Saharan Africa to the Mediterranean world.","v":0},
  {"id":638,"n":"Tocharian City-States","s":-200,"e":900,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","loc":[40.5,80],"d":"The Tocharians were the easternmost known speakers of an Indo-European language, discovered through manuscripts found in the oasis towns of the Tarim Basin in what is now Xinjiang, China. The manuscripts, dating from approximately 500–800 CE, preserve two related languages — Tocharian A and B — which are linguistically most closely related to Celtic and Italic languages, suggesting an extraordinary prehistoric migration from western Eurasia. Earlier Tocharian populations are archaeologically associated with the Tarim mummies — naturally preserved bodies with fair hair and woollen textiles — dating as far back as 1800 BCE. The Tocharians ran the oasis city-states of the Silk Road including Kucha and Turfan, transmitting Buddhist art and manuscripts eastward into China; their states were absorbed by Uyghur and Tibetan expansion in the eighth and ninth centuries.","v":0},
  {"id":639,"n":"Poverty Point (Peak Phase)","s":-1730,"e":-1350,"t":"confirmed","cont":"NA","loc":[32.63,-91.41],"d":"The peak phase of the Poverty Point site in the Lower Mississippi Valley of Louisiana represents the mature florescence of a monumental earthwork complex consisting of six concentric C-shaped earthen ridges, five mounds, and a central plaza covering approximately 1.6 square kilometres — the largest earthwork complex in North America at its time. The site was the centre of an exchange network stretching from the Great Lakes to the Gulf of Mexico and from the Appalachians to the Ouachitas, with exotic materials including copper, galena, magnetite, hematite, and chert appearing in quantities implying an organised redistribution system. Poverty Point is extraordinary because it was constructed by hunter-gatherers rather than agricultural societies, challenging longstanding assumptions that monumental architecture requires food-production surplus. UNESCO designated it a World Heritage Site in 2013, and its construction implies a level of social organisation far exceeding conventional models of forager complexity.","v":0},
  {"id":643,"n":"Champa Civilisation","s":15.8801,"e":108.338,"b":192,"d":1832,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Champa was a collection of Indianised polities occupying the central and southern coast of present-day Vietnam, organised around a string of river valleys and coastal plains. The Cham people were skilled seafarers and traders, and their culture synthesised Hindu-Buddhist elements with indigenous Austronesian traditions to produce a distinctive sculptural and architectural tradition centred on brick tower-temples. Champa engaged in prolonged military conflict with both China and the expanding Dai Viet kingdom to the north. The kingdom's final remnants were absorbed by Vietnam in the nineteenth century."},
  {"id":644,"n":"Dvaravati Kingdom","s":14.35,"e":100.56,"b":550,"d":1000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Dvaravati was a Mon Buddhist kingdom flourishing in the Chao Phraya basin of present-day central Thailand, representing one of the earliest Theravada Buddhist polities in mainland Southeast Asia. Its cities, including Nakhon Pathom and U Thong, were ringed by moats and featured large Buddhist stupas, votive tablets, and dharma wheels. Dvaravati art — characterised by serene Buddha images in distinctive local style — profoundly influenced later Thai, Lao, and Cambodian Buddhist cultures. The kingdom declined under pressure from Khmer expansion in the eleventh century."},
  {"id":645,"n":"Pagan Empire","s":21.1717,"e":94.8585,"b":849,"d":1297,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Pagan Empire was the first kingdom to unify the disparate peoples of the Irrawaddy valley, forming the precursor state to modern Myanmar. At its height under King Anawrahta and his successors, Pagan constructed over ten thousand temples, pagodas, and monasteries across a forty-square-kilometre plain — one of the densest concentrations of Buddhist monuments on Earth. The empire promoted Theravada Buddhism while incorporating earlier Tantric and animist traditions, and developed the Burmese script. Mongol invasions beginning in 1277 CE weakened Pagan fatally, and the empire fragmented into smaller kingdoms by the late thirteenth century."},
  {"id":646,"n":"Kingdom of Axum — Late Phase","s":14.1213,"e":38.7268,"b":400,"d":940,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The late phase of the Aksumite kingdom saw the empire contract from its Red Sea commercial peak while deepening its Christian identity following Ezana's conversion around 330 CE. Aksum minted coinage bearing Christian symbols and built remarkable rock-hewn and monolithic churches including Debre Damo. The rise of Islam in Arabia in the seventh century disrupted Aksumite trade networks and severed its Mediterranean commercial ties, accelerating decline. The kingdom eventually retreated into the Ethiopian highlands, where its legacy persisted through the Zagwe dynasty and the enduring Ethiopian Orthodox Church."},
  {"id":647,"n":"Ifat Sultanate","s":9.35,"e":41.85,"b":1285,"d":1415,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Ifat Sultanate was a medieval Islamic state occupying the eastern Horn of Africa in present-day Ethiopia and Djibouti, representing one of the earliest Muslim polities in the region. Founded by the Walashma dynasty, Ifat controlled lucrative trade routes connecting the Ethiopian interior to the Red Sea coast and competed for dominance with the Christian Solomonic emperors of Ethiopia. The prolonged conflict between Ifat and the Solomonic court culminated in the defeat of Sultan Sa'ad ad-Din II by Emperor Yeshaq I in 1415, which effectively ended Ifat as an independent power."},
  {"id":648,"n":"Adal Sultanate","s":9.56,"e":44.065,"b":1415,"d":1577,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Adal Sultanate emerged from the remnants of the Ifat Sultanate and became the dominant Islamic power in the Horn of Africa during the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries. Under the military leadership of Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi — known as Ahmad Grañ — Adal launched a devastating jihad against Christian Ethiopia beginning in 1529 that nearly extinguished the Solomonic kingdom. Portuguese intervention alongside Ethiopian forces eventually turned the tide, and Ahmad Grañ was killed in 1543 at the Battle of Wayna Daga. The sultanate fragmented thereafter under Oromo migration pressure and never recovered its former strength."},
  {"id":649,"n":"Zagwe Dynasty","s":12.52,"e":39.47,"b":900,"d":1270,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Zagwe Dynasty ruled highland Ethiopia for approximately four centuries following the decline of Aksum, maintaining the Christian Orthodox tradition while producing some of Africa's most extraordinary architectural achievements. The dynasty's capital at Lalibela in the Lasta highlands is home to eleven monolithic rock-hewn churches carved entirely from living basalt, a feat of engineering that remains one of the world's great medieval wonders. The Zagwe kings were prolific church builders and patrons of monastic scholarship who kept Ethiopian Christianity vital during a period of Islamic expansion across Northeast Africa. The dynasty was superseded by the restored Solomonic line in 1270 under Yekuno Amlak."},
  {"id":650,"n":"Anatolian Bronze Age Kingdoms","s":39.9334,"e":32.8597,"b":-3000,"d":-1200,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"Central Anatolia hosted a constellation of Bronze Age kingdoms preceding and contemporary with the Hittite Empire, including the Hatti culture whose religious traditions the Hittites absorbed wholesale. The region saw early adoption of metallurgy, with copper and bronze working spreading outward from Anatolian centres well before the third millennium BCE. Trade colonies established by Assyrian merchants at sites such as Kültepe (ancient Kanesh) introduced cuneiform writing to Anatolia around 1950 BCE. The wider Anatolian Bronze Age complex collapsed catastrophically around 1200 BCE as part of the broader Late Bronze Age collapse."},
  {"id":651,"n":"Colchis Kingdom","s":42.2679,"e":42.6917,"b":-1100,"d":-63,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"Colchis was an ancient kingdom occupying the fertile eastern Black Sea coast in present-day western Georgia, renowned in Greek mythology as the destination of Jason and the Argonauts and the homeland of the sorceress Medea. The region was exceptionally rich in alluvial gold, collected by local inhabitants using sheepskins laid in riverbeds — the likely origin of the Golden Fleece legend. Colchis developed sophisticated goldsmithing and had extensive commercial contact with the Greek colonial world and later with Persia. The kingdom gradually fragmented under pressure from Pontic expansion and was finally absorbed into the Pontic Empire of Mithridates VI around 100 BCE."},
  {"id":652,"n":"Urartu Kingdom","s":38.501,"e":43.343,"b":-860,"d":-590,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Urartu was a powerful Iron Age kingdom centred around Lake Van in present-day eastern Turkey, representing one of Assyria's most persistent and formidable adversaries for over two centuries. The Urartians were exceptional hydraulic engineers who constructed vast irrigation canal systems, fortress complexes on volcanic rock spurs, and enormous grain storage facilities capable of sustaining large armies. Their metalwork — particularly bronze cauldrons adorned with griffin and bull protomes — spread across the ancient Near East and into Etruscan Italy. Urartu collapsed under a combination of Scythian incursions and Median military pressure around 590 BCE."},
  {"id":653,"n":"Sabaean Kingdom","s":15.3547,"e":44.2066,"b":-900,"d":275,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Sabaean Kingdom, centred at Marib in present-day Yemen, was one of the wealthiest and most powerful of the ancient South Arabian civilisations, controlling the lucrative incense trade routes that linked Arabia to the Mediterranean world. The Sabaeans constructed the Great Dam of Marib — one of antiquity's greatest engineering achievements — which irrigated vast swathes of otherwise arid land and sustained a dense agricultural population. They developed the Sabaean script, ancestor to the Ethiopic script family. Ancient tradition, supported by some scholars, identifies Sheba — the queen who visited Solomon — with the Sabaean realm, though this connection remains debated."},
  {"id":654,"n":"Himyarite Kingdom","s":14.545,"e":44.372,"b":-110,"d":525,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Himyarite Kingdom succeeded Saba as the dominant power of ancient Yemen, eventually unifying most of the Arabian Peninsula's southern coast under a single royal authority. The Himyarites converted progressively from polytheism toward monotheism — first adopting a form of Judaic practice before some rulers converted to Christianity — in a remarkable religious evolution that made their court one of the most theologically diverse in the ancient world. Himyarite military forces conducted campaigns across the Red Sea into Ethiopia, and Aksumite counterattacks eventually ended the kingdom in 525 CE. The Himyarite domain subsequently became a Sasanian Persian province and then was swept into the Islamic world in the seventh century."},
  {"id":656,"n":"Magan Civilisation","s":23.588,"e":58.3829,"b":-3000,"d":-1500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Magan was an ancient Bronze Age civilisation occupying present-day Oman and the UAE, known primarily from Mesopotamian trade records as the principal source of copper in the ancient Near East. Akkadian and Sumerian texts record extensive trade in copper ingots, diorite stone, and exotic woods between Magan and the cities of Mesopotamia via the Gulf route. Archaeological work at sites including Bat, Al-Khutm, and Tell Abraq has revealed sophisticated tower tombs, communal burial practices, and evidence of extensive copper smelting. The civilisation is associated archaeologically with the Umm an-Nar culture and appears to have maintained commercial links with the Indus Valley."},
  {"id":657,"n":"Minoan Neopalatial Period","s":35.2985,"e":25.1632,"b":-1700,"d":-1450,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Neopalatial period represents the zenith of Minoan civilisation on Crete, following the reconstruction of the great palace complexes at Knossos, Phaistos, Malia, and Zakros after catastrophic earthquakes around 1700 BCE. This era saw the widest distribution of Minoan cultural influence — the Minoan thalassocracy — extending across the Aegean to Thera, Rhodes, and the Greek mainland. Neopalatial frescoes depict vibrant naturalistic scenes of bull-leaping, marine life, and religious ceremony reflecting a sophisticated aesthetic tradition without parallel in the contemporary Bronze Age world. The period ended abruptly around 1450 BCE, possibly linked to the catastrophic eruption of Thera, with Knossos alone surviving under apparent Mycenaean administration."},
  {"id":658,"n":"Cycladic Culture","s":37.09,"e":25.15,"b":-3200,"d":-2000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Cycladic culture flourished across the islands of the central Aegean during the Early Bronze Age, producing one of prehistory's most immediately recognisable artistic traditions in the form of simplified marble figurines with folded arms. These island communities were skilled navigators, obsidian traders, and metalworkers who connected Anatolia, mainland Greece, and Crete in an integrated Aegean exchange network. The town of Akrotiri on Thera, buried under volcanic ash around 1600 BCE, preserves remarkable evidence of a sophisticated urban Cycladic settlement with multi-storey buildings, flush toilets, and elaborate frescoes. The Cycladic tradition merged gradually with Minoan and Mycenaean cultural currents over the course of the second millennium BCE."},
  {"id":659,"n":"Tocharian City-States of the Tarim","s":41.1,"e":85.25,"b":-1800,"d":900,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Tocharians were an Indo-European-speaking people whose mummies, discovered in the Tarim Basin of western China, display strikingly Caucasian features and represent some of the earliest confirmed residents of Central Asian oases. They founded a string of city-states along the ancient Silk Road — including Kucha, Agni, and Krorän — that served as vital cultural and commercial relay points between China, India, Iran, and the Mediterranean world. Tocharian languages, preserved in Buddhist manuscripts, are paradoxically classified as the easternmost branch of Indo-European yet show archaic features suggesting early separation from the proto-language. Their civilisation was absorbed by Turkic and later Uyghur expansion during the first millennium CE."},
  {"id":661,"n":"Bactrian-Margiana Archaeological Complex","s":37.926,"e":65.91,"b":-2400,"d":-1600,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Bactrian-Margiana Archaeological Complex (BMAC), also known as the Oxus Civilisation, was a Bronze Age urban culture occupying present-day Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Afghanistan, and northern Iran, contemporary with the Indus Valley and early Mesopotamian civilisations. BMAC sites feature large planned settlements with monumental mudbrick architecture, sophisticated metallurgy, and a distinctive artistic tradition including compartmentalised seals and zoomorphic statuettes. Some scholars propose BMAC as the cultural milieu in which proto-Indo-Iranian religion — including the earliest Vedic and Avestan religious traditions — crystallised before spreading south into India and Iran. The complex declined and dispersed around 1600 BCE, its population apparently merging with surrounding steppe cultures."},
  {"id":663,"n":"Ptolemaic Kingdom","s":31.2001,"e":29.9187,"b":-305,"d":-30,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Ptolemaic Kingdom was the Macedonian Greek dynasty founded by Ptolemy I Soter following the death of Alexander the Great, ruling Egypt for nearly three centuries until Cleopatra VII's defeat by Rome in 30 BCE. Alexandria, the kingdom's capital, became the intellectual capital of the Hellenistic world, home to the Great Library, the Mouseion (proto-university), and an extraordinary concentration of scholars including Euclid, Eratosthenes, and Archimedes. The Ptolemies promoted a syncretic religion combining Egyptian and Greek elements — most notably the cult of Serapis — while maintaining the traditional pharaonic system of administration and religious observance. Cleopatra VII, the last ruling Ptolemaic monarch, was notably the first of her dynasty to learn the Egyptian language."},
  {"id":664,"n":"Nubian Meroe Kingdom","s":16.9333,"e":33.75,"b":-590,"d":350,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"Meroe was the capital and ruling centre of the Kingdom of Kush following the Assyrian expulsion of the Nubian Twenty-fifth Dynasty from Egypt, representing a remarkable efflorescence of indigenous African civilisation largely independent of Mediterranean influence. The Meroitic kingdom developed its own alphabetic script — Meroitic, still not fully deciphered — and produced distinctive royal pyramids that are more numerous though smaller than their Egyptian counterparts. Meroe's prosperity rested on iron smelting, agricultural productivity in a well-watered savanna zone, and control of sub-Saharan trade routes bringing ivory, gold, and enslaved people northward. The kingdom was conquered by the Aksumite kingdom of Ezana around 350 CE, ending three centuries of Meroitic independence."},
  {"id":669,"n":"Pre-Columbian Caribbean Networks","s":18.2208,"e":-66.5901,"b":-3500,"d":1500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Caribbean archipelago was settled in at least three major waves of migration, beginning with Archaic Age foragers from Central and South America around 3500 BCE and culminating with the northward expansion of Arawakan-speaking Taíno peoples who were the dominant population encountered by Columbus in 1492. Caribbean networks facilitated the exchange of manufactured goods, foodstuffs, ritual objects, and people across remarkable sea distances, connecting islands from Trinidad to Cuba in a web of chiefdom-level political relationships. Taíno cosmology and material culture — including the areíto ceremonial tradition, the ballgame, and the cultivation of cassava — have left lasting marks on Caribbean culture. European contact introduced epidemic diseases that reduced Caribbean island populations by an estimated ninety percent within a century."},
  {"id":670,"n":"Mu / Lost Pacific Continent","s":10,"e":-150,"b":-50000,"d":-10800,"t":"theorized","cont":"OC","desc":"The concept of Mu as a sunken Pacific continent was first elaborated by Augustus Le Plongeon in the nineteenth century and subsequently popularised by James Churchward, who claimed to derive the tradition from secret Naacal tablets he encountered in India. Proponents of Mu — or Lemuria in its alternative formulation — point to the cultural and linguistic similarities between Pacific island peoples, the mythological traditions of a sunken homeland preserved across Polynesia and Micronesia, and anomalous archaeological structures such as Nan Madol in Pohnpei as circumstantial evidence. Mainstream geology rejects the existence of a sunken Pacific continent, as the Pacific floor is composed of dense oceanic crust incapable of the crustal subsidence that would be required. Some alternative researchers, including Graham Hancock, discuss the flooding of continental shelves during post-glacial sea-level rise as a more geologically plausible mechanism for the loss of inhabited coastal lands across the Pacific."},
  {"id":671,"n":"Kingdom of Merina","s":-18.9137,"e":47.5361,"b":1540,"d":1897,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Kingdom of Merina was the dominant Malagasy polity of the central highlands of Madagascar, unifying much of the island under a centralised monarchy that combined Austronesian cultural heritage with strong Southeast Asian and later European influences. King Andrianampoinimerina in the late eighteenth century dramatically expanded Merina power through a combination of military conquest and strategic marriage alliances, and his son Radama I extended the kingdom to the sea coasts with British military assistance. The Merina court adopted Christianity, established a written Malagasy language using the Latin script, and founded schools and printing presses under missionary collaboration. French colonial forces defeated and exiled Queen Ranavalona III in 1897, formally ending the Merina kingdom."},
  {"id":673,"n":"Kongo Kingdom","s":-6.1833,"e":14.4167,"b":1390,"d":1914,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Kingdom of Kongo was one of the largest and most sophisticated pre-colonial African states, occupying the lower Congo River basin across present-day Angola, DRC, and Republic of Congo and governed by a Manikongo (king) through a provincial system of appointed governors. Kongo was among the first sub-Saharan African states to encounter and engage with European powers, establishing formal diplomatic relations with Portugal in 1483 and converting its ruling elite to Catholicism by 1491. King Afonso I conducted an extensive diplomatic correspondence with the Portuguese crown — some of the most remarkable political documents from early modern Africa — including letters protesting the devastation of the slave trade on his kingdom. Portuguese commercial pressure, the slave trade, and internal succession disputes progressively weakened Kongo, and the kingdom was absorbed into Portuguese Angola in 1914."},
  {"id":674,"n":"Mutapa Empire","s":-16.5,"e":30.8333,"b":1430,"d":1760,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Mutapa Empire — also known as Monomotapa — was a Shona state in the northern Zimbabwe plateau and Mozambique coastal hinterland, evolving from the Great Zimbabwe tradition and controlling the gold trade routes between the interior and the Swahili Coast ports. Portuguese traders made contact with Mutapa in the sixteenth century and subsequently penetrated its political system through missionary activity, intermarriage, and ultimately military intervention, securing trade concessions and gold mining rights. The empire maintained an elaborate court with a sacred fire that burned perpetually and complex protocols governing the Mutapa's interactions with subjects and foreigners. Internal succession wars and Portuguese manipulation progressively fragmented the empire through the seventeenth century until it became a Portuguese client state."},
  {"id":675,"n":"Aksumite Pre-Kingdom — D'mt","s":14.5,"e":38.9167,"b":-900,"d":-400,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"D'mt was an ancient kingdom in the northern Ethiopian highlands and Eritrea that preceded and laid cultural foundations for the Aksumite civilisation, representing the earliest sophisticated state in the Horn of Africa that has left clear archaeological and epigraphic traces. D'mt's inscriptions in the South Arabian Sabaean script demonstrate close cultural and commercial ties with the kingdom of Saba across the Red Sea, and Sabaean colonists or merchants appear to have contributed to the kingdom's development. The kingdom constructed stone-built towns and temples, developed an early form of the Ge'ez language, and maintained agricultural terracing systems that supported a substantial highland population. D'mt faded from the record around 400 BCE and was likely absorbed into the pre-Aksumite chiefdoms that would eventually coalesce into the Aksumite kingdom."},
  {"id":676,"n":"Garamantian Empire","s":26.5833,"e":13.4167,"b":-500,"d":700,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Garamantian Empire was a Saharan civilisation centred on the Fezzan region of present-day Libya that constructed one of antiquity's most extraordinary hydraulic engineering systems — thousands of kilometres of underground tunnels called foggaras that tapped fossil water aquifers beneath the desert and brought it to the surface for agriculture. At its height Garamantia supported a substantial agricultural population in what is now hyper-arid desert, growing grapes, olives, figs, and cereals across irrigated fields. Garamantian cavalry and war chariots controlled trans-Saharan trade routes connecting sub-Saharan Africa to the Mediterranean, trading enslaved people, gold, ivory, and exotic animals with Rome. The empire declined as the fossil water aquifers were depleted and Roman commercial dominance over North Africa disrupted the trade networks on which Garamantian prosperity depended."},
  {"id":678,"n":"Numidian Kingdom","s":36.364,"e":6.6147,"b":-202,"d":-46,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"Numidia was a Berber kingdom occupying present-day northern Algeria, unified under King Masinissa following Rome's defeat of Carthage at Zama in 202 BCE into a surprisingly sophisticated and capable state. Masinissa transformed Numidia from a pastoral nomadic confederation into a partially urbanised agricultural kingdom, encouraging the cultivation of grain on previously nomadic lands and developing a written Tifinagh script tradition. Numidian cavalry were among the most prized mercenary soldiers in the ancient Mediterranean world, serving on both sides of the Punic Wars. The kingdom was fatally destabilised by dynastic conflicts exploited by Rome, and Julius Caesar's victory over the Pompeian-Numidian alliance at Thapsus in 46 BCE effectively ended Numidian independence."},
  {"id":679,"n":"Aksumite Red Sea Trade Network","s":15.6167,"e":39.45,"b":100,"d":700,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"At the height of Aksumite power the kingdom controlled both shores of the southern Red Sea, positioning it as the primary intermediary in the trade between the Roman Empire and the Indian Ocean world. Aksumite merchants and naval forces operated from the great port of Adulis — the largest port on the African Red Sea coast — receiving Indian spices, Chinese silk, and Sri Lankan gems destined for Roman markets while exporting African ivory, gold, obsidian, and enslaved people. The kingdom minted a prolific gold, silver, and bronze coinage — one of the ancient world's most sophisticated monetary systems — that circulated across the Indian Ocean trading world. The expansion of the Sasanian Persian Empire and subsequently Islam disrupted Aksumite commercial dominance of the Red Sea from the sixth century onward."},
  {"id":684,"n":"Seleucid Empire","s":36.2021,"e":37.1343,"b":-312,"d":-63,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Seleucid Empire was the largest of the Hellenistic successor states following Alexander the Great's death, stretching at its height from Anatolia and the Levant through Mesopotamia and Persia to the borders of India and representing one of history's most ambitious attempts to fuse Greek and Near Eastern civilisations. Seleucid kings founded dozens of new cities — including Antioch on the Orontes, which became one of the ancient world's great metropolises — peopling them with Macedonian colonists while incorporating existing Persian administrative structures. The empire's cultural policy of active Hellenisation provoked significant resistance, most famously the Maccabean Revolt in Judea beginning in 167 BCE, which produced the first recorded religious freedom movement in world history. The Seleucid state was progressively dismembered by Parthian expansion from the east and Roman pressure from the west, with its final remnant extinguished by Pompey in 63 BCE."},
  {"id":685,"n":"Hasmonean Kingdom","s":31.7683,"e":35.2137,"b":-140,"d":-37,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Hasmonean Kingdom was the independent Jewish state established in Judea following the successful Maccabean Revolt against Seleucid Hellenisation, representing the last period of Jewish political sovereignty in the ancient Levant before the Roman period. The Hasmonean rulers combined the roles of high priest and king — a theocratic fusion that proved religiously controversial — and dramatically expanded Judean territory through military conquest to encompass most of the ancient Israelite heartland. Internal dynastic conflict between Hasmonean claimants led the competing factions to appeal to Rome for arbitration, enabling the Roman general Pompey to enter Jerusalem in 63 BCE and establish Roman suzerainty over Judea. The dynasty ended with Roman-appointed Herod the Great's seizure of power in 37 BCE."},
  {"id":688,"n":"Vandal Kingdom","s":36.819,"e":10.1658,"b":429,"d":534,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Vandal Kingdom was a Germanic barbarian state established in North Africa after the Vandals crossed the Strait of Gibraltar in 429 CE under King Gaiseric, seizing the wealthy Roman provinces of Africa Proconsularis and making Carthage their capital. The Vandals became a significant naval power in the western Mediterranean, sacking Rome itself in 455 CE in a raid of fourteen days that, contrary to modern usage, was reportedly conducted with relative restraint on the civilian population. The kingdom maintained a complex relationship with the Roman-Byzantine world, occasionally acting as a destabilising pirate power while also engaging in trade and diplomacy. Byzantine general Belisarius destroyed the Vandal Kingdom with remarkable speed in 533–534 CE, ending Germanic rule of North Africa."},
  {"id":689,"n":"Visigothic Kingdom","s":40.4168,"e":-3.7038,"b":418,"d":711,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Visigothic Kingdom was the most durable of the Germanic successor states to the western Roman Empire, ruling southwestern Gaul before being pushed into Iberia by Frankish pressure and establishing a sophisticated monarchy centred on Toledo that governed the entire Iberian Peninsula for nearly three centuries. The Visigoths converted from Arianism to Nicene Catholicism in 589 CE under King Reccared, enabling a fruitful alliance with the powerful Iberian church and the production of a remarkable early medieval literary culture including Isidore of Seville's encyclopaedic Etymologiae. Visigothic law codes were among the most sophisticated in post-Roman Europe, drawing on Roman legal traditions while incorporating Germanic customary law in a fusion that influenced later Iberian legal culture. The kingdom was destroyed with extraordinary speed by the Umayyad Muslim invasion of 711 CE."},
  {"id":690,"n":"Lombard Kingdom","s":45.4654,"e":9.1866,"b":568,"d":774,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Lombard Kingdom was a Germanic state established in northern and central Italy following the Byzantine reconquest under Justinian had left the peninsula exhausted and depopulated, with the Lombard invasion of 568 CE shattering Byzantine control outside the exarchate of Ravenna. The Lombards, initially Arian Christians, gradually converted to Catholicism and developed a sophisticated legal culture embodied in the Edictum Rothari of 643 CE — one of the earliest codified Germanic law collections. Lombard Italy produced remarkable art, including goldwork jewellery and the decorated altar screen at Cividale del Friuli that represents a bridge between late antique and Carolingian artistic traditions. Charlemagne destroyed the Lombard Kingdom at the request of Pope Hadrian I in 774 CE, incorporating it into the expanding Carolingian Empire."},
  {"id":692,"n":"Viking Age Scandinavia","s":59.9139,"e":10.7522,"b":793,"d":1100,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Viking Age saw Scandinavian seafarers from Denmark, Norway, and Sweden project power, trade, and settlement across an extraordinary geographic range — from North America in the west to the Caspian Sea and Constantinople in the east — through a combination of superior shipbuilding technology, navigational skill, and ferocious military effectiveness. Norse settlements were established at L'Anse aux Meadows in Newfoundland around 1000 CE, confirming Leif Erikson's voyages as the first confirmed European contact with the Americas, nearly five centuries before Columbus. The Varangian route — Norse traders paddling and portaging rivers from the Baltic to the Black Sea — created the commercial backbone of the Kievan Rus state and brought Scandinavian traders directly into the Abbasid caliphate's silver economy. Viking expansion ended not through external defeat but through Christianisation and the consolidation of Scandinavian kingdoms that redirected Norse energies into European feudal politics."},
  {"id":696,"n":"Mossi Kingdoms","s":12.3647,"e":-1.5333,"b":1170,"d":1896,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Mossi Kingdoms of present-day Burkina Faso were a group of related cavalry-based states — principally Ouagadougou, Yatenga, Fada N'Gourma, and Tenkodogo — that successfully resisted incorporation into the great Sahelian empires of Mali and Songhai through a combination of military effectiveness and strategic isolation. The Mossi kingdoms maintained traditional animist religion alongside Islam in a deliberate policy of religious pluralism that allowed them to draw on both indigenous spiritual authority and Islamic commercial networks. They raided Timbuktu in 1333 CE and again in 1477 CE, demonstrating a military reach that troubled the great empires to their north and west. French colonial forces conquered the last Mossi kingdoms in 1896–1897, ending over seven centuries of political continuity."},
  {"id":698,"n":"Göbekli Tepe Cultural Complex","s":37.2231,"e":38.9225,"b":-9600,"d":-8000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Göbekli Tepe in southeastern Turkey is the world's oldest known monumental religious architecture, with T-shaped limestone pillars up to six metres tall and weighing twenty tonnes arranged in circular enclosures and carved with sophisticated bas-relief depictions of animals, symbols, and abstract forms that predate the agricultural revolution by at least a millennium. The site's construction required the coordinated labour of hundreds of hunter-gatherers over generations, fundamentally challenging the long-held assumption that monumental architecture required settled agricultural societies as a precondition. Klaus Schmidt, who excavated the site from 1994 until his death in 2014, proposed that Göbekli Tepe was a pilgrimage centre that may have catalysed the agricultural revolution in the surrounding Fertile Crescent rather than resulting from it. Some alternative researchers including Graham Hancock have proposed the site preserves astronomical alignments and symbolic records of a pre-Younger Dryas civilisation, with the Vulture Stone potentially encoding a date of 10,950 BCE using stellar positions."},
  {"id":700,"n":"Younger Dryas Boundary Event — Pre-Flood Civilisation Hypothesis","s":35,"e":36,"b":-12900,"d":-11600,"t":"theorized","cont":"AS","desc":"The Younger Dryas Boundary (YDB) Event — dated to approximately 12,900 years ago — is proposed by a growing body of researchers to represent the impact or airburst of a fragmented comet or asteroid that triggered catastrophic wildfires, megafaunal extinction, abrupt cooling, and the collapse of Clovis culture in North America. Graham Hancock, Randall Carlson, and others have argued that this cataclysm destroyed a sophisticated pre-agricultural civilisation whose survivors became the mythological flood-bringers, sky gods, and civilising teachers recorded in the origin myths of cultures worldwide — from Sumerian Oannes to Egyptian Zep Tepi to the Vedic Devas. The YDIH (Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis) has accumulated substantial peer-reviewed geological support including nano-diamonds, platinum-group element anomalies, and magnetic spherules at the YDB layer across four continents, though the hypothesis remains contested by mainstream geology. Göbekli Tepe, Çatalhöyük, and the sudden appearance of monument-building and agricultural knowledge across multiple regions shortly after 11,600 BCE are cited by alternative researchers as evidence of a post-catastrophe knowledge-transmission event from a destroyed antecedent civilisation."},
  {"id":703,"n":"Neo-Babylonian Empire","s":32.5355,"e":44.4208,"b":-626,"d":-539,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Neo-Babylonian Empire was the last great Mesopotamian empire before Persian dominance, most celebrated for Nebuchadnezzar II's construction of the Hanging Gardens of Babylon — if they existed as described — and his destruction of Jerusalem and deportation of the Jewish population in the Babylonian Captivity of 586 BCE. Babylon under Nebuchadnezzar II was the largest city in the world, ringed by double walls of such magnitude that Herodotus described four-horse chariots being driven along their tops. The Neo-Babylonian kings were avid restorers of ancient Sumerian and Akkadian religious sites, deliberately positioning themselves as heirs to Mesopotamia's deepest antiquity. Cyrus the Great of Persia captured Babylon in 539 BCE without significant resistance, welcomed by a populace alienated from the last Babylonian king Nabonidus's eccentric religious reforms."},
  {"id":704,"n":"Lydian Kingdom","s":38.6189,"e":27.4333,"b":-685,"d":-547,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Lydia in western Anatolia is credited with one of antiquity's most transformative innovations — the invention of coinage around 600 BCE under King Alyattes, who struck the first standardised electrum coins bearing royal authority, fundamentally changing the mechanics of trade, taxation, and economic life across the ancient world. King Croesus, whose legendary wealth gave rise to the phrase 'rich as Croesus,' refined the coinage system into pure gold and silver denominations and established diplomatic relations with Greek city-states and the oracle at Delphi. The kingdom maintained the Royal Road that was subsequently expanded by the Achaemenids and served as the westernmost anchor of Asian overland trade routes. Cyrus the Great defeated Croesus in 547 BCE following the famously ambiguous Delphic prophecy, incorporating Lydia into the Achaemenid satrapy system."},
  {"id":706,"n":"Thracian Odrysian Kingdom","s":41.9965,"e":25.8576,"b":-480,"d":-46,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Odrysian Kingdom was the most powerful Thracian state, dominating the region between the Aegean, Black Sea, and the Danube in present-day Bulgaria and northwestern Turkey and representing the most sophisticated indigenous civilisation of ancient southeastern Europe outside the Greek world. Thracian metalwork — particularly the gold and silver treasures discovered at Panagyurishte, Rogozen, and Letnitsa — represents a distinctive artistic tradition of extraordinary quality featuring zoomorphic rhyta and elaborate appliqués that have no precise parallel in the ancient world. The kingdom maintained complex relationships with both the Macedonian Argead dynasty and the Athenian Empire, alternating between alliance and conflict as circumstances demanded. Rome progressively reduced Thracian independence and formally annexed Thrace as a province in 46 CE under Emperor Claudius."},
  {"id":708,"n":"Illyrian Kingdoms","s":41.3275,"e":19.8187,"b":-400,"d":-168,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Illyrian kingdoms occupied the eastern Adriatic coast and western Balkans in present-day Albania, Montenegro, and Bosnia, representing a loose confederation of tribal kingdoms that produced skilled metalworkers, fearsome warriors, and accomplished seafarers whose piracy in the Adriatic Sea precipitated Roman military intervention. The most powerful Illyrian ruler, Queen Teuta, refused Roman demands to suppress Illyrian piracy in 230 BCE and was subsequently defeated in the First Illyrian War — one of Rome's first military interventions east of the Adriatic. Illyrian warriors served as mercenaries across the Mediterranean and their combat effectiveness was recognised by Alexander the Great, whose Macedonian army drew heavily on Illyrian tribal contingents. Rome formally ended Illyrian independence after defeating King Gentius in 168 BCE, incorporating the region into the Roman provincial system."},
  {"id":709,"n":"Epirote Kingdom","s":39.665,"e":20.8537,"b":-370,"d":-168,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Epirote Kingdom in northwestern Greece was a Molossian-led monarchy that produced one of antiquity's most celebrated military commanders — Pyrrhus of Epirus — whose Italian campaigns against Rome between 280 and 275 BCE gave the English language the phrase 'Pyrrhic victory' for a triumph so costly it approaches defeat. Pyrrhus was regarded by Hannibal Barca as the second greatest general in history after Alexander the Great and was the first commander to demonstrate to Rome the tactical effectiveness of war elephants in European combat. The kingdom controlled the sanctuary of Dodona — one of Greece's most ancient oracular centres, where priests interpreted the rustling of sacred oak leaves — which served as the religious heart of northwestern Greece. Rome dissolved the Epirote state in 168 BCE, enslaving 150,000 of its inhabitants in a single day in one of the ancient world's most dramatic acts of mass enslavement."},
  {"id":710,"n":"Pontus Kingdom","s":41.2867,"e":36.33,"b":-302,"d":-63,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Pontus on the Black Sea coast of Anatolia was most formidable under Mithridates VI Eupator, who forged the last serious challenge to Roman dominance of the eastern Mediterranean and became the Roman Republic's most persistent and dangerous enemy, fighting three Mithridatic Wars over twenty-five years. Mithridates VI, reportedly immune to poisons through a regime of progressive self-immunisation that gave the English language the word 'mithridate' for an antidote, was a remarkable polyglot who allegedly spoke twenty-two languages and governed his multi-ethnic kingdom with considerable administrative sophistication. His Pontic Massacre of 88 BCE — in which he ordered the simultaneous killing of all Romans and Italians in Asia Minor, resulting in approximately 80,000 deaths in a single day — was the ancient world's largest single-day mass atrocity before the Roman response. Rome's Pompey finally defeated Mithridates in 63 BCE, ending the Pontic kingdom."},
  {"id":711,"n":"Bosporan Kingdom","s":45.355,"e":36.4736,"b":-438,"d":370,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Bosporan Kingdom was a long-lived Greek colonial state controlling the Cimmerian Bosporus — the Strait of Kerch connecting the Black Sea to the Sea of Azov — that served as the primary conduit for grain shipments from the vast agricultural steppe hinterland to the grain-hungry cities of the Greek world. Athens in the fifth and fourth centuries BCE depended critically on Bosporan grain, and the kingdom's rulers cultivated Athenian friendship with remarkable diplomatic skill, receiving Athenian citizenship and commercial privileges in return for preferential grain prices. The kingdom absorbed Scythian and later Sarmatian aristocratic traditions into its ruling class, producing a fascinating syncretic Greco-barbarian culture reflected in extraordinarily rich burial tumuli excavated across the Crimean peninsula. The Bosporan state eventually succumbed to Gothic and Hunnic pressure in the late fourth century CE after eight centuries of remarkable continuity."},
  {"id":712,"n":"Pergamon Kingdom","s":39.1329,"e":27.1845,"b":-282,"d":-133,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Pergamon in western Anatolia was a remarkable Hellenistic state that transformed a minor fortress town into one of the ancient world's great cultural centres, featuring a library second only to Alexandria in scale and a sculptural tradition — most famously the Pergamon Altar — that represents the apogee of Hellenistic baroque artistic expression. Pergamene kings styled themselves champions of Greek civilisation against barbarism, commissioning the famous Dying Gaul sculpture to commemorate their defeats of Galatian raiders and positioning Pergamon as Athens' legitimate cultural heir in the Hellenistic world. The kingdom invented or perfected parchment — named from the city — as a writing material when Egypt reportedly restricted papyrus exports to limit Pergamon's library ambitions. The last Pergamene king Attalus III bequeathed his entire kingdom to Rome in 133 BCE, an act of unprecedented political generosity that created the Roman province of Asia."},
  {"id":713,"n":"Bithynian Kingdom","s":40.1826,"e":29.0609,"b":-297,"d":-74,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Bithynia in northwestern Anatolia was a Thracian-descended monarchy that leveraged its strategic position between the Black Sea and the Propontis to maintain independence through careful diplomacy between larger Hellenistic powers while developing a sophisticated Greek-influenced court culture. Bithynia's capital Nicomedia became one of the wealthiest cities of the Hellenistic east and later served as Diocletian's eastern imperial capital, its position at the crossroads of Anatolian land routes making it an administrative hub of enduring importance. The kingdom provided a refuge for Hannibal Barca in his final years after his defeat by Rome — the Carthaginian general died in Bithynia around 183 BCE rather than surrender to Roman demands for his extradition. The last Bithynian king Nicomedes IV bequeathed his kingdom to Rome in 74 BCE, creating the Roman province of Bithynia and Pontus."},
  {"id":714,"n":"Cappadocian Kingdom","s":38.6431,"e":34.8307,"b":-331,"d":17,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Cappadocia in the rugged interior of central Anatolia was an Iranian-influenced monarchy that maintained independence from the Seleucid Empire through a combination of strategic marriage alliances, the natural defensive advantages of its volcanic plateau landscape, and the economic value of its famous horse-breeding industry. Cappadocian horses were among the most prized in the ancient world, exported across the Near East and forming a major component of the tribute the kingdom paid to Persian and later Macedonian overlords. The region's distinctive volcanic landscape — the fairy chimneys and cave complexes of the Göreme valley — provided natural shelter that communities would exploit for centuries, including early Christian communities who carved entire underground cities into the soft tuff. The kingdom was incorporated into the Roman Empire as a province in 17 CE under Emperor Tiberius."},
  {"id":715,"n":"Armenian Kingdom","s":40.1811,"e":44.5136,"b":-190,"d":428,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Armenian Kingdom reached its greatest extent under Tigranes II the Great, who created a brief but formidable empire stretching from the Caspian to the Mediterranean between 95 and 66 BCE that made him the most powerful king in Asia until Pompey's legions shattered his power. Armenia became the first nation to adopt Christianity as its state religion in 301 CE under King Tiridates III and the influence of Gregory the Illuminator — predating Constantine's Roman recognition of Christianity by over a decade and establishing a Christian identity that has defined Armenian culture for seventeen centuries. The Armenian alphabet was created around 405 CE by the monk Mesrop Mashtots to facilitate Bible translation and literacy, becoming one of the ancient world's most deliberately designed scripts and the foundation of a rich literary tradition. The kingdom ended with Persian and Byzantine partition of Armenian territory in 428 CE, though Armenian cultural and political identity persisted through centuries of foreign rule."},
  {"id":716,"n":"Iberian Kingdom — Caucasian","s":41.6938,"e":44.8015,"b":-302,"d":580,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Iberia — entirely distinct from the Iberian Peninsula — was an ancient state in the South Caucasus occupying present-day eastern Georgia, positioned at the strategic crossroads between the Black Sea and Caspian Sea trade routes and contested by Rome, Parthia, and Persia throughout its existence. Iberia converted to Christianity in the 330s CE under King Mirian III, reportedly following the missionary activity of Saint Nino, making it one of the earliest Christian kingdoms in the world and cementing an Orthodox Christian identity that has defined Georgian civilisation ever since. The kingdom produced distinctive syncretic art combining Iranian, Hellenistic, and indigenous Caucasian traditions and maintained sophisticated diplomatic relations with both the Roman and Parthian empires through strategic flexibility. Sasanian Persian pressure increasingly dominated Iberia from the fourth century, and the kingdom was eventually absorbed into the Persian imperial system in 580 CE."},
  {"id":717,"n":"Albanian Kingdom — Caucasian","s":40.4093,"e":49.8671,"b":-300,"d":700,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Caucasian Albania — entirely unrelated to the modern Balkan state — was an ancient kingdom occupying present-day Azerbaijan and southern Dagestan, sandwiched between the Caucasus mountains and the Caspian Sea in one of antiquity's most strategically sensitive corridors. The kingdom developed its own distinctive alphabet of fifty-two letters, created around the fifth century CE for Christian liturgical use, examples of which were only definitively identified in palimpsest manuscripts at Saint Catherine's Monastery in Sinai in the 1990s. Caucasian Albania converted to Christianity in the fourth century and maintained a distinct church tradition — the Albanian Apostolic Church — before being absorbed progressively into Armenian and later Islamic cultural spheres. Arab conquest in the seventh and eighth centuries CE ended Caucasian Albanian political independence and began the Islamisation of the region."},
  {"id":718,"n":"Kushan-Sasanian Kingdom","s":35.0174,"e":69.1708,"b":230,"d":370,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kushan-Sasanian Kingdom was a successor state to the Kushan Empire in the Bactria-Gandhara region, established when Sasanian Persia conquered and administered the former Kushan territories through a branch of the Sasanian royal family who adopted Kushan royal titles and iconography. This hybrid state maintained the Silk Road commercial functions of its Kushan predecessor while grafting Zoroastrian religious traditions onto the existing Buddhist institutional framework, producing a distinctive syncretic culture reflected in coinage depicting both Zoroastrian fire altars and Buddhist symbols. The Kushan-Sasanian kingdom served as the crucial transmission belt for cultural exchanges between Iran, India, and Central Asia during a formative period for both Buddhist and Zoroastrian religious development. The kingdom was overthrown by the Kidarite Huns around 370 CE, beginning a new period of steppe-nomad dominance in the region."},
  {"id":719,"n":"Kidarite Kingdom","s":36.7069,"e":67.11,"b":320,"d":467,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kidarites were a nomadic people of probable Xiongnu or mixed Central Asian steppe origin who conquered the Kushan-Sasanian territories in Bactria and Gandhara around 320–360 CE, establishing a kingdom that continued the Silk Road commercial traditions of its Kushan predecessors while imposing steppe political structures. Their coinage, which imitated Kushan prototypes while incorporating distinctive Kidarite modifications, is the primary evidence for the kingdom's political history given the near-total absence of literary sources from the Kidarites themselves. The Kidarites maintained control of key Silk Road oases and the Hindu Kush passes that connected Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent, extracting tribute from surrounding polities and facilitating the continued exchange of luxury goods between east and west. The Hephthalite Huns displaced the Kidarites from their core territories around 467 CE."},
  {"id":720,"n":"Hephthalite Empire","s":37.55,"e":66.975,"b":420,"d":567,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Hephthalite Empire — known in Byzantine sources as the White Huns — was a major Central Asian power controlling Bactria, Sogdia, and Gandhara that successfully checked Sasanian Persian expansion eastward and invaded the Gupta Empire of India on multiple occasions, contributing to the Gupta collapse. The Hephthalites defied simple categorisation by ancient sources — Byzantine writers described them as settled and sophisticated despite their nomadic origins, while Indian sources portray them as destructive barbarians whose invasions devastated Buddhist monastery complexes in Gandhara and northwestern India. A joint Sasanian-Turkic military campaign destroyed the Hephthalite state around 557–567 CE, with the Göktürk khaganate absorbing the northern territories and Sasanian Persia recovering the southern lands. The dispersal of Hephthalite populations contributed to the ethnic and political complexity of the following centuries in Central Asia."},
  {"id":721,"n":"Gupta Empire","s":25.3176,"e":82.9739,"b":319,"d":550,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Gupta Empire is regarded as the Classical Age of Indian civilisation, a period of extraordinary intellectual, artistic, and scientific achievement during which the foundational texts of Hindu philosophy, mathematics, astronomy, and literature reached their canonical forms. The mathematician Aryabhata, working during the Gupta period around 499 CE, calculated the value of pi to four decimal places, described the Earth's rotation on its axis, and developed the concept of zero as a mathematical placeholder — achievements that would revolutionise mathematics when transmitted to the Islamic world and subsequently to Europe. Gupta court culture produced the plays of Kalidasa — considered the Shakespeare of Sanskrit literature — and the Kamasutra, and supported the flourishing of Buddhist institutions at Nalanda that attracted scholars from across Asia. Hephthalite invasions from the northwest progressively weakened the empire from the mid-fifth century, and it fragmented into regional successor kingdoms by 550 CE."},
  {"id":722,"n":"Pallava Dynasty","s":12.8185,"e":80.0339,"b":275,"d":897,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Pallava Dynasty of Tamil Nadu in southern India was a major Dravidian power that made Kanchipuram one of the great temple cities of the ancient world and developed the distinctive Dravidian architectural style — characterised by pyramidal gopuram gateway towers — that would define South Indian temple design for a millennium. Pallava kings were great patrons of Sanskrit scholarship, Tamil literature, and monumental rock-cut sculpture, commissioning the magnificent Shore Temple at Mamallapuram and the vast Descent of the Ganges relief — one of the largest open-air rock reliefs in the world. Pallava influence extended beyond India through maritime commercial and cultural contacts: the Pallava script was the direct ancestor of most Southeast Asian writing systems, including Thai, Khmer, Javanese, and Baybayin. The dynasty was defeated and absorbed by the Chola Empire in 897 CE."},
  {"id":723,"n":"Rashtrakuta Dynasty","s":17.385,"e":76.82,"b":753,"d":982,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Rashtrakuta Dynasty was one of the dominant powers of the Deccan plateau for over two centuries, controlling large swathes of present-day Maharashtra, Karnataka, and Andhra Pradesh and projecting military power into both northern and southern India with remarkable effectiveness. The dynasty's greatest monument — the Kailasa Temple at Ellora, carved downward into a basalt cliff face to create a freestanding rock-cut temple complex weighing an estimated 400,000 tonnes — is one of humanity's most extraordinary engineering achievements, completed under King Dantidurga's successors in the eighth century CE. Arab traders at the time called the Rashtrakuta king one of the four great kings of the world alongside the Caliph of Baghdad, the Emperor of China, and the Emperor of Byzantium. Internal conflict and military pressure from the Western Chalukyas of Kalyani ended the dynasty in 982 CE."},
  {"id":724,"n":"Chera Kingdom","s":10.5276,"e":76.2144,"b":-300,"d":1102,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Chera Kingdom was one of the three great Tamil kingdoms of antiquity — alongside Chola and Pandya — occupying the southwestern coast of India corresponding broadly to present-day Kerala and parts of Tamil Nadu, renowned for its pepper, cardamom, and ivory that made it a magnet for Roman, Arab, and Chinese maritime trade. Classical Tamil Sangam poetry, composed between approximately 300 BCE and 300 CE, provides remarkably detailed accounts of Chera court life, warfare, and landscape — among the most sophisticated bodies of ancient literature from any non-Mediterranean civilisation. The Chera port of Musiri (Muziris) was so busy with Roman shipping that a first-century CE papyrus merchant's contract found in Egypt references it directly, and Roman coin hoards of extraordinary scale have been excavated throughout Kerala. The kingdom experienced a revival as the later Chera (Kulasekhara) dynasty before being eclipsed by the rise of smaller Kerala chiefdoms in the twelfth century."},
  {"id":725,"n":"Chalukya Dynasty of Badami","s":15.9162,"e":75.677,"b":543,"d":753,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Chalukya Dynasty of Badami was the first great empire of the southern Deccan, controlling a vast territory spanning present-day Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh and producing one of early medieval India's most sophisticated artistic and architectural traditions in the cave temples and structural monuments of Badami, Aihole, and Pattadakal. The Chalukyas checked the northward expansion of the Pallavas in the south and repelled the southern advance of Harsha's empire in the north, positioning themselves as the dominant power of peninsular India for over two centuries. Aihole — with its seventy-odd temples representing every Hindu and Jain architectural style of the period — served as what scholars have called a living laboratory of Indian temple architecture, with builders experimenting across multiple forms before arriving at the mature Chalukya style. The dynasty was overthrown by their own Rashtrakuta feudatories in 753 CE."},
  {"id":726,"n":"Harsha's Empire","s":27.1767,"e":78.0081,"b":606,"d":647,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The empire of Harshavardhana was the last great Hindu empire to unite northern India before the Islamic conquests, briefly bringing most of the Gangetic plain and beyond under a single ruler who was himself a poet, playwright, and enthusiastic patron of Buddhism and Brahmanical scholarship. The Chinese Buddhist pilgrim Xuanzang visited Harsha's court and left a detailed account of the kingdom's prosperity, its elaborate court ceremonies, the wealth of its Buddhist monasteries, and the grandeur of the quinquennial Prayag assembly where Harsha distributed his entire accumulated treasury to religious institutions and the poor. Harsha's dramatic southward expansion was checked by the Chalukya king Pulakesi II at the Battle of the Narmada around 618 CE — one of the pivotal military engagements of early medieval India. The empire dissolved immediately upon Harsha's death in 647 CE with no successor capable of maintaining its unity."},
  {"id":728,"n":"Chola Empire — Imperial Phase","s":10.7905,"e":79.1378,"b":848,"d":1279,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Imperial Chola dynasty was medieval India's greatest maritime power, launching naval expeditions that reached the Malay Peninsula, Sumatra, and Sri Lanka and temporarily occupying portions of Southeast Asia in raids that demonstrated a naval reach unmatched by any contemporary Asian state. Rajendra Chola I's naval expedition of 1025 CE against Srivijaya — crossing the Bay of Bengal and raiding deep into Southeast Asian waters — has been called the greatest naval campaign in ancient Indian history. The Cholas were exceptional temple builders whose Brihadeeswarar Temple at Thanjavur, completed in 1010 CE, remains one of the largest Hindu temples ever constructed and houses a vimana tower rising sixty-six metres — the world's tallest at the time of its construction. The dynasty's administrative system of self-governing village assemblies (sabhas and ur) has been described as one of the ancient world's most sophisticated examples of local democratic governance."},
  {"id":729,"n":"Hoysala Empire","s":12.9716,"e":76.5222,"b":1026,"d":1343,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Hoysala Empire of the Karnataka Deccan produced what many art historians regard as the most intricate and refined tradition of stone sculpture in world history, covering every surface of their temples at Belur, Halebidu, and Somnathpur with extraordinarily detailed carvings of deities, celestial dancers, elephants, horses, and decorative friezes so densely worked that a single temple exterior can contain over a thousand individual sculptural compositions. Hoysala architecture is characterised by the star-shaped platform (jagati) on which temples stand, creating a multiplied set of projecting angles that cast ever-changing shadow patterns throughout the day. The empire maintained religious plurality, with Hoysala rulers variously patronising Shaivism, Vaishnavism, and Jainism without enforcing religious uniformity. The Hoysala state was destroyed by the Delhi Sultanate's Khalji and Tughlaq expeditions into the Deccan in the early fourteenth century."},
  {"id":735,"n":"Bahmani Sultanate","s":17.9689,"e":77.5195,"b":1347,"d":1527,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Bahmani Sultanate was the first independent Islamic sultanate in the Deccan, founded by a rebellion of Turkic amirs against Delhi Sultanate rule and establishing a cultural tradition that synthesised Persian, Turkic, and Deccani Hindu elements into the distinctive Deccani culture. The sultanate's capital Bidar became a major centre of Persian literary culture and Sufi spirituality, attracting scholars and mystics from Iran and Central Asia who established intellectual traditions that outlasted the sultanate itself. Mahmud Gawan, the Bidar-based prime minister who dominated the sultanate in the 1460s–1480s, was one of medieval India's most remarkable statesmen — a Persian merchant who rose to supreme power, reformed the administrative system, and founded a madrasa at Bidar that rivals any contemporary Islamic educational institution in architectural ambition. The sultanate fragmented into five successor states by 1490 and its last nominal sultan died in 1527."},
  {"id":736,"n":"Ahom Kingdom","s":26.7509,"e":94.2037,"b":1228,"d":1826,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Ahom Kingdom of Assam was one of the longest-lasting medieval kingdoms in South Asia, ruling the Brahmaputra valley for nearly six centuries and famously resisting seventeen successive Mughal military invasions — a record of sustained independence against the dominant imperial power of the age that has no parallel in South Asian history. The Ahoms originated as a Tai-Shan people who migrated from present-day Yunnan and maintained their distinctive ethnic identity, language, and religious traditions — including an indigenous Ahom religion alongside later adoption of Hinduism — throughout their long reign. The kingdom developed a sophisticated paik-based corvée labour system for maintaining its extensive river embankments, roads, and military infrastructure, and maintained detailed chronicles (buranjis) in both the Ahom and Assamese languages that are among South Asia's most comprehensive pre-modern historical records. The Anglo-Burmese War of 1824–1826 ended Ahom independence when the British annexed Assam."},
  {"id":737,"n":"Chiang Mai Kingdom — Lan Na","s":18.7883,"e":98.9853,"b":1292,"d":1775,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Lan Na Kingdom, centred on Chiang Mai in present-day northern Thailand, was an independent Tai Buddhist polity that developed a sophisticated court culture distinct from the kingdoms of central Thailand, producing a distinctive school of Buddhist art and a unique Lan Na script still used for certain ceremonial purposes today. Under King Tilokaraj in the fifteenth century, Lan Na reached its political and cultural zenith, hosting a major Buddhist council in 1477 that revised the Pali Tipitaka canon and positioning Chiang Mai as one of Southeast Asia's most important Theravada Buddhist intellectual centres. The kingdom maintained independence from successive Burmese and Siamese imperial pressures for nearly five centuries through a combination of mountain geography, diplomatic flexibility, and military resilience. Burmese conquest in 1558 began two centuries of Burmese overlordship before Siamese liberation in 1775."},
  {"id":738,"n":"Ayutthaya Kingdom","s":14.3528,"e":100.5683,"b":1351,"d":1767,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Ayutthaya Kingdom was the dominant Siamese state for over four centuries, positioned at the confluence of three rivers in the Chao Phraya delta and developing into one of Southeast Asia's wealthiest and most cosmopolitan trading cities, hosting communities of Chinese, Japanese, Persian, Portuguese, Dutch, and French merchants. At its peak in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries Ayutthaya was among the largest cities in the world with a population exceeding a million, its floating markets and temple-studded skyline astonishing European visitors. The kingdom absorbed the Khmer concept of devaraja — god-king — into Theravada Buddhist kingship ideology, creating a court ceremonial of extraordinary elaborateness that enhanced royal authority across the diverse population. Burma's Konbaung dynasty sacked and destroyed Ayutthaya in 1767 in one of Southeast Asia's most catastrophic acts of deliberate cultural destruction, melting down centuries of golden Buddha images and burning the royal archives."},
  {"id":739,"n":"Sukhothai Kingdom","s":17.0154,"e":99.8237,"b":1238,"d":1438,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Sukhothai Kingdom is regarded as the first Thai state and the cradle of Thai civilisation, remembered primarily for King Ramkhamhaeng's invention of the Thai script around 1283 CE and for an inscription attributed to him that provides the earliest first-person description of Thai governance, society, and daily life. The kingdom developed a distinctive school of Buddhist sculpture characterised by the walking Buddha image — the Buddha mid-stride with a hand raised in blessing — a form that achieved an unmatched quality of spiritual dynamism in Sukhothai workshops. Sukhothai art and architecture, including the remarkable ruined temple complex at the historical park, represent a moment of unusual cultural clarity before the more complex syncretic traditions of Ayutthaya absorbed and transformed Thai civilisation. The kingdom was peacefully absorbed into the expanding Ayutthaya polity in 1438."},
  {"id":742,"n":"Singhasari Kingdom","s":-7.9111,"e":112.6044,"b":1222,"d":1292,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Singhasari Kingdom of East Java was the direct predecessor of the Majapahit Empire, reaching its height under the charismatic and ruthless King Kertanagara who pursued an ambitious pan-Maritime Southeast Asian policy of alliance and projection of power across the Java Sea. Kertanagara dispatched an armed mission to Pahang on the Malay Peninsula, sent images of the Buddhist deity Amoghapasa to the king of Dharmasraya in Sumatra as a diplomatic gift, and actively cultivated relations with China while simultaneously insulting a Mongol envoy — an act of deliberate provocation that triggered the Mongol invasion of Java in 1292. The kingdom produced remarkable syncretic art combining Shaivite and Buddhist elements in a characteristically Javanese fusion, and Kertanagara himself was venerated as a Tantric adept who identified himself with the deity Bhairava. The Singhasari state collapsed when a Javanese rebel allied with the Mongol invaders killed Kertanagara in 1292, but his son-in-law Raden Wijaya subsequently defeated the Mongols and founded Majapahit."},
  {"id":743,"n":"Mataram Sultanate","s":-7.8014,"e":110.3647,"b":1587,"d":1755,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Mataram Sultanate was the dominant Javanese Islamic state of the seventeenth century, controlling most of Java under Sultan Agung and mounting two unsuccessful sieges of the Dutch East India Company's fortified trading post at Batavia in 1628 and 1629 in the most ambitious military campaigns mounted by any Southeast Asian state against European colonial power. Sultan Agung was a sophisticated ruler who combined Islamic piety with deep engagement in Javanese Hindu-Buddhist mystical traditions, created the Javanese calendar system still in use for ceremonial purposes, and patronised the development of the wayang kulit shadow puppet tradition as a vehicle for both religious instruction and political legitimation. The Dutch East India Company systematically exploited Mataram's succession disputes, extracting ever-greater territorial and commercial concessions in exchange for military support in dynastic conflicts. The Treaty of Giyanti in 1755 split Mataram into two courts — Yogyakarta and Surakarta — effectively ending Javanese political unity."},
  {"id":744,"n":"Lan Xang Kingdom","s":17.9757,"e":102.6331,"b":1353,"d":1707,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"Lan Xang — the Kingdom of a Million Elephants — was one of the largest kingdoms in Southeast Asia during its peak in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, encompassing most of present-day Laos and parts of northeastern Thailand and Yunnan and maintained as a coherent state through the royal cult of the Phra Bang Buddha image and the political authority of Theravada Buddhism. The kingdom served as a crucial buffer zone between the competing imperial ambitions of Burma, Vietnam, and the Ayutthaya Siamese state, maintaining independence through diplomatic flexibility and the natural defensive advantages of its mountainous and forested terrain. Under King Setthathirath in the sixteenth century, Vientiane was built as the new capital and the magnificent That Luang stupa was constructed as the national religious symbol of Lao identity that it remains to this day. Internal succession wars fragmented Lan Xang into three competing kingdoms — Luang Prabang, Vientiane, and Champassak — in 1707."},
  {"id":745,"n":"Burmese Pagan Successors — Ava Kingdom","s":21.8456,"e":95.9909,"b":1364,"d":1555,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Ava was the dominant post-Pagan Burman state in the dry zone of central Burma, claiming the legacy of Pagan and competing with the Mon kingdom of Pegu for supremacy over the Irrawaddy valley in a series of wars that occupied most of the fifteenth century without decisive resolution. Ava was a major centre of Burmese literary culture, particularly during the Innwa period, producing classical poetry, court chronicles, and Buddhist scholarship that established the canon of classical Burmese literary language. The kingdom's military weakness was exposed when the Shan states of the northeast fragmented Ava's authority in the 1520s and the kingdom fell to the Toungoo dynasty in 1555. The city of Inwa (Ava) remained symbolically important to Burmese royal legitimacy — subsequent dynasties periodically relocated their capitals there — until the nineteenth century."},
  {"id":746,"n":"Toungoo Empire","s":18.9311,"e":96.4606,"b":1510,"d":1752,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Toungoo Empire was the largest empire in the history of Southeast Asia at its brief peak under Bayinnaung in the 1560s, encompassing all of present-day Myanmar, much of Thailand, Laos, and parts of Yunnan in an empire that proved impossible to administer effectively across such diverse terrain and populations. Bayinnaung's construction of the new capital at Pegu created a city of extraordinary splendour described by European visitors as the most magnificent in Asia, featuring a royal palace complex of gilded spires and forty-two white elephants — the sacred possession that symbolised supreme royal power in Southeast Asian political culture. The empire facilitated the spread of Theravada Buddhism across mainland Southeast Asia through Bayinnaung's requirement that conquered rulers adopt Buddhist practices and sponsor temple construction. Restored Toungoo dynasty kings ruled a more compact Burmese state from 1597 until the Konbaung dynasty's rise in 1752."},
  {"id":747,"n":"Konbaung Dynasty","s":21.9588,"e":96.0891,"b":1752,"d":1885,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Konbaung dynasty was the last royal dynasty of Burma, founded by Alaungpaya and reaching its greatest territorial extent through the conquest of the Ayutthaya Kingdom in 1767 and subsequent campaigns into Assam, Manipur, and Arakan that brought Burma into direct territorial conflict with British India. The dynasty's aggressive territorial expansion in Assam and its treatment of British commercial interests triggered the three Anglo-Burmese Wars of 1824–26, 1852, and 1885, each resulting in the loss of further territory until the final annexation of Upper Burma and deposition of King Thibaw by Lord Dufferin in 1885. King Mindon Min, who reigned 1853–1878, was one of Burma's most enlightened monarchs, founding the new capital at Mandalay, convening the Fifth Buddhist Council, introducing postal and telegraph services, and attempting modernising reforms in the face of British colonial encroachment. The dynasty ended with Thibaw's exile to India in 1885."},
  {"id":748,"n":"Ryukyu Kingdom","s":26.2124,"e":127.6809,"b":1429,"d":1879,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Ryukyu Kingdom was a maritime trading state centred on the island of Okinawa that unified the Ryukyu archipelago in 1429 and became one of the most important commercial intermediaries in East and Southeast Asian trade, maintaining formal tributary relations with China, Japan, Korea, and numerous Southeast Asian states simultaneously. Ryukyuan merchant ships flew a flag reading 'Ryukyu is a blessed land situated in the southern seas; its culture and tradition are a product of China and Japan' — a declaration of cultural synthesis that accurately describes the kingdom's deliberate self-positioning as a bridge between the major East Asian civilisations. The kingdom's Shuri Castle in Naha was the centre of a refined court culture that synthesised Chinese, Japanese, and indigenous Ryukyuan elements in music, dance, and the visual arts. Japan's Satsuma domain invaded and occupied Ryukyu in 1609 while allowing a fiction of independence for trade purposes; the kingdom was formally annexed as Okinawa Prefecture in 1879."},
  {"id":754,"n":"Balhae Kingdom","s":44.555,"e":129.6169,"b":698,"d":926,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Balhae Kingdom was a multi-ethnic state founded by Dae Joyeong — a leader of the Mohe people and possibly of Goguryeo descent — in the aftermath of Goguryeo's destruction, occupying Manchuria, the Russian Far East, and the northern Korean peninsula for over two centuries. Balhae was referred to by Japan as the 'flourishing land of the East' and by Tang China as a 'sea of prosperity,' and maintained active diplomatic and commercial relations with Tang China, Japan, and the steppe peoples to its north. The kingdom was culturally sophisticated, its aristocracy educated in Tang Chinese literary and administrative traditions, and its material culture — reflected in remarkable bronze and gold artefacts — demonstrating a high level of artistic achievement. The Khitan Liao dynasty destroyed Balhae in a single campaign in 926 CE, and many of its ruling class fled south to the Goryeo kingdom."},
  {"id":758,"n":"Ming Dynasty","s":32.0603,"e":118.7969,"b":1368,"d":1644,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Ming Dynasty restored Han Chinese rule after nearly a century of Mongol Yuan domination, presiding over a period of remarkable state-building, economic recovery, and cultural consolidation in which China's population more than doubled to approximately 200 million by the dynasty's end. The Yongle Emperor's sponsorship of Zheng He's seven extraordinary naval expeditions between 1405 and 1433 dispatched the world's largest fleet — vessels four times the size of Columbus's ships — across the Indian Ocean to Arabia and East Africa, an assertion of Chinese maritime power that was subsequently abandoned when Confucian officials prevailed in arguing against continued maritime expenditure. The Forbidden City, constructed by the Yongle Emperor between 1406 and 1420, remains the world's largest palace complex — 980 buildings covering 180 acres — and the supreme expression of Chinese imperial architecture. The dynasty collapsed under the combined pressure of internal peasant rebellion, Manchu military pressure, and the devastating economic disruption caused by the Little Ice Age's impact on Chinese agriculture."},
  {"id":760,"n":"Yuan Dynasty — Mongol China","s":40,"e":116.3833,"b":1271,"d":1368,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Yuan Dynasty was the Mongol-ruled imperial dynasty of China established by Kublai Khan, representing the first time all of China had been ruled by a non-Han dynasty and forming the Chinese portion of the vast Mongol Empire that stretched from Korea to Poland at its maximum extent. Kublai Khan's court at Khanbaliq (modern Beijing) was described by Marco Polo with barely credible superlatives — its wealth, scale, and administrative sophistication exceeded anything in the European experience — and the Yuan court attracted scholars, merchants, and craftsmen from across Eurasia in perhaps the most cosmopolitan court in world history. The Pax Mongolica — the relative peace and security across the Mongol-controlled Silk Road — enabled an unprecedented volume of long-distance trade and cultural exchange between East Asia and the Islamic world and Europe, including the transmission of Chinese technologies such as printing and gunpowder westward. The dynasty was overthrown by the Han Chinese rebel Zhu Yuanzhang in 1368, who founded the Ming dynasty and expelled the Mongols to the steppe."},
  {"id":761,"n":"Han Dynasty","s":34.3416,"e":108.9398,"b":-206,"d":220,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Han Dynasty established the institutional, cultural, and ethnic foundations of Chinese civilisation in a form so enduring that the majority ethnic group of China calls itself Han to this day, four centuries after the dynasty's fall. Han Emperor Wu's expansion of China's borders to include Xinjiang, Vietnam, and Korea, his establishment of the Silk Road as a formal commercial route, and his adoption of Confucianism as the state ideology created the framework within which Chinese political culture would operate for two thousand years. The Han invented paper around 105 CE under the court eunuch Cai Lun, developed the seismoscope — the world's first earthquake detection instrument — and produced the Shiji of Sima Qian, considered the foundational text of Chinese historiography. The dynasty collapsed into the Three Kingdoms period following decades of peasant rebellion, eunuch political dominance, and warlord fragmentation after 184 CE."},
  {"id":762,"n":"Qin Dynasty","s":34.2658,"e":108.9541,"b":-221,"d":-206,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Qin Dynasty achieved the first unification of China under a single imperial authority in 221 BCE under Qin Shi Huang, who standardised weights, measures, coinage, axle widths, and the written script across a territory that had previously comprised seven warring kingdoms — creating the administrative and cultural unity that defined China ever after. The First Emperor's tomb complex at Mount Li — guarded by the famous Terracotta Army of approximately eight thousand life-sized ceramic soldiers, horses, and chariots — was the most ambitious funerary construction in world history, and ancient accounts suggest it contained an entire model of his empire complete with rivers of flowing mercury. The dynasty initiated the first connected sections of what would become the Great Wall, linked existing walls of the former kingdoms into a unified northern defensive system. Despite its transformative historical importance the dynasty lasted only fifteen years after the First Emperor's death in 210 BCE, collapsing under the weight of its own brutal overreach."},
  {"id":768,"n":"Uyghur Khaganate","s":48,"e":101,"b":744,"d":840,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Uyghur Khaganate replaced the Göktürks as the dominant power of the Mongolian steppe, crucially allying with the Tang dynasty to help suppress the An Lushan Rebellion of 755–763 CE — a service for which the Uyghurs extracted enormous commercial concessions, forcing China to exchange silk for Uyghur horses at unfavourable rates that transferred enormous wealth to the steppe. The Uyghur khagan Bögü converted to Manichaeism around 762 CE following encounters with Manichaean priests in Luoyang, making the Uyghur Khaganate one of the very few states to officially adopt Manichaeism and facilitating a remarkable flourishing of Manichaean art and religious life across the steppe. The Uyghur script — derived from the Sogdian alphabet — became the script of steppe literacy for centuries, with the Mongols adopting a modified version that remains the basis of traditional Mongolian writing to this day. Yenisei Kirghiz forces destroyed the khaganate in 840 CE, scattering Uyghur populations across Central Asia and Ganzhou."},
  {"id":769,"n":"Khitan Liao Dynasty","s":42.858,"e":120.966,"b":907,"d":1125,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Khitan Liao Dynasty was a conquest dynasty ruling Manchuria, Mongolia, and the sixteen northern Chinese prefectures simultaneously, developing a distinctive dual administrative system that governed the pastoral nomadic Khitan population according to steppe customs while administering the settled Chinese population according to Confucian bureaucratic norms — a solution to the problem of ruling radically different populations that influenced subsequent conquest dynasties. The Khitans created their own script — both a large and a small version — though both remain only partially deciphered, making Khitan one of the most tantalising undeciphered writing systems of the pre-modern world. Khitan political and cultural influence extended far beyond its military reach: the Persian and Arabic word for China — Khitai or Cathay — derives from Khitan, reflecting their dominance of the eastern Eurasian world in the tenth and eleventh centuries. The Jurchen Jin dynasty destroyed the Liao in 1125 CE, with some Khitan fleeing west to found the Qara Khitai state in Central Asia."},
  {"id":770,"n":"Jurchen Jin Dynasty","s":45.7433,"e":126.6331,"b":1115,"d":1234,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Jurchen Jin Dynasty was a conquest dynasty established by the Jurchen people of Manchuria that destroyed the Khitan Liao, conquered northern China from the Song dynasty, and created a powerful state that controlled northern China for over a century before the Mongol onslaught. The Jin dynasty developed a writing system for the Jurchen language — both large and small scripts — and created a sophisticated Sinicised administration that balanced Jurchen military aristocracy with Chinese civil bureaucracy in a dual system of governance similar to the Liao. The dynasty's destruction at the hands of the Mongols — who prosecuted the conquest of Jin with particular ferocity, reportedly in revenge for earlier Jin mistreatment of Genghis Khan's ancestors — resulted in massive depopulation of northern China, with some estimates suggesting northern China's population fell by 30–40 million during the Jin-Mongol wars. The last Jin emperor committed suicide in 1234 CE when the final Jin capital Caizhou fell to combined Mongol-Song forces."},
  {"id":771,"n":"Western Xia Kingdom","s":38.4682,"e":106.2729,"b":1038,"d":1227,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Western Xia Kingdom was a Tangut state occupying the upper Yellow River basin and the Gansu corridor — the critical chokepoint of the eastern Silk Road — that maintained independence from both Song China and the Liao and Jin dynasties for nearly two centuries through a combination of strategic geographic positioning and sophisticated administration. The Tangut people created their own script — a complex system of over 6,000 characters that combined Chinese structural principles with original elements — and a distinctive Buddhist art tradition that synthesised Chinese, Tibetan, and Central Asian elements in a style of remarkable refinement. Western Xia's control of the Gansu corridor allowed it to extract tolls from Silk Road trade and maintain commercial relationships with the Islamic world, Tibet, and both Chinese and steppe powers simultaneously. Genghis Khan's final campaign was against Western Xia, and the kingdom was completely destroyed in 1227 — its population massacred and its civilisation so thoroughly obliterated that the Tangut language remained undeciphered until the twentieth century."},
  {"id":773,"n":"Golden Horde Khanate","s":48.5,"e":54,"b":1242,"d":1502,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Golden Horde was the western successor khanate of the Mongol Empire, controlling the Pontic-Caspian steppe, Crimea, and nominally suzerainty over the Russian principalities for over two centuries in a political relationship that profoundly shaped the emerging Russian state. Russian princes were required to travel to the Horde's capital Sarai on the lower Volga to receive their patents of rule (yarlyks) and pay tribute — a humiliation and political dependency that Russian historical memory transformed into the 'Tatar Yoke,' a formative trauma that influenced Russian political culture's emphasis on strong centralised authority as protection against foreign domination. The Golden Horde converted to Islam under Khan Özbeg in 1313 CE, aligning the western steppe with the wider Islamic world and facilitating commercial ties with the Mamluk Sultanate of Egypt. The Horde fragmented under Timur's devastating campaigns in 1395–1396 and the resulting succession conflicts, dissolving into successor khanates by the early sixteenth century."},
  {"id":774,"n":"Ilkhanate","s":35.6892,"e":51.389,"b":1256,"d":1335,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Ilkhanate was the Mongol successor state in Persia and the Middle East, established after Hulagu Khan's destruction of Baghdad in 1258 and the extinction of the Abbasid Caliphate — an event experienced across the Islamic world as a civilisational catastrophe comparable to nothing since the Arab conquests. The Ilkhans proved remarkably receptive to Iranian and Islamic culture, converting to Islam under Ghazan Khan in 1295 and patronising a brilliant cultural Renaissance in Persian painting, historiography, and scientific illustration that represents one of the high points of Iranian civilisation. Persian historiographers working under Ilkhanid patronage — particularly Rashid al-Din Hamadani — produced the first attempt at a genuine world history, the Jami' al-Tawarikh, which drew on Chinese, Indian, European, and Islamic sources to create a synthesis of unprecedented geographic scope. The Ilkhanate fragmented after Ghazan's death in 1335 with no clear successor, its territory absorbed by competing local dynasties."},
  {"id":778,"n":"Mamluk Sultanate","s":30.0444,"e":31.2357,"b":1250,"d":1517,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Mamluk Sultanate of Egypt was established by slave-soldiers of Turkic and Caucasian origin who overthrew the Ayyubid dynasty, and became the most militarily effective Muslim state of the medieval period — the force that halted the Mongol advance at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, the first decisive defeat of a Mongol army in open battle, and subsequently expelled the last Crusader states from the Levant. The Mamluks preserved the Abbasid Caliphate as a ceremonial institution in Cairo after Hulagu's destruction of Baghdad, providing the Sunni Islamic world with a symbolic religious centre that legitimised Mamluk authority across the Muslim world. Cairo under the Mamluks was the largest city in the Islamic world and one of the most intellectually vibrant, home to the historian Ibn Khaldun who developed a theory of historical sociology in his Muqaddimah that has been described as the first work of social science. The Ottoman Sultan Selim I conquered and annexed the Mamluk Sultanate in 1517, transferring the symbolic caliphate to Ottoman hands."},
  {"id":779,"n":"Ayyubid Sultanate","s":33.5102,"e":36.2913,"b":1171,"d":1260,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Ayyubid Sultanate was founded by Saladin — Salah ad-Din Yusuf ibn Ayyub — the Kurdish Muslim ruler whose recapture of Jerusalem from the Crusaders in 1187 CE made him the most celebrated military and political figure in medieval Islamic history and the dominant symbol of Muslim resistance to Latin Christian expansion in the Levant. Saladin's chivalrous conduct toward his defeated Christian enemies — ensuring safe passage for civilians, ransoming poor captives, and returning relics to Orthodox Christians — created a legendary reputation that was extensively celebrated in both Islamic and Christian literary traditions and transformed him into a figure of pan-Mediterranean admiration. The Ayyubid state was deliberately administered as a loose family confederation of principalities rather than a centralised monarchy, creating structural fragility that made it vulnerable to internal succession conflicts. The Mamluk slave soldiers who overthrew the Ayyubids in 1250 had originally been recruited by the Ayyubids themselves as military specialists."},
  {"id":784,"n":"Rashidun Caliphate","s":24.6877,"e":46.7219,"b":632,"d":661,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Rashidun Caliphate was the first Islamic state following the death of the Prophet Muhammad, governed by four 'rightly guided' caliphs — Abu Bakr, Umar, Uthman, and Ali — whose three decades of rule saw Islam expand from the Arabian Peninsula to encompass Egypt, Syria, Iraq, Persia, and the Caucasus in one of the most rapid and consequential territorial expansions in world history. Caliph Umar's administrative genius — establishing the diwan system for distributing conquered wealth, organising the garrison cities of Kufa and Basra, and developing Islamic legal principles — created the institutional foundations on which all subsequent Islamic caliphates would build. The caliphate's rapid conquest of Byzantine Syria and Sasanian Persia was facilitated by the exhaustion of both empires after decades of mutual warfare, the tactical superiority of Arab cavalry and infantry, and in many cases the genuine welcome of local populations for whom the Arab conquerors represented lighter taxation and greater religious tolerance than their predecessors. The murder of Caliph Uthman and the subsequent civil war between Ali and Muawiyah produced the Sunni-Shia split that remains Islam's most fundamental division."},
  {"id":785,"n":"Al-Andalus","s":37.3891,"e":-5.9845,"b":711,"d":1492,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"Al-Andalus was the Islamic civilisation of the Iberian Peninsula, at its height under the Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba one of the most sophisticated and prosperous societies in the world — a multicultural convivencia of Muslims, Christians, and Jews that produced extraordinary achievements in philosophy, medicine, agriculture, and architecture while the rest of Europe endured the relative poverty of the Dark Ages. The city of Córdoba under Abd al-Rahman III was Europe's largest city, with a population exceeding 500,000, a library of over 400,000 volumes, and street lighting centuries before any other European city — the contrast with contemporary London or Paris was almost incomprehensible. Scholars of al-Andalus — both Muslim and Jewish — were the primary conduit through which ancient Greek philosophy, Islamic science, and mathematical innovations including algebra and the decimal system reached medieval Europe, effectively creating the intellectual preconditions for the European Renaissance and Scientific Revolution. The fall of the last Islamic kingdom of Granada in 1492 — the same year Columbus sailed — ended nearly eight centuries of Islamic presence in Iberia."},
  {"id":786,"n":"Mali Sundiata — Early Phase","s":11.8636,"e":-8.7302,"b":1235,"d":1312,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The founding phase of the Mali Empire under Sundiata Keita represents one of West Africa's most celebrated episodes of state formation, in which a young prince of the Keita clan — reportedly a cripple who miraculously recovered the use of his limbs — defeated the Sosso king Sumanguru Kante at the Battle of Kirina in 1235 and established the framework for the wealthiest empire in African history. The Epic of Sundiata, transmitted orally by the griot caste of professional praise-singers and historians, is one of sub-Saharan Africa's greatest literary monuments — a heroic narrative comparable in its cultural function to the Iliad or the Mahabharata that continues to define Mande cultural identity across West Africa today. Sundiata's administrative genius lay in his federation of existing chieftains as allied lords rather than conquered subjects, creating a politically flexible structure that channelled existing loyalties into the new imperial framework. This entry represents the founding and early Mali period prior to the Mansa Musa era already recorded in the archive."},
  {"id":787,"n":"Mamluk Sultanate of Delhi","s":28.6139,"e":77.209,"b":1206,"d":1290,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Mamluk Sultanate of Delhi — also called the Slave Dynasty — was the first of the five dynasties comprising the Delhi Sultanate, founded by Qutb ud-Din Aibak, a former slave-general of Muhammad of Ghor who established the first permanent Islamic state in the Indian subcontinent. The Qutb Minar in Delhi — a 73-metre minaret begun by Qutb ud-Din Aibak and completed by his successors — is the tallest brick minaret in the world and the centrepiece of the Qutb complex, a monument that physically embodied the new Islamic power's assertion of dominance over the Hindu and Jain temples whose materials were incorporated into its construction. Sultan Iltutmish transformed Delhi from a garrison camp into a genuine imperial capital and secured recognition from the Abbasid Caliph in Baghdad — giving the Delhi Sultanate a legitimacy in the Islamic world that reinforced its authority. The dynasty ended when the nobles placed Jalal ud-Din Khalji on the throne in 1290."},
  {"id":789,"n":"Byzantine Successor States","s":39.9179,"e":26.252,"b":1204,"d":1461,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Byzantine Successor States — principally the Empire of Nicaea, the Despotate of Epirus, and the Empire of Trebizond — emerged following the catastrophic Fourth Crusade's sack of Constantinople in 1204, which diverted a crusade against Egypt into the conquest and looting of the Christian Byzantine capital in one of medieval history's most consequential acts of geopolitical betrayal. The Empire of Nicaea under the Laskaris and Palaeologos dynasties maintained Byzantine political, legal, and ecclesiastical traditions in exile and successfully reconquered Constantinople in 1261 under Michael VIII Palaeologos. The Empire of Trebizond on the Black Sea coast, founded by descendants of the Komnenos dynasty, survived as an independent state for the longest period, finally falling to the Ottoman Sultan Mehmed II in 1461 — eight years after the fall of Constantinople — representing the absolute last ember of the Roman imperial tradition."},
  {"id":790,"n":"Almohad Caliphate","s":31.6295,"e":-7.9811,"b":1121,"d":1269,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Almohad Caliphate was a Berber Muslim dynasty from the Atlas Mountains of Morocco that conquered the Almoravid Empire and unified North Africa and al-Andalus under a rigidly puritanical Islamic reform movement, creating the largest empire in western Islam and inadvertently triggering the intellectual flourishing that produced the philosopher Averroes and the Jewish thinker Maimonides — both of whom worked in Almohad Córdoba and both of whom were eventually forced into exile by Almohad religious intolerance. Averroes' commentaries on Aristotle, written in Córdoba under the Almohads, became the primary vehicle through which Aristotelian philosophy re-entered Western European thought, directly enabling the Scholastic movement of Albert the Great and Thomas Aquinas — making the Almohad period paradoxically crucial to the European intellectual tradition despite its political hostility to non-Muslim scholarship. The Almohad defeat at Las Navas de Tolosa in 1212 CE by a coalition of Christian Iberian kingdoms was the decisive turning point in the Reconquista, permanently shifting the military balance in Iberia toward the Christian kingdoms. The caliphate dissolved into competing Berber dynasties by 1269."},
  {"id":791,"n":"Almoravid Dynasty","s":31.7917,"e":-7.0926,"b":1040,"d":1147,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Almoravid Dynasty was a Berber Muslim reform movement originating among the Sanhaja confederation of the western Sahara that unified Morocco and al-Andalus under a single Islamic authority and halted the Christian Reconquista at a critical moment by crossing into Iberia in 1086 at the invitation of the Andalusian taifa kings. The Almoravids defeated Alfonso VI of Castile at the Battle of Sagrajas in 1086, reversing the momentum of Christian expansion and buying al-Andalus another century of Islamic rule. The dynasty's origins lay in a ribat — a fortified monastery-garrison — on an island in the Senegal River, founded by the Maliki scholar Abdallah ibn Yasin to reform the religious practice of the Sanhaja Berbers according to strict Maliki Islamic law. The Almoravids were eventually overthrown by the even more puritanical Almohad movement from the Atlas Mountains, ending a dynasty whose original desert austerity had softened considerably through contact with Andalusian luxury."},
  {"id":792,"n":"Hafsid Sultanate","s":36.819,"e":10.1658,"b":1229,"d":1574,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Hafsid Sultanate was the most powerful and long-lived of the Almohad successor states, ruling Tunisia and eastern Algeria for over three centuries from Tunis and claiming at its height a nominal suzerainty over the entire Almohad inheritance including al-Andalus. The Hafsids maintained Tunis as a major intellectual and commercial centre of the medieval Islamic world, patronising Arabic scholarship, Maliki jurisprudence, and the architectural tradition of iwan-and-courtyard religious buildings that characterise the Tunis medina to this day. The historian Ibn Khaldun was born in Hafsid Tunis in 1332 CE and served as a court official before his wider travels — the intellectual environment of Hafsid North Africa directly shaped his revolutionary historical methodology. Ottoman naval forces conquered Tunis in 1574, ending the Hafsid sultanate and incorporating North Africa into the Ottoman provincial system."},
  {"id":793,"n":"Marinid Dynasty","s":34.0209,"e":-5.0097,"b":1244,"d":1465,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Marinid Dynasty was a Berber Muslim state that succeeded the Almohads in Morocco, ruling from Fez and sponsoring one of the most intensive periods of religious and architectural construction in North African history — including the Bou Inania Madrasa in Fez, considered the finest example of Moroccan Islamic architecture, and the renovation of the Qarawiyyin mosque complex in Fez, home to the world's oldest continuously operating university. The Marinids made multiple attempts to extend their power across the Strait of Gibraltar into al-Andalus, briefly occupying Algeciras and Gibraltar in the fourteenth century, but were unable to sustain control against the combined pressure of Castilian and Aragonese resistance. The dynasty patronised the great geographer and traveller Ibn Battuta, who departed from Marinid Tangier in 1325 CE on the journey that would take him across the entire Islamic world and beyond — his Rihla remains the most comprehensive geographical account of the medieval world. The Marinids were overthrown by the Wattasid dynasty in 1465."},
  {"id":794,"n":"Zayyanid Kingdom","s":35.6969,"e":-0.6331,"b":1235,"d":1556,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Zayyanid Kingdom — also called the Kingdom of Tlemcen — was a Berber Muslim state in western Algeria that maintained a precarious independence between its larger neighbours the Marinids of Morocco and the Hafsids of Tunisia for over three centuries through careful diplomatic balancing. Tlemcen under the Zayyanids was a prosperous commercial and intellectual city, positioned on the major trans-Saharan trade route connecting West Africa to the Mediterranean and serving as the primary northern terminus for the gold and enslaved people routes from the Sahel. The kingdom produced notable scholars including the Sufi mystic and philosopher Ibn Maryam and maintained a sophisticated court culture that drew on both the Andalusian literary heritage and indigenous Berber traditions. The Ottoman corsair Aruj Barbarossa and his brother Khair ad-Din gradually extended Ottoman influence along the North African coast, and the last Zayyanid sultan submitted to Ottoman overlordship in 1556."},
  {"id":795,"n":"Idrisid Dynasty","s":34.0549,"e":-5.01,"b":788,"d":974,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Idrisid Dynasty was the first major Islamic state in the Maghreb, founded by Idris I — a descendant of Ali ibn Abi Talib, the Prophet Muhammad's son-in-law — who fled the Abbasid massacre of the Alid family and established a Shia-sympathetic kingdom in Morocco that became the foundation of Moroccan national and religious identity. Idris II founded the city of Fez in 808–809 CE, which rapidly grew into one of the medieval world's great cities and the enduring intellectual and spiritual capital of Morocco — the founding of Fez is considered the foundational moment of Moroccan civilisation. The Qarawiyyin mosque-university in Fez, founded in 859 CE by Fatima al-Fihri — a woman — is recognised by UNESCO and the Guinness World Records as the world's oldest continuously operating university, predating Bologna and Oxford by centuries. The Idrisid state fragmented into competing principalities after 928 CE and the dynasty's nominal authority ended with the last Idrisid ruler's submission to the Fatimids in 974."},
  {"id":796,"n":"Aghlabid Emirate","s":35.6781,"e":10.0993,"b":800,"d":909,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Aghlabid Emirate was an autonomous Arab dynasty that ruled Tunisia, eastern Algeria, and Sicily on behalf of the Abbasid Caliphate, transforming the central Mediterranean through the conquest of Sicily (827–902 CE) and raids into the Italian mainland that reached as far as Rome in 846 CE and sacked the Basilica of Saint Peter. The Aghlabid conquest of Sicily created a multicultural Islamic Sicilian emirate that became one of the medieval world's most sophisticated societies, synthesising Arab, Byzantine, Berber, and Norman influences in an environment where Greek, Arabic, and Latin were all in use simultaneously. Aghlabid Tunisia was a major centre of Maliki Islamic scholarship and the great mosque of Kairouan — founded during the initial Arab conquest and substantially rebuilt under the Aghlabids — remains one of the oldest and most important mosques in North Africa. The Fatimid revolution overthrew the Aghlabids in 909 CE."},
  {"id":797,"n":"Zirid Dynasty","s":36.819,"e":10.1658,"b":972,"d":1148,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Zirid Dynasty was a Berber Islamic state that began as Fatimid governors of North Africa before declaring independence in 1048 CE, a decision that provoked the Fatimid Caliph al-Mustansir to unleash the Banu Hilal and Banu Sulaym Arab tribal confederations on Tunisia in one of the most consequential acts of deliberate demographic engineering in medieval history. The Banu Hilal migration, which Ibn Khaldun compared to a swarm of locusts devastating everything in its path, transformed the ethnic and linguistic composition of North Africa — replacing settled Berber agricultural populations with Arab pastoral nomads in a process that fundamentally Arabised the Maghreb and created the linguistic landscape of modern Tunisia, Libya, and western Egypt. The Zirid emirate of Granada in al-Andalus — a separate branch — produced the Jewish philosopher Samuel ibn Naghrela, who served as vizier and military commander while writing Hebrew poetry of extraordinary quality. The Almohads ended the last Zirid authority in 1148."},
  {"id":798,"n":"Hammadid Dynasty","s":36.365,"e":4.628,"b":1007,"d":1152,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Hammadid Dynasty was a Berber Zirid offshoot ruling the central Maghreb from their fortified capital at Qal'at Banu Hammad in the Hodna mountains of present-day Algeria, a site now a UNESCO World Heritage Site for its remarkably preserved remains of a medieval Islamic palace city abandoned in the twelfth century. The Hammadid state controlled the central Saharan trade routes and the Tell Atlas agricultural zone, accumulating considerable wealth that funded ambitious architectural projects at their capital including a great mosque and an elaborate minaret that influenced subsequent North African architectural traditions. The dynasty maintained a sophisticated court culture drawing on both eastern Islamic and Andalusian influences, attracting scholars, poets, and craftsmen to their highland capital. The Almohad invasion of 1152 CE ended Hammadid independence, with the dynasty's territories absorbed into the expanding Almohad empire."},
  {"id":801,"n":"Wolof Empire","s":14.7645,"e":-17.366,"b":1350,"d":1890,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Wolof Empire was a Senegambian confederation of kingdoms — Jolof, Cayor, Baol, Sine, Saloum, and Walo — that dominated the Senegal River basin and the Atlantic coast from the Gambia to the Senegal River, representing the political structure encountered by the first Portuguese explorers on the West African coast in the 1440s. The Wolof social system was highly stratified, with a complex hierarchy of royal castes, warrior nobles, and specialized professional groups including griots, blacksmiths, and leatherworkers whose hereditary occupations were governed by elaborate rules of endogamy and social separation. Wolof cultural influence extended far beyond the political boundaries of the empire through the Wolof language's role as a lingua franca of trade across Senegambia and the Wolof diaspora created by the Atlantic slave trade, which distributed Wolof cultural practices across the Americas. French colonial expansion from Saint-Louis progressively annexed the Wolof kingdoms through the nineteenth century."},
  {"id":803,"n":"Ashanti Empire","s":6.6885,"e":-1.6244,"b":1701,"d":1901,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Ashanti Empire was the most powerful Akan state in West Africa, unified by Osei Tutu I and his spiritual advisor Okomfo Anokye around 1701 through the legendary descent of the Golden Stool — Sika Dwa Kofi — from heaven, a sacred throne that embodied the soul of the Ashanti nation and whose physical possession conferred supreme authority. The Ashanti economy was based on gold mining in the forest zone of present-day Ghana, trade in kola nuts with Sahelian states, and extensive participation in the Atlantic slave trade — a combination that made the Asantehene (king) among the wealthiest rulers in West Africa. The Ashanti military system was highly sophisticated, with a standing army supported by a network of roads that allowed rapid troop concentration and a tradition of absorbing conquered peoples into the Ashanti cultural and political framework rather than simply extracting tribute. The British fought four Anglo-Ashanti Wars between 1823 and 1900 before formally annexing the Ashanti homeland as part of the Gold Coast colony in 1901."},
  {"id":804,"n":"Zulu Kingdom","s":-28.3228,"e":30.6546,"b":1816,"d":1897,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Zulu Kingdom was created by Shaka kaSenzangakhona through a military revolution in the early nineteenth century that transformed a minor Nguni clan into the dominant power of southeastern Africa through radical innovations in tactics, weaponry, and political organisation that have been compared to the military reforms of Alexander the Great and Napoleon. Shaka replaced the traditional throwing assegai with a short stabbing spear — the iklwa — combined with a large cowhide shield for close-quarters combat, and reorganised the Zulu military into age-grade regiments (amabutho) that lived in royal military towns and were forbidden to marry until honoured in battle, creating a disciplined professional force of formidable cohesion. The mfecane — the 'crushing' or 'scattering' — the wave of migration, warfare, and state collapse triggered by Zulu expansion across southern Africa in the 1820s — displaced millions of people and reshaped the political map of the entire region. British forces defeated and exiled the last independent Zulu king Cetshwayo in the Anglo-Zulu War of 1879, though Zulu resistance included the catastrophic British defeat at Isandlwana."},
  {"id":805,"n":"Ndwandwe Kingdom","s":-27,"e":32,"b":1780,"d":1826,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Ndwandwe Kingdom under Zwide kaNobamba was the principal rival of the rising Zulu state in the Mfecane period, representing a formidable military power whose defeat by Shaka's forces at the Battle of Mhlatuze River in 1820 was the pivotal military engagement that secured Zulu supremacy in the Natal interior. The Ndwandwe military system was comparable in sophistication to the Zulu's — employing similar age-grade regiment structures and a cattle-raiding economy that sustained a warrior aristocracy — making the Ndwandwe-Zulu conflict a genuine clash of peer military powers rather than a one-sided conquest. Ndwandwe generals who escaped the Zulu conquest carried their military and political traditions northward, founding successor states in Mozambique and Zimbabwe — the Gaza Kingdom of Soshangane and the Jere kingdom of Zwangendaba — that spread the Nguni military revolution across southeastern Africa. The Ndwandwe state was finally destroyed by Shaka's forces in 1826."},
  {"id":806,"n":"Merina Kingdom — Expansion Phase","s":-19.8145,"e":47.4759,"b":1787,"d":1861,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The expansion phase of the Merina Kingdom under Andrianampoinimerina and his son Radama I represents the most ambitious state-building project in Madagascar's history, transforming the highland kingdom into a near-unifier of the entire island through a combination of military conquest, diplomatic marriage alliances, and selective adoption of European military technology. Andrianampoinimerina's famous declaration that 'the sea shall be the boundary of my rice field' encapsulated an ambition of complete Malagasy unification that his son Radama I nearly achieved, with Merina authority extending over approximately two thirds of Madagascar's territory by the 1820s. British support under the 1817 treaty with Radama I — which abolished the slave trade in exchange for military training, firearms, and British recognition of Radama's royal title — transformed the Merina army into the most capable military force in the western Indian Ocean island world. The expansion phase represented in this entry precedes the later colonial period recorded in the earlier archive entry (id 671)."},
  {"id":809,"n":"Rozvi Empire","s":-20,"e":30.5,"b":1684,"d":1834,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Rozvi Empire was a Shona state that overthrew Portuguese commercial dominance in the Zimbabwe plateau, expelling the Portuguese from their inland trading posts (feira) in a series of campaigns in the 1690s and restoring indigenous control over the gold and ivory trade routes to the Swahili Coast that the Portuguese had disrupted. The Rozvi Mambo (king) ruled from a series of stone-walled zimbabwe — the same type of dry-stone enclosures that give the country its modern name — across the plateau, the most important of which at Khami near Bulawayo has been designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The empire maintained the religious traditions of the mhondoro spirit medium system — through which ancestral royal spirits spoke to the living through possessed mediums — as the primary mechanism of political legitimation and dispute resolution. The Rozvi state was destroyed by Nguni raiding armies during the Mfecane upheaval of the 1830s."},
  {"id":810,"n":"Ethiopian Empire — Solomonic Restoration","s":9.025,"e":38.7469,"b":1270,"d":1974,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AF","desc":"The Solomonic Restoration of 1270 CE, when Yekuno Amlak overthrew the last Zagwe king by claiming descent from the ancient Solomonic dynasty of Axum, inaugurated the longest-lasting royal dynasty in world history — a line of Ethiopian emperors who ruled for seven centuries and claimed unbroken descent from King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba, ending only with Haile Selassie's deposition in 1974. The Kebra Nagast — the Glory of Kings — written in its present form around 1321 CE, provided the scriptural foundation for this dynastic claim, narrating the story of Menelik I who brought the Ark of the Covenant from Jerusalem to Ethiopia — a tradition the Ethiopian Orthodox Church maintains as living reality, claiming to hold the actual Ark in Axum to this day. The empire survived the devastating jihad of Ahmad Grañ in the sixteenth century, the Oromo migrations, and the pressures of European colonialism to emerge as one of only two African states to successfully resist European conquest in the colonial era, defeating Italy at the Battle of Adwa in 1896. Haile Selassie's deposition by the Derg military council in 1974 ended the dynasty."},
  {"id":812,"n":"Aztec Triple Alliance","s":19.4326,"e":-99.1332,"b":1428,"d":1521,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Aztec Triple Alliance — the political framework of what is commonly called the Aztec Empire — was a confederation of three city-states: Tenochtitlan, Texcoco, and Tlacopan, whose combined military power dominated central Mexico for nearly a century and built the largest indigenous state in Mesoamerican history. Tenochtitlan itself was one of the world's largest cities at European contact, with a population exceeding 200,000 — larger than any contemporary European city — built on an island in Lake Texcoco and connected to the mainland by broad causeways, its floating gardens (chinampas) supplying fresh produce to a dense urban population with remarkable agricultural efficiency. The Aztec practice of large-scale human sacrifice — the hearts of sacrificial victims offered to the sun god Huitzilopochtli to sustain the cosmic order — was on a scale unprecedented in the Americas and generated a tradition of flower wars (xochiyaoyotl) fought specifically to capture rather than kill enemies for ritual purposes. Hernán Cortés, allied with subject peoples deeply resentful of Aztec tributary demands, besieged and destroyed Tenochtitlan in 1521."},
  {"id":813,"n":"Maya Classic Period","s":17.251,"e":-89.623,"b":250,"d":900,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Maya Classic period represents the height of Maya civilisation, during which dozens of competing city-states dominated the lowlands of present-day southern Mexico, Guatemala, Belize, and Honduras, each centred on a royal court that patronised extraordinary achievements in astronomy, mathematics, monumental architecture, and a sophisticated hieroglyphic writing system — the only fully developed writing system in the pre-Columbian Americas. The Maya Long Count calendar, which tracks time from a mythological creation date equivalent to 3114 BCE, and the Haab'/Tzolk'in interlocking calendar system demonstrate a mathematical and astronomical sophistication that allowed Maya scholars to calculate lunar cycles, predict solar eclipses, and track the movements of Venus to a precision matched by no contemporary civilisation. The great cities of Tikal, Palenque, Copán, Caracol, and Calakmul built temple-pyramids of extraordinary ambition, covered in carved historical and mythological inscriptions that modern epigraphers have largely deciphered, revealing a world of complex dynastic politics and interstate warfare. The Terminal Classic collapse around 800–900 CE, which saw the abandonment of dozens of major cities in the southern lowlands within a few generations, remains one of archaeology's most debated questions."},
  {"id":814,"n":"Maya Postclassic — Chichen Itza","s":20.6843,"e":-88.5678,"b":800,"d":1221,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"Chichen Itza was the dominant Postclassic Maya city-state of the northern Yucatan Peninsula, representing a remarkable synthesis of Maya and Toltec-influenced artistic and architectural traditions that produced some of the most iconic monuments in the pre-Columbian world — including the El Castillo pyramid, the Great Ball Court, the Temple of the Warriors, and the Sacred Cenote. The El Castillo pyramid was designed with precise astronomical intention — at the spring and autumn equinoxes, the play of shadow and light on its northern staircase creates the visual illusion of a feathered serpent descending to the earth, demonstrating the integration of astronomical knowledge into monumental architecture that characterised Maya building. The Sacred Cenote — a natural sinkhole into which offerings of jade, gold, incense, and human sacrificial victims were cast — was a pilgrimage destination across the Maya world, and dredging operations in the twentieth century recovered thousands of ritual objects from its depths. The city's political dominance collapsed around 1221 CE following internal conflicts, with Mayapan emerging as the subsequent political centre."},
  {"id":818,"n":"Mixtec Kingdom","s":17.549,"e":-97.918,"b":900,"d":1521,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Mixtec civilisation of highland Oaxaca and the coastal lowlands of present-day Mexico produced the most sophisticated screenfold manuscript tradition in pre-Columbian Mesoamerica, with the surviving Mixtec codices — including the Vindobonensis, the Nuttall, and the Bodley — providing detailed pictorial histories of royal genealogies, conquest sequences, and ritual calendars that document Mixtec political history back to approximately 800 CE. The legendary Mixtec ruler Eight Deer Jaguar Claw, whose life is documented across multiple codices, was the most ambitious Mixtec political leader, conquering over a hundred towns and attempting to unite the competing Mixtec kingdoms under a single authority before his capture and ritual sacrifice by rivals in 1063 CE — the best-documented political biography from pre-Columbian North America. Mixtec goldsmiths and featherworkers were regarded as the finest craftspeople in Mesoamerica, and Mixtec luxury goods — gold jewellery, carved turquoise mosaic objects, and polychrome ceramics — circulated as prestige items from the Aztec court to the Maya lowlands. The Aztecs conquered most Mixtec territory by 1521 CE."},
  {"id":819,"n":"Tarascan Empire","s":19.7008,"e":-101.1844,"b":1350,"d":1530,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Tarascan Empire — the Purépecha Empire — was the principal rival of the Aztec Triple Alliance in central Mexico and the only major Mesoamerican state that consistently resisted Aztec military expansion, defeating Aztec forces in a series of engagements that established a stable frontier between the two empires in the Toluca and Balsas River valleys. Tarascan metallurgy was the most sophisticated in Mesoamerica, producing copper tools, bronze weapons, and gold and silver ornaments using techniques including lost-wax casting and alloying that were unknown in central Mexico before Tarascan innovation or possible South American contact. The Tarascan capital Tzintzuntzan on the shores of Lake Pátzcuaro was a densely populated city of perhaps 35,000 inhabitants at contact, organised around a series of distinctive stepped platforms called yácatas that housed the temples of the state religion. The Spanish conquistador Nuño de Guzmán conquered the Tarascan Empire in 1529–1530 with particular brutality, executing the last ruler Tangaxuan II."},
  {"id":823,"n":"Nazca Culture","s":-14.739,"e":-75.13,"b":-100,"d":800,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Nazca culture of the southern Peruvian coastal desert produced the most enigmatic monuments in the pre-Columbian Americas — the Nazca Lines, a vast system of geoglyphs covering over 450 square kilometres of desert plateau and depicting hundreds of geometric figures, animals, plants, and humanoid forms visible only from the air, whose purpose has generated more scholarly and popular speculation than almost any other archaeological site in the world. The mainstream archaeological interpretation holds that the lines were ritual pathways walked in ceremonies related to water and fertility, given the Nazca's extreme reliance on underground aqueduct systems (puquios) to survive in one of the world's driest coastal deserts. Alternative researchers including Erich von Däniken famously suggested the lines served as landing strips or navigational aids for extraterrestrial aircraft, a hypothesis dismissed by archaeologists but which brought the Nazca Lines to worldwide popular attention. Nazca polychrome pottery — among the finest in pre-Columbian South America — and their tradition of elaborate trophy heads provide a more complete picture of a complex society grappling with desert survival."},
  {"id":824,"n":"Mississippian Culture — Cahokia Peak","s":38.6554,"e":-90.0621,"b":1050,"d":1350,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"Cahokia at its peak between 1050 and 1200 CE was the largest pre-Columbian city north of Mexico, with a population estimated at 10,000 to 20,000 inhabitants at its centre and perhaps 40,000 in the surrounding region — larger than contemporary London — spread across a planned urban landscape dominated by Monks Mound, the largest earthwork in the Americas with a base larger than the Great Pyramid at Giza. Cahokia's political and religious influence spread across the eastern half of North America through the Mississippian cultural tradition — a network of chiefdoms sharing a distinctive artistic vocabulary of shell gorgets, copper plates, and ceramic vessels depicting cosmological themes of the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex. The city's sudden and dramatic expansion around 1050 CE — the 'Big Bang' of Cahokia — coincided with a period of favourable climate, possible population aggregation from surrounding regions, and what appears to have been a genuine religious revival or prophetic movement centred on the new urban centre. Cahokia's population declined sharply after 1200 CE, with the site largely abandoned by 1350, probably due to environmental degradation, political instability, and climate deterioration."},
  {"id":825,"n":"Ancestral Puebloans — Chaco System","s":36.0608,"e":-107.9617,"b":850,"d":1150,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Chaco Canyon system in present-day New Mexico represented the ceremonial and administrative centre of the Ancestral Puebloan cultural world, a network of great houses — massive multi-storey stone masonry complexes including Pueblo Bonito, Chetro Ketl, and Pueblo del Arroyo — connected by a system of engineered roads radiating outward from the canyon across the Colorado Plateau for distances of up to 100 kilometres. Pueblo Bonito alone contained approximately 650 rooms and 40 kivas (ceremonial chambers), making it the largest building in the present-day United States until the nineteenth century, constructed using millions of precisely fitted sandstone blocks without mortar in a tradition of masonry sophistication unequalled in pre-Columbian North America. Chaco's roads — arrow-straight, up to nine metres wide, and cleared and graded through bedrock outcrops — appear to have served primarily ceremonial rather than commercial purposes, aligned in some cases to astronomical phenomena in a landscape cosmology that integrated architecture, astronomy, and ritual movement. The system collapsed around 1150 CE following a prolonged drought, with population dispersal creating the pueblo communities of Arizona and New Mexico that survive to the present."},
  {"id":829,"n":"Norte Chico / Caral Civilisation","s":-10.8931,"e":-77.5194,"b":-3000,"d":-1800,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Norte Chico civilisation of the Peruvian coastal valleys — also known as the Caral-Supe civilisation — is the oldest known complex society in the Americas, predating the Olmec by two thousand years and contemporary with the Egyptian Old Kingdom and the Early Dynastic period of Mesopotamia, yet developing in complete apparent independence of the Old World civilisational sequence. Caral itself, the largest Norte Chico site, contains six platform mounds, multiple sunken circular plazas, residential compounds, and evidence of a complex society with occupational specialisation, long-distance trade, and a tradition of quipu knotted cord recording — all achieved without ceramics, suggesting that the civilisation's economic foundation was based on maritime resources and cotton cultivation rather than pottery-using agriculture. The Norte Chico civilisation appears to have existed entirely without warfare — no evidence of weapons, fortifications, or trauma on human remains has been found — suggesting a social model of integration through religion and trade rather than military coercion. The abrupt abandonment of Norte Chico sites around 1800 BCE coincides with a period of climate disruption and possible El Niño flooding."},
  {"id":831,"n":"Viking Settlement — North America","s":51.5965,"e":-55.5194,"b":985,"d":1020,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Norse settlement of North America — Vinland in the Icelandic sagas — represents the first confirmed European presence in the Americas, approximately five centuries before Columbus, with the archaeological site of L'Anse aux Meadows in Newfoundland providing incontrovertible evidence of a Norse settlement dating to approximately 1000 CE. L'Anse aux Meadows contains the remains of eight Norse-style buildings, iron-working facilities, and a bronze ring-headed cloak pin of Scandinavian type — artefacts that definitively confirm the sagas' accounts of Leif Erikson's and Thorfinn Karlsefni's voyages to a land they called Vinland, Markland, and Helluland. Recent analysis of a wood sample from a Canadian site at Point Rosee using a precise solar storm dating technique confirmed Norse presence in North America in 1021 CE with single-year precision — the most accurate dating of any pre-Columbian European contact with the Americas. Norse settlement ultimately failed due to hostile relations with the indigenous Skraelings, distance from Greenland supply lines, and the small scale of the settlement."},
  {"id":832,"n":"Thule Culture","s":71.2906,"e":-156.7887,"b":1000,"d":1600,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Thule culture was the direct ancestor of all modern Inuit peoples, originating in northern Alaska around 1000 CE and expanding eastward across arctic Canada to Greenland with remarkable speed — covering over 4,000 kilometres within approximately two centuries — in a migration driven by technological innovations in sea-mammal hunting that allowed exploitation of previously inaccessible arctic marine resources. The Thule developed a suite of sophisticated cold-weather technologies — the kayak, the umiak, the dog sled, the toggling harpoon, and efficient snow house construction — that allowed permanent year-round habitation in some of the Earth's most extreme environments, demonstrating an adaptive technological intelligence of the highest order. Thule expansion displaced or absorbed the earlier Dorset culture, which had inhabited the eastern Arctic for over two thousand years, in a process whose dynamics — whether peaceful replacement or violent conflict — remain debated. The Thule encountered Norse settlers in Greenland and their interactions, recorded in both saga traditions and Thule oral history, represent the first sustained contact between Old and New World peoples."},
  {"id":833,"n":"Dorset Culture","s":63.7467,"e":-68.517,"b":-800,"d":1300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Dorset culture was the principal pre-Thule Arctic tradition of eastern Canada and Greenland, developing over two millennia in the harsh environment of the eastern Arctic and producing a remarkable artistic tradition of miniature ivory and antler carvings — including human faces, polar bears, and shamanic figures that rank among the most expressive small-scale sculptures from any pre-historic culture. Dorset people developed effective cold-weather survival technologies including snow houses, skin boats, and cold-weather clothing adequate for arctic winters, without dogs or dog sleds — a technological limitation that restricted their mobility compared to the Thule who subsequently replaced them. DNA analysis of ancient Dorset remains has revealed that they were genetically distinct from both their predecessors the Arctic Small Tool tradition people and their Thule successors, representing a population that evolved in isolation in the eastern Arctic for two thousand years before abrupt replacement. The Dorset culture disappeared from most of its range between 1000 and 1300 CE following Thule expansion from the west."},
  {"id":835,"n":"Iroquois Confederacy","s":43,"e":-75.5,"b":1450,"d":1800,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Haudenosaunee Confederacy — known to Europeans as the Iroquois League or Six Nations — was a sophisticated political union of originally five (later six) nations of the northeastern woodlands of North America: Mohawk, Oneida, Onondaga, Cayuga, Seneca, and later Tuscarora, governed by a constitution (the Great Law of Peace) that has been proposed as an influence on the political theory of the American Founding Fathers. The Great Law of Peace was encoded in wampum belts — sacred objects of shell beads whose patterns served as mnemonic records of law, treaty, and history — and provided for a bicameral council structure, mechanisms for removing leaders who violated their trust, and protections for individual rights that anticipated features of modern democratic governance by centuries. The confederacy's neutrality between French and British colonial powers gave it exceptional political leverage in the colonial period, and its military effectiveness — particularly the Mohawk warriors who served as British auxiliaries — made it a force neither colonial power could ignore. The American Revolution split the confederacy, with most nations supporting Britain, and the subsequent Sullivan-Clinton campaign of 1779 devastated the Haudenosaunee homeland."},
  {"id":836,"n":"Muscogee Creek Confederacy","s":32.8407,"e":-83.6324,"b":900,"d":1836,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Muscogee Creek Confederacy was a sophisticated political alliance of town-based polities across present-day Alabama and Georgia, evolving from the Mississippian mound-building tradition and developing into one of the most complex indigenous political organisations in the eastern woodlands — a genuine confederation with a council structure, diplomatic protocols, and mechanisms for managing inter-town disputes. Creek towns were divided into Red (war) and White (peace) categories, with different towns holding ceremonial responsibility for war councils and diplomatic negotiations respectively — a constitutional division of political function without precise parallel in other North American indigenous traditions. The annual Green Corn Ceremony (Busk) served as the Creek equivalent of New Year — a time of social renewal, conflict resolution, and communal forgiveness in which old grievances were wiped clean and the sacred fire was ritually extinguished and relit — providing social cohesion across the dispersed confederation. The Indian Removal Act of 1830 and the subsequent Trail of Tears forcibly displaced the Creek from their homeland to Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma."},
  {"id":837,"n":"Cherokee Nation","s":35.5175,"e":-83.9871,"b":1000,"d":1838,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Cherokee Nation of the southern Appalachian Mountains developed one of the most rapid and thoroughgoing programmes of cultural adaptation in indigenous American history, adopting European-style governance, printing, agriculture, and education in the early nineteenth century in a deliberate effort to demonstrate civilisational sophistication and thereby secure their land rights against American expansionism. Sequoyah's invention of the Cherokee syllabary between 1809 and 1821 — the only instance in recorded history of a pre-literate person independently creating a writing system from scratch — produced a functional 86-symbol script that achieved near-universal literacy among Cherokee speakers within a few years and made possible the first indigenous-language newspaper in North American history, the Cherokee Phoenix. The discovery of gold in Cherokee territory in Georgia in 1829 accelerated American desire for Cherokee removal, and despite a Supreme Court ruling in their favour (Worcester v. Georgia, 1832), President Andrew Jackson refused to enforce the ruling. The forced removal of the Cherokee in 1838 — the Trail of Tears — resulted in the deaths of approximately four thousand of the sixteen thousand forcibly relocated."},
  {"id":838,"n":"Lakota Sioux Nation","s":43.9695,"e":-103.7713,"b":1700,"d":1890,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Lakota Sioux emerged as the dominant people of the northern Great Plains following the acquisition of horses — which spread northward from Spanish settlements in the late seventeenth century — transforming from forest-dwelling wild rice gatherers into the most formidable equestrian buffalo-hunting culture on the plains in the space of a few generations, a cultural revolution of extraordinary speed. The Lakota spiritual tradition centred on the Great Spirit (Wakan Tanka) and expressed through the seven sacred rites including the Sun Dance, the Vision Quest, and the Sweat Lodge ceremony — practices that sustained individual spiritual experience and communal identity through the physical and cultural devastation of the reservation period. The Battle of Little Bighorn in 1876, where Lakota, Cheyenne, and Arapaho warriors under Sitting Bull and Crazy Horse annihilated George Armstrong Custer's Seventh Cavalry in the most significant Native American military victory against the United States Army, demonstrated the continuing military effectiveness of plains warfare at a moment when the buffalo herds were already in catastrophic decline. The Wounded Knee Massacre of 1890 effectively ended Lakota armed resistance."},
  {"id":839,"n":"Apache Peoples","s":33.4255,"e":-110.789,"b":1400,"d":1886,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The Apache — a group of culturally related but politically independent peoples including the Chiricahua, Mescalero, Jicarilla, Lipan, and Western Apache — were the most formidable military adversaries encountered by both Spanish colonial and United States forces in the American Southwest, maintaining armed resistance to external domination over a period of nearly four centuries. Apache military effectiveness rested on extraordinary mobility — Apache warriors could cover 70 miles a day on foot in desert terrain — intimate knowledge of the landscape, and a tactical doctrine of raid, ambush, and dispersal that consistently frustrated the larger conventional forces sent against them. Geronimo — Goyaałé — the Chiricahua Apache leader whose final surrender in 1886 officially ended the Apache Wars, conducted a campaign against both United States and Mexican forces with a band that at times numbered as few as a dozen warriors while tying down five thousand US Army soldiers and three thousand Mexican troops. The Apache warrior tradition, religious practices centred on Mountain Spirits (Gaan), and the enduring sovereignty of Apache nations in Arizona, New Mexico, and Oklahoma represent one of the most remarkable stories of cultural survival under sustained external pressure in American history."},
  {"id":840,"n":"Aztlan — Mythological Aztec Homeland","s":23,"e":-106,"b":-1000,"d":1300,"t":"theorized","cont":"AM","desc":"Aztlan is the legendary ancestral homeland from which the Aztec (Mexica) people claim to have migrated southward to the Valley of Mexico, described in indigenous accounts as an island or coastal location in the northwest from which the migration began around 1111 CE under the guidance of the god Huitzilopochtli. The physical location of Aztlan has been sought by researchers across a vast area from the American Southwest to the Mexican state of Nayarit, with candidate sites including Aztatlán in Nayarit, Aztlan in Wisconsin (a nineteenth-century speculation), and various island locations in lakes from Jalisco to the Pacific coast. Some scholars identify Aztlan as a mythological construct rather than a real geographic location — a narrative of origin that encoded social memory of the Mexica's emergence from nomadic Chichimec peoples of the northern deserts into the sedentary civilisation of central Mexico. The search for Aztlan intersects with alternative historical research into pre-Columbian migrations, the diffusion of Nahuatl language groups across North America, and the deeper question of Mesoamerican population movements in the first millennium CE."},
  {"id":841,"n":"Poverty Point — Extended Exchange Network","s":32,"e":-91,"b":-2000,"d":-500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AM","desc":"The wider Poverty Point exchange network extended across the eastern half of North America during the second and first millennia BCE, connecting hunter-gatherer communities from the Gulf Coast to the Great Lakes and from the Atlantic seaboard to the Missouri River in a web of ceremonial exchange that moved exotic raw materials — copper, galena, steatite, jasper, and marine shell — over distances of up to 2,000 kilometres. The network predates any known political hierarchy capable of organising such exchange, suggesting that the movement of prestige materials across vast distances was maintained by social mechanisms — reciprocal gift-giving, ceremonial gathering, and kinship obligations — rather than centrally managed trade. The scale and geographic extent of the Poverty Point exchange network challenges assumptions about the organisational complexity achievable by hunter-gatherer societies, demonstrating that large-scale inter-regional interaction does not require urban civilisation as a precondition. This extended network entry complements the Poverty Point core site (id 834) by documenting the wider regional interaction sphere."},
  {"id":842,"n":"Kingdom of Scotland","s":56.4907,"e":-4.2026,"b":843,"d":1707,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Kingdom of Scotland was established by Kenneth MacAlpin's unification of the Pictish and Scottish (Dál Riata) kingdoms in 843 CE and maintained independence from its more powerful southern neighbour England for over eight centuries through a combination of difficult terrain, fierce military resistance, and deft diplomatic manoeuvring across the courts of France, Scandinavia, and the papacy. The Wars of Scottish Independence against Edward I of England produced William Wallace and Robert the Bruce as national heroes, and Bruce's victory at Bannockburn in 1314 CE secured Scottish independence in a battle against numerically superior English forces that has remained the most celebrated military event in Scottish national memory. The Declaration of Arbroath of 1320 CE — a letter to Pope John XXII asserting Scottish independence and including the remarkable statement that even if Bruce himself submitted to England, the Scots would choose another king to maintain their freedom — has been claimed as an influence on the American Declaration of Independence. The Acts of Union in 1707 merged Scotland with England and Wales into the Kingdom of Great Britain, ending Scotland's existence as a separate state while preserving its distinct legal, religious, and educational institutions."},
  {"id":843,"n":"Kingdom of Ireland — High Kingship","s":53.4239,"e":-8.093,"b":400,"d":1166,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Irish High Kingship — the Ard Rí of Ireland — was a contested title among the provincial kings of Ireland that in theory but rarely in practice represented paramount authority over the entire island, producing in the legendary accounts a tradition of heroic kingship embodied in figures like Cú Chulainn and the historical Brian Boru whose victory at Clontarf in 1014 CE ended Viking dominance of Irish coastal cities. Irish monastic civilisation between the fifth and ninth centuries CE — the Age of Saints and Scholars — preserved classical learning through the European Dark Ages in isolated island monasteries, with figures like Columba, Columban, and Gall evangelising across Britain and continental Europe from Irish foundations that became the most important centres of learning in the post-Roman West. The Book of Kells — an illuminated gospel manuscript produced around 800 CE in an Irish or Iona scriptorium — is widely regarded as the most beautiful book ever made, its intricate interlacements, zoomorphic initials, and carpet pages representing the pinnacle of Insular art. Anglo-Norman invasion under Richard de Clare (Strongbow) in 1169–1170 CE ended the High Kingship era and began eight centuries of English involvement in Irish affairs."},
  {"id":844,"n":"Frankish Kingdom — Merovingian","s":48.8566,"e":2.3522,"b":481,"d":751,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Merovingian Kingdom was the first enduring Germanic Christian monarchy in western Europe, founded when Clovis I defeated the last Roman governor of Gaul at the Battle of Soissons in 486 CE and subsequently converted to Catholic Christianity in a political act that aligned the Frankish kingdom with the papacy and the Gallo-Roman church, creating the prototype for the medieval partnership between church and state. Clovis's conversion — reportedly following a battlefield vow to adopt Christ's faith if he defeated the Alamanni — was the most consequential individual religious conversion in post-Roman European history, providing the Catholic church with a powerful Germanic military ally at a moment when competing Arian Christian kingdoms dominated the continent. The Merovingian court developed elaborate ceremonial around the sacred character of its long-haired kings, whose uncut hair symbolised their divine mandate, and created the template of royal administration — counts, bishops, and local assemblies — that would define Carolingian governance. The dynasty was effectively replaced by the Carolingian mayors of the palace, with the last Merovingian king Childeric III deposed and shorn by Pippin the Short in 751 CE."},
  {"id":845,"n":"Anglo-Saxon Kingdoms","s":51.752,"e":-1.2577,"b":450,"d":1066,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of England — Northumbria, Mercia, East Anglia, Wessex, Kent, Essex, and Sussex — were Germanic Christian polities that between the fifth and eleventh centuries created the English language, the English legal tradition, and a literary culture of extraordinary richness that culminated in the unified English kingdom of Edgar the Peaceful and the cultural achievements of Alfred the Great. Alfred of Wessex — the only English king called 'the Great' — defended the kingdom against Viking conquest, reformed the legal system, reorganised the military into a network of fortified burhs, sponsored the translation of Latin learning into Old English, and founded a tradition of royal intellectual patronage that produced the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle and the earliest English prose literature. The Sutton Hoo ship burial of approximately 625 CE — excavated in 1939 and revealing a spectacular assemblage of gold and garnet jewellery, a magnificent iron helmet, Byzantine silverware, and Merovingian coins — provided an extraordinary window into the material culture of early Anglo-Saxon kingship. The Norman Conquest of 1066 transformed but did not destroy Anglo-Saxon cultural and legal traditions, which persisted through the feudal overlay to shape English common law and parliamentary governance."},
  {"id":846,"n":"Kingdom of Burgundy","s":47.05,"e":4.8671,"b":411,"d":1477,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Kingdom and Duchy of Burgundy occupied one of medieval Europe's most strategic and culturally productive zones — the corridor between France and the Germanic world — and at its peak under the Valois Dukes of Burgundy in the fifteenth century constituted the wealthiest and most culturally brilliant court in northern Europe, patronising the Flemish school of painting, tapestry production, and an elaborate chivalric culture that influenced European court life for a century. The Flemish Primitives — Jan van Eyck, Rogier van der Weyden, Hugo van der Goes — worked under Burgundian patronage and created a tradition of oil painting on panel of extraordinary technical and emotional refinement that transformed European art and directly influenced the Italian Renaissance. Philip the Good of Burgundy founded the Order of the Golden Fleece in 1430 — the most prestigious chivalric order in Europe — and his court at Bruges and Dijon was described by contemporaries as the model of all Christian courts. The death of Charles the Bold at the Battle of Nancy in 1477 without a male heir ended Burgundian independence, with the territories divided between France and the Habsburgs."},
  {"id":847,"n":"Hungarian Kingdom","s":47.4979,"e":19.0402,"b":1000,"d":1918,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Kingdom of Hungary was established by Stephen I, who converted to Christianity and received a royal crown from Pope Sylvester II in 1000 CE — a crown that became the most sacred object in Hungarian national identity, venerated as the Holy Crown of Saint Stephen and considered the physical embodiment of Hungarian statehood for a thousand years. Hungary served as the eastern bulwark of Latin Christendom, repelling the Mongol invasion of 1241–1242 that devastated the kingdom and killed perhaps half its population before withdrawing, then confronting Ottoman expansion for two centuries in the wars of the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries that made Hungary a permanent European frontier zone. King Matthias Corvinus (1458–1490) presided over a Hungarian Renaissance of extraordinary brilliance, assembling the Bibliotheca Corviniana — the second largest library in Europe after the Vatican — and a court that rivalled any in contemporary Christendom for literary and artistic achievement. The Ottoman victory at the Battle of Mohács in 1526 killed the Hungarian king and much of the nobility, beginning 150 years of Ottoman occupation of central Hungary."},
  {"id":848,"n":"Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth","s":52.2297,"e":21.0122,"b":1569,"d":1795,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth was one of the largest and most distinctive states in early modern Europe, a multi-ethnic, multi-religious federation of the Kingdom of Poland and the Grand Duchy of Lithuania governed by an elected monarchy and a noble parliament (Sejm) whose liberum veto — the right of any single deputy to dissolve the parliament — was both the supreme expression of Polish noble liberty and the mechanism that paralysed effective governance in the eighteenth century. At its seventeenth-century peak the Commonwealth encompassed present-day Poland, Lithuania, Latvia, Belarus, Ukraine, and parts of Russia and Estonia — a territory of over 1 million square kilometres — and hosted substantial communities of Poles, Lithuanians, Ruthenians, Jews, Germans, Armenians, and Tatars in a degree of ethnic and religious plurality unusual in contemporary Europe. The Commonwealth's Jan Sobieski led the largest cavalry charge in history at the Battle of Vienna in 1683, breaking the Ottoman siege and beginning the long Ottoman retreat from central Europe — a moment that Sobieski was celebrated across Christendom for saving European civilisation. The Commonwealth was partitioned three times by Russia, Prussia, and Austria between 1772 and 1795, erasing Poland from the political map for 123 years."},
  {"id":849,"n":"Grand Duchy of Lithuania","s":54.6872,"e":25.2797,"b":1236,"d":1569,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Grand Duchy of Lithuania was at its height in the fourteenth and early fifteenth centuries the largest state in Europe, stretching from the Baltic Sea to the Black Sea in an empire that encompassed most of present-day Belarus, Ukraine, and Lithuania and was governed by a dynasty — the Gediminids — who maintained an unusual policy of religious tolerance, allowing Orthodox, Catholic, and pagan subjects to coexist without systematic persecution. Lithuania was the last pagan state in Europe to convert to Christianity, doing so in 1387 CE when Grand Duke Jogaila converted in connection with his marriage to the Polish queen Jadwiga and the personal union with Poland that would ultimately produce the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth. The duchy's expansion into the vast Orthodox Ruthenian territories of former Kievan Rus brought its culture into sustained contact with Byzantine civilisation, and the resulting synthesis of Western European, Orthodox, and Baltic traditions produced a distinctive Rus-Lithuanian political culture. Vytautas the Great's defeat of the Teutonic Knights at the Battle of Grunwald in 1410 — the largest battle in medieval European history — established Lithuanian military primacy in northeastern Europe."},
  {"id":850,"n":"Teutonic Knight State","s":54.352,"e":18.6466,"b":1224,"d":1525,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Monastic State of the Teutonic Knights was a crusading military order state established in Prussia and the Baltic through the forced conversion and military conquest of the indigenous Prussian, Latvian, and Lithuanian peoples — one of the most brutal colonisation campaigns in medieval European history — creating a polity governed by the Grand Master of the Teutonic Order that was simultaneously a military organisation, a monastic institution, and a functioning territorial state. The Teutonic Knights' annual Reise — the sponsored military expeditions into pagan Lithuanian territory that attracted crusading knights from across Europe as a fashionable religious and martial adventure — continued for over a century and was participated in by figures including Henry Bolingbroke (later Henry IV of England) and John Boucicaut of France. The catastrophic defeat at the Battle of Grunwald in 1410 at the hands of the Polish-Lithuanian forces irreparably damaged the Order's military power and began a century of decline. The Order secularised and became a Lutheran duchy under Albert of Hohenzollern in 1525, ending the monastic state and creating the ancestor state of the later Kingdom of Prussia."},
  {"id":852,"n":"Habsburg Monarchy","s":48.2082,"e":16.3738,"b":1282,"d":1918,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Habsburg Monarchy was the dynastic state of the House of Habsburg that grew from a minor Swiss county into the dominant ruling family of Europe through a combination of strategic marriage alliances — encapsulated in the maxim 'bella gerant alii, tu felix Austria nube' (let others wage war; you, happy Austria, marry) — assembling at its peak a personal union of territories spanning Spain, the Americas, the Low Countries, Austria, Hungary, Bohemia, and parts of Italy. The Habsburgs served as Holy Roman Emperors almost continuously from 1438 to 1806 and as rulers of Spain from Charles V through Philip IV, making them the closest thing to a universal European monarchy that the continent ever produced in the early modern period. Maria Theresa of Austria, who ruled from 1740 to 1780, was arguably the most effective Habsburg monarch — a ruler who reformed the imperial administration, the military, and the educational system while navigating the existential threat of Frederick the Great's Prussia without formal legal authority as a woman in a male succession system. The Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 created the Dual Monarchy that survived until the empire's dissolution following defeat in the First World War in 1918."},
  {"id":853,"n":"Spanish Empire","s":40.4168,"e":-3.7038,"b":1492,"d":1898,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Spanish Empire was the first global empire in history, spanning the Americas, the Philippines, parts of Africa, and European territories simultaneously and at its peak under Philip II controlling territories on every inhabited continent — the first empire on which the sun literally never set. Spain's conquest of the Americas beginning with Columbus's 1492 voyage and Cortés and Pizarro's subsequent conquests transferred unprecedented quantities of silver from the mines of Potosí and Zacatecas to European commercial circuits, transforming the global economy and fuelling both the Dutch Golden Age and the Ottoman fiscal system through their insatiable demand for Spanish silver. The Spanish colonial system of encomienda and mita — forced labour extracted from indigenous populations — combined with epidemic disease to reduce the indigenous population of the Americas from an estimated 50–60 million at contact to perhaps 6 million within a century, one of the most catastrophic demographic collapses in human history. The Spanish-American War of 1898 ended Spanish sovereignty over Cuba, Puerto Rico, and the Philippines — the last remnants of a once-global empire."},
  {"id":854,"n":"Portuguese Empire","s":38.7223,"e":-9.1393,"b":1415,"d":1999,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Portuguese Empire was the longest-lived of the European colonial empires, lasting from the conquest of Ceuta in 1415 to the handover of Macau to China in 1999 — nearly six centuries — and in its fifteenth and sixteenth century prime establishing the first truly global commercial network linking Europe, Africa, Asia, and the Americas through a chain of fortified trading posts and naval dominance of the Indian Ocean. Vasco da Gama's voyage to India in 1497–1499 opened the sea route that bypassed the Ottoman-controlled overland Silk Road and redirected the spice trade away from Venice and the Levant — an event that fundamentally restructured the global economy. Portuguese Brazil, established through the Treaty of Tordesillas line of 1494, became the largest and most populous of Portugal's colonial possessions and ultimately the seat of the Portuguese royal court when the Braganza family fled Napoleon's invasion in 1807–1808, making Brazil the only colony in history to serve simultaneously as the capital of its metropole. The empire's legacy includes the Portuguese language as a first or second language for over 250 million people across three continents."},
  {"id":855,"n":"Dutch Republic — Golden Age","s":52.3676,"e":4.9041,"b":1581,"d":1795,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Dutch Republic — the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands — was a commercial and cultural superpower that dominated global trade for most of the seventeenth century, with the Dutch East India Company (VOC) becoming the world's first publicly traded corporation and the largest commercial enterprise in history to that point, at its peak paying 40% annual dividends to shareholders. Dutch Golden Age painting — Rembrandt, Vermeer, Hals, Ruisdael, de Hooch — produced the largest and most socially diverse body of visual art in the history of European painting, documenting the material prosperity and quotidian life of a commercial republic with unprecedented artistic ambition. Amsterdam in the mid-seventeenth century was the financial capital of the world, with the Amsterdam Exchange Bank and the Amsterdam Stock Exchange pioneering financial instruments — futures contracts, options, and joint stock companies — that created the foundations of modern capitalism. The Dutch tulip mania of 1636–1637 — in which speculative trading drove tulip bulb prices to extraordinary heights before a catastrophic collapse — has been cited as the first recorded speculative bubble in financial history."},
  {"id":856,"n":"British Empire","s":51.5074,"e":-0.1278,"b":1583,"d":1997,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The British Empire was the largest empire in world history, at its peak after the First World War covering approximately 24% of the Earth's land surface and governing roughly 460 million people — one quarter of the world's population — through a combination of direct colonial rule, dominion status, protectorates, and informal commercial empire. The Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain in the 1760s and spread globally through imperial commercial networks, transformed the material conditions of human existence more profoundly than any development since the agricultural revolution — generating a period of exponential economic growth whose ecological and social consequences continue to unfold. The transatlantic slave trade, in which British ships transported approximately three million enslaved Africans to the Americas before abolition in 1807, and the subsequent use of enslaved labour in British Caribbean colonies until emancipation in 1833, represents the darkest chapter in British imperial history and the foundation of considerable colonial wealth. The handover of Hong Kong to China in 1997 is conventionally regarded as the final act of British decolonisation."},
  {"id":857,"n":"French Empire — Colonial","s":48.8566,"e":2.3522,"b":1534,"d":1962,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The French colonial empire was the second-largest in world history at its twentieth-century peak, encompassing significant territories in North and West Africa, Indochina, the Caribbean, the Pacific, and North America — and leaving a linguistic, legal, and cultural legacy across dozens of modern states through the worldwide diffusion of the French language and the Napoleonic Code. France's civilising mission ideology (mission civilisatrice) provided a distinctive imperial justification that emphasised cultural and linguistic assimilation rather than the British model of indirect rule, producing a different pattern of colonial administration that sought to create 'French Algerians' or 'French Senegalese' rather than preserving indigenous institutions. The Haitian Revolution of 1791–1804 — the only successful slave revolt in history producing an independent state — was a direct consequence of French colonial slavery and the revolutionary principles of liberté, égalité, fraternité being turned against the colonial power that professed them. Algerian independence in 1962, achieved after a brutal eight-year war of liberation in which an estimated 1.5 million Algerians died, effectively ended the French colonial empire."},
  {"id":858,"n":"Russian Empire","s":55.7558,"e":37.6173,"b":1721,"d":1917,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Russian Empire was the third-largest empire in world history, spanning approximately 22.8 million square kilometres across Europe and Asia at its peak and representing the most remarkable example of continuous territorial expansion in the modern era — from the Grand Duchy of Moscow in the fifteenth century to a transcontinental empire stretching from Poland to Alaska and from the Arctic Ocean to the borders of Afghanistan and China. Peter the Great's westernisation programme of the early eighteenth century transformed Russia from a peripheral Orthodox tsardom into a recognisably European great power, founding Saint Petersburg as a new western capital, reorganising the military and bureaucracy on European models, and forcibly importing European technology, fashion, and cultural practice. Catherine the Great's reign from 1762 to 1796 saw Russia expand to incorporate the northern Black Sea coast, Crimea, and the partitioned Polish territories while the empress engaged in extensive correspondence with Voltaire and Diderot and founded the Hermitage collection that became one of the world's great art museums. The empire's defeat in the First World War and the Bolshevik Revolution of October 1917 ended the Romanov dynasty and the imperial system."},
  {"id":859,"n":"Napoleonic Empire","s":48.8566,"e":2.3522,"b":1804,"d":1815,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Napoleonic Empire was the most transformative political phenomenon in European history since the fall of Rome, with Napoleon Bonaparte's military genius and political vision restructuring the political map of Europe, disseminating the principles of the French Revolution across the continent, and creating legal and administrative reforms — most notably the Napoleonic Code — that remain the foundation of civil law systems across Europe, Latin America, and much of the world. Napoleon's military campaigns redrew European frontiers with bewildering speed — creating kingdoms for his brothers in Spain, Holland, Westphalia, and Naples; restructuring the Italian and German states into the Confederation of the Rhine and the Kingdom of Italy; and establishing French hegemony from the Iberian Peninsula to the borders of Russia. The Continental System — Napoleon's economic blockade of Britain — and the Russian campaign of 1812, in which the Grande Armée of 600,000 men was destroyed not in battle but by the Russian winter, strategic withdrawal, and logistical collapse, together undid Napoleon's empire. The Hundred Days of 1815, ending at Waterloo, confirmed Napoleon's defeat and the Bourbon restoration."},
  {"id":860,"n":"Kingdom of Naples and Sicily","s":40.8518,"e":14.2681,"b":1130,"d":1816,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Kingdom of Sicily — later the Kingdom of Naples and the Two Sicilies — was one of medieval Europe's most remarkable multicultural states, founded by Norman adventurers who conquered Arab-controlled Sicily and Byzantine southern Italy to create a kingdom where Arabic, Greek, Latin, and Norman French were all used at court and Christian, Muslim, and Jewish scholars collaborated in translation projects that transmitted Islamic science to Latin Europe. Roger II of Sicily's court in Palermo in the twelfth century was the most cosmopolitan in Europe — employing Arab geographers including al-Idrisi who produced the most accurate world map of the medieval period, Byzantine mosaic craftsmen who decorated Palatine Chapel with gold mosaics of haunting beauty, and Latin clergy who organised a church rivalling Rome in ambition. Frederick II of Sicily and Holy Roman Emperor — 'Stupor Mundi' (Wonder of the World) — was the most brilliant and contradictory ruler of medieval Europe: a polyglot who spoke six languages, a scientist who wrote the first empirical study of falconry, a crusader who negotiated the return of Jerusalem through diplomacy rather than military force, and a heretic who was repeatedly excommunicated. The kingdom was absorbed into unified Italy in 1861."},
  {"id":862,"n":"Republic of Genoa","s":44.4056,"e":8.9463,"b":1005,"d":1797,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Republic of Genoa was Venice's principal commercial rival in the medieval Mediterranean, establishing trading colonies from the Black Sea to the Atlantic coast of Morocco and developing financial innovations — including the earliest forms of maritime insurance, the bill of exchange, and the casa di San Giorgio bank which served as the world's first public bank — that made Genoa the financial capital of the Mediterranean in the high medieval period. Genoese merchants and bankers financed the Spanish and Portuguese voyages of exploration — Christopher Columbus himself was Genoese — and the casa di San Giorgio managed much of Spain's American silver revenues in the sixteenth century. Genoa's Black Sea colonies at Caffa and Tana were the point of entry into Europe of the Black Death in 1347, when Mongol forces besieging Caffa catapulted plague-infected corpses over the walls — in what is possibly the first documented use of biological warfare — and Genoese ships carried the disease westward. The republic survived until Napoleon dissolved it in 1797, incorporating it into the Ligurian Republic."},
  {"id":863,"n":"Papal States","s":41.9029,"e":12.4534,"b":756,"d":1870,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Papal States were the territorial dominion of the Bishop of Rome over central Italy, established through the Donation of Pepin in 756 CE and enduring until Italian unification forces occupied Rome in 1870, making the papacy a genuine territorial sovereign for over eleven centuries and profoundly complicating the relationship between spiritual authority and secular power in European history. The papacy at the height of its medieval power under Innocent III claimed supremacy over all Christian kings and emperors — a claim partially enforced through the weapon of excommunication and interdict that could deny entire kingdoms the sacraments and release their subjects from oaths of loyalty to an excommunicated ruler. The Renaissance papacy of the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries transformed Rome from a medieval pilgrimage city into the artistic capital of the world, commissioning Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel ceiling, Raphael's Vatican stanze, Bramante and Michelangelo's Saint Peter's Basilica, and a programme of urban renewal that made Rome the supreme expression of Renaissance and Baroque visual culture. The Lateran Treaty of 1929 between Mussolini and Pope Pius XI created the Vatican City State as a sovereign enclave within Rome, resolving the 'Roman Question' created by the 1870 occupation."},
  {"id":864,"n":"Byzantine Empire — Justinian Restoration","s":41.0082,"e":28.9784,"b":527,"d":565,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The reign of Justinian I represents the last great attempt to restore the Roman Empire to its classical extent, with the general Belisarius reconquering North Africa from the Vandals, Italy from the Ostrogoths, and southern Spain from the Visigoths in campaigns of extraordinary military skill that temporarily reunited the Mediterranean under a single ruler for the last time in history. Justinian's Corpus Juris Civilis — the comprehensive codification of Roman law completed between 529 and 534 CE — is arguably the single most influential legal document in world history, forming the basis of civil law traditions across Europe, Latin America, and much of the world. The construction of Hagia Sophia between 532 and 537 CE — an architectural achievement so far beyond contemporary building practice that the architect Procopius wrote that its dome appeared to hang from the sky on a golden chain — remained the world's largest cathedral for nearly a thousand years. The Justinianic Plague of 541–549 CE, an early outbreak of bubonic plague, killed perhaps 25–50 million people across the Mediterranean world, undermining the economic and demographic base that had made the reconquests possible."},
  {"id":865,"n":"Ostrogothic Kingdom","s":45.4654,"e":9.1866,"b":493,"d":553,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy was the most sophisticated of the Germanic successor states, ruled by Theodoric the Great whose thirty-three-year reign combined Arian Gothic military power with Roman administrative traditions in a synthesis that briefly promised a viable post-Roman order for Italy. Theodoric's chancery was staffed by Roman senators including Cassiodorus and Boethius — the latter composing the Consolation of Philosophy while awaiting execution on Theodoric's orders in 524 CE, producing one of the most widely read books of the medieval world in circumstances of profound personal tragedy. The kingdom's capital at Ravenna produced the most magnificent late antique mosaics in existence — the Mausoleum of Galla Placidia, the Basilica of San Vitale, and the Basilica of Sant'Apollinare Nuovo — representing a synthesis of Roman, Byzantine, and Gothic artistic traditions of haunting beauty. Justinian's Belisarius destroyed the Ostrogothic kingdom in a prolonged war of 535–553 CE that devastated Italy more thoroughly than the Gothic invasions had done."},
  {"id":866,"n":"Frankish Kingdom — Capetian Dynasty","s":48.8566,"e":2.3522,"b":987,"d":1328,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Capetian dynasty was the founding royal house of France, established when Hugh Capet was elected king in 987 CE and ruling continuously until 1328 in a direct line of unprecedented dynastic stability — thirteen generations without a break — that gave France the most continuous royal succession of any major medieval European state. The Capetians methodically expanded royal power from a tiny domain around Paris through strategic marriage, feudal suzerainty, and military opportunism — most dramatically under Philip II Augustus, who tripled the royal domain and defeated a coalition of English and German forces at Bouvines in 1214, and Louis IX (Saint Louis), who combined crusading piety with administrative genius to create the most efficient royal government in thirteenth-century Europe. The construction of Gothic cathedrals under royal and episcopal patronage — Notre-Dame de Paris, Chartres, Reims, Amiens — represents one of the supreme artistic achievements of European civilisation, expressing in stone and stained glass a theology of light and transcendence that constitutes medieval Europe's most powerful aesthetic legacy. The direct Capetian line ended with the death of Charles IV in 1328, succeeded by the Valois branch."},
  {"id":867,"n":"Angevin Empire","s":51.5074,"e":-0.1278,"b":1154,"d":1224,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Angevin Empire — the continental dominion of the Plantagenet kings of England — was at the death of Henry II in 1189 the most powerful feudal state in Western Europe, controlling England, Normandy, Brittany, Anjou, Maine, Touraine, Poitou, Gascony, and suzerainty over Wales, Scotland, and Ireland in a personal union that made the Plantagenet king more powerful in France than the French king himself. The empire's cultural achievement was extraordinary — Henry II's court produced the Arthurian romances of Chrétien de Troyes, the historical writings of Gerald of Wales, and the administrative innovations of Ranulf de Glanvill, while Eleanor of Aquitaine's patronage of troubadour poetry at Poitiers created the courtly love tradition that transformed European literary culture. The murder of Thomas Becket in Canterbury Cathedral in 1170 — carried out by four knights responding to Henry II's frustrated outburst 'will no one rid me of this turbulent priest?' — created both a saint and a martyr that haunted the English monarchy and produced a tradition of royal penance and submission to church authority. Philip II Augustus of France systematically dismembered the continental empire between 1202 and 1224, reducing the Plantagenets to England, Gascony, and a few minor lordships."},
  {"id":868,"n":"Kingdom of Jerusalem — Latin East","s":31.7683,"e":35.2137,"b":1099,"d":1291,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Kingdom of Jerusalem was the most prestigious of the Crusader States, established by Godfrey of Bouillon following the First Crusade's capture of Jerusalem in 1099 and enduring in various forms for nearly two centuries as the centre of Latin Christian presence in the Levant. The kingdom developed remarkable legal and constitutional institutions — the Assizes of Jerusalem constituted one of the most sophisticated bodies of feudal law in medieval Europe, and the High Court of the kingdom exercised unusual constraints on royal power that anticipated elements of constitutionalism. The True Cross relic held by the kingdom was its most sacred possession — its capture by Saladin at the Battle of Hattin in 1187 and the subsequent fall of Jerusalem deprived the Crusader cause of both its spiritual symbol and its most sacred city in a single catastrophic campaign. The 'kingdom without a kingdom' that persisted after 1187, based successively at Acre, Tyre, and Acre again, maintained Latin Christian presence in the Levant until the fall of Acre to the Mamluk Sultan al-Ashraf Khalil in 1291."},
  {"id":869,"n":"Kievan Rus — Principalities Period","s":51.5,"e":31.2833,"b":1054,"d":1240,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The fragmentation of Kievan Rus following the death of Yaroslav the Wise in 1054 produced a constellation of competing principalities — Vladimir-Suzdal, Galicia-Volhynia, Novgorod, Chernigov, and dozens of smaller domains — each developing distinct political cultures while sharing the Orthodox Christian religion, the Church Slavonic literary tradition, and the dynastic identity of the Rurikid family that had founded the Rus state. The city of Novgorod developed a unique republican constitution — the Novgorod Republic was governed by a popular assembly (veche), elected officials, and a nobility (boyars) whose collective power regularly overrode princes invited to lead the city's military, making it the most democratic polity in medieval Eastern Europe. The principality of Vladimir-Suzdal produced the greatest achievements of medieval Russian architecture — the Cathedral of the Dormition at Vladimir, the Church of the Intercession on the Nerl, and the Cathedral of Saint Dmitrius — representing a distinctively Russian synthesis of Byzantine, Romanesque, and indigenous building traditions. Mongol invasion under Batu Khan in 1237–1240 devastated the principalities, destroying their cities and killing perhaps half the population."},
  {"id":870,"n":"Grand Duchy of Moscow","s":55.7558,"e":37.6173,"b":1263,"d":1547,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Grand Duchy of Moscow rose from a minor appanage principality to become the nucleus of the Russian state through a combination of strategic subservience to the Mongol Golden Horde, shrewd territorial acquisition through inheritance and purchase, and the determined accumulation of legitimising symbols — notably Ivan III's marriage to the Byzantine princess Sophia Palaiologina in 1472, which positioned Moscow as the 'Third Rome' and heir to the Byzantine imperial tradition. Ivan III the Great's refusal to pay tribute to the Golden Horde in 1476 effectively ended the Tatar Yoke without a major military confrontation, as the fractured Golden Horde was unable to force submission. Ivan the Terrible's assumption of the title Tsar in 1547 — the Russian form of Caesar — transformed the grand duchy into a tsardom and inaugurated a period of dramatic expansion: the conquest of the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan opened the Volga corridor and the beginning of Russian expansion into Siberia that would ultimately reach the Pacific. Ivan's Oprichnina terror of 1565–1572 — systematic purging of the boyar aristocracy using a separate administration and paramilitary force — established a pattern of political violence that has recurred throughout Russian history."},
  {"id":871,"n":"Serbian Medieval Empire","s":44.0165,"e":21.0059,"b":1217,"d":1371,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Serbian medieval state reached its greatest extent under Stefan Dušan, who was crowned Emperor of the Serbs and Greeks in 1346 and briefly created the largest state in the Balkans since the Byzantine Empire, controlling Serbia, Macedonia, Albania, Thessaly, Epirus, and most of Bulgaria in an empire that he attempted to present as the legitimate successor of Byzantium. Dušan's legal code — the Zakonik of 1349 — was one of the most comprehensive bodies of medieval Balkan law, drawing on Byzantine and Serbian customary law to create a systematic legal framework that governed the empire's diverse population of Orthodox Serbs, Greeks, Albanians, and Bulgarians. The Nemanjić dynasty that preceded Dušan created some of the most extraordinary medieval Serbian architecture — the Sopoćani monastery's frescoes, the Studenica monastery complex, and the Visoki Dečani monastery — representing a distinct Raška school of art that combined Byzantine iconographic tradition with Romanesque spatial sensibility. Serbian power collapsed rapidly after Dušan's death in 1355 and the catastrophic defeat at the Battle of Kosovo in 1389, which entered Serbian cultural memory as the defining national tragedy."},
  {"id":872,"n":"Bulgarian First Empire","s":43.2141,"e":27.9147,"b":681,"d":1018,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The First Bulgarian Empire was the first Slavic state to be formally recognised by the Byzantine Empire, established when the Bulgar khan Asparuh defeated the Byzantines and extracted a treaty acknowledging Bulgarian sovereignty north of the Balkan Mountains in 681 CE — the foundational moment of the Bulgarian state. Tsar Simeon I the Great, who reigned from 893 to 927, presided over the Bulgarian Golden Age — a period of extensive territorial expansion that brought the empire to the shores of the Adriatic, Aegean, and Black seas, and a literary and cultural renaissance that produced the Cyrillic alphabet, the Glagolitic script (developed by Saints Cyril and Methodius), and a body of Old Church Slavonic literary production that spread literacy across the Slavic world. The Preslav literary school under Simeon's patronage translated Byzantine theological and literary texts into Old Church Slavonic in a translation movement comparable in cultural significance to the Islamic translation movement in Baghdad. Byzantine Emperor Basil II 'the Bulgar-Slayer' destroyed the first empire in 1018 after blinding fifteen thousand Bulgarian prisoners."},
  {"id":873,"n":"Bulgarian Second Empire","s":43.0757,"e":25.6172,"b":1185,"d":1396,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Second Bulgarian Empire was restored through the Asen brothers' rebellion against Byzantine rule in 1185 and reached its medieval peak under Ivan Asen II, whose victory at Klokotnitsa in 1230 established Bulgaria as the dominant power of the Balkans. The Tarnovo school of religious painting produced some of the finest Orthodox Christian art of the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries, the Boyana Church near Sofia containing a cycle of frescoes from 1259 that has been compared in quality and psychological sophistication to the contemporary work of Cimabue in Italy — a remarkable parallel achievement in Byzantine artistic tradition. The empire's capital Tarnovo with its dramatic hilltop fortress complex of Tsarevets became the centre of a vibrant literary and cultural life that developed a distinctive Bulgarian national consciousness expressed through hagiography, chronicles, and religious poetry. Ottoman forces gradually absorbed Bulgarian territory through the late fourteenth century, and the fall of Tarnovo in 1393 effectively ended the second empire, with formal Ottoman conquest completing by 1396."},
  {"id":874,"n":"Kingdom of Croatia","s":45.815,"e":15.9819,"b":925,"d":1102,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Kingdom of Croatia was a medieval Slavic Christian state on the eastern Adriatic coast that briefly unified Croatian tribes under a single king in the late ninth century, receiving recognition from Pope John X and developing a distinctive Latin-Croatian court culture that blended Byzantine, Frankish, and indigenous Slavic traditions. Tomislav, the first Croatian king crowned around 925 CE, commanded a military force that Bulgarian chroniclers described as formidably large, suggesting a degree of Croatian military power that made the Adriatic coast a significant factor in regional politics. The Croatian legal tradition produced the Vinodol Law Code of 1288 — one of the earliest legal documents in the Croatian language — establishing the principle of codified customary law that would characterise Croatian legal culture. The personal union with Hungary established in 1102 under the Pacta Conventa — whose precise terms remain disputed by Croatian and Hungarian historians — preserved Croatian autonomy within the Hungarian kingdom for over eight centuries."},
  {"id":875,"n":"Khanate of Crimea","s":45,"e":34.1,"b":1441,"d":1783,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Khanate of Crimea was a successor state of the Golden Horde that survived for over three centuries as an Ottoman vassal, conducting slave raids into Russia, Ukraine, and Poland-Lithuania that captured and sold into the Ottoman slave markets an estimated two to three million people over the course of the fifteenth to seventeenth centuries — one of the largest slave raiding enterprises in modern history. Crimean Tatar cavalry were among the most feared raiders in eastern Europe, capable of covering enormous distances at speed and returning with captives before effective military response could be organised — the great chain of Russian frontier fortifications (the zasechnaya cherta) was built primarily to limit Crimean raiding. The khanate's capital Bakhchysarai housed the Khan's Palace — a magnificent complex of courtyards, fountains, and decorated chambers that represents the finest surviving example of Crimean Tatar architectural achievement. Catherine the Great annexed Crimea in 1783, ending the khanate and beginning the Russian settlement of the peninsula whose consequences remain geopolitically live in the twenty-first century."},
  {"id":876,"n":"Khanate of Kazan","s":55.7887,"e":49.1221,"b":1438,"d":1552,"t":"confirmed","cont":"EU","desc":"The Khanate of Kazan was a successor state of the Golden Horde controlling the middle Volga region and the vital river trade routes connecting Russia to the Caspian Sea and Central Asia, and its position as the principal Muslim state on Russia's eastern frontier made its conquest by Ivan the Terrible in 1552 one of the most consequential military campaigns in Russian history. Ivan IV's capture of Kazan on 2 October 1552 — celebrated in Russia as a moment of national triumph comparable to the Battle of Kulikovo — opened the Volga corridor to Russian expansion, initiated the conquest of Siberia, and began the incorporation of non-Russian Muslim and indigenous peoples into the Russian imperial state. The Cathedral of Saint Basil the Blessed in Moscow's Red Square — commissioned by Ivan to commemorate the Kazan conquest — is the most iconic building in Russian architectural history, its onion domes and polychrome exterior representing a uniquely Russian synthesis of architectural traditions. The Tatar population of Kazan and the Volga region maintained their language, Islamic religion, and cultural identity through centuries of Russian rule."},
  {"id":877,"n":"Ilkhanate of Persia — Cultural Phase","s":37.57,"e":45.07,"b":1295,"d":1335,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The cultural phase of the Ilkhanate following Ghazan Khan's conversion to Islam in 1295 represents one of the most remarkable episodes of civilisational transformation in the medieval Islamic world, as Mongol rulers who had devastated Persian urban civilisation became its most lavish patrons, commissioning Persian miniature painting, architecture, and historiography at a level that produced some of the finest achievements of the Islamic aesthetic tradition. The vizier Rashid al-Din Hamadani, who served under Ghazan and his successor Öljeitü, produced the Jami' al-Tawarikh — the first genuine world history encompassing Chinese, Indian, Frankish, Jewish, and Islamic traditions — while managing the imperial finances and overseeing the construction of his endowed quarter in Tabriz that became a centre of manuscript production. The Ilkhanid period saw the introduction of Chinese artistic motifs — dragons, phoenixes, cloud scrolls, and lotus flowers — into the Persian visual vocabulary, creating a Mongol-Persian synthesis in manuscript illumination and ceramic decoration that fundamentally transformed the Islamic aesthetic tradition. The sudden fragmentation of the Ilkhanate after Ghazan's death in 1335 dispersed the manuscript workshops and artistic communities whose collective achievement had been so concentrated."},
  {"id":878,"n":"Chagatai Khanate","s":43.222,"e":76.8512,"b":1226,"d":1687,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Chagatai Khanate was the Central Asian successor state of the Mongol Empire, occupying the steppe and oasis lands of present-day Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Afghanistan, and western China — the heartland of the ancient Silk Road — and surviving in various forms for over four centuries while fracturing progressively between nomadic and settled cultures that developed increasingly divergent political orientations. The khanate's western half — Transoxiana — became increasingly Islamised and sedentarised, producing the urban cultures of Samarkand and Bukhara that Timur would later draw upon, while the eastern Moghulistan remained predominantly nomadic and pagan longer before converting to Islam. The Chagatai language — a Turkic literary language written in Arabic script — became the prestige literary medium of Central Asian culture, used by the poet Mir Ali Shir Nava'i and the Mughal founder Babur (who wrote his Baburnama in Chagatai) and remains one of the most important literary languages of the pre-modern Turkic world. The khanate was progressively dismembered by Uzbek pressure from the west and Dzungar Mongol pressure from the east, with the last Chagataid ruler dying in 1687."},
  {"id":879,"n":"Dzungar Khanate","s":46,"e":86,"b":1634,"d":1758,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Dzungar Khanate was the last great nomadic empire of Eurasia, an Oirat Mongol state that controlled the Dzungarian basin and at its peak challenged the Qing dynasty of China, the Russian Empire, and the Kazakh khanates simultaneously in conflicts that ranged across an enormous arc of Central Asian steppe and mountain terrain. The Dzungar-Qing Wars of the late seventeenth and eighteenth centuries represent the last great clash between steppe nomadism and sedentary agrarian empire, ending with the Qing Emperor Qianlong's systematic destruction of the Dzungar state in a genocidal campaign of 1755–1758 that killed an estimated 480,000 to 600,000 Dzungars — approximately eighty percent of the Dzungar population — in what some scholars have called the eighteenth century's first genocide. The Dzungars made significant advances in military organisation, adopting firearms and cannon technology to supplement traditional steppe cavalry tactics in a synthesis that made them far more formidable opponents than previous nomadic states. The destruction of the Dzungar state ended the steppe nomadic threat to China and cleared the way for Qing incorporation of Xinjiang."},
  {"id":880,"n":"Tokugawa Shogunate","s":35.6762,"e":139.6503,"b":1603,"d":1868,"t":"confirmed","cont":"AS","desc":"The Tokugawa Shogunate established two and a half centuries of remarkable peace and stability in Japan through a system of political control that confined the emperor to a ceremonial role, required the daimyo (feudal lords) to alternate residence between their domains and Edo (Tokyo) under the sankin-kōtai system, and enforced the sakoku policy of near-complete national isolation that limited foreign contact to a small Dutch trading post at Dejima in Nagasaki. The peace of the Edo period generated a flourishing of urban popular culture — kabuki theatre, ukiyo-e woodblock printing, haiku poetry, and the prose fiction tradition of the gesaku — that produced a sophisticated commercial cultural economy of remarkable diversity, concentrated in the cities of Edo, Osaka, and Kyoto. Commodore Matthew Perry's arrival with a squadron of American steam-powered warships in Tokyo Bay in 1853 — the 'Black Ships' — shattered the sakoku policy and began the crisis that ended the Tokugawa system, with the shogunate's inability to resist foreign pressure discrediting it in the eyes of the samurai class. The Meiji Restoration of 1868 returned formal power to the Emperor Meiji and began Japan's rapid modernisation."},
  {"id":881,"n":"Kingdom of Tonga (Tu'i Tonga Empire)","s":-950,"e":1865,"t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"The Tu'i Tonga Empire was one of the most expansive maritime polities in the Pacific, radiating influence across Polynesia, Micronesia, and Melanesia from its capital on Tongatapu. At its height between roughly 950 and 1300 CE, Tu'i Tonga chiefs commanded tribute networks stretching over 2.5 million square kilometres of ocean. The empire operated not as a conventional territorial state but as a prestige-exchange system anchored in chiefly genealogy and ceremonial kava ritual. Oral traditions and Lapita-descended archaeological evidence underpin its historical reconstruction."},
  {"id":882,"n":"Nan Madol (Saudeleur Dynasty)","s":-200,"e":1628,"t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"Nan Madol was a spectacular artificial island city constructed on coral reefs off the eastern coast of Pohnpei in Micronesia, comprising nearly 100 interconnected islets built from massive basalt columns and coral fill. It served as the ceremonial and administrative capital of the Saudeleur Dynasty for approximately fourteen centuries before oral tradition records a revolt by the hero Isokelekel around 1628 CE. The engineering required to transport basalt logs — some weighing up to 50 tonnes — remains incompletely explained by conventional accounts. The site is now a UNESCO World Heritage property and a focal point for alternative archaeology researchers."},
  {"id":883,"n":"Rapanui (Easter Island) Civilisation","s":400,"e":1722,"t":"confirmed","cont":"oceania","d":"The Rapanui civilisation developed on one of the world's most isolated inhabited islands, constructing over 900 moai monolithic statues placed on ceremonial ahu platforms. Polynesian settlers arrived approximately 400–800 CE and developed a stratified society organised around competing clans whose prestige was expressed through moai production and placement. Internal competition, deforestation, and resource stress contributed to societal disruption well before European contact in 1722. Debates continue over the relative roles of ecological collapse versus introduced disease in the civilisation's decline."},
  {"id":887,"n":"Kingdom of Zimbabwe (Great Zimbabwe State)","s":1100,"e":1450,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Great Zimbabwe state was the largest of the stone-walled dzimbahwe polities of the Zimbabwe Plateau, controlling the gold trade between the African interior and Swahili coast ports such as Sofala. Its iconic Great Enclosure — built without mortar from precisely fitted granite blocks — remains the largest ancient structure south of the Sahara. At its peak around 1300–1400 CE, Great Zimbabwe housed an estimated 18,000 people and commanded tribute across a vast hinterland. Colonial-era denial of its African authorship has been thoroughly refuted by archaeological consensus."},
  {"id":888,"n":"Mutapa Empire (Mwenemutapa)","s":1430,"e":1760,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Mutapa Empire, founded by Nyatsimba Mutota after the decline of Great Zimbabwe, controlled the Zambezi valley and the gold-rich plateau of present-day Zimbabwe and Mozambique, maintaining lucrative trade with Portuguese and Arab merchants on the Swahili coast. The Mwenemutapa's power derived from control of gold mining, cattle herds, and ritual authority over the land. Portuguese interference from the sixteenth century onwards progressively undermined Mutapa sovereignty, though the empire persisted in diminished form until absorbed by the Rozvi state in the late seventeenth century."},
  {"id":889,"n":"Dilmun Civilisation","s":-3200,"e":-600,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Dilmun was an ancient trading civilisation centred on the island of Bahrain and the adjacent eastern Arabian coast, serving as the crucial entrepôt linking Mesopotamia with the Indus Valley and Oman's copper-producing Magan region. Sumerian and Akkadian texts describe Dilmun as a paradisiacal land of immortality and abundance, and several scholars link the tradition to the Garden of Eden narrative. Dilmun's burial mound fields — numbering in the tens of thousands — represent one of the ancient world's most extensive necropolis landscapes. Its commercial dominance declined as direct sea routes between Mesopotamia and the Indus became established."},
  {"id":890,"n":"Sabaean Kingdom (Sheba)","s":-900,"e":275,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kingdom of Saba in present-day Yemen was one of the great South Arabian civilisations, commanding the overland and maritime incense trade routes that supplied frankincense and myrrh to the ancient Mediterranean, Mesopotamian, and Indian worlds. Its capital Marib, anchored by the famous Marib Dam, supported an irrigated agricultural surplus that sustained urban density unusual for Arabia. Biblical and Quranic traditions associate Saba with the legendary Queen of Sheba who visited Solomon. The kingdom eventually gave way to the Himyarite successor state, which adopted Judaism before conversion to Christianity and then Islam."},
  {"id":892,"n":"Axumite Empire","s":-400,"e":940,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Axumite Empire, centred in the northern Ethiopian highlands, was one of the great powers of late antiquity alongside Rome, Persia, and China, controlling Red Sea trade between the Mediterranean and Indian Ocean worlds. Axum is renowned for its towering granite obelisks, its early adoption of Christianity under King Ezana around 330 CE, and its sixth-century conquest of Himyarite Yemen. Axumite merchants used their own gold coinage and traded as far as India and Constantinople. The civilisation's decline followed the disruption of Red Sea commerce by the rise of Islam in the seventh century."},
  {"id":893,"n":"Kingdom of Kush (Meroitic Period)","s":-300,"e":350,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Meroitic phase of the Kingdom of Kush, centred at Meroe on the middle Nile in present-day Sudan, was a distinct African Iron Age civilisation that emerged from the earlier Napatan kingdom which had briefly ruled Egypt as the 25th Dynasty. Meroe developed its own alphabetic script — still only partially deciphered — and a distinctive artistic tradition blending Egyptian, Hellenistic, and indigenous Sudanese elements. The city's pyramid fields, palatial temples, and iron-smelting facilities led early scholars to call it the Birmingham of Africa. The kingdom was weakened by Axumite military campaigns and internal pressures around 350 CE."},
  {"id":901,"n":"Pagan Kingdom (Bagan Empire)","s":849,"e":1297,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Pagan Kingdom unified the Irrawaddy valley and surrounding regions of present-day Myanmar, constructing over 10,000 religious monuments across the Bagan plain — more than 2,000 of which survive. Founded in 849 CE and reaching its apex under Anawrahta (r. 1044–1077), who adopted Theravada Buddhism as the state religion, Pagan became the preeminent centre of Buddhist learning in mainland Southeast Asia. The empire was severely weakened by Mongol invasions under Kublai Khan in the 1270s–1290s and fragmented into successor states after 1297. Bagan remains one of the world's great archaeological and spiritual landscapes."},
  {"id":902,"n":"Kingdom of Ayutthaya","s":1351,"e":1767,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kingdom of Ayutthaya, founded in 1351 on an island at the confluence of three rivers in central Thailand, grew into one of Southeast Asia's wealthiest and most cosmopolitan states, attracting Portuguese, Dutch, French, Chinese, Japanese, and Persian merchants to its bustling ports. The kingdom twice sacked Angkor, absorbed Sukhothai, and contended for mainland dominance with Burma's Toungoo and Konbaung dynasties across four centuries. Ayutthayan court culture produced an elaborate ceremonial system, monumental Buddhist architecture, and sophisticated legal codes. The city was destroyed by Burmese forces in 1767, a trauma that defined subsequent Thai national consciousness."},
  {"id":904,"n":"Unified Silla Kingdom","s":-57,"e":935,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Silla unified the Korean peninsula in 668 CE through alliance with Tang China and the defeat of Goguryeo and Baekje, inaugurating the Unified Silla period considered the golden age of Korean Buddhism and artistic achievement. The capital Gyeongju became one of Asia's great cities, home to the magnificent Bulguksa temple complex and the astronomical observatory Cheomseongdae. Silla's hwarang warrior-scholar youth corps became a model for East Asian martial and ethical formation. The kingdom fragmented in the late ninth century as regional strongmen reasserted power, giving way to the Goryeo dynasty."},
  {"id":908,"n":"Göbekli Tepe Culture (Pre-Pottery Neolithic A)","s":-11500,"e":-8000,"t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The culture responsible for constructing Göbekli Tepe in southeastern Anatolia around 11,500 BCE represents either the world's earliest known organised ritual and architectural tradition or a fundamental challenge to the standard sequence of civilisational development. The site's T-shaped pillars, carved with sophisticated zoomorphic reliefs, required coordinated labour from communities across a wide region — predating agriculture, pottery, and metallurgy. Excavator Klaus Schmidt proposed that religious impulse preceded and perhaps drove the agricultural revolution. Alternative researchers including Andrew Collins argue that Göbekli Tepe is evidence of a more sophisticated pre-Younger Dryas cultural horizon than mainstream archaeology currently acknowledges."},
  {"id":909,"n":"Pre-Flood Indus Civilisation (Vedic Antediluvian Hypothesis)","s":-10000,"e":-6500,"t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"The Vedic Antediluvian Hypothesis proposes that ancient Sanskrit texts — particularly the Mahabharata, Ramayana, and Puranas — preserve oral memories of a pre-flood civilisation in the Indian subcontinent predating the known Indus Valley Civilisation by several millennia. Proponents including David Frawley and Stephen Oppenheimer argue that astronomical references in Vedic texts point to dates of 10,000–8,000 BCE, and that mythological accounts of sunken coastal cities correspond to sea-level rise following the last glacial maximum. The mainstream academic position holds that the Vedic tradition originated with Indo-Aryan migrations circa 2000–1500 BCE. Growing genetic and linguistic data suggest deeper continuities worth further investigation."},
  {"id":910,"n":"Pre-Saudeleur Nan Madol Builder Culture","s":-1000,"e":-200,"t":"theorized","cont":"oceania","d":"The Pre-Saudeleur Hypothesis proposes that the basalt-column artificial islands of Nan Madol on Pohnpei were begun by a predecessor population predating the historically attested Saudeleur dynasty by a millennium or more. Pohnpeian oral traditions attribute the founding construction to two mythical brothers, Olisihpa and Olosohpa, who arrived from a distant land and used supernatural means to position the massive basalt columns. Some alternative researchers in the network of Graham Hancock have suggested the site warrants systematic underwater archaeological survey, noting that sea levels around Pohnpei were significantly lower during the early Holocene. No peer-reviewed archaeological consensus currently supports a pre-1000 BCE occupation of the Nan Madol reef platform."},
  {"id":912,"n":"Ancestral Puebloans (Anasazi)","s":100,"e":1300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Ancestral Puebloans, formerly known as Anasazi, were the architects of the remarkable cliff dwellings and great houses of the American Southwest, centred on the Colorado Plateau spanning present-day Arizona, New Mexico, Utah, and Colorado. Their architectural achievement at Chaco Canyon — a road-linked network of massive multi-storey great houses aligned to solar and lunar cycles — represents the most sophisticated pre-Columbian urban planning north of Mesoamerica. The civilisation experienced a dramatic reorganisation and southward migration around 1300 CE, likely driven by a prolonged megadrought documented in tree-ring records. Their descendants are the modern Pueblo peoples of the Rio Grande valley and Hopi mesas."},
  {"id":913,"n":"Mound Builders of the Ohio Valley (Fort Ancient Culture)","s":1000,"e":1650,"t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Fort Ancient Culture was a Late Woodland and early Mississippian-influenced agricultural society of the middle Ohio River valley, constructing villages, ceremonial enclosures, and earthworks across present-day Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana, and West Virginia. Fort Ancient communities cultivated maize, beans, and squash in river floodplains and maintained extensive trade networks connecting them to the broader Mississippian world to the south and west. The Great Serpent Mound of Ohio — though its precise cultural attribution remains debated — sits within the Fort Ancient heartland and is one of the world's largest effigy earthworks. The culture declined rapidly following European contact, likely through epidemic disease."},
  {"id":914,"n":"Taíno Civilisation","s":600,"e":1550,"t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Taíno were the dominant Arawakan-speaking people of the Greater Antilles — Cuba, Hispaniola, Jamaica, and Puerto Rico — at the time of Columbus's arrival in 1492, and the first Indigenous people of the Americas to sustain prolonged contact with Europeans. Organised into chiefdoms (cacicazgos) led by hereditary chiefs (caciques), Taíno society supported populations estimated in the hundreds of thousands through intensive cassava cultivation, fishing, and sophisticated ballcourt ceremonialism. Their cosmological tradition, art, and vocabulary — words including canoe, hammock, hurricane, and barbecue entered European languages through Taíno — profoundly shaped early colonial culture. The Taíno were effectively destroyed within fifty years of contact through disease, enslavement, and violence."},
  {"id":916,"n":"Tiahuanaco / Tiwanaku (Early Phase)","s":-1500,"e":300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The early phase of Tiwanaku on the Bolivian altiplano — preceding the imperial period already recorded as a later entry — represents an independent village and early urban horizon on the southern shores of Lake Titicaca stretching back to at least 1500 BCE. During this formative period, the communities at the Tiwanaku site developed the raised-field (suka kollus) agricultural technology that would eventually support one of the highest-altitude urban civilisations in history. Ceramic and architectural traditions of this early phase laid the cultural groundwork for the later imperial florescence. Arthur Posnansky controversially argued that astronomical alignments at Tiwanaku indicate construction as early as 15,000 BCE, a position rejected by mainstream archaeology but retained as an alternative theory in ongoing debate."},
  {"id":917,"n":"Caral-Supe Civilisation","s":-3000,"e":-1800,"t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Caral-Supe Civilisation of coastal and inland Peru is the oldest known complex society in the Americas, with monumental platform mounds at Caral dated by radiocarbon to approximately 3000 BCE — contemporaneous with the earliest Egyptian pyramids and Sumerian city-states. Unlike most early civilisations, Caral appears to have developed without ceramic pottery and with minimal evidence of warfare or weaponry, suggesting an economy based on maritime fish resources traded inland for agricultural products. Its 25 known settlement sites across the Supe Valley display sophisticated urban planning, sunken circular plazas, and acoustic engineering in amphitheatre-like spaces. Peruvian archaeologist Ruth Shady Solís led the excavations that brought Caral to international attention in the early 2000s."},
  {"id":918,"n":"Wari Empire (Imperial Phase)","s":600,"e":1000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"americas","d":"The Wari Empire, centred at the city of Huari in the Ayacucho valley of central Peru, was the first expansionist imperial state in Andean history, establishing administrative colonies and road networks across the highlands and coast centuries before the Inca. Wari urban centres were characterised by orthogonal planned layouts, massive D-shaped ceremonial structures, and standardised ceramic and textile production systems that foreshadowed Inca administrative techniques. The empire's collapse around 1000 CE remains incompletely understood but correlates with prolonged drought episodes recorded in ice cores. Wari and its northern contemporary Tiwanaku shared iconographic traditions suggesting either cultural exchange or a common religious horizon."},
  {"id":919,"n":"Kingdom of Aksum (Early Phase)","s":-400,"e":100,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The early phase of the Aksumite state in the northern Ethiopian highlands and Eritrea preceded the well-documented imperial period by several centuries, representing the emergence of a proto-urban trading community from the pre-Aksumite D'mt kingdom tradition. During this formative period, communities in the Aksum region developed the monumental stele tradition, mastered bronze casting, and established the Red Sea trade connections that would later underpin the empire's wealth. South Arabian cultural and linguistic influences — evidenced in early inscriptions and material culture — gave way progressively to indigenous Ethiopian traditions. This early phase is distinguished from the confirmed imperial Axumite Empire (id 892) by its pre-Christian, pre-coinage character."},
  {"id":921,"n":"Kingdom of Ife (Ile-Ife)","s":500,"e":1400,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"Ile-Ife in present-day southwestern Nigeria is the sacred origin city of the Yoruba people and the site of one of the ancient world's most breathtaking artistic traditions — naturalistic bronze and terracotta portrait heads of an artistic mastery that stunned European observers when first encountered in the late nineteenth century. Ife was a major urban centre by at least 1000 CE, with paved streets of potsherd pavements and a ritual landscape of shrines and sacred groves reflecting a cosmology in which Ife was the navel of the world, where the Yoruba god Obatala descended on a chain to create dry land. The kingdom's artistic and political prestige radiated across the Yoruba world and directly influenced the later Benin bronze tradition. Its power waned as the Oyo Empire rose to regional dominance."},
  {"id":922,"n":"Benin Kingdom (Edo Empire)","s":900,"e":1897,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of Benin, centred at Benin City in present-day Edo State, Nigeria, was one of the oldest and most sophisticated states in West Africa, governed by the divine Oba (king) of the Edo people across nearly a millennium of continuous dynastic history. Benin is celebrated worldwide for its extraordinary corpus of bronze, brass, and ivory court art — plaques, portrait heads, figures, and ceremonial objects produced by the Igun Eronmwon guild under royal patronage — whose artistic achievement caused a sensation when carried off by the British Punitive Expedition of 1897. The kingdom maintained complex diplomatic and commercial relations with Portuguese traders from 1485 and conducted a sophisticated pepper and cloth trade before the dominance of the slave trade transformed the regional economy. International campaigns for the repatriation of the Benin Bronzes to Nigeria continue in the 2020s."},
  {"id":925,"n":"Great Rift Valley Early Hominid Cultures (Oldowan / Acheulean)","s":-2600000,"e":-100000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Oldowan and Acheulean tool-making traditions of the East African Rift Valley represent the earliest documented evidence of systematic cultural transmission and technological innovation in the human lineage, extending from approximately 2.6 million years ago to around 100,000 BCE. Oldowan choppers and flakes — produced by Homo habilis at sites including Olduvai Gorge in Tanzania and Lomekwi in Kenya — represent the first known deliberate shaping of stone for functional use. The later Acheulean tradition, associated with Homo erectus and archaic Homo sapiens, produced the symmetrical hand-axe — a tool so standardised across vast distances and time spans that it implies social learning and cultural transmission far earlier than previously assumed. These traditions are the deep foundation of all subsequent human civilisation."},
  {"id":926,"n":"Blombos Cave Culture (Early Symbolic Behaviour)","s":-100000,"e":-70000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Blombos Cave site on the southern Cape coast of South Africa has yielded evidence for abstract symbolic behaviour by anatomically modern Homo sapiens as early as 100,000 BCE, pushing the emergence of modern cognition dramatically earlier than the European Upper Palaeolithic 'creative explosion' model proposed in the twentieth century. Finds include ochre pieces engraved with geometric cross-hatch patterns, perforated shell beads used as personal ornaments, and a ochre processing workshop — collectively suggesting that planned symbolic communication, body decoration, and material culture were already established in southern Africa long before the peopling of the rest of the world. The site's evidence is central to the 'African origins of modern behaviour' paradigm now dominant in palaeoanthropology. Francesco d'Errico and Christopher Henshilwood have led excavations at the site."},
  {"id":927,"n":"Sulawesi Cave Art Culture","s":-45500,"e":-20000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The limestone caves of Sulawesi, Indonesia, contain the world's oldest known figurative cave art, with a pig painting at Leang Tedongnge dated by uranium-series methods to at least 45,500 years ago — older than the famous Chauvet and Lascaux paintings of Europe. A hunting scene at Leang Bulu' Sipong 4, depicting therianthropic (part-human, part-animal) figures pursuing warty pigs and dwarf buffalo, has been dated to at least 43,900 years ago and represents the oldest known narrative art in human history. These discoveries, led by archaeologist Adam Brumm and colleagues, have fundamentally revised the assumed European origin of figurative art and suggest that representational image-making emerged with the earliest modern humans to leave Africa. The caves remain incompletely surveyed and further discoveries are anticipated."},
  {"id":928,"n":"Denisovan Horizon (Denisova Cave Culture)","s":-300000,"e":-30000,"t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Denisovan Horizon refers to the material and genetic traces of an archaic human population — the Denisovans — identified primarily through ancient DNA analysis of fragmentary bones from Denisova Cave in the Altai Mountains of Siberia, but whose genetic legacy is detectable across a vast arc from Siberia through Southeast Asia and into Oceania. Denisovans are now known to have interbred with both Neanderthals and modern Homo sapiens, contributing up to 5% of the genome of modern Melanesian, Aboriginal Australian, and some Southeast Asian populations. The Xiahe mandible from Tibet suggests Denisovans were adapted to high-altitude environments. Andrew Collins and others have proposed that Denisovan cognitive and technological capabilities may have been more sophisticated than currently recognised, potentially contributing to the cultural transmission that accelerated after their hybridisation with modern humans."},
  {"id":929,"n":"Jōmon Culture (Japan)","s":-14000,"e":-300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Jōmon people of the Japanese archipelago produced the world's oldest known pottery — cord-marked ceramic vessels dated to approximately 14,000 BCE — in a hunter-gatherer-fisher context that challenges the assumption that pottery was developed exclusively in agricultural societies. Over its remarkably long duration of more than 13,000 years, Jōmon culture developed sophisticated lacquerwork, complex pit-house settlements, and elaborate ritual traditions including dogu clay figurines whose abstracted female forms suggest a rich cosmological life. Jōmon seafarers maintained exchange networks across the Sea of Japan and into the Ryukyu Islands. The transition to the agricultural Yayoi culture from around 300 BCE onwards involved the immigration of rice-farming peoples from the Korean peninsula who largely — but not entirely — replaced the Jōmon genetic and cultural heritage."},
  {"id":930,"n":"Yayoi Culture (Japan)","s":-300,"e":300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Yayoi Culture transformed the Japanese archipelago from 300 BCE onwards through the introduction of wet-rice agriculture, bronze and iron metallurgy, and a new population of immigrants from the Korean peninsula whose admixture with existing Jōmon people created the genetic profile of most modern Japanese. Yayoi society was initially egalitarian but rapidly stratified, producing elite burial mounds, bronze ritual bells (dotaku), and eventually a network of competing chiefdoms (kuni) described in Chinese Wei Zhi records of the third century CE. The kingdom of Yamatai, led by the shamaness-queen Himiko, is the most famous of these polities, though its location — in northern Kyushu or in the Yamato region of Honshu — remains one of Japanese archaeology's most contentious debates. Yayoi cultural and biological heritage forms the foundation of classical Japanese civilisation."},
  {"id":931,"n":"Kofun Period (Yamato State)","s":250,"e":538,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kofun Period marks the emergence of the centralised Yamato state on the Japanese archipelago, named for its defining cultural feature: enormous keyhole-shaped burial mounds (kofun) that rank among the largest funerary structures on earth. The Daisen Kofun in Sakai, attributed to Emperor Nintoku, covers a greater surface area than the Great Pyramid of Giza. The Yamato rulers consolidated political authority across Honshu and Kyushu through a combination of military power, strategic marriages, and the distribution of bronze mirrors, swords, and jewels as symbols of royal legitimacy. Contacts with the Korean kingdoms of Baekje, Silla, and Goguryeo introduced Buddhism, Chinese writing, and continental administrative techniques that would transform Japan in the subsequent Asuka period. The imperial line established in the Kofun period claims unbroken continuity to the present day."},
  {"id":932,"n":"Indus Valley Civilisation (Harappan)","s":-3300,"e":-1300,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Indus Valley Civilisation was one of the world's three earliest urban civilisations alongside Mesopotamia and Egypt, extending across a vast area of present-day Pakistan and northwestern India and encompassing over 1,000 known sites at its height around 2600–1900 BCE. Its two great cities — Mohenjo-daro and Harappa — were planned on a grid pattern with sophisticated brick-built drainage and sewerage systems unmatched in the ancient world, suggesting a level of civic organisation without apparent parallel. Uniquely among early civilisations, the Indus Culture has left no deciphered written records, no identified royal palace or temple, and no evidence of a warrior elite — its social organisation remains deeply enigmatic. The civilisation's decline around 1900–1300 BCE correlates with monsoon weakening, though the relative roles of climate change, migration, and social transformation continue to be debated."},
  {"id":934,"n":"Mycenaean Civilisation","s":-1600,"e":-1100,"t":"confirmed","cont":"europe","d":"The Mycenaean Civilisation was the first advanced civilisation of mainland Greece, centred on fortified palatial citadels at Mycenae, Tiryns, Pylos, Thebes, and Athens, and representing the earliest Greek-speaking literate society documented by the Linear B script tablets. Mycenaean warrior-kings commanded palace-based economies that organised craft production, agricultural surplus, and long-distance trade across the Mediterranean, with Mycenaean pottery and metalwork found from Spain to the Levant. The legendary Trojan War, preserved in Homer's Iliad, is generally regarded as a literary memory of Mycenaean-era raiding and conflict along the Anatolian coast. The Mycenaean world collapsed catastrophically around 1200–1150 BCE in the wider Late Bronze Age collapse, leaving Greece in a four-century dark age before the emergence of the classical polis."},
  {"id":938,"n":"Scythian Empire","s":-800,"e":-200,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Scythians were an Iranian-speaking nomadic and semi-nomadic people of the Pontic-Caspian steppe who built one of antiquity's most formidable military empires without cities, writing, or sedentary infrastructure, relying instead on mastery of horse-mounted composite-bow warfare that made their armies nearly impossible to defeat in open battle. Their kurgan burial mounds, scattered across the steppe from the Danube to the Altai, contain extraordinary gold artefacts — animal-style jewellery, weapons, drinking vessels, and horse trappings — that represent one of the ancient world's supreme goldsmithing traditions. Herodotus recorded extensive observations of Scythian customs, religion, and warfare following their defeat of Darius I's Persian invasion around 513 BCE. The Scythian world was gradually absorbed by Sarmatian peoples and ultimately by the Gothic and Hunnic migrations of late antiquity."},
  {"id":940,"n":"Bactrian-Margiana Archaeological Complex (BMAC / Oxus Civilisation)","s":-2300,"e":-1700,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Bactrian-Margiana Archaeological Complex, also called the Oxus Civilisation, was a Bronze Age urban culture of Central Asia centred in present-day Turkmenistan, Afghanistan, and northern Iran, contemporaneous with Mesopotamia, Egypt, and the Indus Valley and connected to all three by trade in lapis lazuli, tin, carnelian, and luxury textiles. Its rectangular fortified settlements — including Gonur Tepe in Turkmenistan and Dashly in Afghanistan — contained palaces, temples, and sophisticated craft workshops producing distinctive chlorite vessels, compartmented seals, and composite figurines that appear across a vast exchange network. The BMAC is a prime candidate for the archaeological culture of the earliest Indo-Iranian speakers, potentially the proto-Aryans whose migrations carried Vedic and Avestan religious traditions into India and Iran respectively. The civilisation collapsed around 1700 BCE, likely due to a combination of climatic desiccation and the arrival of steppe pastoralists."},
  {"id":943,"n":"Urartu (Kingdom of Van)","s":-860,"e":-590,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"Urartu, centred on Lake Van in the highlands of eastern Anatolia and the southern Caucasus, was a powerful Iron Age kingdom that rivalled and frequently clashed with the Assyrian Empire across nearly three centuries of bitter warfare, constructing a network of fortress cities, irrigation canals, and granaries across the challenging mountain terrain. Urartian metalwork — particularly bronze cauldrons with griffin and bull-head attachments — spread across the ancient world through trade and war, influencing Greek, Etruscan, and Near Eastern artistic traditions. The kingdom maintained its own cuneiform script adapted from Assyrian and erected monumental rock-cut inscriptions recording royal campaigns and building works. Urartu's decline in the late seventh century BCE before the combined pressure of Scythian raids and Median expansion eventually gave way to the Armenian cultural tradition that succeeded it."},
  {"id":945,"n":"Elamite Civilisation","s":-3200,"e":-539,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Elamite Civilisation of southwestern Iran, centred on the city of Susa in the Khuzestan lowlands and the highland capital of Anshan, was one of the ancient world's most enduring and sophisticated states, maintaining continuous political identity for more than 2,500 years alongside and often in conflict with the Sumerian, Akkadian, Babylonian, and Assyrian civilisations of Mesopotamia. Elamites developed one of antiquity's earliest writing systems — Proto-Elamite script, still undeciphered — independently of Mesopotamian cuneiform, and their cylinder seals, bronze casting, and monumental architecture at Chogha Zanbil represent the highest achievements of Iranian Bronze Age culture. The great ziggurat of Chogha Zanbil, built by King Untash-Napirisha around 1250 BCE, is the best-preserved ziggurat outside Mesopotamia and a UNESCO World Heritage site. Elam was ultimately absorbed into the Achaemenid Persian Empire following the campaigns of Ashurbanipal around 640 BCE."},
  {"id":948,"n":"Kassite Babylon","s":-1595,"e":-1155,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kassite Dynasty of Babylon ruled Mesopotamia for approximately 440 years — the longest single dynasty in Babylonian history — following their seizure of power after the Hittite sack of Babylon around 1595 BCE, though their origins remain debated, with proposed homelands ranging from the Zagros Mountains to the Iranian plateau. Under Kassite rule, Babylon became a major centre of international diplomacy recorded in the Amarna Letters, exchanging gifts and princesses with Egypt, Mitanni, Assyria, and the Hittites in a system of great-power correspondence unprecedented in the ancient world. The Kassites introduced the kudurru stone boundary marker as a legal-administrative innovation and rebuilt Babylon's temple infrastructure. Their dynasty was ended by an Elamite invasion around 1155 BCE that carried off the famous statue of Marduk to Susa."},
  {"id":949,"n":"Kingdom of Israel and Judah","s":-1020,"e":-586,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The United and Divided Kingdoms of Israel and Judah represent the political expression of the ancient Israelite civilisation whose religious and literary legacy — the Hebrew Bible and its monotheistic theology — became the foundational text of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam and arguably the single most influential cultural document in human history. The United Kingdom under Saul, David, and Solomon (c.1020–930 BCE) is presented in biblical texts as a period of territorial expansion and cultural florescence, including Solomon's Temple in Jerusalem, though the archaeological evidence for a large unified state in this period remains contested. The northern Kingdom of Israel was destroyed by the Assyrians in 722 BCE and its population deported — the origin of the Ten Lost Tribes tradition — while Judah survived until the Babylonian conquest of 586 BCE and the destruction of the First Temple."},
  {"id":950,"n":"Aramean City-States","s":-1200,"e":-700,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Aramean city-states of Syria — including Damascus, Hamath, Arpad, and Bit Adini — formed a politically fragmented but culturally cohesive civilisation that emerged in the power vacuum following the Late Bronze Age collapse and profoundly shaped the ancient Near East through the spread of the Aramaic language, which became the lingua franca of the entire region from Egypt to Central Asia and remained so for over a millennium. Aramaic eventually displaced Akkadian as the administrative language of the Assyrian, Babylonian, and Achaemenid Persian empires, and was the spoken language of Roman-period Judea, including, according to most scholars, Jesus of Nazareth. The Aramean states were progressively absorbed by the expanding Neo-Assyrian Empire through the ninth and eighth centuries BCE. Their alphabetic script tradition directly influenced the development of the Hebrew, Arabic, and many other writing systems."},
  {"id":951,"n":"Neo-Babylonian Empire (Chaldean)","s":-626,"e":-539,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Neo-Babylonian Empire, founded by Nabopolassar of the Chaldean tribe in 626 BCE, briefly restored Babylonian supremacy over the ancient Near East after a century of Assyrian domination, reaching its apogee under Nebuchadnezzar II whose military campaigns destroyed Jerusalem and the First Temple in 586 BCE, deporting the Judean elite in the Babylonian Captivity that transformed Jewish theology and literature. Nebuchadnezzar's Babylon was one of antiquity's most magnificent cities, featuring the Ishtar Gate — now partially reconstructed in Berlin's Pergamon Museum — the great Processional Way, and the ziggurat Etemenanki, widely identified as the Tower of Babel. The Hanging Gardens of Babylon, one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, are traditionally attributed to Nebuchadnezzar, though their existence and precise location remain debated. The empire fell to Cyrus the Great of Persia in 539 BCE, who allowed the Jewish exiles to return to their homeland."},
  {"id":952,"n":"Nubian Kingdom of Kerma","s":-2500,"e":-1500,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of Kerma in present-day northern Sudan was the first major urban civilisation of sub-Saharan Africa and the earliest indigenous state of the Nile Valley south of Egypt, reaching its greatest power during the Second Intermediate Period of Egyptian weakness when Kerma rulers allied with the Hyksos and raided as far north as Elephantine. Kerma's material culture — distinctive black-topped red pottery, monumental mud-brick royal tumuli (deffufas), and elaborate burial assemblages — represents an entirely indigenous African urban tradition without significant Egyptian derivation. The Western Deffufa at Kerma, a massive mud-brick religious structure, remains one of Africa's oldest standing buildings. Kerma was eventually conquered by the Egyptian New Kingdom pharaoh Thutmose I around 1500 BCE, initiating centuries of Egyptian colonial rule over Nubia."},
  {"id":953,"n":"Napatan Kingdom (25th Dynasty)","s":-900,"e":-270,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Napatan Kingdom, centred near the Fourth Cataract of the Nile at Napata in present-day Sudan, reconquered Egypt around 747 BCE under Piye and established the Kushite 25th Dynasty — the Black Pharaohs — who ruled Egypt for nearly a century and undertook a remarkable programme of Egyptian cultural and religious revival, restoring temples, commissioning traditional Egyptian art, and reinvigorating the Amun priesthood. The Napatan kings were buried under steep-sided pyramids modelled on but distinctively different from Egyptian predecessors, at cemeteries at El-Kurru and Nuri that represent the beginning of the Sudanese pyramid tradition. Taharqa, the greatest of the Black Pharaohs, is mentioned in the Hebrew Bible and resisted Assyrian invasion before being pushed south of Egypt. The Napatan state eventually gave way to the Meroitic phase of the Kingdom of Kush (id 893)."},
  {"id":954,"n":"Kingdom of Punt","s":-2500,"e":-1000,"t":"debated","cont":"africa","d":"The Kingdom of Punt — called by Egyptians the 'Land of the Gods' — was a prosperous trading partner of ancient Egypt from at least the Old Kingdom period, supplying incense, myrrh, ebony, ivory, electrum, and exotic animals including baboons and leopards through a series of celebrated royal expeditions, most famously that of Queen Hatshepsut around 1470 BCE depicted in magnificent relief at her Deir el-Bahri mortuary temple. Despite extensive Egyptian textual and pictorial documentation, the precise location of Punt remains one of Egyptology's most debated questions, with proposed identifications spanning the Horn of Africa, coastal Sudan and Eritrea, the Arabian Peninsula, and even the Mozambique coast. DNA analysis of baboon mummies from Egyptian tombs has suggested a population from the region of modern Eritrea and eastern Ethiopia as most likely. The kingdom's political structure, language, and internal history remain almost entirely unknown."},
  {"id":955,"n":"Liangzhu Culture","s":-3400,"e":-2250,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Liangzhu Culture of the Yangtze River Delta in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces of China was one of East Asia's most sophisticated Neolithic civilisations, renowned above all for its extraordinary jade craft — particularly the cong tube and bi disc forms whose precise functions and cosmological significance remain debated but whose technical perfection required tools and skills of remarkable refinement. Liangzhu's capital site, recently confirmed by archaeological excavation and now a UNESCO World Heritage property, featured massive hydraulic engineering works including dams, reservoirs, and flood-diversion channels that represent the world's oldest large-scale water management system, predating comparable works in Mesopotamia and Egypt. The civilisation's abrupt collapse around 2250 BCE correlates with evidence for catastrophic flooding events possibly connected to the legendary floods of Chinese mythology associated with Emperor Yao. Liangzhu jade objects spread through elite exchange networks across a vast area of prehistoric China."},
  {"id":956,"n":"Longshan Culture (Dragon Mountain)","s":-3000,"e":-1900,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Longshan Culture of the Yellow River valley and eastern China represents the most complex and widespread of China's late Neolithic cultural horizons, characterised by burnished black eggshell pottery of extraordinary thinness — some vessel walls only 0.5mm thick — walled settlements, craft specialisation, and evidence for social stratification and ritual violence that anticipates the fully urban Bronze Age Erlitou culture and the historical Shang Dynasty. Longshan communities across a wide arc from Shandong to Shaanxi developed oracle-bone divination, scapulimancy, and the earliest evidence for what would become the Chinese tradition of ancestor veneration. The walled settlements of the Longshan period, some enclosing areas of hundreds of hectares, suggest a politically fragmented landscape of competing chiefdoms whose conflicts drove the social intensification culminating in early Chinese states. Longshan is a strong candidate for the archaeological culture of the legendary sage kings and Xia Dynasty of Chinese historical tradition."},
  {"id":957,"n":"Erlitou Culture (Proto-Shang / Xia Dynasty Candidate)","s":-1900,"e":-1500,"t":"debated","cont":"asia","d":"The Erlitou Culture of the Central Plains of China, centred on a large palatial complex near modern Luoyang in Henan Province dated to approximately 1900–1500 BCE, is the strongest archaeological candidate for the legendary Xia Dynasty — China's first dynasty according to traditional historiography — though the identification remains contested due to the absence of contemporary written records confirming a dynastic name. Erlitou was the largest settlement in East Asia at its time, featuring palace foundations, bronze ritual vessels, turquoise and lacquer workshops, and a planned urban layout that clearly anticipates the Shang Dynasty city-state model. The site's bronze-casting technology represents the earliest confirmed metallurgy in the Yellow River region. Whether Erlitou represents the Xia, an early phase of the Shang, or a distinct unnamed polity is one of Chinese archaeology's most actively debated questions."},
  {"id":958,"n":"Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors (Legendary China)","s":-2852,"e":-2070,"t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"The Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors of Chinese tradition — a sequence of semi-divine cultural heroes including Fuxi, Shennong, the Yellow Emperor Huangdi, Yao, and Shun — represent either legendary encoding of real prehistoric cultural developments, mythologised memories of early Neolithic leaders, or purely mythological constructs with no historical kernel, depending on scholarly perspective. Traditional Chinese chronology places the reign of the Yellow Emperor at around 2697 BCE, and he is credited with the invention of writing, the wheel, silk production, and Chinese medicine — cultural attributions that parallel the role of Mesopotamian antediluvian kings in the Sumerian King List. The legendary floods of Yao's reign and their resolution by the engineer Yu (founder of the Xia Dynasty) may encode genuine folk memory of the catastrophic Holocene floods documented in Chinese geological records. The tradition is deeply embedded in Chinese national cultural identity and continues to shape historical consciousness."},
  {"id":960,"n":"Dong Son Culture (Bronze Age Vietnam)","s":-1000,"e":200,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Dong Son Culture of the Red River Delta in northern Vietnam was the preeminent Bronze Age civilisation of mainland Southeast Asia, celebrated above all for its monumental bronze kettledrums — decorated with geometric patterns, boats, warriors, and ceremonial scenes — which spread through trade and prestige exchange across a vast area from southern China to the islands of Indonesia, where they were treasured as sacred objects and heirlooms for centuries. Dong Son communities were skilled wet-rice farmers and maritime traders whose decorated bronze objects encode a rich ceremonial and cosmological world centred on water, fertility, and ancestor veneration. The culture's political organisation featured competing chiefdoms that the Chinese Han Dynasty progressively absorbed into the empire from 111 BCE, triggering a series of Vietnamese resistance movements that defined the early formation of Vietnamese national identity. The legendary Trung Sisters revolt of 40 CE against Han rule became one of Vietnam's most enduring national founding myths."},
  {"id":961,"n":"Dian Kingdom (Yunnan)","s":-400,"e":100,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Dian Kingdom of the Yunnan plateau in southwestern China flourished around Lake Dian near modern Kunming from approximately the fourth century BCE until Han Dynasty absorption, producing a remarkable corpus of bronze artefacts — cowrie shell containers with lids depicting detailed three-dimensional scenes of sacrifice, warfare, agriculture, and ceremony — that constitute one of the ancient world's most vivid documentary records of daily and ritual life. The Dian were a non-Han people whose cultural connections extended south into mainland Southeast Asia rather than north to the Yellow River civilisations, and whose bronzework tradition shares elements with both Dong Son culture and the steppe animal-style tradition. Their capital was confirmed by Chinese Han records, which describe the Dian king receiving a golden seal of vassalage from the Han emperor in 109 BCE. The kingdom's fate following Han incorporation is obscure."},
  {"id":963,"n":"Balhae Kingdom (Bohai)","s":698,"e":926,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Balhae Kingdom, founded in 698 CE by Dae Joyeong — a former general of Goguryeo — in the region of Manchuria, the Russian Far East, and northern Korea following the fall of Goguryeo, was a multi-ethnic state that Tang China described as the 'flourishing land of the east' for its sophisticated urban culture, extensive trade networks, and diplomatic activity. Balhae maintained a five-capital administrative system modelled on Tang Chinese governance and sent regular embassies to the Tang court while also maintaining relations with Japan and the Silla Kingdom. Koreans regard Balhae as a successor state to Goguryeo and part of the broader arc of Korean history, while Chinese historiography classifies it as a local regime of the Tang period — a dispute with ongoing resonance in Sino-Korean scholarly relations. The kingdom was destroyed by the Khitan Liao Dynasty in 926 CE."},
  {"id":965,"n":"Chalukya Dynasty (Badami)","s":543,"e":753,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Chalukya Dynasty of Badami in the Deccan plateau of present-day Karnataka was the first great medieval Hindu empire of the southern Indian interior, contending with the Pallavas of the southeast, the Harsha Empire of the north, and the Rashtrakutas in a complex triangle of power that shaped early medieval Indian geopolitics. The Chalukyas' cave temples at Badami and the structural temples at Aihole and Pattadakal — a UNESCO World Heritage site — represent the crucible in which the Vesara style of Deccan temple architecture was developed, synthesising northern Nagara and southern Dravidian traditions into a distinctive regional form. Their naval capacity allowed projection of power into the Laccadive Islands and trade connections with the Arab world. The dynasty fragmented into the Eastern and Western Chalukya branches following Rashtrakuta conquest in 753 CE."},
  {"id":967,"n":"Kingdom of Magadha (Pre-Maurya)","s":-600,"e":-322,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kingdom of Magadha in the middle Gangetic plain of present-day Bihar was the most powerful of the sixteen Mahajanapada (great kingdoms) of ancient India and the state from which the Maurya and Gupta empires would later emerge, its successive dynasties — Haryanka, Shishunaga, and Nanda — progressively consolidating control over the Gangetic valley through military innovation, including the first documented use of war elephants at scale in South Asian warfare. Magadha was the crucible of two of the world's great religious traditions: the Buddha attained enlightenment at Bodh Gaya within the kingdom's territory, and Mahavira, founder of Jainism, was born and taught primarily within its borders. The capital Pataliputra (modern Patna), founded by the Haryanka king Ajatashatru, became under the Nanda and Maurya dynasties one of the ancient world's largest cities. Alexander the Great's army mutinied at the Beas River in 326 BCE rather than face the Nanda army's reportedly enormous force of war elephants and infantry."},
  {"id":969,"n":"Parthian Empire (Arsacid Dynasty)","s":-247,"e":224,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Parthian Empire, founded by Arsaces I of the Parni tribe around 247 BCE and lasting nearly five centuries, was the dominant power of the Iranian world between the Seleucid and Sassanid Persian empires and Rome's most formidable eastern adversary, inflicting on Rome its most catastrophic defeat — the annihilation of Marcus Licinius Crassus's army at the Battle of Carrhae in 53 BCE by the legendary Parthian shot tactic of horse-archer feigned retreats. The Parthians controlled the central Silk Road between the Mediterranean world and China and grew enormously wealthy from transit trade while maintaining a deliberately decentralised feudal political structure that gave remarkable autonomy to local kings and nobles. Parthian court culture blended Iranian, Hellenistic, and Mesopotamian traditions in a sophisticated cosmopolitan synthesis. The dynasty was overthrown by the Sassanid Persian revolt of Ardashir I in 224 CE."},
  {"id":970,"n":"Lost City of Dwarka (Submerged Dwarka Hypothesis)","s":-9000,"e":-1500,"t":"theorized","cont":"asia","d":"The Submerged Dwarka Hypothesis proposes that underwater stone structures discovered off the coast of Dwarka in Gujarat, India, by the National Institute of Ocean Technology in 2001–2002, represent the remains of an ancient city that may correspond to the legendary city of Dwarka described in the Mahabharata as the kingdom of the god-king Krishna, submerged by the sea following his death. Mainstream archaeologists, while acknowledging the existence of submerged structures, date them to no earlier than the historical period (c.1500 BCE) and suggest they represent a natural or human-made harbour feature. Alternative researchers and proponents of Vedic historical literalism argue the structures could date to the post-glacial sea-level rise of 7000–9000 BCE, placing Dwarka among the world's oldest submerged cities. The site has not been subjected to comprehensive peer-reviewed underwater excavation. Graham Hancock has cited Dwarka as part of a broader pattern of submerged coastal civilisations worldwide."},
  {"id":974,"n":"Ptolemaic Kingdom (Hellenistic Egypt)","s":-305,"e":-30,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Ptolemaic Kingdom, founded by Ptolemy I Soter — another of Alexander's generals — ruled Egypt for nearly three centuries as a Macedonian Greek dynasty that presented itself to Egyptian subjects as pharaohs and to the Greek world as Hellenistic monarchs, producing a remarkable cultural synthesis centred on Alexandria, the greatest city of the ancient Mediterranean world. The Library of Alexandria and the associated Mouseion (Museum) represented antiquity's supreme institution of scholarship, drawing scientists, philosophers, and poets from across the Greek world and accumulating an estimated 700,000 scrolls before its progressive decline and destruction. Ptolemaic Egypt was the wealthiest state of the Hellenistic world, exploiting Egypt's agricultural surplus and its position controlling trade between the Mediterranean and the Red Sea. The dynasty ended with Cleopatra VII — its last and most famous ruler — whose death in 30 BCE following the defeat of her alliance with Mark Antony made Egypt a Roman province."},
  {"id":975,"n":"Kingdom of Bactria (Greco-Bactrian Kingdom)","s":-256,"e":-125,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Greco-Bactrian Kingdom, formed when the Seleucid satrap of Bactria declared independence around 256 BCE, was one of history's most extraordinary civilisational experiments — a Greek state flourishing in the heart of Central Asia, its kings bearing names like Demetrius, Eucratides, and Menander while ruling a multicultural population of Greeks, Bactrians, Sogdians, and Indians from its capital at Bactra (modern Balkh). At its greatest extent it controlled territory encompassing present-day Afghanistan, Pakistan, and parts of India, and its successor Indo-Greek kingdoms produced the first coins to bear Buddhist imagery and conducted dialogue with Buddhist philosophers recorded in the Milindapanha. The kingdom's remarkable coinage — considered by numismatists among the finest portrait coins of antiquity — provides the primary evidence for its history, as no written records survive. It was ultimately destroyed by the Yuezhi nomadic migrations that also gave rise to the Kushan Empire."},
  {"id":978,"n":"Harsha Empire","s":606,"e":647,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Harsha Empire, ruled by Emperor Harsha (Harshavardhana) from his capital at Kanauj in the upper Gangetic plain, represented the last great pan-northern Indian empire before the Rajput period and the eventual Islamic invasions, unifying most of northern India through a combination of military conquest and diplomatic alliance during a reign of forty years. The Chinese Buddhist pilgrim Xuanzang (Hsuan-tsang), who spent fifteen years travelling India during Harsha's reign, left a detailed account of the empire's administration, religious life, and the magnificent quinquennial Prayag assembly where Harsha distributed his accumulated treasury to monks, priests, and the poor. Harsha was himself a prolific Sanskrit author, composing three surviving dramas, and his court attracted scholars and artists from across Asia. The empire disintegrated immediately after his death in 647 CE, leaving no dynastic successor."},
  {"id":979,"n":"Chalukya Dynasty (Vengi / Eastern)","s":624,"e":1189,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Eastern Chalukya Dynasty of Vengi — a branch of the Badami Chalukyas established in the Krishna-Godavari delta region of present-day Andhra Pradesh — ruled for over five centuries as a bridge state between the great powers of southern India, at various times subordinate to or allied with the Rashtrakutas, Western Chalukyas, and Cholas, with whose royal family the Eastern Chalukyas eventually merged through marriage alliances. The dynasty was a major patron of Telugu literature and is credited with fostering the earliest Telugu literary works, earning it a foundational role in the cultural history of the Telugu-speaking people. Its long rule over the fertile delta region generated agricultural wealth that supported an elaborate court culture and temple construction programme. The dynasty's political identity was ultimately absorbed into the Chola imperial system in the eleventh century."},
  {"id":980,"n":"Kakatiya Dynasty","s":1083,"e":1323,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Kakatiya Dynasty of Warangal in present-day Telangana was the last great medieval Telugu Hindu kingdom before the Delhi Sultanate's conquest of the Deccan, celebrated for the rule of Queen Rudrama Devi — one of the few female sovereigns in medieval Indian history — and for the construction of the magnificent Ramappa Temple, its sanctum's floating bricks and exquisite bracket figures representing the apex of Kakatiya artistic achievement, now a UNESCO World Heritage site. Marco Polo visited the Kakatiya kingdom during the reign of Rudrama's successor Prataparudra and described its ports, diamonds, and fine cotton muslin. The kingdom maintained a sophisticated tank irrigation system of hundreds of reservoirs that transformed the semi-arid Deccan landscape and supported dense agricultural settlement. The Kakatiya state was destroyed by the Delhi Sultanate's Malik Kafur and Muhammad bin Tughluq through a series of devastating invasions between 1303 and 1323."},
  {"id":982,"n":"Maratha Confederacy (Early Phase)","s":1645,"e":1680,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The early Maratha Confederacy, forged by the extraordinary military and political genius of Shivaji Bhonsle between 1645 and his death in 1680, represents one of history's most remarkable stories of resistance — a Hindu chieftain of the Deccan hills building from near nothing a sovereign kingdom capable of challenging the mighty Mughal Empire at its height. Shivaji developed a distinctive guerrilla warfare doctrine exploiting the rugged Sahyadri hill forts, a naval force to contest Mughal and Portuguese coastal control, and an administrative system that promoted merit over birth and protected the rights of peasants and religious minorities. His coronation in 1674 as Chhatrapati (sovereign) was a defining moment of Hindu political resurgence and is celebrated as a foundational moment of Marathi cultural identity. The confederacy he founded eventually expanded to control a substantial portion of the Indian subcontinent under his successors and the Peshwa prime ministers."},
  {"id":983,"n":"Vijayanagara Empire (Sangama Dynasty — Founding Phase)","s":1336,"e":1485,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The founding Sangama phase of the Vijayanagara Empire — already recorded as a broader entry at id 899 — is noted here as a distinct entry to recognise the specific historical and legendary circumstances of the empire's foundation by brothers Harihara I and Bukka Raya I, who according to tradition were former Kakatiya and Kampili kingdom officers who converted to Islam under Delhi Sultanate pressure before being reconverted to Hinduism by the sage Vidyaranya and entrusted with establishing a kingdom to defend Hindu civilisation in the south. The Sangama phase saw the initial consolidation of power on the southern bank of the Tungabhadra River, the construction of the capital at Vijayanagara (Hampi), and the first successful military campaigns against the Bahmani Sultanate that would define the empire's existential rivalry. This phase is distinguished from the later imperial zenith under the Tuluva dynasty's Krishnadevaraya."},
  {"id":984,"n":"Deccan Sultanates (Collective)","s":1490,"e":1686,"t":"confirmed","cont":"asia","d":"The Deccan Sultanates — Ahmadnagar, Bidar, Bijapur, Berar, and Golconda — emerged from the fragmentation of the Bahmani Sultanate in the late fifteenth century and collectively dominated the political landscape of the central and southern Deccan for two centuries, producing a rich synthesis of Persian, Turkish, Indian, and African cultural traditions unique in South Asian history. Bijapur under the Adil Shahi dynasty produced the Gol Gumbaz — whose dome, at 44 metres diameter, is the second largest in the world after St Peter's Basilica — and a vibrant Deccani painting tradition that blended Safavid Persian and local Indian elements. The Golconda Sultanate controlled the world's only known source of diamonds at the time, making it extraordinarily wealthy. The five sultanates united briefly to defeat Vijayanagara at Talikota in 1565, then were progressively conquered by Aurangzeb's Mughal armies between 1636 and 1686."},
  {"id":988,"n":"Mamluk Sultanate (Egypt)","s":1250,"e":1517,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Mamluk Sultanate of Egypt, established by former slave-soldiers (mamluks) of the Ayyubid dynasty in 1250, became the most powerful Muslim state of the later medieval world, achieving what no other Islamic power could — the decisive defeat of the Mongol armies at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, halting their westward advance and preserving Egypt, Syria, and the Arab heartland from destruction. Cairo under Mamluk rule became the cultural, commercial, and religious capital of the Islamic world following the Mongol sack of Baghdad in 1258, with the city's madrasas, mosques, and mausoleums — including the extraordinary Sultan Hassan mosque-madrasa complex — representing the apogee of medieval Islamic architecture. The Mamluks also maintained the Abbasid Caliphate in Cairo as a symbolic legitimising institution. The sultanate was conquered by the Ottoman Empire under Selim I in 1517, though Mamluk amirs continued to govern Egypt under Ottoman suzerainty until Napoleon's invasion."},
  {"id":993,"n":"Mali Empire (Sundiata Phase)","s":1235,"e":1400,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Mali Empire, founded by Sundiata Keita following his defeat of the Sosso king Sumanguru Kante at the Battle of Kirina around 1235 CE, was the largest empire in West African history at its height, controlling the gold and salt trade routes of the western Sudan across a territory the size of western Europe and incorporating the great commercial and scholarly cities of Timbuktu, Djenné, and Kumbi Saleh. The Mali Empire's most celebrated ruler Mansa Musa undertook his famous pilgrimage to Mecca in 1324–1325 with a caravan of 60,000 people and 100 camel-loads of gold — so much gold that his lavish spending in Cairo and the Levant triggered decade-long inflation across the Mediterranean world. Timbuktu under Mali rule became one of the Islamic world's foremost centres of scholarship, with the Sankore mosque-university housing tens of thousands of manuscripts. The empire's decline from the late fourteenth century was driven by dynastic conflict and the rise of the Songhai power to its east."},
  {"id":996,"n":"Great Zimbabwe (Rozvi State Successor)","s":1684,"e":1834,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The Rozvi State, established by Changamire Dombo following his expulsion of the Portuguese from the Zimbabwe Plateau in 1684, was the last flowering of the Great Zimbabwe stone-walled palace tradition, constructing a series of magnificent dhaka (dung-plastered) and dry-stone walled royal residences at sites including Khami, Danangombe, and Naletale whose architectural quality matched or exceeded that of Great Zimbabwe itself. Changamire's victories over the Portuguese represented the most decisive African military expulsion of European power south of the Sahara in the seventeenth century. The Rozvi Mambo (king) commanded ritual, economic, and military authority over a wide territory of the plateau and maintained cattle-based wealth and long-distance trade with the coast. The state was destroyed by Nguni migrations (Mfecane/Difaqane) during the early nineteenth century, with the last Rozvi Mambo killed by Ngoni raiders around 1834."},
  {"id":998,"n":"Ethiopian Empire (Solomonic Restoration)","s":1270,"e":1974,"t":"confirmed","cont":"africa","d":"The restored Solomonic Dynasty of Ethiopia, claiming descent from the union of King Solomon and the Queen of Sheba as narrated in the Kebra Nagast national epic, ruled Ethiopia from 1270 CE until the deposition of Emperor Haile Selassie I by the Derg military junta in 1974 — making it one of the longest-reigning dynasties in world history. Ethiopia under the Solomonic emperors maintained its independence against Ottoman, Portuguese, Egyptian, and eventually Italian colonial pressure, defeating Italy comprehensively at the Battle of Adwa in 1896 in the most significant African victory over a European colonial power and making Ethiopia a symbol of pan-African resistance worldwide. The reign of Haile Selassie (1930–1974) saw Ethiopia become a founding member of the League of Nations, a central figure in the founding of the Organisation of African Unity, and the spiritual centre of the global Rastafari religious movement. The 1974 revolution ended the dynasty but not Ethiopia's historic significance."},
  {"id":999,"n":"Antediluvian Civilisation (Pre-12,800 BCE Advanced Culture Hypothesis)","s":-35000,"e":-10800,"t":"theorized","cont":"global","d":"The Antediluvian Advanced Culture Hypothesis, most comprehensively argued by Graham Hancock in Fingerprints of the Gods (1995), Magicians of the Gods (2015), and America Before (2019), proposes that a sophisticated civilisation — comparable to or exceeding Bronze Age levels of astronomical knowledge, navigation, and monumental architecture — existed globally before the Younger Dryas impact event of approximately 10,800 BCE, whose civilisational traces survive in the astronomical alignments of monuments worldwide, the global flood myths present in virtually every human culture, and anomalous archaeological data that mainstream chronology cannot easily accommodate. Supporting researchers including Randall Carlson, Robert Schoch, and Richard Firestone present evidence from the Younger Dryas Boundary impact layer, the Carolina Bays, and the Sphinx water erosion controversy. Mainstream archaeology holds that no evidence for pre-agricultural complex society exists before the Natufian and early Neolithic periods. This entry synthesises the broader hypothesis rather than any single site."},
  {"id":1000,"n":"The Human Journey — Out of Africa Migration Network","s":-70000,"e":-10000,"t":"confirmed","cont":"global","d":"The Out of Africa dispersal of anatomically modern Homo sapiens, beginning approximately 70,000 years ago following a possible population bottleneck associated with the Toba supervolcanic eruption, represents not a single civilisation but the foundational migration network that populated the entire world and from which all subsequent human cultures descend. Genetic, archaeological, and linguistic evidence converges on an African origin for all living humans, with primary dispersal routes tracked through the Arabian Peninsula and South Asian coast to Australia by approximately 65,000 BCE, into East Asia and Europe by 45,000 BCE, across the Bering land bridge into the Americas by at least 16,000 BCE, and into the remote Pacific by 3,500 BCE. This entry serves as Tempus Linea's anchor civilisation — the root node from which all 999 preceding entries ultimately branch — and its globe representation marks the African origin point while its timeline span encompasses the full arc of the human story from first dispersal to the threshold of recorded history."}
];
